<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The American dream of the day laborer
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Jaime is a carpenter from Veracruz, working
during the week as a framer for a local builder. He's been here a
year, and his wife and two children still live in Mexico. Jaime
lives with a roommate in a tiny frame home down a pothole-pitted
dirt driveway on the south side of town. He's going back home in
November to visit his family, which he's obviously looking forward
to.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime knows a fair amount of English for having been here a
relatively short time. That, and my limited knowledge of Spanish,
make it possible for us to converse fairly extensively, though we
both hit pockets of no comprendo and have to move on to another
subject.
</P>
<P>
   I've hired Jaime on a Sunday morning for $6 an hour to clean out
flower beds and do other light yard work. Despite the light
drizzle, about a dozen Mexican men come heading toward my Jeep as I
pull into the day-labor area near downtown, jostling each other to
be first to the vehicle. I hold up a single finger _ one worker
only needed _ and Jaime wins the short footrace. The others trudge
back to where they can stay somewhat dry under the canopy of the
pecan trees, waiting for the next potential employer.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime loves the Jeep, points to the stick shift and says,
``Standard. That's good.'' in a thick accent. He doesn't have a car
yet, and when I try to ask if it's because he doesn't have a green
card _ tarjeta verde, I say in my pidgin Spanish _ he gets nervous,
especially when I say immigracion in an attempt to make him
understand what I'm asking. I'm just curious and have no intention
of turning him over to the INS. Time to change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   I show him what to do and he gets to work, but the clouds decide
to open up. I offer him the option of quitting, but he takes the
poncho I dig out and works in the pouring rain while I go back to
building a chair out of black walnut in the woodshop.
</P>
<P>
   The rain slackens for a while, but then a real trash-hauler
ensues, and I tell Jaime to come in the shop and forget the flower
bed, which at this rate may be under water soon. I show him the
chair I'm building, and that sets him off talking about how houses
are constructed in Veracruz _ concrete blocks and adobe _ and about
his friend who was a master woodcarver in Mexico. Then he starts
talking about hurricanes and how wooden houses can't withstand the
wind, but a concrete-and adobe house will do just fine, even if
it's flooded.
</P>
<P>
   He's a talker, Jaime is, gesturing expansively as he walks
around the shop, admiring the tools and giving the Spanish names
for them _ torno for the lathe, for example, which makes eminent
sense. After all, a lathe turns wood. I tell him the English
equivalent, and he repeats the word several times, committing it to
memory.
</P>
<P>
   I hire day laborers a few times a year when I need someone to do
things I'm too old or lazy to do, or when I simply need a strong
back to help me. A few months ago I hired Davy to help me put in
some sod and move dirt around. He lives a few houses down from
Jaime and works during the week as an auto mechanic at a shop out
in the country. He was from near Monterrey, as I recall, with a
wife and two kids living here. While not quite as loquacious as
Jaime, Davy also showed an aptitude and desire to learn English,
worked hard with rare breaks, was unfailingly polite and
conscientious about doing a good job.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other Mexican day laborers I've hired over the
years, young and middle-aged men who work on weekends to supplement
what they make during the week doing whatever it takes to get by _
working at poultry farms, fixing fences, cutting brush. Some work
harder than others, but all of them are doing jobs nobody else
seems willing to do. Unemployment in these parts, after all is next
to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   These men and women are trying to support families either here
or back home. The dream, if their families still live south of the
Rio Grande, is to eventually move them to America. To a man, each
one when asked has told me they love living in East Texas. They pay
taxes on their income, on what they buy and indirectly on the homes
they rent.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not the American dream, the guiding principle upon
which this country was founded, then what is?
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor of The Lufkin Daily News. E-mail:
gborders at coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
