<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Friday, June 16, 2000 are moving today
to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIALS-KOREA _ The United States has a large stake in easing
of tensions in Korea. Now's the time for Washington to work a deal
with Pyongyng _ a freeze in missile development and exports in
exhange for relaxation of economic sanctions. (The Atlanta
Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Ever wonder why a
threshold is called that? Or where ``dead ringer,'' ``graveyard
shift'' or ``saved by the bell'' comes from? Nope? Me either. But
friends who e-mail me on a regular basis and have access to a wide
range of useless information have shared with me some little known
facts from 14th century England. (Ernest Murray is managing editor
of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Jaime is a carpenter from
Veracruz, working during the week as a framer for a local builder.
He's been here a year, and his wife and two children still live in
Mexico. Jaime lives with a roommate in a tiny frame home down a
pothole-pitted dirt driveway on the south side of town. He's going
back home in November to visit his family, which he's obviously
looking forward to. (Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ HOUSTON, Texas _ The rap from the Democrats
nationally _ particularly the camp of Vice President Al Gore _ is
that Texas Gov. George W. Bush may not have the gear to be
president. Americans will have a chance to decide for themselves
during the election campaign this fall. But at least Bush is smart
enough not to appear at the Republican state convention here this
weekend. (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Terrorism, harassment, anti-choice
policies. To exercise her right to a politically charged medical
option, a woman can run a gauntlet. Now, add bureaucrats to the
picket line? An important innovation is on the runway that can
de-acidify much anti-abortion vinegar in America and spoil some
in-your-face theatrics: early abortions without surgery. (John
Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED.
</P>
