<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, June 16,
2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   PANOS-SONS _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta's most successful restaurateur,
Pano Karatassos, is passing on his legacy to sons Pano Jr. _ sous
chef of the country's most renowned restaurant _ the French Laundry
in Napa _ and his other son who runs the front of the house at
Atlanta's hottest new restaurant, bluepointe. The sons have dreams
of one day opening their own restaurant together. A look at the
personalities behind the dynasty. (Kessler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET LIFESTYLE PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet LIFESTYLE page for the current week.
This layout is available today after 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET LIFESTYLES 0615 _ School's out for the summer and to help
children make the most of their vacation from the classroom, we
found some very cool toys to occupy them during the long, hot
summer. (Morrow, Atlanta-Journal Constitution) Art includes a
2-column color photo of a dinosaur toy, a 1-column color photo of a
Street Glide, a 2-column color photo of a Firefly lantern, a
2-column color photo of a Jam Cam, a 2-column color photo of a Tie
Dye Kit, a 2-column color photo of a Matchbox Car Wash.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE TOY SHOPPING LIST: Here is a list of Web sites to help
you shop for toys online. (Morrow, Atlanta-Journal Constitution)
Art includes a 6-pica color illustration of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER Q&AMP;A _ Columnist answers consumer-related questions.
(Greig, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   VOYEUR-TV _ It's a scary new world _ plain old reality TV is
giving way to dangerous reality TV _ and viewers are watching. Why
are shows like ``Survivor'' and ``The Real World'' so popular?
(Holloway, Austin American-Statesman).. 45. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   HITECH-ARTMUSEUM _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The Austin Museum of Art has
gone high-tech. Thanks to a partnership with Dell, the museum now
has an interactive web site, where it is featuring artwork from an
exhibit, Liberated Voices: Contemporary Art From South Africa, on
display at the museum from May 13 to Aug. 13. The web site has a
new educational tool, X-Ray Artvision, on the web site that
teachses the user about the painting and the artist by reading
caption boxes that appear as the mouse arrow moves around the image
of the artwork. The museum also now features a Dell learning lab,
offering access to the site and a way to correspond online with the
curator and artists. (Gee, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-NET _ The Internet is changing the way we listen to music,
but it's also affecting the way musicians and the recording
industry are marketing and selling their products. The ChangeMusic
Atlanta festival, in town this weekend, explores the possibilities
of new technology. We talk to CMJ founder Bobby Haber about the
changes afoot and profile a local band and manager who believe the
Internet is replacing the bar circuit as the launch pad of choice
for new artists. (SHarrison, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND _ Phil Kloer's weekly TV viewing guide for the
weekend. Sunday is Father's Day and the conventional TV wisdom is
that the medium's portrayal of dads is a classic case of reverse
evolution, from Ward Cleaver to Homer Simpson _ Father Knows Best
to Father Knows Squat. There's some truth in that but there's more.
Actually, TV's portrayal of fathers today is richly diverse, from
loving, anxiety-riddled Andy Sipowicz (Dennis Franz) on ``NYPD
Blue'' to struggling , deeply flawed Jake Manning (Jeffrey
Nordling(CQ)) on ``Once and Again.'' Ray Barone on ``Everybody
Loves Raymond'' is a weak but caring dad while Ken Titus on
``Titus'' is strong and uncaring. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BOYSGIRLS _ Review of ``Boys and Girls'', with Freddie
Prinze Jr. in another twentysomething epic. Grade: C. (StMurray,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-PARADISE _ Review of ``The Color Of Paradise.'' Iranian
film about blind boy. Grade: A. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-HONOR _ Review of ``Return with Honor.'' Good, solid
documentary about Vietnam and POWs. Grade: A. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 19.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-HONOR _ Review of ``Shaft,'' with Samuel L. Jackson in
the redo as the original John Shaft's nephew. ETA: Tuesday
afternoon. Grade: B-. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-TITAN _ Review of ``Titan A.E.,'' animated sci-fi. Grade:
C-. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 11.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-WOMEN _ Review of ``81/2 Women.'' Peter Greenaway's
really gone off his rocker. Grade: D. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-FANTASIA _ Review of the redone Fantasia. Some of the
animation can't live up to the standard of Toy Story 2. B-.
(Larsen, Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
