</P>
<P>
   COXNET LIFESTYLES 0615 _ School's out for the summer and to help
children make the most of their vacation from the classroom, we
found some very cool toys to occupy them during the long, hot
summer. (Morrow, Atlanta-Journal Constitution) Art includes a
2-column color photo of a dinosaur toy, a 1-column color photo of a
Street Glide, a 2-column color photo of a Firefly lantern, a
2-column color photo of a Jam Cam, a 2-column color photo ofhe way
we listen to music, but it's also affecting the way musicians and
the recording industry are marketing and selling their products.
The ChangeMusic Atlanta festival, in town this weekend, explores
the possibilities of new technology. We talk to CMJ founder Bobby
Haber about the changes afoot and profile a local band and manager
who believe the Internet is replacing the bar circuit as the launch
pad of choice for new artists. (SHarrison, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND _ Phil Kloer's weekly TV viewing guide for the
weekend. Sunday is Father's Day and the conventional TV wisdom is
that the medium's portrayal of dads is a classic case of reverse
evolution, from Ward Cleaver to Homer Simpson _ Father Knows Best
to Father Knows Squat. There's some truth in that but there's more.
Actually, TV's portrayal of fathers today is richly diverse, from
loving, anxiety-riddled Andy Sipowicz (Dennis Franz) on ``NYPD
Blue'' to struggling , deeply flawed Jake Manning (Jeffrey
Nordling(CQ)) on ``Once and Again.'' Ray Barone on ``Everybody
Loves Raymond'' is a weak but caring dad while Ken Titus on
``Titus'' is strong and uncaring. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
