<HEADER>
A4717 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0616-CO     06-15 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The show must go on without Gov. Bush
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON, Texas _ The rap from the Democrats nationally _
particularly the camp of Vice President Al Gore _ is that Texas
Gov. George W. Bush may not have the gear to be president.
</P>
<P>
   Americans will have a chance to decide for themselves during the
election campaign this fall. But at least Bush is smart enough not
to appear at the Republican state convention here this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The official reason is that Bush is expected to carry the state
so easily in November that it makes no sense for him to waste
valuable time at the convention. He and the party are much better
off if he's campaigning in swing states, where his presence might
make the difference between winning and losing some electoral
votes.
</P>
<P>
   That said, it's also not unreasonable to suggest that Bush's
camp views an appearance before the Republican Party of Texas a bit
like legendary University of Texas football coach Darrell Royal
used to view the forward pass: When you throw the football, three
things can happen, and two of them are bad.
</P>
<P>
   During the state Democratic convention last week, some speakers
had fun with Bush's planned absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you notice,'' asked Democratic state Sen. Gonzalo
Barrientos of Austin, ``how during the presidential primaries there
was not a right-wing leader or institution anywhere in the country
that Gov. Bush did not visit and address?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that he needs to move to the middle, what is the first
far-right group he has declined to visit and address? That's right
_ the Texas Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party of Texas represented at the state
convention in recent years has been significantly more influenced
by religious conservatives than is the Republican Party at large,
and certainly more than the state and national electorate.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty easy for Barrientos _ and Bush _ to remember that
the Texas Republicans at their convention four years ago chose to
deny their governor the honor of heading the Texas delegation to
the national convention in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they picked party chairman Tom Pauken. Neither
Barrientos nor Bush have forgotten that Pauken wouldn't have been
party chairman, or the delegation chairman in 1996, without the
significant help of the party's religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to remember that the same bunch that year almost
denied Texas U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison the ability to attend
that national convention as a delegate because of her failure to
endorse the absolutist anti-abortion view the religious
conservatives have written into the party's platform.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the fact that Bush was re-elected with almost 70
percent of the vote in 1998, it's easy for the Bushies to remember
that some of those absolutists still showed up at Republican
precinct conventions this year and worked their way to the state
convention.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in the game, Bush has lots of national media types
trailing him around _ though the crowd has thinned out a little,
for now, since the hot battle with John McCain in the primaries
ended early in March.
</P>
<P>
   Does it make sense now, when Bush is trying to appeal to a broad
national electorate, to go to an event where at least reporters
might ask him nasty questions such as why he thinks the platform
plank on abortion in his home state's Republican Party should
remain unchanged, even though he doesn't agree with it?
</P>
<P>
   Might he worry about being asked whether it made sense last year
to insist on a $1 billion property tax cut that few felt because of
rising property values rather than spend the money on education?
</P>
<P>
   Does Bush worry how he'd explain why he now says it was a good
thing to expand the number of Texas kids covered under the
Children's Health Insurance Program, when he wanted fewer kids
covered back when the Legislature was considering the issue?
</P>
<P>
   Bush probably would be warmly cheered at the convention. His
wife, Laura, is scheduled to appear, and she'll probably be warmly
cheered. It might have been completely harmless for Bush to go to
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But if you were George W. Bush, and you wanted to be president,
would you?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
