<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4718 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0616-COX     06-15 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed restrictions on legal abortion pill make no sense
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Terrorism, harassment, anti-choice policies. To
exercise her right to a politically charged medical option, a woman
can run a gauntlet.
</P>
<P>
   Now, add bureaucrats to the picket line?
</P>
<P>
   An important innovation is on the runway that can de-acidify
much anti-abortion vinegar in America and spoil some in-your-face
theatrics: early abortions without surgery.
</P>
<P>
   RU 486 _ mifepristone _ has worked safely for more than 500,000
European women in the first seven weeks of pregnancy. (Key point:
The drug has not increased the number of abortions in its home base
of France, only the percentage done without surgery, and early.)
</P>
<P>
   In February the Food and Drug Administration notified Danco
Laboratories, which plans to market the pill here, that final
approval was near.
</P>
<P>
   However, reports indicate the possibility of self-defeating FDA
conditions. Most troubling would be to allow only doctors certified
in surgical abortion to prescribe the abortion pill. Providers also
would be placed on a national registry.
</P>
<P>
   This would destroy one of the benefits of RU486, which is to
make it impossible for packs of proselytizers to know where
abortion happens.
</P>
<P>
   The only apparent medical reason for the FDA's proposed
regulation is that if the pill fails to work, surgical abortion
would be necessary and entrusted to the physician who prescribed
the drug. But that's a contingency for which a patient can be
referred.
</P>
<P>
   If this pill is safe as France has demonstrated and as the FDA
is set to pronounce, then any physician should be able to prescribe
it. And there is no more need for a registry of such providers than
there is for those who prescribe birth-control pills.
</P>
<P>
   SHORTAGE OF PROVIDERS
</P>
<P>
   The FDA requirement effectively would mean no availibility in
regions that have few or no abortion providers. That problem
continues to get more pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Alan Guttmacher Institute, between 1992 and
1996 the number of abortion providers fell 14 percent, to 2,042
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-six percent of American counties had no known abortion
provider at that point. One third of all women of reproductive age
live in these counties.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE IS THE TRAINING?
</P>
<P>
   Harassment, physical violence and threats aren't the only
factors contributing to the shortage of these physicians. Another
factor is that fewer and fewer medical schools are teaching the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of medical schools that train in obstetrics and
gynecology, only 12 percent routinely train in abortion techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Considering how common it is for obstetricians to have to
perform medically necessary abortions, this is a serious deficiency
for which those who teach medicine need to answer.
</P>
<P>
   The 5,000-member Medical Students for Choice has formed to
confront this, as well as the tendency for reproductive health to
get a short shrift from medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Anderson, executive director of the group, is critical
of the proposed FDA restrictions on who could prescribe RU 486.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense among physicians of, `I'd be willing to do
medical (non-surgical) abortion even if I don't do surgical
abortion,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under this proposal, that would be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is a friend of reproductive rights in
every way _ with the president having supplied the slogan that
speaks for most Americans: ``Early, safe and rare.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``rare'' we make possible by assuring that contraception and
sex education are fundamental.
</P>
<P>
   The administration must not let someone's bureucratic zest
undermine this non-surgical means by which ``early'' and ``safe''
become fundamental as well _ more choice, fewer women running
someone's gauntlet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
