<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CASUAL-DRESS (Albany, N.Y.) _ A nationwide campaign aimed at
reversing the trend of casual dress in the workplace has been
launched by a clothier who is spearheading ``Dress-up Thursdays,''
an initiative that he and others hope will bring a sense of
traditionalism back to the business workplace and sales back to the
tailored clothing industry. By DANIELLE T. FURFARO.
</P>
<P>
   DIABETICS-DEPRESSION (San Antonio) _ When a diabetic is
depressed, it may not be just a case of the blues. Now research
released by the American Diabetes Association indicates that
diabetics experience decreased depression and improved blood sugar
levels after only eight weeks of treatment with the popular
anti-depressant fluoxetine, or Prozac. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   OBESITY-HORMONE (San Antonio) _ Scientists caused a stir five
years ago when they announced they could cause fat mice to lose
weight by giving them leptin, a weight-regulating hormone secreted
by fat cells. But producing the same results in humans has proven
infinitely more complex. Obese people, it turns out, have lots of
leptin circulating in their systems, but somehow have lost the
ability to respond to it. By CINDY TUMIEL.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-DIVIDE (Undated) _ The Digital Divide will shrink
significantly in coming years, but ethnic minorities and
economically disadvantaged members of society will continue having
trouble jumping on the Internet bandwagon, according to the latest
analysis of the much-hyped ``divide,'' which refers to the gap
between those connected to the Internet and those who are not. By
ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPING-GEAR (Albany, N.Y.) _ The newest generation of
camping/hiking gear might not be cheaper, but it's definitely
lighter, stronger, and better than that of past decades, or even
just a few years ago. When you're really using the stuff outside,
it needs to be functional more than fashionable. Here are things to
keep in mind. By RICK KARLIN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBI-SHARPSHOOTER (San Francisco) _ An FBI sharpshooter acted
reasonably and can't be prosecuted for killing the wife of white
separatist Randy Weaver while firing at a fleeing friend in Ruby
Ridge, Idaho, a federal appeals court says _ a ruling that a
dissenter likened to a James Bond-style license to kill. By BOB
EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-BLACK (Houston) _ Lewis Black may be one of the funniest
people on the planet, but the comedian also is one of the angriest.
Spotting laggards, injustice or incongruity sets Black into
poisonous motion, with a rage reminiscent of Lenny Bruce, Richard
Pryor and George Carlin. Stand back and beware the spew _
especially if it's about politics. By MIKE McDANIEL.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-TRACY-BYRD (San Antonio) _ If the easy-going smile that
the good-natured Tracy Byrd wears during his performances seems
broader than usual, consider this: RCA allowed the country
traditionalist more creative control than ever before on his
seventh album, ``It's About Time,'' and the album was greeted by
more critical acclaim than any of his previous efforts. By JOHN
GOODSPEED.
</P>
<P>
   ELLEN-DeGENERES (Houston) _ Ellen DeGeneres is back, and she's
taking the route that made her a star _ stand-up. Her eight-week,
35-city bus tour (yes, bus tour) will eventually take her to New
York, where her show will be taped for a July 23 HBO special. She's
playing it straight, so to speak. The show is not about her being a
lesbian. It's not a forum for civil rights. It's about funny. By
MIKE McDANIEL.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEWS (Undated) _ Reviews of these movies now out on
video: ``The Green Mile'' with Tom Hanks and Robin Williams'
``Bicentennial Man.'' By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRENDY-BEANS (Undated) _ Beans not exciting? Well, perhaps
interesting, delicious, affordable, versatile and easy to prepare
are better words to describe beans. Dress them up, coax them into
bolder roles, find a better cast of supporting characters and you
might just stage an unexpected hit. By BONNIE WALKER.
</P>
