   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-MONTGOMERIE (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ Colin Montgomerie
always seems to come into the U.S. Open as one of the favorites. He
has yet to walk away with a win. Montgomerie, 36, is a star, and a
very rich man, thanks to the European Tour, where he has won twice
in nine tries this year. But he joins a list of the game's biggest
names _ including David Duval, Phil Mickelson and Jesper Parnevik _
who have never won a major. By MICHELLE SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-BORICH (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ Mike Borich, head pro
at Utah's Meadow Brook Golf Course, is flattered that his autograph
is in demand here at the U.S. Open. And then there's the question,
``What's your name?'' By SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-SANCHEZ (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ Javier Sanchez still
doesn't seem real. Even after a 20-minute conversation, I consider
him a work of fiction, a character invented by the USGA to prove
that golf really and truly can belong to anyone. Sanchez sneaked
across the Mexican border 24 years ago, because he believed that
washing dishes in a Bay Area restaurant could be the start of
something big. Today, he is teeing off in his fifth U.S. Open, at
one of the most opulent resorts in the world. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
