<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DEADLOCKED-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY THING `DEADLOCKED' IS THE LOGIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on or after June 18 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to June 18.) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since any disciplined explanation would kill this thing right
off the bat, ``Deadlocked'' dispenses with the dramaturgy. As the
film opens, a young African-American (Jo D. Jonz) is found guilty
of raping and murdering a high-society white woman, and his father
(Charles S. Dutton) takes the jury hostage, insisting the
prosecuting attorney (David Caruso) find exculpatory evidence in 24
hours, or there'll be a body count.
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course, given that the defendant hasn't spoken a word
to anyone since his arrest, your first move as someone charged with
freeing a convicted killer would be to get his story. But of
course, that would be too easy. So ``Deadlocked'' lopes through its
motions in the usual fashion _ dramatically charged but logically
leaden, with gratuitously seamy flashbacks _ before its
all-too-predictable finale. And both Dutton's and Caruso's
characters get time to bond meaningfully, schematically and
allegedly touchingly with their sons before the final reel's
pyrotechnics.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton imbues his character with far more conviction than you
might imagine (he seems to honestly believe that the film really
is, as it somewhat cavalierly posits, about how the wealthy can buy
justice and the poor can't buy anything but misery). Caruso isn't
bad, but carries a certain actorlike swagger in his performance.
``Deadlocked'' moves serviceably, but it should come with a caveat:
No thinking allowed. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The show: ``Deadlocked.'' &QL; 
What: Courtroom thriller in which a father kidnaps the jury that
convicted his son of murder. &QL; 
The stars: David Caruso, Charles S. Dutton, Jo D. Jonz. &QL; 
Where: TNT. &QL; 
When: 8, 10 and midnight tonight; also Monday, Tuesday, Saturday
and June 25. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
