<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4744 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-TIE-SIDEBAR-LADN &LR;      06-15 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIE-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN GIVING TIES, DON'T FORGET THE BOW
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after June 18 by by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: goes with men's tie feature) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We don't normally refer to bow-tie wearers as wild men, but
among tie guys, that's what they are. Nobody will blink if you wear
one to a formal occasion with a tuxedo. But strap on a bow tie
during daylight hours and you're pretty much guaranteed to have
people think you're an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 100 million to 200 million ties sold in the United States
each year, approximately 3 to 5 percent are bow ties, according to
market research conducted by Beau Ties Ltd. of Vermont, a
specialist in bow ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who wear them are generally a little more on the
individualistic side, a step or two out of the mainstream,'' says
Gerald Andersen, executive director of the Neckwear Association of
America. ``A major inhibiting factor to their sale is that most men
don't know how to tie them.''
</P>
<P>
   The bow tie seems to be most popular with university professors,
lawyers and judges. Pediatricians sometimes favor bow ties since a
young patient can't grab them by the tie if it's way up there on
the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts insist that even though the bow tie is smaller than
a typical four-in-hand, it can be made to look quite decorative.
Beau Ties Ltd. sells 150 different styles of bow ties, more than
you'll find in any menswear store in existence, says company
president Bill Kenerson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're dedicated to wearing them, you'll find your own
source,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Kenerson's grandfather was an avid bow-tie wearer. When the
younger Kenerson got a job on an assembly line, he tried one of his
grandfather's relics for safety. He's been wearing them ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I got razzed for wearing a bow tie _ and that was
enough for me to continue wearing them,'' Kenerson said. ``I don't
even have a four-in-hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the more celebrated bow-tie wearers: President Harry
Truman, Winston Churchill, Orville Redenbacher and Louis
Farrakhan. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1223EDT &QL; 
