<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-MEN'S-TIES-FEATURE-LA     06-15 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN'S-TIES-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS `NO NOOSE' GOOD NEWS?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after Sun., June 18, 2000 by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can bet neckwear manufacturers everywhere breathed a
collective sigh of relief when some wardrobe consultant decided
Regis Philbin didn't need to go for the casual look in his hosting
duties for the phenomenally successful ABC show ``Who Wants to be a
Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   No sweaters or priest collars for Reege. Instead, his choice of
wardrobe practically guaranteed that children everywhere would have
a new spin on the traditional Father's Day gift option at their
fingertips. Pardon me, Mr. Department Store menswear specialist, I
want the ``Regis Look'' for my dad.
</P>
<P>
   Right this way, young sir or miss. You'll need a colored shirt,
and, of course, a matching single-toned satin ...
</P>
<P>
   Necktie.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the tie, aka the cravat, ascot, foulard _ known
colloquially as a noose or arrow. Once a mark of military
distinction and forever the bane of casual dressers and young
children (``Aw, do I !ital!have to wear one?''). The centuries-old
device, always more decorative than practical, has seen its
popularity wane with the rise of business casual attire and young
entrepreneurs who won't work for a company that forces them to
cinch themselves on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   But as unpopular as ties might seem, they never go away. In
fact, manufacturers say despite the business casual trend, the tie
remains a popular item.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Blame shifting fashion trends. And these days, blame Regis
(whose neckwear, by the way, is manufactured by Philips-Van Heusen
and sold at Macy's).
</P>
<P>
   ``Regis has had an effect. He has made people think about
neckties as a way of dressing up,'' says Stuart Nifoussi, publisher
of Men's Retailer (MR) magazine. ``What we're seeing is necktie
sales have been stagnant. Now they're starting to move up again.
People are investing in better neckwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, it's probably more appropriate than ever to buy
your father a tie, since they probably won't get as many as the
year before,'' Nifoussi added. ``The average casual man's tie
wardrobe is probably getting pretty old.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you're looking for a useful Father's Day gift, go
with a razor or something for the tool box. Long gone are the days
when the necktie, regardless of its material, served any function.
We don't use them as neck-warming devices anymore, and, despite the
popularity of ``ham and eggs'' models in the 1940s _ that
supposedly guaranteed spills wouldn't be noticed _ there are
certainly more effective napkins than a $150 Hermes purchased in
Beverly Hills. Besides, most men simply don't like to wear ties,
finding them uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   So why a tie? Who invented it, and for what reason? There are
about as many theories as there are knots, and many seem to
contradict each other. If, as psychologists claim, the male species
is more inclined to blend in than stand out, why on earth would he
stick a vertical line down the center of his chest with the tip
pointing arrowlike to the genitals?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because as decoration goes, the tie is the man's only
option. Women have jewelry, various types of head gear and scarves;
men have ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only wardrobe accessory men have,'' says Gerald
Andersen, executive director of the Neckwear Association of America
in New York. ``It's what makes that blue or gray shirt look
different from the last time you wore it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is its front-and-center placement accidental, says Andersen.
Long before they started fussing with Windsor knots or ruffles, men
looked for ways to draw attention to their chests. The tie is just
a logical extension of ceremonial beads, tattoos, war paint and
scars. Apes scare each other off by pounding their chests; human
beings break out a showier power tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tie is a showcase window, drawing the eye to that area,''
says Anderson ``and it has always been fraught with masculine
symbolism.''
</P>
<P>
   But why make such a symbol so blasted uncomfortable, wonders
Christopher Morganstern, curator of the Judith Tamkin Fashion
Center at Woodbury University in Burbank. Why not a badge, or
something that doesn't have the power to strangle you?
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you very subservient and vulnerable,'' said
Morganstern, whose collection at Woodbury includes more than 1,000
pieces of vintage clothing, including several boxes full of ties.
``If somebody grabbed you by the tie, they could literally strangle
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Morganstern compares the tie to the woman's high-heeled shoe, an
item that wouldn't save any woman in the event of an attack. The
tie, instead of being an item of power, is a self-regulating
device.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called civilization,'' Morganstern says. ``Civilization
is all about restricting those impulses. It's the same reason we
don't carry swords and guns to restaurants and start cutting each
other up. The civilizing impulses strip men of the possibility of
being violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Tie lore has it that the first male neckwear to serve as a means
of identification occurred in the early part of the 17th century,
when Louis IV of France adopted the decorative silk scarves worn by
Croatian mercenaries. The term ``cravat'' supposedly derived from
the French word for ``Croat.'' By the time of the French Revolution
a century and a half later, neckwear had taken on a political
significance as Republicans wore large colored neckcloths _
fittingly called ``incroyables'' _ to proclaim their allegiance. It
eventually made its way to England, enjoying great popularity in
the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The tie as we know it evolved in the 1920s, known as a
``four-in-hand'' because the knot approximates the knotted reins
used by a coach driver to control a team of horses. American tie
manufacturer Jesse Langsdorf patented the all-weather, wrinkle-free
tie. Langsdorf cut against the thread to achieve the maximum
stretch effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The research I did shows that neckties for business were worn
during the industrial revolution when managers wanted to set
themselves apart from their workers, give themselves a little more
authority,'' says Sherry Maysonave, author of ``Casual Power: How
to Power Up Your Nonverbal Communication and Dress Down for
Success.'' ``It's a vertical shape, that adds that touch of power
to the man, and allows him to have some color.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 20th century, the tie has seen its appearance
widen, shrink and widen again, often to coincide with the shifting
sizes of coat lapels and shirt collars. We've gone from the 5-inch
``belly warmers'' of the 1940s to the skinny slim-Jims of the
1950s, from the '80s power tie to the limited-edition Nicole Miller
designs and the constant knock-offs.
</P>
<P>
   As designers continue to demonstrate, you can put absolutely any
motif on a tie _ your school colors or military regiment to a
repeated pattern that associates you with a specific club or
organization. Feeling more whimsical? How about dental X-rays,
Betty Boop, the logo of your favorite sports team or a single big
old ugly trout? In the 1940s, surrealist Salvador Dali put his
melting clocks on a line of ties. Forty years later, Grateful Dead
frontman Jerry Garcia got into the act, creating colorful
art-inspired ties. During the 1992 presidential race, candidates
Bill Clinton and Al Gore donned Garcia ties on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Think you know what will be hot next? Get out there and slap it
together. You might be surprised at what catches on with the
clothes-buying public.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had that big explosion of floral ties in the late '80s
and early '90s, that's one I wouldn't have predicted,'' said
Michael Jacobs, president of Jacobs &AMP; Roberts tie manufacturers in
Los Angeles. ``Even now, that solid satin that Regis Philbin is
wearing, that also would have been difficult to predict.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
