<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYBOY-JAZZ-RAWLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL RAWLS, HOT JAZZ
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on or after Sun., June 18 by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `today' refers to Sun., June 18, 2000.) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long known as the personification of cool, velvety crooner Lou
Rawls can make a love song simmer with barely restrained passion.
</P>
<P>
   Rawls says his sauve style evolved naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened to Nat Cole, Billy Eckstine and, of course,
Sinatra. I think the primary thing about them that was so
attractive was you always understood what they were singing, their
diction. That influenced me. I've heard a lot of records and I
don't always know what they're actually singing.''
</P>
<P>
   None other than Sinatra once said Rawls has the ``classiest
singing and silkiest chops in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Born on Chicago's South Side, Rawls began singing in his church
choir at the age of 7. Inspired by doo-wop, gospel, jazz, blues and
r&AMP;b, the singer moved to Los Angeles where he signed with Capitol
and issued 20 records in the '60s alone.
</P>
<P>
   Famous for such soulful pop-r&AMP;b smashes as ``You'll Never Find
Another Love Like Mine,'' ``Love is a Hurtin' Thing,'' ``Dead End
Street,'' ``Your Good Thing (Is About to End)'' and ``A Natural
Man,'' Rawls brings a sophisticated and jazzy delivery to soul
music.
</P>
<P>
   Rawls, 64, headlines the second day of the 22nd annual Playboy
Jazz Festival today at the Hollywood Bowl. With a career that spans
four decades, numerous gold and platinum records and 13 Grammy
nominations, those in the stands will no doubt be excited to hear
Rawls and his five-piece band perform many of the hits that made
him famous.
</P>
<P>
   He is proud of his choice of stellar session musicians who often
back him on his albums. Session greats such as r&AMP;b guitarist
Cornell Dupree and saxophonists Stanley Turrentine and David
``Fathead'' Newman have helped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look for players that really feel the music,'' Rawls said.
``People that aren't just playing notes on paper. See, a lot of
musicians just play the music but don't give anything to it. People
like Dupree, the written notes are just a guide, but they put
themselves and their own feeling into it.''
</P>
<P>
   For his Playboy set, he could've chosen to use a full orchestra,
but he's aiming for a more intimate experience by fronting a
quintet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the intimacy comes in,'' he said. ``An orchestra
wouldn't give me the feeling I'm after.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill also features Celia Cruz, Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra
with Wynton Marsalis, Ruben Blades &AMP; Editus, Elvin Jones Jazz
Machine, Bela Fleck &AMP; the Flecktones, the Cos of Good Music V,
Norman Brown and the David Sanchez Sextet.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, for those who will miss the festival, jazz radio
KLON-FM (88.1) will broadcast the entire event on July 3 and 4. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
Who: ``Playboy Jazz Festival 2000.'' &QL; 
Starring: Lou Rawls, Celia Cruz, Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra with
Wynton Marsalis, Ruben Blades &AMP; Editus, Elvin Jones Jazz Machine,
Bela Fleck &AMP; the Flecktones, the Cos of Good Music V, Norman Brown,
David Sanchez Sextet, Bonesoir and the Spotlight Awards Alumni Jazz
Band.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Hollywood Bowl, 2301 N. Highland Ave., Hollywood. &QL; 
When: 2 p.m. today. &QL; 
Tickets: $25 and $35. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
