<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4763 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-OBESITY-HORMONE-HNS &LR;      06-15 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBESITY-HORMONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCHERS TRY TO UNRAVEL OBESITY HOMONE MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Scientists caused a stir five years ago when they
announced they could cause fat mice to lose weight by giving them
leptin, a weight-regulating hormone secreted by fat cells.
</P>
<P>
   But producing the same results in humans has proven infinitely
more complex. Obese people, it turns out, have lots of leptin
circulating in their systems, but somehow have lost the ability to
respond to it.
</P>
<P>
   Unraveling the leptin mystery is a key target of diabetes
researchers. Obesity is strongly linked to Type 2 diabetes, a
serious disease affecting some 15 million Americans that is
characterized by the body's inability to use blood sugar.
Untreated, diabetes can cause deteriorating eyesight, kidney
failure, heart disease and death.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians and researchers attending the American Diabetes
Association's 60th Annual Meeting and Scientific Sessions in San
Antonio this week got an update on the state of leptin research,
including the puzzle of leptin resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of leptin-related studies have been done in the past
five years. While progress is being made, scientists also cautioned
that they are a long way from understanding the complex interaction
between fat cells, leptin, the brain and appetite.
</P>
<P>
   But working with laboratory animals, researchers at the Harvard
University School of Medicine say they have identified two
potential brain pathways that influence leptin resistance. They
found sites within the hypothalamus, an area deep inside the brain
that contains the body's appetite control center, where leptin
causes different reactions in thin mice than in fat ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we know the identity of some of the potential sites of the
problem,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Flier, and endocrinologist and
professor of medicine at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   But other sites also likely exist, he said, and identifying each
will fill in just one piece of the complex chain of chemical
reactions taking place when people eat food or expend energy.
</P>
<P>
   Leptin, dubbed the ``anti-obesity hormone,'' is a protein fat
cells secrete that is supposed to tell the brain it's time to stop
eating. The brain, in turn, sends out messages to the body,
controlling everything from fat storage to the attractiveness of
food to hunger pangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be the problem of getting leptin to the area of the
brain where it needs to be,'' Flier said. ``There can also be a
defect in the ability of the brain to activate the correct signal
pathway for talking with the cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we know some of the potential sites of the problem in the
hypothalamus.''
</P>
<P>
   The studies have involved only animal brains, which may be
vastly different from humans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to treat human obesity with leptin have been
disappointing. But once scientists understand this relay system
between leptin and the brain, other ways of treating obesity could
be possible, Flier said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists may be able to manipulate the leptin reaction in the
brain, or target some of the downstream systems it influences
through the brain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the hope,'' he said. ``But all these hopes don't
always turn into drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Cindy Tumiel by e-mail at ctumiel(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4766 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-INTERNET-TRAVEL-HNS &LR;      06-15 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TRAVEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ON-LINE INFORMATION FOR VACATIONERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was impressed to read recently that travel has been proclaimed
the No.
</P>
<P>
   1 ``legitimate'' source of on-line commerce.
</P>
<P>
   And not so impressed to find that it still lags behind
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   But today's focus isn't on Web sites that sell (at least not as
a reason for being); it's about new and updated enterprises that
can help in planning our summer vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some Web sites that are worth exploring:
</P>
<P>
   At www.medicineplanet.com, visitors can obtain free
health-related information pertaining to countries throughout the
world. Searches can be made by destination or for specific
diseases, risks or immunizations.
</P>
<P>
   Separate content areas focus on issues affecting women,
children, seniors and adventure travelers. Another segment features
travel-related articles authored by leading physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Browsers who register as a member (at no charge) can create a
health profile and receive information targeted to individual
needs. Members also can submit questions and participate in chat
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   An on-line health store (no surprise there) is included.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control continues to expand its site at
www.
</P>
<P>
   cdc.gov/travel. It, too, offers specific information for
travelers with children, for pregnant travelers and for travelers
with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccination recommendations are provided, as are tips on how to
avoid illness from food or water.
</P>
<P>
   This is the place to look for sanitation reports on individual
cruise ships. I was disappointed at first glance to note that the
most recent listing was for November 1999, but by clicking on
``Search database of inspection scores for all cruise ships,'' I
accessed up-to-date inspection scores.
</P>
<P>
   A new site, www.officialtravelinfo.com, eases the process of
searching for destination information.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the International Association of Convention and
Visitor Bureaus, this venture links the official tourism sites of
more than 900 tourism agencies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are links for weather information, local newspaper
reports, passport and visa information, U.S. State Department
travel warnings and public announcements, currency conversion,
world time zone specifics and maps and driving directions.
</P>
<P>
   Not new but recommended, too, as a good source for pinpointing
tourism bureau sites is www.towd.com (tourism offices worldwide
directory).
</P>
<P>
   Search by U.S. states or foreign destinations.
</P>
<P>
   To order free brochures, access www.wwb.com (another
long-standing site) where more than 15,000 travel guides, maps and
brochures are available.
</P>
<P>
   Just fill out the form as instructed, and the literature you
request will be sent by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Designed for families that travel internationally,
www.travelforkids.com offers suggestions for ``fun things for you
and your kids to do'' in eight European countries, four South
American nations, five Asian destinations, Mexico, Costa Rica,
Cuba, British Columbia, Australia and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   The site, launched by Globetracks, is stronger in some areas
than others. I didn't learn much about the Yucatn Peninsula _ the
only region of Mexico covered for now _ that isn't available in
guidebooks and newspaper articles. But the section on France caught
my fancy.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers who visit Notre Dame, the site points to ``a
charming little play area on the south side of the church, with a
great sand toy and park benches. Any exhausted parent can sit
peacefully to watch the boats on the Seine while the kids play
under the shadow of this great cathedral.''
</P>
<P>
   Another useful feature is a directory of English-speaking
pediatric doctors, dentists and orthodontists aboard. For now, this
segment covers 16 nations.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers with disabilities and mature travelers are the focus
of www.access-able.com.
</P>
<P>
   Included are recommendations on travel agencies that specialize
in working with those who have special needs, a list of accessible
cruise ships and cabins, tour recommendations, suggested
literature, articles submitted by travelers with disabilities, TTY
and voice telephone contacts and other information.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the quest is heli-hiking in Canada's Purcell Mountains
or self-guided cycling in France's Provence, adventure travelers
have found a new on line home at www.adventureseek.com.
</P>
<P>
   Listings are provided for adventure-oriented trips worldwide.
Other prominent features include safety information and forums to
share experiences. Trips and gear can be purchased here, too.
</P>
<P>
   As experienced browsers know, literally thousands more sites
cater to travelers _ and many provide important trip-planning
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Here are just a few at the top of my list: www.travelocity.com,
www.expedia.com and www.previewtravel.com (for a wide range of
general information); www.digitalcity.com and www.citysearch.com
(for information about specific cities); www.nps.gov (for links to
National Parks sites); www.cruising.org (for links to most but not
all major cruise lines); www.travel.state.gov (for U.S. State
Department travel warnings, public announcements and Consular
Information Sheets and also for passport and visa information);
www.customs.gov/travel/travel.htm (for U.S. Customs Service ``know
before you go'' information); www.astanet.com (to find a travel
agency in your area); www.mapquest.com; www.weather.com and
www.accu-weather.com; and www.xe.net/currency (for currency
conversions).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
