<HEADER>
A4767 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-LEWIS-BLACK-HNS &LR;      06-15 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-BLACK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANGRY EDGE MARKS LEWIS BLACK'S COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MIKE McDANIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Lewis Black may be one of the funniest people on the
planet. He certainly is one of the angriest.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting laggards, phonies, injustice or incongruity sets Black
into poisonous motion, with a rage reminiscent of Lenny Bruce,
Richard Pryor and George Carlin.
</P>
<P>
   Stand back and beware the spew.
</P>
<P>
   Especially if it's about politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes me mad about George W. Bush is the fact that
Republicans seem to like him because he reminds them of George
Bush,'' says Black, on the phone from Chicago. ``If they're so
enamored with George Bush, get him. Compared to George W. and Al
Gore, he's Winston Churchill. How sad is that? ``I've said time and
again I'd take a dead Hubert Humphrey over these guys. When people
want to talk to the president, you send them to the grave site and
let them deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Black took time off from his gig as political commentator on
Comedy Central's The Daily Show With Jon Stewart to play the Laff
Stop in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Better bring him Valium.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Black says he's in control of that black edge that
earmarks his comedy. In other words, don't worry about him stroking
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I'm in those modes. Where I go, `I'm taking this a
little too seriously.' I'm in pretty much control of it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hold the Valium.
</P>
<P>
   But bring Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   Black on Elian Gonzales and U.S.-Cuba relations: ``That makes me
livid. Fidel Castro has driven every president psychotic. Why
didn't they just give him a baseball team? How tough was that? If
they had asked him to join the National League, there would be no
problems. And I mean that.''
</P>
<P>
   On polls: ``I don't believe them. A sample of 1,675 people can
tell you everything that's going on in this country? That's
patently absurd.
</P>
<P>
   It's insane.''
</P>
<P>
   On Bosnia: ``I don't understand how a Slovak and a Croat and a
Muslim can tell each other apart. Does one group wear suspenders?
Does one group have teeth on the top and another teeth on the
bottom?''
</P>
<P>
   Black may be familiar to Houston audiences for his work as
playwright.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not. He's collaborated on some 40 plays, including The
Czar of Rock &AMP; Roll, which played the Alley in 1990. Chronicle
theater critic Everett Evans labeled the show ``scattershot
satire.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Black says he's still writing plays, but his experience
here ``really drove me into becoming a full-time comic. It's not
just the Alley. The regional theater experience, which is terrific
for reaching people, can be brutal if you're a writer. I don't
think there's a play I've produced, except for maybe a couple of
times, where I didn't have to give back part of my salary to get
what I wanted in terms of either set or acting.''
</P>
<P>
   So there were some lean times?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, till about last Thursday,'' he says. ``I was stone
broke because I refused to do anything except what I wanted to do
for a living. I ran a club (a theater-bar) in New York City for
eight years and was earning about 500 bucks a week, which in New
York City .... I mean, I had a bank account, but I never had
anything in it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he ``found'' stand-up, ``I started going on the road; I
started making a living.''
</P>
<P>
   That living includes some acting stints, too, including roles as
the sports announcer on Showtime's Hoop Life, Bernie on The Days
and Nights of Molly Dodd and bit roles on Homicide, Mad About You
and in such movies as Hannah and Her Sisters and Jacob's Ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Today he's more high-profile than ever, thanks to his The Daily
Show appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's meant a career,'' he says of the Comedy Central gig. ``I
had a career, but it gave me access to a wider audience. I was
wandering wondering around this country like some Willy Loman.''
</P>
<P>
   Black, 51, says his early comedic influences were Jonathan
Winters, Bob Newhart and Shelley Berman. He also recognizes in
himself a bit of Lily Tomlin, Bruce, Pryor and Carlin.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin is on record as saying Black is one of the few comedians
whose work he consistently enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant a lot to me (to hear about that), and it meant a lot
more to my mother, who was ecstatic over this,'' Black says. ``And
he left me a very nice message on my phone machine, and this was
very early on in The Daily Show, before I'd gotten any recognition.
I thought, `Wow.' I felt like I was doing something right, because
he's someone who really had an effect on me. He's somebody I look
up to.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, people looking for humor are looking up to Black.
He's got so much support now that should a heckler create grief,
``It's like if you tell the audience, `Kill,' they would go, `OK,
we'll get him for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Heady times. Gigs galore. Money in the bank. Sometimes it pays
to be angry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
