<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4768 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-ELLEN-DEGENERES-HNS &LR;      06-15 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLEN-DEGENERES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     ELLEN DeGENERES HITS THE ROAD WITH COMEDY TOUR  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MIKE McDANIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ This is the nature of the TV beast. One day you're on
top of the world, making history, pulling in big numbers. Next day,
you're meat. A star with no fire, no future. In danger of slipping
into the black hole of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Afraid to come out. Then coming out. Then hit in the face with a
banana creme pie. Pink-slipped. Rejected. Dismissed. Fired.
Unwanted.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, this was Ellen DeGeneres. Declaring herself gay
in national magazines as well as on her ABC sitcom, ``Ellen,'' she
encountered/embraced/endured a period of celebrity that was too
white-hot to maintain. And when her show began to take on a
preachy, gay-centric and often unfunny tone, even her biggest
admirers came out against her. She was out in April 1997, off the
air by May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She never quite left our consciousness _ there were a couple of
movies she made before the sitcom died, and girlfriend Anne Heche
cast her recently in HBO's If These Walls Could Talk II. She and
Heche would show up at celebrity events together.
</P>
<P>
   But DeGeneres wasn't working, and that was not acceptable to
someone with workaholic tendencies. It drove her back into a
closet. Maybe not the one dealing with sexuality, but one that had
some of its elements.
</P>
<P>
   She felt confused, undesired, paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some people's minds, it may seem like I didn't disappear,
but those movies (EdTV, Goodbye Lover) were done before my show was
canceled, except for The Love Letter, which was immediately
after,'' the 42-year-old comedian said. ``But it's been three years
since I've done anything except for the HBO piece, and the only
reason that happened was because Anne wrote and directed it for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she's back, and she's taking the route that made her a star
_ stand-up. Her eight-week, 35-city bus tour (yes, bus tour)
stopped in Houston and eventually she'll wend her way to New York,
where her show will be taped for a July 23 HBO special.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, she's playing it straight, so to speak. The show
is not about her being a lesbian. It's not a forum for civil
rights. It's about funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want this to be a big show about me being gay,'' she
said. ``I wanted to blend everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a big gaping hole if I didn't address at all my
life for the last three years. So I do talk about it in the
beginning, just to get it out of the way, but I do it in a funny
way. I don't really talk about so much as show you _ and that's all
I'll say.''
</P>
<P>
   She's proud she came out, she says, but the rejection she
suffered when her show got axed tapped into feelings of
worthlessness and rejection gay people fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``During that time, yeah, I was wounded, I was like an open
sore.
</P>
<P>
   Anything affected me. Anything. There was a period of time I
couldn't turn on TV without being a sketch on Saturday Night Live
or the butt of a joke in a monologue. Whatever. It just got to be
too much. That was my first glimpse of, wow, this is such a
negative world, and it's every arena: it's television, it's press,
it's just people talking, it's sitcoms. You don't notice it until
you are the recipient of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started seeing that everybody is making fun of somebody
else. There's a joke at someone else's expense. Or it's a cynical
sense of humor or critical and I thought, `That's not what I've
ever done. My comedy has been nice, and it's always been gentle and
lots of silence and pauses, and I need to bring that out to the
world. That's missing right now.'
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I'm a comedian. One of the reasons for the tour
is I wanted to refocus everyone on what I do. Yes, I'm gay, and
everybody knows that. Now let's get beyond that and remember how I
got here in the first place. I was a comedian; people did like me;
and if I left some audience members along the way, that's more
about them than it is about me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to remind people about who I am as an artist,
that I'm funny and love giving people joy. I became a
representation of someone who's gay and kind of became a symbol
instead of an artist, and now I hope I'm a representation of
survival.''
</P>
<P>
   The critical buzz of those who've seen her on this ``comeback
tour'' has been good and strong, just the affirmation DeGeneres
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was a risk,'' DeGeneres said of her return to the
stage. ``What if they say I'm not as funny as I used to be? What if
I'm not as funny? What if I can't write anymore? All these what-ifs
started creeping in, and you can paralyze yourself like that. I
just finally decided that `They win then. They stopped me.' I can't
send that message out. It's not the way I want to live my life, and
I can't stay down, I've got to get back up.''
</P>
<P>
   She never intended to be gone this long. When the pink slip came
from ABC, she immediately starting thinking about stand-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, I can't just disappear,'' she said. ``I'm a shark,
in a sense; if I'm not moving constantly, I die. That's been my
life. I've always been a workaholic. So I thought I should get
right back and do stand-up and I made the deal with HBO, and then I
got scared out of my mind and pulled it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into a deep depression and didn't do anything for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   Then I came out of that thinking I should do the HBO special and
was trying to push, but I was not ready and pulled it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now by this time HBO is getting aggravated, right? So I
finally started writing again and felt confident enough that if I
just set a date, I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is in two parts: one part stand-up, the other audience
participation. For the latter, DeGeneres takes questions from the
audience, and sometimes calls out Heche from backstage.
</P>
<P>
   Heche is filming a behind-the-scenes documentary of the tour.
(She's also making a movie, so it is not known whether she will be
here Friday or in Vancouver for the film.) The documentary may
become a theatrical release or could go straight to video. It's not
part of the HBO special.
</P>
<P>
   The trip, being made with two touring buses, has been a return
of the bump and grind for the road-tested DeGeneres, who last
performed stand-up seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared of flying, and it's such a big tour,'' she said.
``We have such a big crew and so much equipment, it just seemed
easier (than flying).''
</P>
<P>
   Yet reality is setting in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're sleeping on top of a motor _ or not sleeping. It's
really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But here is the reward: DeGeneres is doing what she was born to
do: making people laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Her optimism peaking, she will start work on a variety show for
CBS immediately after the tour ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to put on the good old-fashioned variety shows, like
Carol Burnett, where things were funny because they were, not
because they were meanspirited or too hip or too edgy and pushing
the envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   She said CBS president Leslie Moonves has advised her to have a
show ready by October. He's given the green light for six episodes.
And in a throwback to Burnett, DeGeneres will talk off-the-cuff
with the studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   And in another bow to Burnett, Tim Conway has signed on as a
cast member, along with Sean Cullen (Cop Land) and Jennifer Irwin
(Harlan County War).
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a risky show,'' said the woman who knows what risk is.
``Nobody's doing a show like this, and they haven't in a long time.
People have tried and failed. I just really believe I can do it,
and I believe there are people out there that are ready to see that
kind of comedy come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1242EDT &QL; 
