</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENDS-NEXTGEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS WARM UP TO SOME COOL SUMMER FLICKS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Subs to delete NYT Magazine reference in editor's note.)  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article is for use by clients of
the TRENDS-NEXTGEN column. Nonsubscribers can use these articles
only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see end of
text. 
 By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM   
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe you've watched the movie previews or read the critics'
opinions, but when it comes to what movies young people actually
want to see, you may not have heard from the experts _ teen-agers
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I gathered a group of teens in New York, L.A. and
Chicago and showed them descriptions of some summer movies to see
what the true authorities had to say about the potential
blockbusters. Here are their picks for the biggest hits.
</P>
<P>
   'SHAFT'
</P>
<P>
   While the 1980s might be back in fashion, the 1970s are ruling
the silver screen. Teens are jonesing for Jackson _ Samuel L.
Jackson _ who plays the title character in a re-creation of the
1971 ``blaxploitation'' classic that inspired two sequels and a
short-lived television series.
</P>
<P>
   As one 17-year-old male from New York summed up, ``Shaft's just
so cool. He's got an awesome job, he gets the girls and he's out
for justice. You just know he's gonna be a badass and there will be
a lot of action, but he's the good guy. They don't make shows like
that anymore.'' No they don't; but if the movie does as well as
these teens expect, there will, undoubtedly be a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   'THE PERFECT STORM'
</P>
<P>
   While both teen males and females are looking forward to this
film, the appeal comes from places as different as a sunny day and
a stormy one. Males are interested in the action, the story and the
cool effects (``How do they DO that wave thing?'' asked one
15-year-old male in Chicago). Females, on the other hand, have
their eye on George Clooney and Mark Wahlberg rather than the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, females who aren't even that interested in the
film expect to ride out the opening tempest. As one 16-year-old
girl from New York explained, ``I know all my guy friends are gonna
want to see it the night it opens, so I'd go see it just to hang
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   'LOSER'
</P>
<P>
   Together again, teen sex symbol Mena Suvari and teen jokester
Jason Biggs may be just the right match to bring in the young
audience. But while the two stars grabbed the groups' attention,
previews and word of mouth may ultimately decide the film's fate.
</P>
<P>
   As one 16-year-old male in Chicago said, ``There are so many
movies about teen-agers today. Lately most of them suck. It's like
they (movie studios) think we'll see anything, but that's not true.
If I hear a film sucks, I'll skip it or wait till it comes out on
video.''
</P>
<P>
   'COYOTE UGLY'
</P>
<P>
   Think ``Cocktail,'' think ``Flashdance,'' think ``Footloose'' or
``Dirty Dancing.'' Every generation needs its shamelessly sexy,
coming-of-age movie under the guise of female (or male)
empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry that these films are corrupting the minds of
tomorrow's leaders. As one 17-year-old female summed it up, ``Come
on, we don't take these films seriously. They're hysterical _ but
they've got great music It's a world you wish really existed and
some stupid romance that you know winds up with a happy ending My
life is hard enough. I don't mind a good escape for a few hours.''
</P>
<P>
   'CHICKEN RUN'
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers today know the difference between a Disney cartoon
meant for their younger siblings and the more sophisticated and
often racier animation of ``The Simpsons'' and ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Teens expect ``Chicken Run,'' an animated feature that tells the
story of some chickens trapped in a World War II-like prison camp,
to be entertaining and innovative. As one 16-year-old girl in L.A.
said, ``It's just going to be a funny, easy movie I'd see with my
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   'GIRLFIGHT'
</P>
<P>
   While this film showed more limited appeal, it did reveal the
love for the independent spirit we see among teens. It also
demonstrated how savvy teens are about indie films, not just
blockbusters. A surprisingly large number were familiar with the
fact that ``Girlfight'' won a Grand Jury Prize at The Sundance Film
Festival. In addition, both males and females liked the premise of
a female boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tough chicks are cool,'' said one 14-year-old New York male.
``It's really good that they show strong women,'' added one
15-year-old girl from L.A.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Here Today &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Palm Pilot
</P>
<P>
   Coral lipstick
</P>
<P>
   Belly piercing
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coming Tomorrow &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cybiko
</P>
<P>
   Burgundy lipstick
</P>
<P>
   Belly chains
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
