<HEADER>
A4771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS &LR;      06-15 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VIDEO REVIEWS OF `THE GREEN MILE,' `BICENTENNIAL MAN' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE WESTBROOK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile''
</P>
<P>
   In serial form as six thin paperbacks, Stephen King's The Green
Mile was a breeze of a read. As a film, it's a three-hour epic.
</P>
<P>
   Blame Tom Hanks' star power for such excess, or blame
writer-director Frank Darabont. After the huzzahs for his work on
King's The Shawshank Redemption _ a prison yarn which ran 40 fewer
minutes _ perhaps he got carried away.
</P>
<P>
   But video does offer intermissions on command, and on any screen
Mile offers ample rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Those unfamiliar with the novel will be engaged by its surprises
as the tale slowly unfolds. Those who know the story should be
pleased that Darabont is faithful to it.
</P>
<P>
   Mile also is impeccably cast. Each actor seems born to play his
part, and none shines more brightly than deserving Oscar nominee
Michael Clarke Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   He portrays John Coffey, a hulking, uneducated, gentle man who's
unjustly convicted of killing two girls in Depression-era
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   When he's locked in a cell on a prison's death row (whose green
floor lends the tale's title), things get interesting.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Coffey has unexplained supernatural powers.
</P>
<P>
   With a touch, he can read minds, transmit his thoughts and _
most importantly _ draw suffering into himself with healing
inhalations.
</P>
<P>
   His benign powers spark dramatic events involving the ailing
chief guard (Hanks), the desperately ill wife of the warden, a
maniacally murderous inmate and an amazingly obedient mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned the film also has horrific executions (one of which is
marred by twisted Creepshow gore), and its heart-rending tragedies
can be too much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   Most are triggered by two characters: a condemned man (Sam
Rockwell) who's gleefully vicious, and a cowardly guard (Doug
Hutchison) whose insidious hatred sparks the most appalling scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mile isn't engulfed by woe. It has a strong sense of
humanism if not almost serene spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, it's an absorbing prison story in which
monstrousness resides on both sides of cells. At the most, it's an
allegory for humanity's worst episodes of cruelty, offset by
moments of forgiveness and grace.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A- 1999, R, Warner, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Bicentennial Man''
</P>
<P>
   In his 20-year film career, Robin Williams has created a virtual
genre.
</P>
<P>
   Call it ``hand-wringing dramas whose high-minded pathos never
compensates for submerging Williams' comic talents in a sea of
sentimental tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, he's entitled to stretch as an actor and play dramatic
roles, which rightly won him an Oscar for Good Will Hunting. But
for years it seems that's all he's done, and he just won't quit.
</P>
<P>
   In stand-up-comic parlance, take this movie _ please.
</P>
<P>
   It is as leadenly earnest and weepy as far too many Williams
efforts, from Patch Adams and What Dreams May Come to Jakob the
Liar and Jack.
</P>
<P>
   He plays a household appliance _ that is, a humanlike robot of
the future, purchased by a wealthy man (Sam Neill) for his family.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to many complications _ some comical, others serious
_ as the family adjusts to the robot and the machine assimilates
human qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Through new technology and preachy advocacy of biological
glories, he progresses (if that's the word) toward a true human
state.
</P>
<P>
   In short, this is the old Pinocchio character arc, which Brent
Spiner played on Star Trek: The Next Generation for seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It's an arc Williams plays with the same old touchy-feely
sensitivity, wearing his heart on his sleeve like a romantic
schoolboy who's just discovered Deep Thoughts. He's got comic bits,
to be sure, but they're buried in fields of corn.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the world's greatest comedian again squanders the gift of
laughter. Robin, you're robbin' us.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C- 1999, PG, Touchstone, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD
$32.99
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
