<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TRACY-BYRD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRACY BYRD IS TRUE TO HIS COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GOODSPEED  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Like a lot of guys, Tracy Byrd loves hunting,
fishing and country music.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a lot of guys, Byrd is building successful careers with
his hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   So if the easy-going smile the good-natured singer wears during
his performance Friday night at the Far West Rodeo seems broader
than usual, consider this:
</P>
<P>
   _ A new record label, RCA, which allowed the country
traditionalist more creative control than ever before on his
seventh album, ``It's About Time,'' which was greeted by more
critical acclaim than any of his previous efforts.
</P>
<P>
   _ A top-10 single from that album, ``Put Your Hand in Mine,'' a
touching song about a child who keeps his parents from breaking up.
It marks Byrd's departure from his prior label's pigeonholing as a
novelty hitmaker with such tunes as ``Watermelon Crawl'' and ``I'm
From the Country.''
</P>
<P>
   _ His sophomore year as host of TNN's block of weekend outdoors
shows, which draws 8 million viewers a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ A just-released RCA album, ``Wonders of Wildlife'' _ spawned
from Byrd's recent TNN special of the same name to support wildlife
conservation _ features hits from fellow country stars who share
his love of the outdoors. It also has a new song from Byrd, ``Pass
It On,'' which concerns handing off to the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, who has sold more than 5 million albums and is known for
such No. 1 hits as ``Keeper of the Stars'' and ``Holdin' Heaven,''
fell in love with the outdoors before country music, and his
grandmother Mavis Vaughn was the matchmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nana started taking me fishing when I was about 4 and hunting
when I was about 6, and I've been doing it ever since,'' the native
of the far Southeast Texas town of Vidor said, adding they hunted
and fished together regularly until he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   They still do on occasion. Two springs ago, Byrd took Vaughn on
her first turkey hunt. The outing was taped for TNN's ``Hunting the
Country,'' and Byrd called up three gobblers at daylight. Vaughn,
in her 70s, shot the one with the smallest beard _ 9 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was pretty fired up about it anyway,'' Byrd said.
</P>
<P>
   Like on the song ``Pass It On,'' Byrd hands off what he learned
from Vaughn to his daughter, Evee, 5, and son, Logan, 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've both caught fish and they love it,'' Byrd said.
``They're just not quite old enough to hunt yet. I grew up in the
woods and on the water, and I want my kids to do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outdoors offers a great education for a child. Above and
beyond everything else, it teaches them respect for nature and the
power of God to create something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, 33, keeps his roots solidly planted in Beaumont, Texas,
where he moved when he was 19. When in Nashville, Tenn., he stays
in an apartment in his office building on Music Row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in Nashville for business and that's about it,'' Byrd
said. ``I like living in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd is proud that his album ``It's About Time'' reflects his
Texas roots, with an old Johnny Bush hit, ``Undo the Right,''
written by Willie Nelson and Hank Cochran, and famous fiddler
Johnny Gimble of Tyler playing on several tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'd ever showcased my vocal ability and really
got some songs with some real meat to them, really great
traditional country songs,'' Byrd said. ``That's what I set out to
do on `It's About Time.'''
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Byrd wants to host his own outdoors TV show,
although his touring schedule prevents him from taping the
necessary 16 episodes. But his music exposes fans to the outdoors,
too _ sometimes in unexpected ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tons of my lady fans now sit down with their husbands to watch
TNN Outdoors,'' Byrd said. ``I've had husbands say, `My wife used
to gripe all the time about not being able to watch what she wanted
on TV on Saturday mornings and Sunday nights. Now I can't get her
to quit watching it with me because you're on there.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact John Goodspeed by e-mail at
jgoodspeed(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
