<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4784 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-TRENDY-BEANS-HNS &LR;      06-15 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENDY-BEANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GIVE BEANS A CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE WALKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tired of those summer reruns?
</P>
<P>
   When coleslaw, chips and salsa, frozen yogurt, tuna sandwiches
and hot dogs start to fade in appeal, it's time to switch to
something more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Let us suggest ... beans.
</P>
<P>
   Not exciting? Well, perhaps interesting, delicious, affordable,
versatile and easy to prepare are better words to describe beans.
Dress them up, coax them into bolder roles, find a better cast of
supporting characters and you might just stage an unexpected hit.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, beans have come into their own as a ``trendy'' food. Hot
new cooking styles, such as Nuevo Latino, not only give beans star
billing, they also use them in salsas, sauces and garnishes.
Growing numbers of vegetarians don't just like beans, they revere
them as reliable, delicious sources of protein. And never before in
history has a bean received so much press as the soybean has in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   With the obesity rate in the United States rising, cutting back
on fat and introducing more fiber into the diet is of special
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Beans are one of the ideal foods for doing this, says Patricia
Parker, a registered, licensed dietitian and certified diabetes
educator with the Texas Diabetes Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're high in soluble fiber, which is one of the types of
fiber that is important for lowering cholesterol,'' she says.
Soluble fiber is especially good for people with diabetes. Because
it takes longer to digest, it slows down the time it takes for food
to enter into the bloodstream, which helps normalize blood sugar
levels. It prevents constipation and helps keep you feeling fuller
longer. ``So you'll have less snacking later,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to get between 25-30 grams of fiber a day. You
aren't going to get this with a slice of bread,'' says Parker.
Bread may have between 1-2 grams of fiber, or up to 3 grams if it
is whole grain. A half cup of kidney beans has 9 grams; for the
same amount of pinto beans, it's 5 grams and for black beans, 7
grams.
</P>
<P>
   Also, says Parker, beans are high in protein and iron as well as
isoflavones, nutritional substances that have been shown to have
important cancer-fighting benefits.
</P>
<P>
   If the family doesn't care for beans, says Parker, there are
ways to slowly introduce such foods into the diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as a dietitian, I had to learn to eat beans. And it was
probably one of the hardest things I had to learn. I used to
swallow them like you would a pill. Now I can eat a whole bowl-full
at a time and I love them.''
</P>
<P>
   How did she learn to love them?
</P>
<P>
   ``One bean at a time,'' says Parker, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Parker says that in her experience children like beans best when
they are mashed and served over something, like rice. To get them
(or adults) accustomed to eating more beans, ``add them as a
garnish or in a salad where they're not the main ingredient,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, where pinto beans, black beans and black-eyed
peas are popular, the challenge is to cook them without too much
added fat but to make them flavorful.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's us,'' says Roy Holley, a cook at La Fiesta Patio Cafe.
The flavor secret of La Fiesta's beans is olive oil, a more
healthful, monounsaturated fat. No bacon, no lard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a tad of olive oil is all you need, then regular spices
and seasonings,'' says Holley.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is a perfect time to give beans a chance _ and there are
many colorful, flavorful varieties from which to choose. Here are a
few tips from Parker, ``The Nutrition Bible'' (Morrow, $30) and the
American Dry Bean Board for using beans:
</P>
<P>
   Soaking dry beans: To soak or not to soak is a frequently asked
question. The answer is yes, soak. First, it softens and returns
moisture to the beans and reduces cooking time. Second it allows
some of the gas-producing substances to dissolve in the soaking
water.
</P>
<P>
   How to soak: For every pound (2 cups) of beans, add 10 cups hot
water. Heat the beans and water to boiling, then turn off the heat,
cover and set aside for 1 to 4 hours. For every pound of dry beans,
you'll get 6 cups cooked beans.
</P>
<P>
   Discarding water: The longer beans soak and the more soaking
water you pour out, the less gas-producing beans will be. Yes, some
nutrients are lost when soaking water is poured out, but so are
some of the gas-producing properties.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking beans: Boil the beans for about 10 minutes, then simmer
them until tender, usually 1 to 2 hours. Never add anything acidic
while the beans are cooking, such as tomatoes, vinegar, wine or
citrus juices. Add these after the beans are tender. Seasonings
such as garlic, onion, oregano or parsley can be added while
they're cooking. After cooking, beans may be refrigerated for 4 to
5 days, or they may be frozen if packaged in moisture- and
vapor-proof containers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Bonnie Walker by e-mail at
bwalker1(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
