<HEADLINE>
IN MEXICO'S TIGHT RACE, VOTER INTIMIDATION FEARED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Two leading presidential candidates warn of
trouble if next month's vote is close. Mexico's currency dips to a
15-month low. And the country's Roman Catholic Church is urging
members not to ``vote out of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   It's little wonder, then, that Mexican voters, with less than
three weeks to go before the closest presidential election since
the Great Depression, are starting to feel nervous about July 2.
</P>
<P>
   In a race that most opinion polls show is a statistical tie
between the ruling party and the conservative opposition, voters,
analysts and observers are complaining that the candidates and
their respective organizations are trying to intimidate voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a campaign of fear that we've seen lately by certain
groups that is creating an anxiety among people,'' said Jaime
Cardenas, a board member of the Federal Electoral Institute, the
independent agency coordinating the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers say the jitters emerged last month when Vicente
Fox Quesada, the 57-year-old former Coca Cola executive and
candidate for the center-right National Action Party, said he would
question the election results if he lost by less than 10 percentage
points. He has backtracked a bit since, maintaining that he would
accept the results if they are endorsed by the electoral agency.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's earlier comments were matched by those of governing party
candidate Francisco Labastida Ochoa, who envisioned ``problems in
the country, demonstrations and disturbances,'' if he didn't win by
a large margin.
</P>
<P>
   Several financial analysts blamed both statements for the quick
fall of the Mexican peso last week. It dipped slightly over 10 to
the US dollar, its lowest point in more than a year, raising fears
of an economic crisis similar to that during the last transition of
power six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone tells us that the economy is much better now and not
to worry,'' said Rogelio Parra, who manages a photo studio in the
Polanco neighborhood of Mexico City. ``That's what the government
told us six years ago, but they lied. You can't blame us for being
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the Mexican jitters is the uncertainty over
how desperate the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party,
known as the PRI, will be to win next month's vote. Many observers
and experts worry that the party, known for past fraud and
vote-buying schemes in maintaining 71 uninterrupted years of power,
may be returning to its old ways.
</P>
<P>
   There are already signs that the old PRI machine may be humming
away. Last week, members of an opposition party in Quintana Roo
state discovered a warehouse of 300 brand new bicycles, allegedly
bought by the state's PRI organization and intended as gifts for
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Other recent vote-buying stories disclosed by the watchdog group
Alianza Civica on Tuesday include 500 washing machines, bags of
cattle feed, water for rural communities and new drainage systems
for villages hard hit by recent rainstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Observers also worry that the government's 3-year-old welfare
program known as Progresa, which provides assistance to parents who
make sure their children stay in school, may be more vulnerable to
political manipulation by officials who allegedly warn recipients
that their support will be cut off unless they vote for the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church, which was banned from political affairs in
Mexico for decades until reforms were passed in 1992, has also
expressed concerns about pressuring voters and possible fraud.
Church officials are posting messages in 7,000 parishes telling
members that ``to collaborate directly or indirectly with
electorial fraud is a serious sin that harms human rights and
offends God.''
</P>
<P>
   PRI leaders and the government have gone to great lengths to
insist that this year's elections will be the cleanest ever, mostly
because they are being organized for the first time by a
nonpartisan agency.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the electoral institute, created four years ago, say
they have so far received 12 formal complaints of vote-buying and
intimidation tactics, 10 of them against the PRI and two against
the Alliance for Mexico leftist coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the agency has been broadcasting radio and
television commercials reminding voters that vote-buying and
coercion are illegal. But electoral officials know that detecting
fraud and punishing violators will be hard to do unless they are
given more resources and more enforcement powers against everyone _
even the president.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, the agency sent a letter to Zedillo demanding
his government stop broadcasting pro-government ads on television
because it amounted to a PRI campaign commercial. Zedillo did not
respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our chief of state and should be an example,'' one
electoral official said this week. ``He says he's committed to
transparent elections, but we still have no answer from him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
