<HEADLINE>
HOW MANY MILES PER GALLON? IN A BENTLEY, WHO CARES? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what do I know from labels?
</P>
<P>
   Black Labels, in cans, on ice in a galvanized bucket, at the end
of the dock on a hot day of fishing. Those labels I know.
</P>
<P>
   Red Label, Green Label, winged and affixed to the hoods of
motorcars that cost upward of $200,000? Not in the little town in
New Hamphshire where I grew up. Yuppies there drove Volvos and
Saabs, not Bentleys. We drove mostly fourth-hand Chevys.
</P>
<P>
   So when my pal Bugsy _ who can best be described as my pusher
when it comes to the cars I end up testing every week _ called to
see if I'd like a Bentley Arnage over Memorial Day weekend, the
internal debate lingered as long as spit on a hot woodstove.
</P>
<P>
   I did not ask, ``Red Label or Green?''
</P>
<P>
   I got the Red, which is by far the peppier of the two lumbering
sedans _ nearly three tons of steel and aluminum and leather (so
much leather you have to count it in the overall curb weight) that
can, with amazing wonder, screech off the line and hurtle down the
highway _ all as you relax inside in quiet comfort. Hey, you can
barely hear the horn when you blow it, so insulated is the Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   Its presence caused no small dilemma over the long holiday
weekend. What shall I drive, I found myself muttering whenever I
had to go to the town recycling center, one of my kid's baseball
games, off to a barbecue, or out to dine at a restaurant. The
turbocharged Bentley or the supercharged Jaguar XKR convertible?
</P>
<P>
   Three-hundred-thousand dollars worth of cars, so little time.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the small rear seat of the Jag holds baseball
gear just fine. The trunk of the Bentley holds five plastic bags of
garbage, a bag of cans, a bag of bottles, a stack of cardboard, and
a week's worth of three different newspapers. Either will get you
to chow and back.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Bentley that had the oddest effect on folks.
They'd gawk. They'd ask to just sit in it. They'd ask what it was
and what it cost, gasping at the answer to the latter.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Monica was so touched by the experience of traveling
to dinner in such luxury that she suggested that she and my wife
pop up through the open sunroof and perform as though they were at
a rave concert at Foxboro Stadium, and I'm not talking moshing. She
was dissuaded.
</P>
<P>
   At dinner, our quartet arrived just behind a couple. The maitre
'd asked the couple what they needed, nodded, and then turned to
us. The gentleman in the couple, worried that we might edge ahead,
asked if we had arrived before them _ implying we had no business
asking for a table before he was seated.
</P>
<P>
   Before I could point out that we had reservations, Monica told
him that, no, we were not there ahead, and then advised him, ``But
we came in a Bentley.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bentley Arnage Red Label, stronger brother of the Green
Label, was unveiled to the world at the 1999 Frankfurt auto show.
It was Volkswagen's attempt (yes, VW had purchased Bentley) to show
that it could crank out power with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   And crank it out it does.
</P>
<P>
   In turbocharged form, its 6.75-liter V-8 produces 420
horsepower. More than respectable. But it also manages something
over 630 lb.-ft. of torque. I've seen tow trucks with less torque
than that. I could haul both the Suburban and the ski boat I tow
with it with the Red Label.
</P>
<P>
   The Arnage is named for a famous, tortuous turn at LeMans, in
reverence for the long ago days when Bentleys won the 24 Hours of
LeMans five times.
</P>
<P>
   I guess the folks who made the Green Label didn't think it quite
lived up to that heritage, so they crammed this bigger, more
powerful engine into the Arnage and named it Red. As in, Right On,
Red.
</P>
<P>
   When I say crammed in, I mean crammed in. Pop the hood and you'd
be hard pressed to get a piece of dental floss to travel cleanly
from the top of the engine compartment to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But should you own a Bentley, you probably shouldn't have to
look under the hood anyway. Grease and other yukky things might be
found there. Stains silks, ruins finger sandwiches at picnics.
</P>
<P>
   You belong back inside the car, where select people go. Riding
smoothly, free from the noise and bumps of the outside world.
Independent suspension, automatic height control, load
compensators, automatic stability control, even self-leveling
headlights, and thicker insulation than you find in a refrigerator,
protect you from the vagaries and insults of the open road.
</P>
<P>
   And who can blame Monica her, shall we say, ``enthusiasm''?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, even the ceiling in the Bentley is coated with leather.
Cream leather everywhere, thick leather on the seats, dash,
steering wheel. Seats in the front as big as easy chairs and
probably more comfortable than the easy chairs most of us normally
sit in.
</P>
<P>
   The split sections of the rear seat move back, on their own,
when you open a rear door. Easy egress if you ever want to get out,
which you almost always do reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   Nice parchment color to the gauges. Wonderful retro chrome
pull-knobs that open and close air vents. Carpeting thick as an old
forest floor. Miles per gallon? Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Next time, Monica drives. I rise through the sunroof and there
is no stopping me. I lift my shirt . . . because I'm in a Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
