<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4791 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-RESEND-EGG-DONORS-LAD     06-15 1646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEND-EGG-DONORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GIFT THAT KEEPS ON GIVING 
RESENT TO ACCOMMODATE SAN BERNARDINO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANGELA LEMIRE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, Dawn Wright was sedated for 45 minutes as a
doctor, using an ultrasound probe, removed 12 or so eggs from her
uterus _ far more than the usual single egg normally released
during ovulation.
</P>
<P>
   To get to this point, she had spent a month injecting herself
with 2-inch needles: three weeks of Lupron in the stomach to stop
that month's production of reproductive eggs; one week of Metrodin
and Pergonal, egg follicle-stimulating hormones, in the hip; then a
single injection of another hormonal mixture as her ovaries swelled
to nearly the size of grapefruits.
</P>
<P>
   She did all this voluntarily, despite the medical risks and side
effects such as hot flashes, nausea, fatigue, water retention and
cramping.
</P>
<P>
   She did it to make pregnancy possible for a woman she would
never meet; a woman who, most likely, had already exhausted years
and up to $30,000 on previous infertility treatments before
considering third-party in vitro fertilization, or egg donation.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Wright, now 29, says she felt blessed to have her
own son _ now a healthy, active 5-year-old _ and wanted to share
her gift with someone who truly wanted motherhood, even a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt others should be so lucky,'' says Wright, a Santa
Clarita resident. ``I thought, `It's just so hard for so many
couples. It's not always so easy to adopt.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Carole Lieber Wilkins, a West Los Angeles psychotherapist, was
only 33 when she became pregnant using anonymous donor eggs. Three
years earlier, she had learned she could not conceive a child with
her own eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're facing that a part of your body has failed you and
you're not able to create a child with your partner in the way you
always imagined,'' says Wilkins, who now has a 12-year-old son from
that process, and later adopted another son. ``You're also getting
over the fantasy that you're going to having a little you, your own
genetic offspring. But once you get past that, you should look at
(egg donors) as a great option, because it is.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, more infertile women and couples have
opted for third-party in vitro as success rates improved to a
remarkable 70 percent and risky multiple-birth rates decreased,
according to Dr. Paul Greenberg, a fertility expert whose practice
is based at Encino-Tarzana Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Also making the process more appealing is the greater
availability of donors who come forward either for the monetary
compensation, humanitarian desires or both.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, Greenberg's practice, which he once shared
with retired partner Dr. Sheldon Schein in Thousand Oaks, was among
a handful in Greater Los Angeles to offer various types of in vitro
procedures. They performed only two or three egg donor transfers
per year in the early 1990s. But by last year, egg donation
transfers had become so commonplace that they accounted for 20
percent of the 70 in vitro fertilizations Greenberg performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that third-party in vitro, or egg
donations, is the fastest-growing industry in the medical
profession,'' says Karen Synesiou, co-owner and director of the
Center for Surrogate Parenting &AMP; Egg Donation Inc. in Beverly
Hills, one of Los Angeles' busiest egg donation clinics. Egg
donations have increased from roughly three successful cycles per
year in the early 1990s to more than 300 last year.
</P>
<P>
   According to National Centers for Disease Control (CDC)
statistics updated through 1997, California's 33 clinics _ about 10
percent of nationwide egg donor clinics at the time _ reported more
than 2,300 successful donor cycles in 1997. Industry insiders since
then have pinned nationwide estimates for annual egg donor cycles
at up to 15,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Linda (not her real name), a San Fernando Valley resident in her
early 50s, conceived a son with anonymous donor eggs eight years
ago. She opted for the procedure after a miscarriage 12 weeks into
a pregnancy two years before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have gone to any length to get pregnant,'' Linda
recalled. ``I had achieved my career goals, I had traveled all over
the world, and could still do those things if I wanted to, but I
was suddenly willing to put it all aside to have my child. I don't
know of any other way to describe that longing to others who
haven't felt it.''
</P>
<P>
   She had been considering adoption when she learned of egg
donation, then a new and little-known procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great blessing for me that someone did this,'' says
Linda of her anonymous donor. ``I got it all: I got pregnant, I got
to nurse, I got motherhood. And my husband, too, is genetically
connected to our child.''
</P>
<P>
   ---Money motivates some donors &QL; 
Aside from women who assist infertile friends or relatives in
getting pregnant, medical professionals and donors say money is, to
some degree, a prime motivating factor for most egg donors.
</P>
<P>
   Donor fees _ which technically compensate women for time,
inconvenience and medical risk, not the eggs _ are typically
between $2,500 and $5,000 in California, and $5,000 to $8,000 on
the East Coast, where fewer donors are available.
</P>
<P>
   The well-publicized online auctions for fashion models' eggs and
$50,000 offers for specific donor traits are rare, experts say, and
most donors are of average appearance.
</P>
<P>
   A divorced mother with a young son, Wright figured she could put
the donor fee toward emergency savings. And the $2,500 she received
eventually came in handy when costly car repairs came up
unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she insists her primary motivation was more humanitarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really go into it just looking at the money or it's
not going to be enjoyable for you to have to go through all that.
Mentally you can't handle it,'' says Wright, recalling the daily
injections and physical discomfort afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Money) was definitely some part of it, but I was more
interested in the medical part.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Derrick, a 29-year-old West Los Angeles resident and
free-lance writer, has undergone nine donor cycles in the last four
years. The money she received has helped to pay off her college
education and enabled her to take a vacation in South America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about the money,'' she says of her first donation. ``It
still is.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 10th donation, she vows, will be her last. Financially,
she's doing well enough between writing and working as a personal
trainer that she no longer needs the extra money.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other concerns, she admits, like health risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be connected to any one thing like that _ you
know, that puts your body through so many changes,'' Derrick says.
``And I know there's risks.''
</P>
<P>
   She has recently begun thinking more about times like her ninth
donation, when she had to take birth control pills to regulate her
hormones. She detested the unsettling mood swings that came over
her.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, she's reminded of the risk of hyperstimulation, when
hormone injections cause ovaries to produce an unusually large
number of eggs. Doctors retrieved about 30 eggs _ more than double
the amount usually harvested _ and she went through two weeks of
cramps, nausea, bloating and severe fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   She swore she'd never donate her eggs again, but changed her
mind four months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes on, you get used to what you have to do,'' says
Derrick. ``And it doesn't seem like a big deal after a while _ even
the needles.''
</P>
<P>
   It is encouraging that she's helped someone in the process, she
says, particularly people who've already tried previous fertility
treatments and want children so badly. Every now and then, she's
reminded of that by personal thank you notes or gifts she receives
from her egg recipients.
</P>
<P>
   California's open donor policy gives recipients and donors the
option to meet or make contact and enables recipients to get more
personal information about donors, such as academic records and
hobbies _ even pictures. Anonymous programs _ the prevailing
practice on the East Coast _ forbids contact or exchange of more
personal information, including names.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Derrick, ``They're all winners in this. I think if (the
recipients) go through all that effort to have a child, and they'd
be good parents, they should.''
</P>
<P>
   ---It's not the best option for everyone &QL; 
Wilkins, whose own experience as a recipient now guides her in
counseling couples and women coping with grief, cautions that
third-party egg donation is not the only answer to the infertility
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because there's a high success rate doesn't mean this is
the right choice for everyone,'' says Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   Before even considering other family-building alternatives,
women must grieve ``the loss of a genetic child,'' she says, adding
that it takes time to mourn, accept and make peace with one's own
infertility.
</P>
<P>
   Egg donor in vitro is not recommended for women whose moral or
ethical beliefs might pose insurmountable issues, she says, or for
those who would feel embarrassment or shame, or who anticipate that
grandparents and other relatives would not accept the children, or
who feel coerced into having the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   And a woman who opts for egg donations in vitro must also decide
how to explain her decision to the child. Wilkins advises parents
to explain it to children in simplistic terms at an early age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not genetically connected, but I'm biologically
connected,'' says Linda, anticipating the explanation she'll likely
give her own son in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he's going to react. But I hope the love we
have given him will outweigh any concerns about any part a third
person has played in this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' she says. ``I have no precedent for this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
