<HEADLINE>
PEBBLE BEACH A TRUE AMERICAN BEAUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ The answer is as clear as the wind on
your face as you stare out at a Pacific Ocean that is unrelenting
in its force, yet rhythmic in its soothing roar. This, you tell
yourself, is why they have journeyed here for all these years,
sparing no cost, seduced not by the game, but by the splendor that
intoxicates the senses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty. I think everybody who thinks about Pebble Beach,
the first thing they think about is not that it is a par-72 golf
course,'' said Tom Watson. ``They think about the beauty of this
place because that is what it represents.''
</P>
<P>
   The 100th United State Golf Association's Open championship is
being played over 18 historic holes that are unrivaled, but for
most of the 156 contestants, the event began weeks, perhaps months
ago when Pebble froze their thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pebble is Pebble,'' said Brad Faxon. ``It's perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest place in the world,'' said Brett Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like no other golf setting anywhere,'' said Bobby
Clampett. ``Like no other golf experience you can have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course has always had a special place in my heart,''
said Tiger Woods. ``One, for its pristine beauty, another for its
mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the thoughts of today's golfers, but they were the
thoughts of yesterday's golfers. Go back to the days of primitive
travel and a game too few people could play and you can hear
Scotland's Jim Barnes: ``It's too dom beautiful, I ken not keep my
mind on the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Translated years later by Jack Nicklaus: ``I've always said that
if I had one round of golf to play, I'd go to Pebble Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he has returned _ again. This is where he won his second
US Amateur (1961) and his second US Open (1972). Perfectly fitting
then that he has, by all indications, chosen this venue to bring
down the curtain after his 44th US Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will I smell the flowers?'' Nicklaus laughed. ``No, I'd
probably sneeze too much. But will I enjoy this week? Yes, because
it's Pebble Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When he was in his 90s, Jack Neville would still come around the
Lodge, walk part of the course, and one day in 1975 Bill Spence had
the chance to meet him. ``I remember sitting there,'' said Spence,
now at The Country Club in Brookline, Mass., but back then the
young superintendent of Pebble Beach, ``and thinking, `This is the
guy who created this golf course.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Neville _ who was hired along with fellow amateur golfer Douglas
Grant in 1916 to design Pebble Beach for New England native Samuel
F.B. Morse _ told Spence of the days when sheep would graze the
fairways and how God had truly created Pebble Beach. Morse wanted a
course modeled after Pinehurst, and to preserve the majestic
coastline property, he shrewedly bought back the lots so that
Neville had a natural setting with which to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I've always loved about Pebble,'' said Spence. ``It
has maintained the old style, a ruggedness that Tour courses don't
have today.''
</P>
<P>
   More than that, Pebble Beach has established itself as an
American landmark, a place held in such reverence that the prices,
no matter how high they soar, refuse to deter golfers. A round of
golf costs $300 for those who are staying at Pebble Beach Lodge,
where rooms are in the neighborhood of $400. Can't move into that
neighborhood? No problem, because some daily tee times are set
aside for walk-ons, for $325, though you best call ahead because it
is booked months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Mind-numbing numbers, for sure, though they strike at the heart
of Pebble's appeal. Which is: You are as welcome there as the next
guy, even if that next guy is a dot.com disciple who can string
together seven zeros next to a 1 when he buys a home on the golf
course. It is a public golf course, and though they don't exactly
use the old ball-in-the-ballrack method, an endless string of
everyday people have for years counted their rounds at Pebble Beach
as a near-religious experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many people have come up to us at the end
of the day and thanked us, and left with a smile,'' said Bill
Perocchi, CEO of Pebble Beach Co. and a native of Lawrence, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   They go away happy, no matter if the round took 125 shots, a
dozen golf balls, six hours, and three crisp $100 bills. It is a
small price to pay for sharing in an American story that has no end
to its appeal. Every morsel of information about Pebble Beach is
important, nothing is trivial, because it belongs to everyone. Most
likely they will never set foot on Augusta National or Pine Valley
or Shinnecock Hills or Winged Foot or Seminole or any of the other
shrines of American golf. But Pebble Beach? That belongs to the
public, a different breed of golf course and to mess with it is to
mess with a slice of America.
</P>
<P>
   All of which explains, perhaps, that at this US Open more than
others, course set-up and condition are topics of intense
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Most serious is the decision by the USGA to turn the second hole
into a par 4. Normally it plays as a par 5 and players are
virtually unanimous in their displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the life me, I've never understood why you change that,''
said Nicklaus. ``It doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   His fellow competitors agree, almost unison in their annual
charge that the USGA is simply determined to keep the winning score
as close to par as possible, and lowering it from 288 to 284 does
just that. But the USGA cites an entirely different rationale
behind the decision: pitch canker.
</P>
<P>
   That's the name of the disease that claimed two large Monterey
pines at the left side of the second green, leaving players free to
flail away with no obstacle in their way. Make it a par 4, the USGA
reasoned, and hit away.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch canker also threatens two Monterey pines down the right
side of the 18th fairway, noteworthy signatures on perhaps the most
famous hole in American golf. Resigned to the inevitable, golf
course personnel have planted two Cypress trees, which grow quickly
and in the near future will dominate the landscape at that point of
the course.
</P>
<P>
   Some will shed tears over the change in complexion, but those
who hold Pebble Beach near and dear to their hearts will remind you
that the glory has lived on in spite of past shifts.
</P>
<P>
   --For instance, the 18th hole was originally designed as a par 4
before being changed in 1922 into the classic par 5 that it is. Not
long ago, it was stretched even longer, to 543 yards when the tee
was moved out over the water.
</P>
<P>
   --Neville, said Spence, had one regret: ``He was never able to
purchase the land to put the fifth green along the cliffs.'' So the
hole turned inland, the ``only dogleg par 3 in the world,'' and was
perhaps the only hole that players disliked. Then, a few years ago,
the land was secured and Nicklaus redesigned it, moving the green
near the cliffs where players must now negotiate 188 yards with
genuine concern for losing a tee shot onto the beach.
</P>
<P>
   --The infamous Kikuyu, so thick and nasty and impossible to hit
out of, was eradicated in 1990 _ two years before the US Open was
to return for its third appearance _ and replaced with perennial
rye. It was a huge gamble, but the decision has paid off because
the course condition has reached magnificent standards never before
seen.
</P>
<P>
   --Twice, Pebble Beach has been owned by Japanese interests _
Minuro Isutani, who paid $840 million in 1990, and Taiheiyo Club
Inc., which took control for a mere $500 million two years later.
The former ownership was a nightmare, but the latter is given
credit for pumping money and life into Pebble Beach before choosing
the ideal American partnership (Peter Ueberroth, Arnold Palmer,
Clint Eastwood et al) to sell to in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Through all the changes, the people have continued to pour
through the course, hundred-dollar bills in their pockets, visions
of grandeur in their minds. That isn't likely to change, not with a
program that allows course owners to use reclaimed water to keep
things green; not with a robust economy that keeps money in
people's bank accounts; not with the level of golf reaching
dizzying heights.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always like this, said Spence, who was on board from
1975-78 during which time a serious drought left the place brown
and hard. The ``ugliest PGA championship ever,'' he said, was here
in 1977 because ``we couldn't water.'' Only parts of the fairways
were green.
</P>
<P>
   When you turn on your TV today, you'll see no such problem.
Plush shades of green will jump out at you, until the camera
shifts, that is, and shows you the different tones of Pacific blue.
``The scenery couldn't be more spectacular,'' said Phil Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Mickelson and 155 others, the scenery is not
why they have come to Pebble Beach. There is golf to be played and
no one is predicting that the golf will match the splendor of the
view, because the rough is up, the greens are fast, the fairways
hard, and wind is in the forecast, a combination that produces
visions of bogeys and long, frustrating rounds.
</P>
<P>
   That, said Spence, is what makes Pebble Beach ``the best Open
site'' available when June comes around. ``It doesn't rain and the
temperatures and fog allow you to do anything you want with the
grass. It's always different everytime you play it.''
</P>
<P>
   It took the USGA a long, long time to bring an Open here, but
after Nicklaus won in 1972, the returns were swift _ 1982 (Watson)
and 1992 (Tom Kite). ``And in each case,'' said Spence, ``Pebble
Beach never failed to identify the best player.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is only fitting for America's best public course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
