<HEADER>
A4796 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     06-15 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUNING IN TO THE VIRTUAL ACCORDION FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cliff Furnwald would be the first to admit that he has a sort of
wacky passion for all things accordion. Right now, he's sitting at
his computer producing the Third Annual Free Reed Festival, a
month-long celebration of the accordion being held exclusively on
the Internet. To Furnwald, this seems like a perfectly logical
endeavor, but to the uninitiated, the idea of a virtual accordion
festival raises a lot of questions. As in, why, why, and why?
</P>
<P>
   But the real burning question is: What do you wear?
</P>
<P>
   Do you pull out the lederhosen and dust off the dirndl? Or do
you rent a polyester tuxedo, something in the style of, say,
Lawrence Welk?
</P>
<P>
   ``When people think of the accordion, they think of the guys in
the powder blue suits playing the birthday parties,'' says
Furnwald, a freelance music critic and founder of rootsworld.com,
which is hosting the festival. ``We're going to surprise the hell
out of them. They expect oompah, oompah, oompah, and there will be
none of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival will feature articles, reviews, and recordings
contributed by 30 artists from all over the world. The site is
updated with new material every day, and judging from some of the
artists featured so far, this isn't about your typical polka band.
For instance, a group called the Edge City Collective plays bizarre
improvisational music that proves that even the accordion can be
totally inaccessible. On the other hand, the avant-garde duo of Guy
Klucevsek and Alan Bern create a fascinating sound that is nothing
like anything you have ever heard on this instrument; at times,
Klucevsek bangs on the instrument and makes the thing sound like a
drum. On the more traditional side, there is Mats Eden, a Swedish
musician who recorded waltzes and reels in his kitchen, offering a
pure interpretation of vintage accordion tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, this stuff is an acquired taste, but Furnwald says
that last year's festival attracted about 25,000 visitors each
week. The whole affair has the sort of quirky grassroots flavor
that used to define the Internet before it got commercial. Furnwald
doesn't make any money on the festival: He just does it because he
can. ``You could never pull this off before the Internet,'' he
says. ``Maybe you could do a worldwide Mariah Carey festival, but
you couldn't do a festival featuring avant-garde duets on the
accordion.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are those who would be happier with the guys in
the powder blue suits (there's one in every crowd). One visitor to
the festival message boards wrote: ``Forget about all the Finnish
nonsense, and Senegalese bongo drums, and whatever else this
festival thing is all about. What the world needs is more Lawrence
Welk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does the world really need another entertainment Web site
offering TV-style programming? The answer is an emphatic maybe _
especially if they're offering programs for college-educated
zombies. (Trust me on this one.)
</P>
<P>
   The latest entry to the online entertainment field is
Icebox.com, a site staffed by writers and producers with credits on
such shows as ``The Simpsons,'' ``Seinfeld,'' and ``The X-Files.''
Icebox is producing animated shorts for the Internet, with the hope
that one or two of these shows will be picked up by a major
network.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they might as well get in line.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in Hollywood is trying to figure out how to exploit
this new medium, and so far, there have been some pretty dramatic
failures. DEN and Pixelon folded last month after burning through
piles of money. Other companies that offer short liveaction videos,
like iFilm.com and Atom Films, have yet to attract a mainstream
following.
</P>
<P>
   But still, everyone wants to produce the next ``Blair Witch
Project,'' so the sites keep launching. Icebox cofounder Howard
Gordon says the idea was born ``out of the ashes of despair.'' The
former executive producer for ``The X-Files'' had just finished
writing a 13-episode show called ``Strange World''; it ran briefly
on ABC before it was yanked from the air. ``I didn't want to be
restricted by time slots and ratings,'' Gordon says.
</P>
<P>
   Icebox recruited an impressive staff of writers to produce a
roster of irreverent material. ``Our two mandates are no porn and
no hate,'' says Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, animation is far superior to live action video,
but Icebox still has some kinks in its technology. It crashed my
browser eight times in an hour, and sometimes the sound didn't
work. ``The bugs will be ironed out,'' Gordon says. ``They better
be, or we are doomed.''
</P>
<P>
   And a show has to be really compelling in order for folks to put
up with computer bugs. Here's the Icebox lineup, saving the best
for last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hidden Celebrity Webcam'' _ Imagine a camera in the freezer
of, say, President Clinton or Calista Flockhart. Not exactly food
for thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senior House'' _ Geezers fight the evil landlord. Kidney jokes
abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superhero Roommate'' _ A slacker gets up off the couch to
throw out the garbage, and he turns into a superhero. As plot-free
as ``Seinfeld,'' without the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heaven'' _ ``Cheers'' with dead presidents, princesses, and a
laugh track. Featuring the great Shakespearean actor, Kato Kaelin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard Drinkin' Lincoln'' _ The great emancipator stars as a
raging alcoholic; like Kenny in ``South Park,'' he dies in every
episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garbage Island'' _ A promising show about a world where it's
Christmas every day. A little boy tries desperately to hold onto
his old rag doll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zombie College'' _ The story of Scott and Zelda, two
all-American kids who end up at a university where the undead
mingle with the zombies. The humor is dead-on funny; when our hero
announces that he was attacked by a zombie, his girlfriend asks,
``Was she prettier than me?'' Over in the 24-hour snack shack, the
students devour livers and other organs; these fun-loving kids
enjoy munching on eyeballs, and the show just might attract enough
eyeballs to establish a following for Icebox.
</P>
<P>
   But first they have to iron out the bugs _ or maggots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
