<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA PLANS A SURPRISE PARTY FOR MOSLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shane Mosley has boxed more than 60 rounds with
Oscar De La Hoya, sparring with him repeatedly during their
formative years in Los Angeles when each was an amateur champion
hoping for a moment like the one that awaits each of them Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Out of those many rounds, Mosley believes he has learned all
there is to know about the WBC welterweight champion he will fight
for glory (and $4.5 million) at the Staples Center. Mosley believes
he understands De La Hoya's speed of hand and foot and how they
work against an opponent. Mosley believes he understands how De La
Hoya's mind works. Mosley believes he understands how De La Hoya's
sets up a fighter and how he destroys one after he has set his
trap.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley believes, in other words, that nothing De La Hoya can do
to him will surprise him Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the amiable business partner, De La Hoya didn't want to
disagree with his foil Wednesday. Instead, he merely pointed out
that in eight years a few things may have changed that Shane Mosley
will learn about the hard way, the same hard way most lessons in
boxing are learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's seen everything, he certainly hasn't felt it,'' De La
Hoya said of the undefeated former lightweight champion's opinion
of him. ``My power is stronger. I'm not the same fighter I was at
19. And it's not the same feeling when you're wearing 8-ounce
gloves (rather than 20-ounce training gloves). My punches hurt a
lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has made that point to 26 of his 33 opponents,
knocking them all flat while running up a 32-1 record and winning
world championships in four weight classes. It is a point he
intends to make once again at Mosley's expense. He has promised to
fight four times and produce four knockouts this year. To do it, he
must knock out a fighter who is 34-0 and claims to have never even
been knocked off his feet in 20 years in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   This knockout promise is all part of the latest version of De La
Hoya, who seems to repackage himself every year or two. The ``new''
De La Hoya is actually a resurrection of the old one who knocked
people out with a nasty left hook and a nastier uppercut when he
was fighting at 130 and 135 pounds. The problem is, as he's made
his way up to 147 (winning four world titles along the way), his
punch seems to have taken the road less traveled and that has made
all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Or so Shane Mosley believes.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has knocked out fewer and fewer people as he has
moved up. He has beaten people into submission, to be sure, but
since he became a junior welterweight in 1997 De La Hoya has gone
the distance five times and was unable to stop Pernell Whitaker,
Ike Quartey, or Felix Trinidad, arguably his three toughest
opponents at 147 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them, Whitaker and Trinidad, were never even hurt by him.
So one wonders if the power he says Mosley will feel is still with
him.
</P>
<P>
   To try and preserve it, De La Hoya has gone on a specially
designed eating plan formulated by the people from Met-Rx, the
supplement kings of professional sports. Dr. Scott Connelly,
founder of Met-Rx Engineered Nutrition, designed a program he
claims is specifically built to overcome the problems Mosley poses,
problems that will require De La Hoya to have both increased power
and muscle endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Since the guy has never had 6 ounces of fat anywhere on his
body, it's difficult to see how nutritional changes will produce
noticeable changes in De La Hoya's power or its effect on Mosley,
although Connelly insisted Wednesday, ``His endurance and power
have increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but De La Hoya was working with the Met-Rx people
before his fight with Trinidad. By the end of it, he claimed he
could barely raise his arms and fought like it, hence one has to
wonder. But De La Hoya insisted Mosley may have his own things to
wonder about once the fighting begins, the biggest one being that
some things never change. Another is that he was better than Mosley
in 1992 and he's better than him today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say we fought (when De La Hoya was 11 and Mosley 12),''
De La Hoya said, feigning ignorance of it all. ``I have no idea. If
he won, great! Good for him. He was older. He was heavier. He
should have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Colorado Springs (when they were training for the 1992
Olympic team), we'd stay in the same building, but he was always on
the `B' team and I was on the `A' team, so I don't really know him
much.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya smiles the assassin's smile as he slips that stiletto
in. The truth is Mosley was on the ``A'' team at 139 pounds, as was
De La Hoya at 132. But when the Olympic Trials came, only De La
Hoya survived, going on to become the United States' only gold
medalist in Barcelona. Mosley, who failed to defeat Vernon Forrest
in the Olympic Trials, became a struggling six-round professional
for a time, while De La Hoya became boxing's Golden Boy from his
first pro fight.
</P>
<P>
   Although De La Hoya says it subtly, he says it all the same.
When their first big night came, only one of them delivered. Shane
Mosley knows that, too, as De La Hoya tries to make clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a great fighter to bring out the best in me,'' De La
Hoya said. ``Maybe Shane Mosley is the one. Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``He says the first round could be like (Marvin) Hagler-(Thomas)
Hearns. Fine. I can take a punch and I know I can bang with
anybody. What I trained for is to throw combinations and come
forward. If he's in my way, you'll see a hell of a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to talk. It's always more difficult when the event
comes, especially a big event. You can talk the talk, but can you
walk the walk? That's a question I always ask my opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has been asked that question by several opponents who
have knocked him down, including Quartey. His response has been to
get up and return fire, knocking Quartey flat in the final round to
carry the night in a tough fight against a tough opponent, the kind
Mosley knows nothing about because he has never faced such a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Not until Saturday night at least, when he will walk into the
ring thinking he knows all there is to know about a guy who
believes he has a few surprises left in him for an old friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience brings a lot to the table,'' De La Hoya said.
``Every great fighter has been knocked down and had to get up. It's
hard. I don't know how he'll react if it happens. Neither does he.
He doesn't know how that feels yet.''
</P>
<P>
   No he doesn't, but if Oscar De La Hoya is true to his promise,
Shane Mosley will get the chance to learn something new about him .
. . and perhaps something new about himself as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
