<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ'S TALENT HIDDEN BY OTHERS' EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some days you go to work, put in your time, and leave
with a single thought: People are crazy. Wednesday in the Bronx,
Red Sox employee No. 45 finished his six-inning shift and nearly
had the thought himself.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old employee's name is Pedro Martinez. He is good at
what he does. Maybe he is at the point where he is so good that
people don't recognize how good he really is. His work is done in
stadiums, while standing on a raised mound of dirt. But he has
flourishes of genius that make you think the mound is actually an
elevated stage at the Apollo or the Village Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday at Yankee Stadium, you could say he was in
business-casual mode: six innings, one run. He was rewarded with a
no-decision in the 2-1 loss to the Yankees. If another pitcher has
a day like that, reporters sidle up to them afterward and request
details on the brilliant day. Martinez, though, asked if his
performance disappointed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I? A robot?'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, he stood in the middle of the visiting
clubhouse, still confused by the question. Disappointed? Why would
someone think that? ``I'm telling you, 80 times out of 100 _ well,
I'm not going to say 80. I'll say 90. Ninety times out of 100, if
you have a pitcher give you six innings and one run he's going to
win the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He still had the faint smile as he walked away. It must be true.
People are crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like people expect him to be Michael Jordan every time or
something,'' said coworker Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Another coworker, Carl Everett, was more blunt: ``When you're as
good as he is, people are going to ask you stupid things. Who asked
him if he was disappointed? That was dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he wanted to, Pedro couldn't be the new Jordan. There's
not enough patience for that. Jordan was scheduled to perform 82
times per season, which means that a few ``off'' nights _ which
really weren't true, Acie Earl off-nights _ were expected. Martinez
hasn't had 82 starts in his Boston career. (He has made 74.)
</P>
<P>
   Each time he takes the mound, he is shrouded with a torrent of
expectations. Baseball fans see his 0.99 ERA and praise him as one
of the few men capable of stopping the Home Run Plague that has
swept through the majors. Dominicans in Boston and New York wave
flags when he pitches. There is a Cuban restaurant in Boston where,
on the wall, a smiling Pedro is pictured with the owner. (Pedro is
so good that he is good for business.)
</P>
<P>
   I am sure, even subconsciously, the Sox have unrealistic
expectations for him. They always expect him to be the man who wins
a series or stops a losing streak. They depend on him too much.
They have given him eight runs in his last four starts, so it's
amazing that he has a 2-1 record and one no-decision in that span.
He can't be the employee who covers everyone's shift.
</P>
<P>
   The easy thing to say after Wednesday's loss was that the team
could use Sammy Sosa. Not true. This season Sosa has struck out 70
times, an amount that comes close to equaling the combined
strikeout totals of Nomar Garciaparra and Everett. The Sox could
use a high-average, high-contact, low-strikeout hitter more than
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   They could also use a non-Tim Wakefield type to finish off
Martinez's starts. Nothing against the knuckleballer, but
Martinez-to-Wakefield is not what I consider a secure relay
combination. Wakefield is Norman Rockwell to Martinez's Jean-Michel
Basquiat: Both are fine artists, but combining the two doesn't
work.
</P>
<P>
   When Wakefield entered Wednesday's game in the seventh, I
immediately empathized with thousands of nervous Sox fans who I
imagined screaming, ``No, Jimy!'' at their televisions. Wakefield
gave up the winning home run to Tino Martinez in the eighth, even
though lefthander Rheal Cormier was available.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the ending anyone expected on Pedro Day. At times, he
was so good that he was able to be pitcher and analyst. He looked
at Roger Clemens in the first and wondered, ``What's wrong with
Roger?'' He said the Yankee starter looked ``awful.'' He was right;
Clemens had a strained right groin and left the game after an
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also didn't look good early. After the first inning, an
inning in which he walked in a run for the first time since 1998,
he was surrounded by a Sox tribunal on the bench. Joe Kerrigan, Jim
Rowe, and John Cumberland circled him, wondering about the shaky
first.
</P>
<P>
   Four innings later, Martinez was laughing on the mound. It made
you wonder if there was a portable DVD player tucked in his glove,
showing his favorite comedy. But he was giggling at home plate
umpire Dan Morrison's call of ``ball'' on a pitch that rested over
the middle of the plate. Chuck Knoblauch got a reprieve on the
call. A brief reprieve. Martinez eventually struck him out.
</P>
<P>
   There were 54,834 fans in the Bronx, but you could sense
individual disappointment when Martinez left after six innings.
Everyone wanted a little more, which is always the case when you
regularly produce greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Did Martinez want to keep pitching?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just an employee,'' he said. ``I work here. They tell me
what to do. I'm an employee.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on days like Wednesday, he is the best employee in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
