<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GETTING AHEAD AT WORK WITH AN END RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you look back at Steve Young's years with the
San Francisco 49ers, you can learn a lot about your own career,
even if you don't know the difference between a safety blitz and a
cheese blintz.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that Young has played his last game (you can never be
too sure about an athlete's retirement), his years as the 49ers'
star quarterback were not as glorious as he deserved. Young's
career was more bittersweet, just like your average Joe's.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few things you can learn from it:
</P>
<P>
   _ Know your predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   It took Young's series of concussions to knock some sense into
49er fans. Until then, a lot of them didn't appreciate just how
talented he was.
</P>
<P>
   That is what happens when you follow Joe Montana. Young was one
of the greatest quarterbacks in football history, but he didn't win
the four Super Bowls that Montana did. He won only one, which is
still one more than a lot of other great players.
</P>
<P>
   When you are interviewing for a job, find out whatever you can
about your predecessor. Was she universally loved and respected, or
were even the atheists tempted to say ``thank God'' when she walked
out the door? Did he leave because of a logical move up, or did he
just quit in frustration?
</P>
<P>
   This is a time when networking can be a huge help. If you can
talk to people who worked with your potential predecessor _ or,
better yet, to the predecessor _ you will know what you are getting
into. You'll also have a better grasp of the job, which can help
you give better answers during the interview.
</P>
<P>
   If your network is no help and you are not desperate to land the
job, ask your interviewer about the predecessor. If the answer
seems vague or unresponsive, ask to speak with him. If you get some
mumbled answer about not knowing how to reach him, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   Young knew what he was getting into, of course. He chose to take
the challenge, and you might, too. You just don't want to get
blindsided.
</P>
<P>
   Managers also have to make sure they don't show the same lack of
appreciation that 49er fans often did. If you replace a terrific
salesperson with one who is also terrific, it's easy to take the
second one for granted. You won't realize your mistake until the
second one feels unappreciated and leaves, and you find yourself
hiring someone who is only average.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sometimes you have to yell to get your boss's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the 1994 season, as the 49ers were getting clobbered by
the Philadelphia Eagles, then-coach George Seifert pulled Young out
of the game. The normally low-key Young screamed on the sidelines,
feeling like the scapegoat for a miserable team effort.
</P>
<P>
   He and Seifert soon worked things out, and the Eagles loss
became the turning point of the season. The 49ers went on to win
the Super Bowl that year.
</P>
<P>
   Screaming at your boss is rarely a good idea, but sometimes you
have to resort to extreme measures to get your voice heard. Even a
confrontation often is better than being miserable in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Before any confrontation, though, think about what you hope to
gain, and whether the potential damage is worth it. Is the issue
something that will haunt you for years, or will it blow over in a
week?
</P>
<P>
   Young's anger drew so much attention because it was so rare. If
you get a reputation for bellyaching, though, you'll never be able
to scream loud enough to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Understand what makes you special.
</P>
<P>
   Even if your predecessor was a superstar, you can still
distinguish yourself if you emphasize those things that you do
spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   Young was a terrific passer, of course, but his most famous play
was probably a 49-yard touchdown run against the Minnesota Vikings
back in 1988. You didn't know who would pass out first: Young or
announcer Lon Simmons, trying to describe the play on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   It was Young at his most spectacular, eluding defenders,
breaking tackles and going through a ``Perils of Pauline'' routine
before finally staggering into the end zone. It showed his speed,
his elusiveness and his stamina, but most of all it showed his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   No other Super Bowl-winning quarterback could have made that
run. Not even Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
