<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4804 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-BOYSGIRLS16-CO     06-15 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOYSGIRLS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An old-fashioned romantic comedy in college attire
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the young leads of ``Boys and Girls'' had ever watched ``When
Harry Met Sally,'' they could've saved us at least an hour. Ryan
(Freddie Prinze Jr.) and Jennifer (Claire Forlani) spend most of
their movie's running time ignoring the fact that, as the most
photogenic and articulate of the screen characters, it's their
Hollywood imperative to quit bantering and get into bed.
</P>
<P>
   A peculiarly old-fashioned romantic comedy trapped in college
clothing, ``Boys and Girls'' throws in one innovative switch by
reversing gender roles. Here it's Jennifer who's the casual
one-night-stander and Ryan the near-virginal ingenue who natters on
about having ``to work at love if you want it to last.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie predictably trashes this switcheroo by making Jennifer
change her ways. In the last reel it's the girl who chases the boy,
proving her love by giving up her plans for travel and further
study. Gee, maybe in the sequel we'll get to watch Jennifer make
Ryan breakfast or clean their condo while he goes to his important
job in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The two meet as cute young adolescents, airplane seatmates en
route from New York to their hometown, Los Angeles. Feisty Jennifer
explains that she almost missed the flight because ``I got my first
period.'' It's a brusque little intro that actually doesn't reflect
the rest of the movie's squishy dialogue. You might wish for some
of the grosser excesses of ``Road Trip'' or ``American Pie'' just
to stay awake.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer and Ryan keep running into each other, first in high
school, then in college at Berkeley, which seems to have been
chosen primarily for its proximity to pretty San Francisco. These
kids never study. They spend their time walking around scenic spots
in the Golden Gate city, drinking coffee in cool cafes and checking
out the dance clubs. Though neither of them appears to own a car,
they hang out around the Marin County headlands across the bay,
miles from campus; that's probably because its scenic view is
almost as pretty as their movie star faces.
</P>
<P>
   Prinze is charming but bland; he can't fill in the blanks that
shortchange his character. It's surprising that none of Ryan's
classmates speculate that this handsome, non-dating dude might
actually be gay. Forlani, who has the wittier role, also scores the
livelier performance.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Detmer makes an impression as Forlani's live-wire
roommate, though the script never decides whether she's just wacky
or seriously in need of psychotropic medication. As Prinze's
roomie, Jason Biggs of ``American Pie'' plays a buffoon who lies to
impress girls. Like Detmer, he suffers from having to play a
character who's never developed beyond easy comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Heather Donahue, of ``The Blair Witch Project,'' as
a very brief romantic interest for Ryan. In this flick, she doesn't
scream or cry, but shows some skill at playing comic neurosis.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, her appearance might finally hush those
gullibles who still think she really did disappear in those
Maryland woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys and Girls''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Freddie Prinze Jr. and Claire Forlani. Rated PG-13 for
sexual content. 1 hour, 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A predictable romantic comedy for the Clearasil
set.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4805 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-HONOR16-COX     06-15 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HONOR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Horrific stories tell how POWs won their war
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It doesn't matter which side you were on during the Vietnam War.
Hawks and doves alike will be amazed by the emotionally compelling
documentary ``Return With Honor.'' And honor is the operative word
here. This movie is a record of honorable behavior by honorable men
under unspeakable circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   What Academy Award winners Frieda Lee Mock and Terry Sanders
(for the documentary ``Maya Lin: A Strong Clear Vision'') have done
is interview 20 or so American pilots who were shot down during the
war and spent anywhere from four to eight years as prisoners of
war. Interwoven into their testimonies are remarkable archival
materials: North Vietnamese newsreels documenting their captivity;
drawings made from memory by one of the former prisoners;
television clips from the era showing everything from raging
politicians to raging anti-war protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The most astonishing _ and disturbing _ stuff is the footage
made available by the now-friendly Vietnamese government. Much like
the Nazis, the North Vietnamese believed in recording their actions
for posterity as potent propaganda fodder. We see them parading
their ``catches'' through an enraged civilian population, like
trophies brought home from a hunt. We watch as these battered men
are ushered into a makeshift TV studio to tape speeches, prepared
by their captors, for world consumption. (One POW outsmarted them
by blinking ``torture'' in Morse code.)
</P>
<P>
   The interviewees, who include Sen. John McCain and former vice
presidential candidate Jim Stockdale, are now middle-aged men,
looking incongruously content in their golf shirts. They speak with
the measured discipline and strength of character that enabled them
to survive the ``Hanoi Hilton,'' as they dubbed their prison. Their
stories are frankly horrific: beatings, torture, solitary
confinement. Yet these men can also be emotional and, at times,
even wryly humorous about their ordeal. Everett Alvarez, the first
pilot to be shot down and captured, figured that he would be
protected by the Geneva Convention, which set up international
rules governing the treatment of POWs. Then he was told he wasn't a
POW; he was a war criminal. Says Alvarez: ``I remember thinking,
`Whoops, what do I do now?'''
</P>
<P>
   As their numbers grew, they developed survival tactics. A
complex series of taps, coughs and sniffles to communicate.
Exercise regimens designed for a 6-foot cell. An annual Christmas
service consisting of the Lord's Prayer and the Pledge of
Allegiance. Their tacit agreement _ their slogan, if you will _
became the movie's title. They would return with honor. That is,
they would do nothing they would be ashamed to talk about once they
made it home.
</P>
<P>
   Both the men and the movie are remarkably apolitical, especially
considering that Vietnam can still be a flash point 30 years later.
What these heroic men seem to say is that the protesters and the
politicians were equally culpable. One pilot recalls being told by
his guards that the war would be won on the streets of New York
(cut to a huge anti-war march). Another recalls President Johnson
announcing to the world that the United States was going to resort
to air strikes right before his squadron left on its mission. ``We
took off knowing the Vietnamese knew we were coming.'' And then
there's the brave and tenacious cadre of POW wives, who had to
fight Congress tooth and nail to make their husbands' plight
public.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of listening to some 50-ish men talk about torture
and survival, pus and cockroaches, sounds grueling at best. But
``Return With Honor'' is anything but. Rather, it's a truly
thrilling picture, one that blasts all the special-effects heroics
of the summer blockbusters to vapid dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return With Honor''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by Frieda Lee Mock and Terry Sanders. Not rated,
but there are intense descriptions of torture and POW life. 1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Don't miss these amazing profiles in courage.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
