<HEADER>
A4809 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-PARADISE16-COX     06-15 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PARADISE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Visually rich story of blind boy tells a powerful fable
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a bit of intentional irony, a blind boy named Mohammad
(Mohsen Ramezani) is the central character of a visually rapturous
movie. ``The Color of Paradise'' engulfs his small frame in a
landscape whose intense beauty he can't himself see.
</P>
<P>
   Not with his eyes, anyway, but he's adept at communing with
nature _ his fingertips forever coaxing meaning from the world. He
deciphers hidden Braille letters in the bumpy pods of wheat and in
the pebbly surface of a stream bed. The cries of nesting birds
represent a secret language he hopes to unlock. You could say he's
more appreciative of the physical world than those whose eyes it
fills every day. It's a mystery he wants to crack.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian writer-director Majid Majidi (``The Children of
Heaven'') begins his moving drama in a drab urban setting: the
school for the blind where 8-year-old Mohammad waits for his father
long after the other children have been picked up by parents for
summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   When his widowed father, Hashem (Hossein Mahjoub), finally
arrives, he regards his son with a mixture of guilt, helplessness
and revulsion. You fear that the worst will come to pass.
``Paradise'' is filled with a nameless tension, as Hashem takes
Mohammad home to the family farm in the rolling mountains of
northern Iran, where his doting grandmother (Salime Feizi) and two
sisters show him all the love his father can't, or won't.
</P>
<P>
   For Hashem, Mohammad's blindness represents a personal shame,
failure. He sees his son as an obstacle to the marriage he's
arranging with the daughter of a local family. Like a guilty
secret, Mohammad is whisked out of sight, to the workshop of a
blind carpenter who agrees to teach him the trade. But all Mohammad
can feel is sorrow, abandoned (he thinks) by his family, and by the
deity who has brought him sightless into the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reach out everywhere for God,'' Mohammad cries, in the
movie's most powerful scene, an emotional passage played
heart-rendingly by young Ramezani (in his film debut).
</P>
<P>
   Filled with dread and beauty, ``The Color of Paradise'' summons
the power of a fable, suggesting that those with sight can be the
blindest of all. Stunningly shot by Mohammad Davudi, the film puts
an emphasis on young Mohammad's hands stretching out into the
natural world. Director Majidi uses his palette of sloping meadows
and animal sounds to terrific poetic effect. It's a movie you feel
as much as see.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Color of Paradise''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mohsen Ramezani and Hossein Mahjub. Rated PG for
thematic elements. In Persian with subtitles. 1 hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A gorgeous meditation on blindness, both physical
and spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
