<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-WOMEN16-COX     06-15 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-WOMEN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director lets self-indulgence color chilly `8 1/2'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time I took a pal to a Peter Greenaway movie _ ``The
Pillow Book'' _ the friendship almost ended. And I'm talking about
someone who not only endured but was actually intrigued by such
outer-limits fare as David Cronenberg's ``Crash'' and David Lynch's
``Lost Highway.''
</P>
<P>
   For myself, Greenaway has always been guilty perversion _ sort
of like a combination of a hidden heroin addiction and reading old
Archie comic books from the 1950s. I was knocked out by ``The
Draughtman's Contract,'' fascinated by ``Drowning by Numbers,''
admiring of ``Prospero's Books'' and even found something redeeming
in the immensely disturbing ``The Belly of the Architect.'' As for
Greenaway's relatively famous ``The Cook, the Thief, His Wife and
Her Lover,''
</P>
<P>
   I always thought of it as ``American Pie'' for art-movie lovers:
a gross-out flick with bite.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is a lengthy prologue to admitting that even I gave
up on Greenaway's newest film, ``8 1/2 Women.'' An homage of sorts
to Fellini's famed phantasmagoria ``8 1/2,'' Greenaway gives us a
wealthy father (John Standing) and satyric son (Matthew Delamere),
both bereaved by the recent death of their wife-mother. They seek
solace in each other's arms (literally), which sparks a better
idea: Why not turn dad's fancy Swiss mansion into a kind of fantasy
brothel? Bring out the funk, bring on the girls.
</P>
<P>
   The son, who manages some gambling houses in Japan, imports an
in-debt player (Shizuka Inoh), a no-nonsense businesswoman (Vivian
Wu from ``The Pillow Book'') and a woman (Kirina Mano) who longs to
be as ultrafeminine as a female impersonator from the kabuki
theater. Other additions include a nun shaved from head to toe
(Toni Collette from ``The Sixth Sense''), an injured equestrian
(Amanda Plummer) who loves horses and her giant pig, and a knowing
British professional call girl (Polly Walker). And so on. And so
on. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled throughout are the director's usual obsessions:
numbers, nudity, eroticism so chilly it's anti-erotic. And,
naturally, the film looks exquisite, even when there's nothing
worth looking at.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Greenaway is starting to remind me of the late Andy
Kaufman _ creating less for an audience than for himself. It's an
annoying selfishness that renders the viewer superfluous. ``8 1/2
Women'' isn't juicy enough to be appalling or even truly offensive.
But it's often downright boring. And there's something about its
open disdain that's insulting. If you're a Greenaway fan, you may
have to try it, but otherwise, there are more rewarding
``difficult'' movies out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``8 1/2 Women''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Standing. Directed by Peter Greenaway. Not rated,
but contains nudity and perverse sexual themes.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 56 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Peter Greenaway loses his grip.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Jorurnal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
