<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-MONTGOMERIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN '92, MONTGOMERIE CAME SO CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ When _ or if _ he prevails in a major
championship, Colin Montgomerie figures he has a sense of how it
will feel. After all, he experienced the sensation for a short
while when the US Open was played at Pebble Beach in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I holed a very good putt at the last hole, a 5-footer
left-to-right and I must admit, I felt over the putt that it was to
win the tournament,'' said Montgomerie, who was making his US Open
debut that year. The Scotsman converted the par-saving putt to
close with a 2-under 70 and finish at even-par 288, which observers
felt would be good enough given the winds had kicked up
ferociously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happened to play the first six holes without much wind,''
said Montgomerie. ``Six clear holes that the leaders didn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Tom Kite's 3-under total would plummet once he got into
the teeth of a wind that was howling at a steady 35 miles per hour.
None other than Jack Nicklaus offered congratulations to
Montgomerie, who finished as Kite was playing the fifth hole. It
proved to be a jinx of a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give credit to Tom Kite,'' said Montgomerie, not at all
haunted by the fact that Kite put together a 72 to finish at
3-under 285 to win his only major championship. ``And also to Jeff
Sluman (71_287), who played very, very well to take second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things. It could have happened, and it
just didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   It did, however, set him off on a wonderful run of US Open
appearances. He has made the cut in all eight of his starts, with
that third in 1992 alongside a second in 1997, a T-2 in 1994 when
he lost a playoff at Oakmont with Ernie Els, and a top 10 in 1996.
Only once has he finished outside the top 30.
</P>
<P>
   But Montgomerie knows that great players are measured by major
titles and on that count he is empty. He knows that, but tries to
keep things in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there's slightly more pressure on the situation, but it
won't affect me in any way, shape or form if I do happen to win a
major. I've just been unfortunate at the end that someone has done
better than me, and that's the way of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike 1992, Montgomerie does not come in here an unknown
entity. For seven straight years he has led the Order of Merit
(European Tour money list) and racked up 24 victories. As Seve
Ballesteros and Nick Faldo have faded from the world stage,
Montgomerie is the pride from across the pond, an exquisite
ball-striker and virtual top-10 lock every time he tees it up. No
doubt, he said, he's a much better player than the last time he
walked these links.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm stronger, I'm mentally stronger than I was, and
feel I can cope with the situation better than I could in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation in 1992 was such that no one would like to see a
repeat of it. Players such as Hale Irwin claim the final round that
year was ``over the top'' and virtually unplayable. USGA officials
do not disagree, but the problem was not course set-up, but a fluke
of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three days that year we had clouds and fog,'' said Tim
Moraghan of the USGA. ``Then, on Sunday, the winds whipped up and
dried out greens that were not very good to start with. The greens
now are totally different and that wouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Sindelar remembers standing on the tee at the 106-yard
seventh hole and watching Nick Faldo hit his shot over the green.
``Then I hit a 6-iron and heard the crowd go crazy. I didn't know
why until I found out I was the first guy in something like 20 to
put a ball on the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman said he had a long putt up a slope to the pin at the
back of the 17th green, but when he came up short, the wind blew
the ball right back at him. ``I had a 30-footer for birdie and a
40-footer for par,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kite stood to make a sure bogey at the seventh but his chip
across the green hit the pin and dropped for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   It's all just part of the mystique of golf, said Montgomerie.
``I've been through enough to learn and to cope with any situation
that's thrown against me. I just hope Lady Luck throws in a shot or
two to my side.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he is owed it?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think you're owed anything. You make your own luck
and your own game. But I'm a great believer that the winner has
never stood up and written a speech and said he was unlucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite true, though there was that time once when the third-place
finisher was congratulated on his victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
