<HEADLINE>
HERD MENTALITY RIDES ROUGHSHOD OVER SOME FIDELITY FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes `Losing ground' text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stockbrokers have an old saying about the market: The trend is
your friend. The people who sell mutual funds at Fidelity
Investments might be less sanguine on fashions of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Fund investors have been buying with a herd mentality for years
now. Aggressive growth funds are getting most of the new money on
the table today. Not long ago, the same winner-take-almost-all
psychology was pushing the chips into index funds.
</P>
<P>
   The trend of the moment has turned Janus Capital Corp. into a
powerhouse at the expense of most other mutual-fund companies.
Before Janus, the Vanguard Group soared on the popularity of
indexing.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Fidelity, so big it has funds of every stripe
investing serious amounts of money. The span of investments, more
than 250 funds, guarantees Fidelity will be simultaneously in and
out of favor as long as trends drive so much of America's
investing.
</P>
<P>
   The fund industry's giant appears locked in the middle of the
pack with no obvious way to get out.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, the world's biggest fund company, ranked seventh in
net sales through April, according to Financial Research Corp.
Those sales figures ranked third in Boston, trailing results at
Putnam Investments and MFS Investment Management.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has some big sales hits in its portfolio, principally
its two most visible aggressive growth funds and a handful of
sector funds. But the lion's share of those sales gains are
canceled out by money exiting less popular Fidelity funds,
particularly growth and income vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   No one is crying for Fidelity. It still pulled in nearly $3.7
billion in net new money through April and that figure increased to
more than $5.1 billion by the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
   But trend investing has created a mutual fund world with one
sales leader and a crowd of followers somewhere in the dust. Janus
and its pack of wildly popular growth funds pulled down more than
$32 billion through April, more than its next five competitors
combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just a growth shop like many of our competitors,''
said Fidelity spokeswoman Anne Crowley. ``If you look just at our
growth funds, which is what happens when you look at Janus, you
would see sales that are significant and competitive with others
focused just on that market.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's growth funds and sector funds, the parts of its
investment roster that would be compared head to head with Janus,
recorded net sales of $26 billion by the end of May. But start
subtracting elsewhere and you're back to that $5.1 billion
company-wide total.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor pushing Fidelity into the middle of the sales
pack: Most of its biggest funds aren't generating very much new
business.
</P>
<P>
   Calculate sales activity and investment performance among
Fidelity's 10 largest retail mutual funds and you will discover
seven of them managed less money by May 31 than they did at the
start of the year. As a group, they managed $16 billion less than
they did last Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The three largest funds, all a bit smaller now, are competing at
a disadvantage because they are technically closed to new
investors. But millions of customers can buy at least some of three
funds _ Magellan, Contrafund, and Growth and Income _ because they
remained open to existing shareholders and participants in some
retirement plans at the time they were closed.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's biggest sales winners, its Growth Company and
Aggressive Growth funds, appear to have generated net new sales in
the range of $13 billion through May and can compete dollar for
dollar with nearly any fund sold by Janus. They ranked second and
third through April, trailing only Janus Worldwide in net sales.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes a lot of sales to make up for the investors who are
giving up on value or growth and income oriented investment
products. Fidelity's Growth and Income fund alone has shrunk by
more than $6.6 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of actual investment performance, Fidelity can go head
to head as well. James Lowell, editor of Fidelity Investor, an
independent newsletter, said Fidelity's leading aggressive growth
funds are delivering better results than comparable Janus products
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to Fidelity's business, selling mutual funds,
the industry giant seems stuck in the middle of the pack as long it
offers big funds for every fashion in a world that has lost its
taste for diversification.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
LOSING GROUND
</P>
<P>
   (! used as column separator) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Assets under management at Fidelity's 10 largest retail mutual
funds on May 31 and Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ! May 31 ! Dec. 31 ! Change &QL; 
Magellan ! $100,939 ! $105,939 ! -$5,000 &QL; 
