<HEADER>
A4816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-WAR-RULES-HNS &LR;      06-15 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-RULES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WARRIORS NEED TO BE HELD ACCOUNTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GAIL BENSINGER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The 21st century has barely begun, and already
it promises to be just as bloody and war-raddled as all the others
that have gone before.
</P>
<P>
   Names many of us would be hard-put to find on a map _ Congo,
Sierra Leone, Colombia, Sri Lanka _ continue to yield a ghastly
toll in body counts and interrupted lives and failed governments.
</P>
<P>
   And yet war, like other human institutions, has evolved.
Consider this fact: During World War I, at the beginning of the
20th century, 90 percent of those who died were wearing uniforms.
Many of them died of something other than actual warfare _ bad
medicine or influenza or accidents _ but the overwhelming number of
victims were combatants.
</P>
<P>
   At century's end, however, 90 percent of the victims in the
collapse of the former Yugoslavia were civilians, intentionally
turned into targets as former neighbors turned murderous. The
century that began with ``the war to end all wars'' moved on to
``genocide'' and ended with ``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way we acquired verbal shorthand for the slaughter of
noncombatants: the Holocaust, of course, but also Dresden and
Hiroshima and the Blitz, My Lai and the Khmer Rouge, the intifada
and the contras and the disappeared, Northern Ireland and Rwanda
and East Timor. General populations became the targets, not the
``collateral damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Two types of warfare are waged these days, high-tech and
low-tech, and civilians are at risk in both.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech warfare, obviously, belongs to the United States and
the other industrialized nations capable of conducting assaults
without ever having to see the whites of the enemy's eyes. Kosovo
was the most obvious example, but so are Chechnya and the
continuing bombardments of Iraq. Precision bombing and missile
technology are the chief weapons in such arsenals. The point is for
the country waging such a war not to lose any troops on the ground,
or indeed even to have any troops on the ground until after the
shooting stops and the post-war ``peacekeeping'' begins.
</P>
<P>
   Low-tech warfare is far messier, both to combatants and to the
general population. Very occasionally, as in Ethiopia and Eritrea,
such a war involves two opposing armies. More common is for one
side _ or both _ to be some sort of insurgency movement with a
loose sense of organization, and much of the killing is up close
and personal.
</P>
<P>
   The byproducts of such a war are horrific: rape camps, child
soldiers, mutilations, forced removals of entire populations,
intentional starvation, land mining, destruction of farmland and
livestock, decimation of religious and cultural monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to this insidious stew is the economic system that
sustains such warfare. Arms are easy to get in the international
bazaar, but they are expensive. Governments of impoverished nations
at war don't pay for health care and education and clean water and
other things that would make civilians' lives better. Insurgencies
raise money through illegal sales of commodities that find plenty
of customers in the First World _ diamonds, emeralds, oil, timber,
gold, drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet alongside the evolution of warfare from dueling armies to
endangered civilians, another 20th-century idea has developed:
accountability. The Geneva conventions and all the other pacts and
treaties that comprise the growing body of international
humanitarian law, or IHL, set out the rules for warfare and the
treatment of combatants and civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The codification of such law does not prevent war or keep it
from taking its terrible toll. But the existence of rules and
war-crimes tribunals to try the people who break them gives the
world a methodology for making sure those responsible do not get
away with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon pays attention to IHL in its planning for high-tech
warfare. Troops get briefings on war law and war crimes as part of
combat training. In planning each action, military lawyers versed
in IHL sit in command centers next to officers selecting targets
for high-tech sorties. Such vetting didn't prevent such spectacular
lapses as last year's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade,
but attention is being paid.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of televised war and instant information,
investigations of possible war crimes have been speeded up, too.
Rather than wait until unconditional surrender, as was the case in
the Nuremburg trials in Germany after World War II, investigators
now begin collecting evidence while the shooting is going on.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, refugees were interviewed as soon as they came over
the border for information that could lead to the pursuit of war
criminals _ for example, possible sites of mass killings and
descriptions of those conducting forced removals.
</P>
<P>
   Two international tribunals are pursuing war criminals from
Bosnia and Rwanda. Both courts are slow and bureaucratic, and many
of the worst perpetrators have yet to be arrested, much less tried.
But both have full dockets, grinding away at crimes against
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   A permanent Rome-based tribunal, known as the International
Criminal Court, was approved in 1998, although it is yet to get
under way. That court is seriously hampered by the fact that the
United States refuses to participate, on grounds that it never
wants to see any of its own soldiers tried by foreign jurists.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will the United States participate in a number of other
international protocols for curbing war's excesses, such as child
soldiers (the Pentagon recruits 17-year-olds, and the accord sets
18 as the minimum age) and land mines (the United States still uses
them).
</P>
<P>
   Such tribunals and conventions setting out the international
rules of warfare probably have little effect on the mayhem caused
by wars waged on TV screens or out of public view. But the people
pulling the strings are as aware of the rules as the Pentagon
commanders sitting in war rooms with lawyers at their sides.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident that in agreeing to a peace deal he had no
intention of observing, Sierra Leone insurgency leader Foday Sankoh
negotiated himself an amnesty for the war crimes he had already
committed. He watches CNN and listens to the BBC, too.
</P>
<P>
   Tribunals are imperfect ways to pursue justice, but they are
certainly better than just sweeping war crimes away with the debris
of history. Other experiments _ South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission and the legal pursuit of former Chilean
strongman Augusto Pinochet _ demonstrate a hunger for
accountability once the shooting stops.
</P>
<P>
   And the shooting will stop someday, in every war, everywhere.
War is not the normal state of affairs, even in places where armed
thugs are right now taking potshots at neighbors or whacking off
their limbs or forcing their women into sexual slavery.
</P>
<P>
   We shouldn't assume, ever, that since war is so prevalent, the
world can do nothing about the particular crimes of people who
cause these things to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting will stop. And somewhere else, sometime soon, it
will start again. Every time that warfare spills beyond the bounds
of international humanitarian law, the transgressors should be held
accountable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gail Bensinger is the foreign/national editor of the San
Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4817 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-15 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CRUELTIES OF THE ESTATE TAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For naked class warfare, it is hard to beat the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to give a prize for the single worst idea to come
forward from a group that's been rife with them, it would be
this,'' fumed US Rep. Barney Frank as the House voted by a healthy
margin to phase out the federal tax on inheritances. ``Their idea
is this: `Let's make the tax code of America better for very rich
people. Let's give substantial tax relief to the richest people we
can find.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Does Frank really believe that? ``The richest people we can
find'' don't pay death taxes, and neither do their heirs. They hire
estate planners and take advantage of the Internal Revenue Code's
loopholes to make sure that most of their wealth does not go to
Uncle Sam when they shuffle off this mortal coil. So well known is
this effect among economists that two prominent ones _ the
Brookings Institution's Henry Aaron and Alicia Munnell of Boston
College, a former member of President Clinton's Council of Economic
Advisers _ have actually described estate taxes not as taxes but as
``penalties imposed on those who neglect to plan ahead or who
retain unskilled estate planners.''
</P>
<P>
   The super rich, and those whose families have long been wealthy,
can always arrange their affairs to minimize the tax bite. But it
is a particular cruelty of the estate tax to fall most heavily on
those whose wealth is newly acquired, or who may not even have
realized they were ``rich.''
</P>
<P>
   By way of example, Kerri Houston of the Institute for Policy
Innovation describes a farmer, land-rich but cash-poor, who lives
modestly and works hard. At his death, he passes to his children
his only meaningful asset _ his land. ``Although our farmer eked
out an income of just $40,000 last year, he had the misfortune of
purchasing his land a quarter-century ago,'' Houston writes. ``It
is now worth $800,000, and Uncle Sam wants $56,500 of it. Now.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a nightmare scenario for small business owners. A 1995
survey on the impact of estate taxes found that 51 percent of
family businesses would have trouble surviving the death of a
principal owner, largely because of taxes. Thirty percent of
respondents said they would have to sell all or part of the
business to pay the tax bill; 14 percent said they would have to
shut the business down.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only the heirs who suffer, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the death of our founder,'' says W. J. Grundy, the former
chairman of Jomac Inc., a manufacturer of protective gloves, ``we
spent over $3 million to redeem stock so estate taxes could be paid
and control of the company could be maintained. This was $3 million
not available for operations, and the division in trouble was sold
_ reducing our employment by about 30 employees and our sales by
about $5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   It may please the class warriors to imagine that death taxes
sting only the rich. Those 30 laid-off Jomac employees know better.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton promises a quick veto if the estate tax repeal
reaches his desk. (A Senate vote hasn't yet been scheduled.) ``The
House has jeopardized our fiscal discipline'' with its ``costly,
irresponsible, and regressive plan,'' he said after the vote last
week.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the tax nets the Treasury almost nothing. It brings in
just $23 billion a year, or a little more than 1 percent of federal
revenues. Of each dollar raised, more than 65 cents is eaten up in
``compliance costs'' _ the expenses of collection and
administration. If the estate tax were wiped out tomorrow, the
Treasury would barely hiccup. Which is not to say repeal wouldn't
cause some pain: The 16,000 members of the American Bar Association
who specialize in trust, probate, and estate law would doubtless be
very sorry indeed if Americans no longer had to spend lavishly to
protect their families from the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, the estate tax should be abolished not
because of finances or economics, but as a matter of simple
decency. It rewards the worst kind of behavior, while punishing
parents for doing something admirable and deeply rooted in human
nature: leaving the fruit of their labor to their children.
</P>
<P>
   A multimillionaire who wants to avoid all death taxes can
readily do so without even hiring a lawyer: He can simply spend all
his wealth before he dies. A recent bestseller _ ``Die Broke'' _
advises doing just that. The estate tax cannot reach the wealth of
someone who uses it to finance a life of luxury and indolence,
spending instead of saving. A rational tax code would smile on
individuals who work hard, live simply, and save for the future.
Ours rewards the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, the estate tax has been repealed in 20 states,
including such liberal bastions as Oregon, Vermont, and
Massachusetts. It has recently been abolished in Canada, Australia,
and Israel. It ought to be junked in America as well. Any tax that
penalizes people who provide for their families is immoral and
indefensible. One that does so at the very hour when those families
are bent with grief is not only senseless but sadistic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Jacoby is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
