<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT SO EASY GOING GLOBAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apart from the occasional dose of carpet-bombing, America hasn't
had much of a foreign policy since the Berlin Wall fell. But our
nation's big-time Internet companies are cobbling together their
own approach to international relations. They'd better. The rest of
the world is rapidly logging on to the Internet, and they have no
particular inclination for doing things the American way.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, watch out for those wily Europeans. ``They're
coming after us,'' warns Charles Baxter, president and CEO of
eTranslate Inc. of San Francisco. ``In the last four or five years,
they've all heard about how America can do no wrong... Their best
scientists, their best researchers, they're getting one-way tickets
to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Europe wants revenge. Ironically fortified with streams of
American venture capital, European companies are storming onto the
Internet. Their first goal is to secure dominance in their own
countries, hauling down the Yahoo flag and replacing it with
strange, alien banners like France's Wannadoo. After that, they can
copy America's playbook and begin to expand globally. The deal by
Spain's Terra Networks to acquire Waltham's Lycos Inc. is a good
example.
</P>
<P>
   The best defense for American Web firms is to intensify their
own international efforts. That's where companies like eTranslate
come in. They're in the tiny but promising business of Web
globalization. They make sure that a company's Internet message
doesn't get lost when translated into another language and culture.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a matter of translating the Drudge Report into
Urdu, either. The minute you switch languages, you introduce a raft
of Web design issues that the typical American never thinks about.
For instance, there's the problem of ``text swelling.'' According
to Baxter, the typical English sentence becomes 40 percent longer
when it's translated into German. That forces a complete rethink of
your page design.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a simple case. What happens when you go to Japan?
People there read text in two different directions _ from the top
down as well as left to right. In Israel, people read right to
left. Each national Web site has to take these issues into account.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's our casual assumption that people in the rest of
the world share our corn-fed tastes in symbols and images. ``The
AOL mailbox, that's a mailbox that comes straight off a farm in
Nebraska,'' Baxter says. Even most Americans don't have mailboxes
like that, but at least we recognize them. In other parts of the
world, the Mayberry look is totally alien. AOL uses the image of an
envelope on its French Web site, but sports the traditional mailbox
at AOL Japan. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Even colors are in play. Baxter notes that Web designers should
go easy on green backgrounds when creating sites aimed at Islamic
users, because the color green is a traditional symbol of that
religion.
</P>
<P>
   If you're selling online, how do you deliver the goods? ``In
Japan, few people are comfortable having goods delivered to their
homes,'' says Donald DePalma, vice president of corporate strategy
of Idiom Inc., a globalization firm in Cambridge, Mass. ``Instead
they have goods delivered to the nearest convenience store.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a company's marketing approach has to change. Ron
Sege, senior vice president at Lycos, says that his company's
Tripod free Web site service is used in America mainly by
hobbyists. But in southeast Asia, it's especially popular with
political activists, and so Tripod is marketed there as a way for
the little guy to have a say on the big issues.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even though America rules the desktops, wireless is
the wave of the future. International Data Corp. predicts that by
2004, 1.3 billion people worldwide will use cell phones with
browsers to visit the Internet. And obviously, most of them won't
be Americans. Already, the Japanese have leapfrogged us with a
technology called i-mode, that allows cell phone users to stay
connected to the Internet all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all American Web sites are designed for use on desktop
computer monitors. But the future of the Internet will be written
on screens just two inches wide. And there's a good chance it won't
be written in English.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
