<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4820 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      06-15 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURING PIPES SOFTLY WILL REDUCE RATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am getting a rattling sound in the pipe in one of my
bathrooms when I turn on the hot water. The bathrooms are stacked
on top of each other on three floors, but only one bathroom is
affected. How can I stop that?
</P>
<P>
   STEVE WEBLER, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's a common complaint with plumbing: When water flows, it
tends to vibrate the pipe, and if the pipe is not properly secured,
the pipe may bump the wood stud or any other wood through which it
passes, or bump its anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Securing the pipe is the answer, which is difficult because the
pipes are hidden in the wall. But sometimes you can secure exposed
pipes, say in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   While it is important to secure the pipe, it is also important
to secure it firmly but gently. If it is held too tightly, more
noise may result, from flowing water or from expansion and
contraction. To gently secure the pipe, line the holder with a soft
rubber sleeve, which will cushion the blows of the bumping pipe.
Or, use foam-tube pipe insulation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The red cedar shingles on the north side of my house are not
curled or warped, but brother, they look horrible. They are
untreated and very dark. How can I make them new-looking again and
keep them new-looking?
</P>
<P>
   BARRY CARLE, Hingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Red cedar shingles do not weather very well, resulting
usually in a blotchy black, red, brown, tan, and gray combo.
Really, a mess. OK, to bring them back to new-looking and to stay
new-looking, apply a coat of CWF (clear wood finish), widely sold
in paint stores. This may turn the shingles to an orange color. If
you like that, fine.
</P>
<P>
   There is another way to get them better looking: Wash the
shingles with a solution of one part household bleach and three
parts water. This will kill and remove any black mold, but will
also bleach the shingles. Then let them continue to weather or
apply bleaching oil; only one coat is needed and in most cases no
future coats are needed. This oil will provide a uniform light-gray
color, and allow further weathering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I moved into a handsome Greek Revival farmhouse, and
discovered that someone put a layer of 1/4-inch-thick real brick
around the fireplace and chimney. It is ugly and very fake-looking.
Can I paint it?
</P>
<P>
   RUTH KAUMEHEIWA, Weymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can paint the thin brick because it is real brick. You
could do the same if it were plastic. To paint, apply a latex
enamel undercoat, then finish with an eggshell-finish latex wall
paint. You will probably need a second coat of the eggshell wall
paint. As always, thin coats succeed, thick ones do not.
</P>
<P>
   Some day, when you get tired of the paint, you can pry off that
thin stuff, sand or scrape off the adhesive, and put up the proper
thing, such as tile. You might even find real brick behind the thin
material.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In my house in Brewster, Mass. the winds blow so hard that my
oil burner flames out. I plan to put a cap on my chimney. Would
that help? If not, are there any other ways to prevent such
flameouts?
</P>
<P>
   SIDDIQ SATTAR, Avon, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. Brother, that is one helluva downdraft you have. A downdraft
that can blow out an oil-burner flame under pressure certainly is
powerful. I think a cap will help. If it doesn't, have your oil
burner serviceman check it out. He should be able to do something.
It may mean a simple baffle in the smoke pipe or nearby to keep
that downdraft from coming in directly against the flame, but don't
try anything like that yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to paint my wallpaper. Is that possible, or even
feasible? It is real paper, 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ANN WARD, West Roxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you can paint wallpaper, and the same technque applies
whether the paper is vinyl-coated or not. If you use a latex paint,
you run the risk of the water in the paint softening the paste and
creating wrinkles. This happened to the handyman, so he knows it
can happen, but when the paint dried, the wrinkles went away for
the most part, enough to be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   OK, as for the technique: Sand the paper lightly, to roughen the
finish. Wipe off sanding dust, and apply a thin layer of latex
enamel. Finish with two coats of an eggshell-finish latex wall
paint. To avoid wrinkling, use oil-based Kilz (a primer) in place
of the latex enamel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My deck floor was replaced with fir boards, which I would
like to keep new-looking and allow to weather. I have thought of a
clear sealer to seal it. If I seal it, can I put on a stain in the
future?
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL MONIZ, Roslindale, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You cannot keep the boards new looking and let weather. That
is impossible. But you can seal the boards, which will protect then
and allow them to weather to a gray color. But you have to apply
the sealer every year, which is kind of dumb, especially if you
have a huge deck. Instead, I suggest you apply a semitransparent
stain of a light gray color. You will get a similar effect and will
not have to repeat for three to five years. And only one coat is
needed at a time.
</P>
<P>
   If you seal the boards, you can't put a stain on them until the
sealer wears off, in a year or more. The stain will not penetrate
the sealer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
