<HEADLINE>
RED SOX FAN'S PHILOSOPHY OF CAN'T 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything I need to know about life I learned from being a Red
Sox fan.
</P>
<P>
   Honesty is sometimes the best policy.
</P>
<P>
   Never put off until tomorrow what you can screw up today.
</P>
<P>
   If you must scratch a body part in public, act nonchalant.
</P>
<P>
   The Lord helps those who help themselves to as much money as
they can grab before their knees give out.
</P>
<P>
   Love your neighbor as yourself, especially if you want to build
a new ballpark in his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   To whom much is given, much is required, except for Mike
Greenwell.
</P>
<P>
   It's better to give abuse than to
</P>
<P>
   receive it.
</P>
<P>
   Never hurt anyone deliberately, unless he gets in your way.
</P>
<P>
   The grass is always greener in Joe Mooney's outfield.
</P>
<P>
   If absence makes the heart grow fonder, spring training makes
the heart grow fonder still.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get your story straight, stick to it.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever lives up to his full potential, except for Pedro and
Carl.
</P>
<P>
   Batting 300 is a lot harder than it looks.
</P>
<P>
   When the going gets tough, blame somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   You can take it with you, if you're traded with a guaranteed
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Where there's life there's hope, especially if you think you
have a shot at signing Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Divided we stand, united we fall.
</P>
<P>
   Actions speak louder than words, but words will do if you're on
the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Money is the root of all evil, especially when it comes dressed
in Yankee pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   Laugh and the world laughs with you, weep and you weep alone,
unless you're a Red Sox fan, in which case you have plenty of
company.
</P>
<P>
   Where there's a Wil Cordero, there's no way.
</P>
<P>
   One rotten third baseman can spoil a whole infield.
</P>
<P>
   To err is human, but to err more than once in a game is stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who remember the past all too vividly are condemned
to repeat it.
</P>
<P>
   Every cloud has a silver lining, except for the one that hovers
over Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The truth will out, but usually you can talk your way around it.
</P>
<P>
   Charity should never begin at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Money can't buy happiness, but it can buy world championships.
</P>
<P>
   It's not over till it's over, unless you're a Red Sox fan in
which case it's over before it's begun.
</P>
<P>
   Familiarity with the Red Sox breeds cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   Ask not what you can do for the team, ask what your agent can do
for you.
</P>
<P>
   The best things in life are taxpayer-funded.
</P>
<P>
   A person who is good at making excuses is seldom good at
anything else, except playing in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Winning isn't everything. Some days just showing up is as good
as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Never judge a team by its coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Miracles can happen, even to the Red Sox, every hundred years or
so, give or take.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy the sweet, but learn to take the bitter plain, straight
up, without a chaser.
</P>
<P>
   Hope for the best, but prepare for the worst. You won't be
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
