<HEADLINE>
GLOBE SUIT HIGHLIGHTS NET USAGE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lawsuit against The Boston Globe filed by a group of the
paper's freelancers may well become a significant test case in the
battle over ownership of online content raging everywhere from
Napster to the newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a coalition that includes The National Writers Union,
the Graphic Artists Guild, and the American Society of Media
Photographers, the freelancers' suit challenges a licensing
agreement that seeks their consent to allow the Globe to reproduce
their past and future freelance work in other forms, including
online, without additional compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the Globe the rights to distribute the material,''
said plaintiffs' attorney Ira Sills. ``What's the consideration and
benefit given to the freelancer for that? Zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the suit ``without merit,'' Globe spokesman Rick Gulla
said the license deal only seeks freelancers' permission to ``use
their work under a Globe brand. We're not going to resell it to a
third party because they own the copyright.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulla pointed out that since Globe freelancers maintain their
copyright, they can sell their work to other outlets. The
plaintiffs counter that the paper's ability to re-use that work _
on Web sites or elsewhere _ depresses that resale market and
deprives them of a deserving paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of several large newspapers around the country
indicates that, at least for now, many freelancer arrangements
allow news organizations virtually unlimited reuse of their work
online or in other forms. The Globe's policy on freelancer reuse
seems to be roughly in line with that of other large papers.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying this dispute is the reality that cyberspace has
created thorny intellectual property issues certain to be hashed
out in the courts. In essence, publishers want to treat their
online sites as a natural extension of the company's brand while
freelancers see it as a separate medium with its own revenue pie
that ought to be shared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that (freelance contributions) are valuable
commodities . . . in this new era that is emerging,'' said Dennis
DeMaio, vice president of The National Writers' Union. ``What
really makes the Globe contract unfair and deceptive is that they
are trying not only to hoodwink people into forfeiting their future
rights, but their past rights as well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows we're in a new age of distribution,'' said
Gulla. ``What we're intending to do is to make the Boston Globe a
premier news medium whether it's in print or online . . . It's the
same Boston Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' view has support inside the Globe newsroom.
Robert Jordan, president of the Newspaper Guild local at the Globe,
has sent a letter to Globe management protesting a contract that
``would usurp virtually all of the rights of the freelancers.'' And
as of Wednesday, nearly 80 staffers had signed a ``free the
freelancers!'' petition asking the paper to scrap ``a patently
unfair license agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown sparked by Monday's litigation has been building
for some time. One crucial turning point was a recent ruling in the
case of Tasini vs. The New York Times that publishers could not
simply reuse freelancers' work electronically without their
consent. (Times spokeswoman Catherine Mathis said the newspaper is
seeking US Supreme Court review of that ruling.)
</P>
<P>
   According to Gulla, the Globe licensing agreement was sent to
about 750 regular freelancers and nearly 300 have signed to date.
But any freelancer who does not sign on by July 1 will have his
relationship with the paper terminated. Calling the Globe case
``sort of the son of Tasini,'' Sills accused the paper of trying to
limit ``its enormous copyright violation exposure,'' by trying to
get freelancers to sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Gulla acknowledged that ``Tasini was the impetus behind the
(Globe's) new license agreement,'' which he said ``was not
influenced'' by its New York Times parent company, but was
``developed by Globe editors after reviewing the licensing
agreements throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Inquirer spokeswoman Pamela Browner said
freelancers there sign a contract giving the paper ``non-exclusive
rights to reuse their material anywhere, including the Web,'' and a
similar system exists at The Washington Post. The Times, Mathis
said, retains the freelancers' copyright and ``the exclusive right
to use his or her article in any medium.'' Freelancers at Newsday
agree to allow the paper to repackage their material ``online . . .
on our database and in other forms,'' said Bob Keane, assistant to
the publisher. ``We've had writers who've said they've preferred
not to do that. But it hasn't been much of an issue.'' The Boston
Herald also recently sent a contract to its freelancers stipulating
that the paper owns the copyright on their work ``in any and all
media and forms of publication.'' (Herald officials could not be
reached.)
</P>
<P>
   While the Globe case looms as a major legal precedent, DeMaio
said that ``there are a lot of these publishers who are pirating
these rights. . . . We see this as only the beginning of a very
large war. We anticipate there will be other cases. We're widening
the war against these contracts and we intend to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Sills compares the freelancer situation to that of the fierce
legal wrangle over Napster, the digital music-sharing service that
has many music producers crying copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's intellectual property,'' he said. The issue is ``who
controls the intellectual property and what's a fair and equitable
way of doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
