<HEADLINE>
FORD SPORT TRAC MELDS TRUCK AND SUV 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photos are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a rig for gearheads. That's not gearheads as in folks
who like nothing more than to tear into the mechanical intricacies
of what they drive. It's gearheads who like their vehicles to carry
lots of stuff: skis, snowboards, bikes, kayaks, garden tools,
manure, lumber, groceries.
</P>
<P>
   I call it a rig because, like many people who have test driven
the Ford Explorer Sport Trac, I don't know if it's a truck or an
SUV. And with its ability to carry six adults in absolute,
sedan-like comfort, you could argue that it's a station wagon, as
well. Ah, when world's collide.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a pickup truck-SUV boom, Ford has done a fine
job of melding the two.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it does not deliver the pure benefits of either but
does a good turn in letting you at least sample the best of each.
</P>
<P>
   It's got a longer wheelbase than the Explorer SUV on which it is
based. This makes it a bit more sure-footed headed down the
highway. Off-road, however, coupled with a ground clearance that's
not quite 7 inches, it doesn't chew up slop and steep the way the
shorter-wheelbase Explorer does. But you don't buy this rig for
serious off-roading. You buy it for hauling and for good travel in
winter slop. Living in New England, I would not consider a
two-wheel-version. Go with the four.
</P>
<P>
   As a pickup truck, it's a small one. The cargo bed _ made of
dent-and-ding-resistant sturdy plastic _ is only 50 inches long.
Add the optional plastic tonneau cover and you get a huge, lockable
trunk. Travel with five and luggage and you've got dry storage.
</P>
<P>
   Without the cover, the open bed offers lots of options.
</P>
<P>
   Six tie-downs, shaped like dock cleats, are positioned outside
the cargo bed's upper rails. Ropes can go up and over any load
inside the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Four more tie-downs are mounted on the inside of the box to hold
down shorter-stacked loads. An optional divider can split the cargo
bed into two bins.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the Sport Trac's rear window _ a la old-time station
wagons _ slides down into the rear wall and lets you project longer
loads into the cabin _ though if you use this option, particularly
with heavy objects such as skis or lumber, you'd better be sure
you've got the load tied down so it won't come hurtling forward if
you have to brake suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   A better option for long loads, I found, was the optional
cage/bed extender that flips out onto an open tailgate and adds
about two feet of length to the bed. You're still not going to get
a sheet of plywood into the bed _ though you could tie plywood down
over this setup _ but for hauling boards, the bed extender's open
slots form great support through which to insert the load into the
bed. In addition, the bed extender simply gives you more room for
multiple, shorter items you can sort within the bed.
</P>
<P>
   The Sport Trac also comes with standard roof rails, good for
other loads that active lifestyles entail.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so you can load it up with gear. What about people?
</P>
<P>
   Big, firm leather bucket seats up front. A big, firm leather
bench in the rear _ think three adults sitting comfortably on a
couch with plenty of room to extend their legs. Back to gear for a
moment: Fold that split rear seat down and you get a cavernous area
for luggage, groceries, or other goodies. Added treat: behind the
seats are two bins, with doors, for smaller items.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomically, all is delightfully simple.
</P>
<P>
   Big buttons run your audio. Three dials control climate.
Windows, door locks, and mirrors are controlled from driver's door.
A button at center console raises and lowers the rear window.
</P>
<P>
   To haul all this potential load, Ford has given the Sport Trac
one of the best V-6 engines I've run across. It's a 4.0-liter DOHC
that produces 205 horsepower. Some critics have bemoaned the lack
of a V-8, and I'm sure Ford could sell that option if they chose
to, but I found the six to be plenty peppy. I got almost 18 miles
per gallon in a week of driving the Sport Trac _ respectable for
all it will haul. Early models offer only a 5-speed automatic
transmission. I'd hold out for the 5-speed manual due by fall.
</P>
<P>
   Confident, with a fine burble, I'd say were I a wine critic.
</P>
<P>
   Handling was very nice straight ahead on the highway, owing to
not only the extra wheelbase but also a stiffer frame than on the
SUV Explorer. The rear tended to be skittish off road and in quick
turns _ it's light because of its plastic composite, after all, and
it does have leaf springs. The latter are good for load absorption,
not as good as shocks when the load is light.
</P>
<P>
   You don't want to be fully loaded, charging down the highway at
high speed, and making those crazy commuter lane shifts in the
Sport Trac. That's because it is, in many ways, an SUV.
</P>
<P>
   You don't want to count on the Sport Trac to haul massive gear
through the bogs and steep woods of Maine on your next hunting
trip. It's not made for that.
</P>
<P>
   And you're not going to hang out your construction company
shingle and buy this truck for hauling tools and lumber from site
to site. It's not made for that either.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy one, here's what it is made for: hauling family and
friends and all their assorted luggage and gear on active, outdoor
vacations. It will get you to the campground, the lodge, even to
reasonably accessible backwoods campsites. And it will get you
there with SUV-like roominess with a small pickup truck's load
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The long tubular door grips on the inside panels. Grip them
with your whole hand and slam away.
</P>
<P>
   --The tightly-bound rubber flooring (beneath removable carpets).
You could gently hose this thing out if you got it muddy inside.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   -- With the great job Ford did positioning tie-downs, they
missed when they didn't put any directly on the floor of the cargo
bed. Physics dictates that tying a stacked load from a low point
let's you cinch it down better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $25,270 &QL; 
Price as tested: $30,410 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 205/240 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 125 inches/205.9 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 71.8 inches/70.6 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 4,400 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1404EDT &QL; 
