and balloons are long gone. Driven by boom times, youthful
exuberance and the matrimonial-industrial complex of high fashion,
catering halls and luxury car rentals, the prom is no longer just a
rite of passage; it has become a serious expenditure. By Michael
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MEAT-PLANT (Tar Heel, N.C.) _ The first thing you learn at
the Smithfield hog plant here is the value of a sharp knife. The
second thing you learn is that not everyone has to work with a
knife. White, blacks, American Indians and Mexicans, they all have
their separate stations, but it is blacks and Mexicans that are
left to battle over the dirty jobs at the factory, one of the only
places within a 50-mile radius in this muddy corner of North
Carolina where a person might make more than $8 an hour. While
Smithfield's profits nearly doubled over the past year, wages have
remained flat. So a lot of Americans have quit and a lot of
Mexicans have been hired to take their places. But more than
management, the workers see one another as the problem, and they
see the competition in skin tones. By Charlie LeDuff. (With photos)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This is the sixth story in the ``How Race is Lived in
America'' series, which The New York Times began publishing on June
4 and will continue for several weeks. The series is the outcome of
a yearlong effort by a team of Times reporters to capture some of
the voices of ordinary people and some of the troubling issues that
Americans continue to face. Previous articles can be resent to News
Service clients. For additional information, please see
RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY, which has moved.)
