<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4834 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-RU-486-HNS &LR;      06-15 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RU-486-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REGULATORS PLAY POLITICS WITH ABORTION PILL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARGOT MAGOWAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Why are American women so behind the times? We
are supposed to have the most advanced medical system in the world,
but the abortion pill, RU-486, is still not available in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming legal in France 12 years ago, RU-486 has been
used by more than 600,000 women worldwide with 95 percent
effectiveness. Nearly 90 percent of these women report they are
very satisfied with this option.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Food and Drug Administration said that RU-486 may
be prescribed only by doctors who can also perform surgical
abortions. This seems a strange stipulation. Why would you need a
surgeon to take a pill?
</P>
<P>
   One of the benefits of RU-486 is that more doctors can prescribe
it precisely because no surgery is necessary. Only 5 percent of
women who have used RU-486 have needed follow-up medical care. In
those cases, patients were referred to qualified doctors, as is the
case in every other medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   More doctors means more access. RU-486 could free women from
their dependency on abortion clinics. This would be especially
beneficial to rural women who live far from abortion service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the need for a specified clinic also gives women
privacy and safety. Anti-abortion rights activists cannot identify
and target prescriptions the way they can clinics.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA eliminated privacy for doctors and patients when it
mandated that RU-486 will be approved only if there is a national
registry of doctors who prescribe it. This national stigma
infringes on basic privacy rights and will radically discourage
doctors from giving out the pill.
</P>
<P>
   At best, these FDA conditions are extremely paternalistic. At
worst, they are blatantly political. Either way, they don't serve
women.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA first pronounced RU-486 safe and effective back in 1996,
but delayed full approval because of unspecified production issues.
And now, when asked about the proposed restrictions, FDA officials
reply with ``no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   This response is more befitting a politician than a non-partisan
agency that should be basing its decisions on science, not
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the FDA hasn't demonstrated some rather odd health
priorities. It rushed to legalize Viagra almost immediately after
the drug was created.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the likelihood of insisting there be a national registry
for doctors who prescribe a pill for erectile dysfunction. Viagra
turned out to have dangerous side effects for some men.
</P>
<P>
   Even Fen-Phen, the diet drug recalled because of fatal
consequences, was released before RU-486. And silicon breast
implants are still legal, even though many doctors and thousands of
victims believe the implants can leak dangerous toxins. The FDA
permitted these risky procedures for the sake of potent men,
reduced body fat, and large breasts _ all the while delaying a pill
that can safely terminate pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA's recommendations for RU-486, in terms of certification
and the licensing of providers, is beyond what has been required of
any other drug. It's time for the Clinton administration to take
some leadership and liberate a medical process from a political
one.
</P>
<P>
   Just as critically, Vice President Al Gore, who has consistently
taken pro-women positions, and has recently made privacy rights a
hot issue of his presidential campaign, should speak to these
inconsistencies in the FDA. Allowing American women access to a
safe and effective drug should be a national priority. We have
waited long enough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Margot Magowan is the co-founder of Women Count and the
Woodhull Institute.)
</P>
</TEXT>
