<P>
   &UR; THE ENIGMA OF HAFEZ AL-ASSAD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `SPHINX'-ASSAD-800&AMP;ADD-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Hafez al-Assad's on-again, off-again approach to the
Middle East peace process frequently drove U.S. and Israeli
policymakers to distraction. Was the Syrian leader, who died
suddenly Saturday at 69, temperamental and unpredictable? Were his
enemies gulled by the mistaken view that Assad, a maddeningly
clever negotiator, was entirely trustworthy once he had given his
word? Many pundits in Israel and the United States think so. But
this view is a serious and unfair misreading of Assad. In fact, his
behavior was anything but erratic; it was consistent and
predictable. To understand that consistency, one must understand
the enigmatic man known as the ``sphinx of Damascus'' and the world
in which he lived. To the end, Assad remained the uncompromisingly
tough, unyielding defender of Arab honor....By Henry Siegman,
Foreign Affairs magazine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 300; 1,325 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BASHAR ASSAD: LIKE FATHER, LIKE SON? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BASHAR-SYRIA-FISK-INDEPENDENT-275&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ In Syria, the streets have been decorated for years
with three pictures: that of President Hafez al-Assad, who died
Saturday, his dead son, Basil _ killed in a car accident in 1994 _
and his other son, Bashar. Under Hafez's picture, it says: ``The
Leader.'' Under Basil's it reads: ``The Example.'' Under Bashar's,
it announces: ``The Future.'' Lebanon's former prime minister,
Rafiq Harari, has said it would be impossible to imagine the Middle
East without Hafez al-Assad. So is it possible to imagine Syria led
by Bashar al-Assad?....By Robert Fisk, The Independent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 200-word optional trim; 1,275 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SYRIANS CANNOT ESCAPE ASSAD'S EYES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `BIG-BROTHER'-ASSAD-850&AMP;ADD-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAMASCUS _ You cannot escape Hafez al-Assad. Even as Syria was
preparing for the president's state funeral through the streets of
Damascus Tuesday, his eyes stared down at us. Thoughtful eyes. Sad
eyes. Intelligent eyes. Hard eyes. Smiling eyes. Father. Uncle.
Brother. Big Brother?....By Robert Fisk, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 200-word optional trim; 1,250 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISRAEL REMEMBERS ITS ENEMY, HAFEZ ASSAD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASSAD-ISRAELIS-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NORTHEASTERN SHORES OF THE SEA OF GALILEE _ Israel already
has a monument by which to remember its old adversary, Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad. It sits above the Sea of Galilee,
overlooking the highway that skirts the lake's eastern edge. It is,
of course, highly unflattering. The Syrian leader is perching on
top of a grassy crag, a hook-nosed vulture-like figure with a
fishing rod. This is the Assad as he was seen by most Israelis: a
malevolent predator roosting on the landscape, waiting patiently
for the chance to sling his hook again into Jewish waters, and to
plunder its treasures....By Phil Reeves, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SYRIA ELEVATES HEIR TO SUDDEN GOD-LIKE STATUS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSTANT-GOD-BASHAR-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAMASCUS AND WASHINGTON _ ``Assad sleeps next to God,'' the
banners say. But his son Bashar Sunday was promoted to the almost
equally God-like status of commander-in-chief of the Syrian army _
in effect making him the next president of the Arab world's
toughest nation. A 34-year-old English-trained ophthalmologist,
Bashar Assad could never have dreamt five years ago that he would
be handed his father's torch....By Robert Fisk and Andrew Marshall,
The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (350 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEATH OF SYRIA'S ASSAD PROFOUNDLY CONFUSES PEACE HOPES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASSAD-WHAT-NOW?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ The sudden death of President Hafez Assad of Syria
Saturday threw the Middle East into shock and profound uncertainty
as one of the Arab world's most powerful military nations found
itself leaderless. Ever since 1982, when he suffered his first
heart problems, Assad's health has been a subject for constant
speculation. But there had been no prior hint of his imminent
death, which has left Syrians unprepared for the great changes
which must now lie ahead in their country....By Robert Fisk, The
Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
