<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UMASS-ONLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS MAY BRING EDUCATION TO THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a bid to become the state's premier online campus,
the University of Massachusetts may soon launch a
multimillion-dollar campuswide Internet education program.
</P>
<P>
   A new report commissioned by the university supports a push
toward electronic learning by President William M. Bulger's office
and concludes that UMass would enjoy ``explosive growth'' by
enrolling thousands of students in online classes.
</P>
<P>
   UMass, primarily the Amherst and Lowell campuses, already
provides Internet classes to more than 1,750 students. But the lack
of a coordinated plan, the report says, has taken a toll. UMass
trails many public university systems, including the University of
Illinois, which enrolls 4,500 students; the University of Nebraska,
with 15,000 students; and the University of Maryland, which has
30,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Potential online students include government workers, corporate
employees, grade school teachers, and high school students
interested in college-level classes. The report by
PricewaterhouseCoopers found nearly 1.5 million Massachusetts
residents ``somewhat-to-very-likely'' to pursue education or
training within two years. Of those, an estimated 45,000 said they
would be interested in taking classes exclusively over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the increasing competition in the field, and the need
for UMass to establish an identity as an online information
provider, the report cautions that a crucial element of success is
speed. The report, which cost UMass $300,000, starts out by quoting
Bulger's call to action:
</P>
<P>
   ``The risks and opportunities . . . preclude the option of
waiting for the market to mature and provide greater clarity,''
Bulger said late last year in a letter to the board of trustees.
``Waiting, or complacency, will give competitors an advantage in
the market and erode our competitive advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference between letting the status quo run its course and
following the consultants' plan could amount to a loss of almost
$60 million in potential profits, according to the report. After
losing $20 million the first two years, UMass would earn $93.3 in
annual gross revenue by the fourth year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tuition, the online plan provides for other forms
of revenue. The report suggests advertising on the Web site,
revenue-sharing deals with online book companies such as Amazon.com
and BarnesandNobles.com, and the resale of everything from class
notes to exams provided over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The key to beating the increasing field of competitors _ which
include Harvard, MIT, Boston University, Northeastern, and Babson
College _ is the price. The cost of current UMass courses
($520-$650 for undergraduate) is significantly less than other
schools, the consultants say.
</P>
<P>
   And to reduce the current redundancies between campuses and
increase efficiency, the report suggests the university create a
separate administrative body that would be controlled by the
president instead of any one campus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many professors are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Some view the proposal as an attack on academic integrity, fear
the plan would dilute profits they already earn from the individual
campus's online education programs, and believe the investment
would be too risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the potential to be the `Big Dig' of public higher
education in Massachusetts,'' said Joe Larson, professor of natural
resources and leader of the faculty senate at UMass-Amherst. ``So
much money would be put at risk, it would be devastating for us to
lose it. Given our lean budget, it would have a major negative
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the report says, the potential long-term profits of
providing classes over the Internet are enormous. In 1998, 710,000
students across the country enrolled in such distance-education
programs, which generated more than $1 billion in revenue, the
consultants say. By 2002, they say, more than 2.2 billion students
will be taking Internet-based classes, with annual revenues rising
above $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the report, however, sounds like a nightmare to some
professors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts the standard rules of academic governance on its
head,'' said Robert Parkin, a mechanical engineering professor and
president of the faculty senate at UMass-Lowell. ``The faculty has
primary responsibility over academic matters. The report takes that
away from the faculty.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Parkin and six other UMass-Lowell professors on the
faculty senate sent this week to Bulger's office, they outlined
their dismay over the report's corporate focus. Parkin said the
consultants forgot they were reviewing the future of a university.
And he said he is outraged they would advise Bulger to consider
advertising or selling professors' class notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can the system afford such a high risk, potentially
budget-busting activity that would seriously damage the reputation
of UMass if and when it fails?'' Parkin writes.
</P>
<P>
   A professor on the faculty senate at UMass-Boston, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, also questioned the online program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really concerned about this because there hasn't been
any real discussion about this,'' the professor said. ``And I think
there is some suspicion that (Bulger) is trying to amass power in
himself. This campus might have no control over the program.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials, however, emphasized that the
PricewaterCoopers report is only a proposal.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost of their concerns, they say, is ensuring
academic integrity and faculty involvement. And while enhancing
revenue is a significant perk, they said they believe that, more
importantly, the university will further its mission by increasing
students' access to public education.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Connolly, a spokesman for Bulger, said the president
would consult the faculty and hopes to have a plan ready by
September. He said that while he understands professors'
uneasiness, he believes central coordination can make the online
program work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an arena that the university has to be in,'' he said.
``We're now in the process of how the university should go about
it. Either way, I believe this will go forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
