<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING THE GOOD FIGHT AGAINST LIGHT POLLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you ever fly at night over the megalopolis from Portland,
Maine, to Washington, D.C., you can see what a river of light it is
_ much of it wasted, really.
</P>
<P>
   For hundreds of miles, you see light escaping upwards into the
blackness. It is an ongoing headache, draining resources to
generate unneeded power, and cities don't seem to be doing much
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Why not eliminate the glare, or at least that light that is
shooting straight up? That is a goal of the lightscaping industry,
the people who install lighting in gardens and yards. It's a big
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But it is relatively easy to install night lighting on your
property with hardly a ray escaping to the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Charles Callahan of Hull does. He heads NightScape
of Cohasset. Callahan says, ``Your home is our showroom,'' meaning
your nightscape can't help but show others what it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he could use his own house as a showroom. He has
installed lights under the rails of his front steps, and also
fixtures called foot lights, which are really downlights, copper
affairs that look like tulips or lilies.
</P>
<P>
   The railing lights are hidden, until they are turned on at
night, when they convert the railing to a fence of lights.
</P>
<P>
   The copper foot lights, which plunge into the ground, are always
visible. The 12-inch-high fixtures light a small area of ground;
24-inch fixtures light more, and the 36-inch units even more.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan started as a landscaper, and still is, but went into
nightscaping 20 years ago. He is on the Net at
www.landscapelight.com, or call 781-383-2375.
</P>
<P>
   There are many nice things about nightscaping, and one is that
most of the fixtures run on 12 volts, converted with transformers
to that low voltage from the power of 120 volts.
</P>
<P>
   The transformers are compact and easy to use. Wiring is simple,
and can be buried without extra protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a whole new concept in night lighting, Callahan said:
``Buy quality fixtures, and we'll put them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a collection of favorite lights that I like to use. We
provide safety, security and peace of mind. I also bail out
screwups,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The idea in lightscaping is to remove 90 percent of the uplight,
which Callahan calls ``burning your retina out,'' and use the 10
percent left over to light the ground, trees, and other objects in
the garden and yard.
</P>
<P>
   The lights to do so are downlights, pathway lights, tree lights,
moon lights and ground lights.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these are obvious, but tree lights and moon lights need
explaining. Tree lights can be various types: One is a light aiming
into the tree, highlighting it, but you have to be careful to avoid
glare and direct light. Another tree light illuminates a wall
behind a tree, silhouetting the plant and eliminating glare. This
is particularly effective in winter.
</P>
<P>
   A moon light is a wide-angle lamp at the top of a tree flooding
the tree like a full moon. Here again you must be careful to avoid
glare and direct lights.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a nightscaper has to be alert to avoid glare at all
times.
</P>
<P>
   When he can't avoid glare, Callahan paints the bulbs white or
etches them.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury vapor lights are gaining in popularity because they
produce a lot of light for the voltage, although most of them need
line voltage of 120 volts. Low-voltage mercury vapor lights are
coming, said Callahan.
</P>
<P>
   Fluorescent lights are also being used more and more. Callahan
says he likes their blue light to enhance blue spruces and other
evergreens.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the homeowner can do, if he does not want to have it
done, is to buy the pathway or foot lights and place them where he
wants them. All they need is sticking in the ground, being careful
to keep the wires underground.
</P>
<P>
   Nightscaping is not necessarily expensive; Callahan said a
10-light system is about $1,650, making a nice potpourri, a little
light up, a little light down, and a little moon. Callahan's Web
site has packages for $750 and less.
</P>
<P>
   So, start small. Then go on to bigger and brighter things. But
not too bright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
