<HEADER>
A4868 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FAIR-$ADV17-CO     06-15 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FAIR-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLAWED CAMPAIGN MAY HURT VOTER TRUST IN 'CLEAN' PRESIDENTIAL
ELECTION, MEXICAN OFFICIALS SAY
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., June 17 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It hasn't taken place yet, but Mexico's July 2
presidential election is already being called the cleanest and most
competitive in this country's tarnished electoral history.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some top election officials here complain that the campaign
leading up to election day has been tainted by reports of pressure
tactics, vote-buying and ongoing government propaganda in the media
that boosts Mexico's 71-year-old ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our position of responsibility as electoral authorities,
any vote that is manipulated, coerced or bought undermines the
integrity of the election,'' said Emilio Zebadua, one of nine
counselors at Mexico's Federal Elections Institute (IFE), an
autonomous government agency that will supervise a presidential
election for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much can it affect the outcome of the election? We don't
know. It might depend on how close the election is,'' said Zebadua,
who, along with three other counselors, spoke to a group of foreign
correspondents Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The election is indeed expected to be tight. This is the first
race since 1929 that Mexico's long-ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, faces the real possibility of losing
the presidency. Recent polls indicate the PRI candidate Francisco
Labastida Ochoa is slightly ahead or even with challenger Vicente
Fox Quesada of the National Action Party, or PAN.
</P>
<P>
   As election day approaches, the PRI and the government have been
accused of stockpiling gifts _ bicycles and washing machines in
Yucatan and bags of cement in Mexico state _ to dole out to
supporters around or on election day.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the watchdog group Civic Alliance _ which is under
contract to Mexico's Congress to report irregularities _ presented
a list of more than 80 examples of alleged unlawful pressure
tactics or vote-buying. The group announced a ``crusade'' for
democracy and said it will join forces with other citizens'
organizations to dispatch 10,000 people throughout the country to
promote free voting.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a high-ranking manager at the government-owned
Mexican Petroleum company in Tabasco state held a news conference
to denounce an alleged campaign to force public workers to pressure
their subordinates to vote for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your bosses can threaten you with losing your job, but don't
let them make you commit (electoral) crimes,'' Ramiro Berron,
technical coordinator for oil exploration in Mexico's southern
region, said in an appeal to fellow workers published in Reforma
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts of food, building supplies and other materials that have
been doled out already in some areas are not necessarily illegal.
But it is forbidden to tie handouts to votes, or for public
officials to use their position or government resources to
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has challenged anyone who is complaining to come forward
with evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The IFE, which has devised a sophisticated balloting system for
Mexico, is investigating 12 complaints of coercion or vote-buying _
10 against the PRI and two against other parties.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he has faith in the electoral system, candidate
Fox has said, ``I fully trust the Federal Elections Institute. It
is in good hands. But it is not in control of the whole process.''
</P>
<P>
   A special section of the Mexican attorney general's office is
responsible for prosecuting cases of electoral fraud or pressure.
Mexico's Ministry of Social Development, which administers welfare
programs, said Tuesday it has investigated four complaints of
pressure campaigns using social programs as bait and has discounted
all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Zebadua said reports of irregularities ``contaminates the
(election) environment. In spite of this, the Federal Elections
Institute is trying to march in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   After an investment of about $1.7 billion since 1998 on
technology, staffing and public funding for parties, election
officials believe that the actual balloting on July 2 will be free
of wholesale fraud if nearly 800,000 trained supervisors show up as
planned.
</P>
<P>
   The country's 113,000 polling places are the ``neurological
center'' of the election, said election counselor Jesus Cantu. Only
voters with a photo credential matched to their name, photo and
number on registration lists at polling places will be allowed to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   A limited number of ballots will be available at each station.
The teams that will supervise the balloting are citizens who were
selected by lottery and trained by the IFE.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the legitimacy of the voting are representatives of the
political parties, who are allowed to observe the balloting and
help count votes at each station before ballot boxes are delivered
to regional offices.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about irregularities will be investigated by a
tribunal, which has reportedly added extra lawyers for the
election. Only the tribunal has the power to annul ballots.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The PAN says it has assigned representatives to about 88 percent
of polling stations and is working toward 100-percent coverage,
according to Robert Pastor of the Atlanta-based Carter Center.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor and others from the Carter Center, which has observed 28
elections in 20 countries, have been invited to spend election day
at each party's headquarters to assess complaints or observations
that come in from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Precisely because the parties have the most at stake,'' Pastor
said, ``they will be the best eyes and ears.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most competitive election in Mexican history,'' he
added. ``There is no important issue that is not being debated
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   To address the perception of campaign inequity, election
officials here have been waging a battle against the federal
government _ including President Ernesto Zedillo _ over alleged
abuse of the media.
</P>
<P>
   Last month election officials asked Zedillo to suspend a series
of pro-government television and radio commercials at least 30 days
before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo has been credited with opening up Mexican democracy
during his six-year term, but election officials say that the
publicly funded commercials Zedillo refuses to pull from the
airwaves constitute extra publicity for Labastida and the ruling
party.
</P>
<P>
   Zebadua called the ads ``the most extensive publicity campaign
in the history of the six-year administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads cast the government in a positive light, showing sunny
public workers dedicated to their jobs or details about recent
government achievements. In a letter defending the ads, Zedillo
spokesman Marco Provencio denied the commercials were
``propaganda'' and said ``the federal government is obligated to
inform citizens'' about its activities.
</P>
<P>
   There is no law requiring the ads to be suspended, but officials
said that before the 1994 presidential election the federal
government agreed to take similar spots off the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suspension of publicity and public works and government
propaganda (prior to voting day) contributed to the legitimacy of
then-candidate Zedillo's election,'' said election counselor Juan
Molinar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today as (President Zedillo) doesn't answer our letter and he
continues propaganda on behalf of his party,'' Molinar said. ``That
seems like a bad example to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Election officials were also upset by a two-month gap prior to
May when television stations refused to air hard-hitting public
service ads advising Mexicans not to be ``puppets'' and to ignore
attempts to buy or coerce votes.
</P>
<P>
   Stations argued that the IFE was not eligible for free
government time since it was autonomous. Mexico's Ministry of
Internal Affairs dragged its feet in coming to the institute's
defense, Zebadua said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent public appearances, Zedillo has tried to blunt
criticism that the PRI has an unfair advantage in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government no longer interferes in the organization of
elections,'' Zedillo said Wednesday in a speech before Mexican
architects. ``The Mexican electoral system is one of the best and
most complete in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org (Washington Office on Latin America)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
