<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4872 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN16-CO     06-15 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Listen to Jesus, not Paul, about
women's role in church
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Should women be allowed to serve as ministers in
Baptist churches?
</P>
<P>
   That's sex, religion and politics, all in one -- a trinity unto
itself.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday morning when I visited First Baptist Church
of Washington, D.C., Dr. Robert Troutman of Alexandria, Va., a
retired minister with 35 years of experience, had something to say
on the question.
</P>
<P>
   Be it noted that First Baptist Church of Washington is in the
process of calling a new pastor. Dr. Troutman, who is a graduate of
Baylor University in Waco, Texas, and Southern Theological Seminary
in Louisville, Ky., was filling in.
</P>
<P>
   You often get your best sermons from retired preachers who are
filling in.
</P>
<P>
   Preaching from their heart and soul, they also tend to speak
their mind.
</P>
<P>
   Not allowing women to be ordained as ministers is tied to a
verse in 1st Timothy, 2:12, Dr. Troutman reminded the congregation,
in which the Apostle Paul admonishes women ``to be in silence'' in
the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul might have had a bad day when he wrote what he did,'' Dr.
Troutman allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Better we should place our faith in the actions of Jesus, not
the words of Paul, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the Gospel story of the woman at the well, which Dr.
Troutman considers ``the most important event for women in the
whole Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesus asks for a drink of water from a Samaritan woman who has
come to the community well. She is shocked. Jews did not associate
with Samaritans.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between the two peoples involved a difference in
doctrine, according to Dr. Troutman: Samaritans believing that the
Mount of Moses was the most sacred spot on Earth and the Jews
convinced that it was Jerusalem. As a result, they hadn't been on
speaking terms for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   But Jesus always dealt with people on an individual basis,
``relating one on one with a human being,'' without concern for
race or gender, the preacher said.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this point, when Jesus offers her ``living water''
through salvation and everlasting life, Dr. Troutman said, ``He
made a woman equal to every man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done well with this, even into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   The Samaritan woman rushes home to tell all her friends and
relatives about Jesus, and brings such crowds to hear Him that
Jesus spends two days speaking with all who come.
</P>
<P>
   What did that make her? ``She was an evangelist,'' said Dr.
Troutman. She literally ``brought people to Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is, Dr. Troutman concluded, when a young girl asks him if
she can be a minister, he will ask her only this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that what the Lord is telling you to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``If she says yes, I say 'Amen.'''
</P>
<P>
   And the congregation, on this particular Sunday morning at this
particular Baptist church, said ``Amen.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0075 </DOCNO>
