<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN18-CO     06-15 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: How do you get rid of Castro, with TV ads?
 &HT;    RESENDING TO CORRECT SPELLING OF ``DESPERATE' IN TWO PLACES
 &HT;    For release June 18, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI - Backed by seemingly limitless funds from within their
community, Cuban exiles are launching a series of nationwide
television ads designed to showcase the evils of the Fidel Castro
regime. This, of course, is in an attempt to reverse the negative
image among Americans on the heels of the Elian Gonzalez hysteria:
the screeching Marisleysis, the Cuban flag waving, the exploitation
of the child.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it is intended to inhibit the growing swell for ending the
boycott of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   So once again, the Cuban exile community declares war on Fidel
in the wrong place: in the U.S. instead of in Cuba. Let's face it,
the embargo _ now in its 50th year -- is a sham, nothing more than
political salve. Everyone in the world is trading with Cuba.
Americans break the embargo by the thousands and travel there, and
Cuban exiles themselves pump billions of dollars onto the island
each year in the form of funds and materials to their famililies
still there.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Castro's record is worth scrutinizing. His inexplicable
charisma that so excites (and fools) so many is a mask for his many
human rights crimes. But the exiles are waging a wrong kind of war
against Castro. Ads on television, legal battles over Elian,
boycotts of Cuba-based performers are not counter-revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   If the goal is to overthrow Castro, then that's got to be done
within Cuba. Better the exile community -- whose members include
some fabulously wealthy people should go about creating problems
for Castro on the island, rather than on the streets of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Recent U.S. Coast Guard videos reveal how desperate Cubans are
to get away from their island prison. They show rafters wielding
machetes against Coast Guard personnel attempting to interdict them
at sea. One must wonder why the machetes never have been wielded
against Castro officials on the island in an attempt to overturn
the oppression of his regime.
</P>
<P>
   The end of Castroism begins somewhere in Cuba, just as the
beginning of Castroism began there _ in the mountains, with rebels,
with guns, with martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 40 years since the Bay of Pigs fiasco and almost
that long since the United States, in a deal with the Soviets,
agreed to put the lid on military counter-revolutionary incursions
by Cubans from the U.S. It was a lousy deal then, still is.
</P>
<P>
   But that should not prevent the exiles from pursuing their
cause. Certainly raids on Cuba would go against much of world
opinion, and terrorism in the form of making it difficult for
tourists to consider Cuba a safe visit would be seen as
reprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the way to undermine Castro. That's what he did in
1959. Certainly, the world has changed since _ but the
revolutionary world has not. The only way to overthrow a repressive
government (other than by democratic election) is to physically
pitch it out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Let the disenchanted, desperate people of Cuba stay in Cuba and
do something about it instead of rafting to South Florida and
joining in the anti-Castro rhetoric here. And let the exiles show
some bravado.
</P>
<P>
   Arms smuggling, these days, is easy; everyone in the world is
doing it. Give the disenchanted on the island firepower instead of
machetes, dislodge the tourist industry and foreign investment
there, cause internal problems with infrastructure (what there is
of it) and make life miserable for Fidel Castro as he did for
Fulgencio Batista.
</P>
<P>
   This does not need to be done with the approval of the United
States, a nation incapable of stopping the flow of illegal drugs
and aliens in the region and just as unlikely to be able to stop
the flow of illegal arms and other counter-revolutionary
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The First Marine Division is not going to take back Cuba for the
exiles; they and those inside Cuba must do it. What good is a
positive image (via TV ads) if your life's goal -- the cause _ is
nowhere close to being realized?
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis long ago stopped worrying about world opinion, and
paid attention to the nasty business they had to deal with. And
that's what Cuban exiles need to be doing.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
