<HEADER>
A4877 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CAMPING-GEAR-HNS &LR;      06-15 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPING-GEAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GETTING YOUR CAMPING KIT IN ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICK KARLIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The newest generation of camping/hiking gear
might not be cheaper, but it's definitely lighter, stronger, and
better than that of past decades, or even just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a lot more of it, from fashionable hiking boots and
cargo pants to the ubiquitous backpack. ``They call it the `Jeep'
look,'' said Dave Dillenbeck, of Ragged Mountain outdoor store in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   When you're really using the stuff outside, though, it needs to
be functional more than fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   Here are things to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for different properties, depending on whether you are
backpacking or car-camping. When you're hauling everything on your
back, lightness and compactness are paramount.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are traveling in the backcountry, avoid cotton. It will
stay wet if you are caught in the rain or if you work up a sweat.
On a hot, humid day, that moisture is merely uncomfortable, but if
the temperature cools, which can happen year-round in the
mountains, it can become downright dangerous. Clothing made of
water-repelling fibers such as polypropylene or, for colder
weather, fleece, is a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   _ For sleeping bags, almost anything that's comfortable and warm
enough will do in the summer if you're in a campground. Most
sleeping bags have temperature ratings that serve as guides.
Traditionally, down is the warmest and lightest filling for a
sleeping bag, but it has fallen out of favor as synthetic
insulation has become more efficient. While down remains
incomparably light and comfortable, it becomes almost useless when
wet.
</P>
<P>
   Backpackers often prefer mummy bags that are smaller and
lighter, but they do constrict movement and can be uncomfortable
for those who toss and turn while they sleep.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't use a cot, take along a specialized backpacking
mattress like a ThermaRest or dense foam pad.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tents run the gamut from huge car-camping palaces to light
backpacking models. Get one from a reputable manufacturer such as
Eureka, North Face or other well-known brand, and if there are
seams, cover them with sealant before you use it. As with much
backpacking gear, ``the more you are willing to spend, the lighter
it can be,'' notes Neil Woodworth, deputy executive director of the
Adirondack Mountain Club.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the backcountry, you'll need a water filter or purifier to
guard against Giardia lamblia, those microscopic organisms that
cause severe diarrhea. Thoroughly boiling your drinking and cooking
water also will protect you, as will iodine, but filters and
purifiers are hard to beat for convenience.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boots: there is a dizzying array of styles, brands, materials
and prices. The best advice is the most simple: Get a pair that
offer good ankle support and fit well, with adequate room for your
toes when walking downhill.
</P>
<P>
   _ A final bit of advice for techies: don't rely solely on that
nifty new Global Positioning System device for pathfinding. GPS
devices use microwave links to satellites to give the users
latitude and longitude. But if you don't have a map for referencing
the terrain, or can't figure out which direction you should go to
get home, a GPS is useless.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should you become dependent on your cell phone. Reception
can be spotty in mountainous areas, and of course, batteries can
fail at the most inauspicious moments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
