<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4878 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CASUAL-DRESS-1STLD-WR     06-15 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASUAL-DRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLOTHIERS STITCH TOGETHER CAMPAIGN AGAINST CASUAL GARB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Subs entire text)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DANIELLE T. FURFARO   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A nationwide campaign aimed at reversing the
trend of casual dress in the workplace has been launched by a
clothier who is spearheading ``Dress-up Thursdays,'' an initiative
that he and others hope will bring a sense of traditionalism back
to the office and sales back to the tailored clothing industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dress code of America has slipped into the gutter,'' said
Vince Rua, owner of Christopher's Mens Stores Inc. in Albany. ``If
you have something that you would wear to your kid's soccer game on
the weekend, you shouldn't wear it to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Rua and his industry peers _ including Steve Toia, national
sales manager at Arnold Brant; George Zimmer, president of Men's
Wearhouse; and James Ammeen, president and chief executive officer
of Neema Clothing _ are on the steering committee for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has spent the last few months gearing up for a
Sept. 21 kickoff for Dress-up Thursdays by developing a marketing
plan, collecting contributions and contacting business executives
to get them to incorporate the day into their company culture.
</P>
<P>
   At his office in downtown Albany, Rua rattles off a list of
studies and anecdotes that show a correlation between casual dress
policies and lower productivity/higher absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
   ``In white-collar situations, when the dress code is relaxed,
office decorum suffers tremendously,'' he said. ``Productivity
suffers all week and Fridays don't even exist.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, management consultant and behavioral scientist Jeffrey
L. Magee of Tulsa undertook a study to determine the effect casual
dress had on productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My clients were complaining a lot about problems in the
office,'' Magee said. ``I started noticing a correlation between HR
(human resources) people having to spend time on babysitting issues
and casual-dress policies.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Magee's study, which Rua uses in his crusade
against ``business casual,'' ethics, productivity and morality in
the workplace all go down when casual-dress policies are in place,
while instances of absenteeism, sexual harassment and offensive
language increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in a blue-collar situation, when dress is allowed to be
more casual, the level of service is also more casual,'' Magee
said. ``If you are talking on the phone and a customer comes in,
you are more likely to get off the phone right away if you are in a
suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rua said Dress-up Thursdays is not an effort to increase sales
at his three retail stores. He said he does hope the campaign will
increase sales across the $62 billion tailored-clothing industry.
Others on the steering committee agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clothing sales have declined in the past 10 years, especially
in the tailored-clothing segment,'' said Ammeen, whose Neema
Clothing is a manufacturer in New York City. ``So this is a
grass-roots movement to get some of that back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammeen and Rua both put the blame for the start of business
casual on Levi Straus &AMP; Co., the San Francisco company that more
than a decade ago began sending out promotional packages to
executives touting the benefits of dressing casually on the job.
The packet included a videotape and brochures of sharp-looking
casual wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point in time, every CEO in the country found this
package on their desk,'' Rua said. ``And now, a major bank just
announced they were going casual. And why? It's because the
competitor did it. They don't even bother to look into the
statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide trend toward casual might keep companies from
implementing Dress-up Thursdays, at least in the beginning, some
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``As CPAs, we really follow trends, as opposed to lead,'' said
M. Bruce Cohen, managing partner of the PricewaterhouseCoopers
office in Albany. ``So as long as our clients are dressed casual,
we are going to do what they do. If our clients dress casually on a
Thursday, we will be dressed casually, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
