<P>
   FILMS-NOVELS (Undated) _ Film and the novel are cousins not far
removed, and the DNA they share is narrative. But their narrative
codes _ owing partly to obvious differences of media and partly to
their divergent histories _ have grown farther and farther apart.
By A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   PORTUGUESE-MODERNIST (New York) _ Modernism may or may not be
over, but that hasn't kept historians from widening its roll call,
adding names from more parts of the world. One of the latest
additions is the Portuguese painter Amedeo de Souza Cardoso, whose
work is now being seen in the United States for the first time in a
show of pieces borrowed primarily from the Gulbenkian Museum in
Lisbon. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BOWERY-HISTORY (New York) _ The Bowery deserves better than
its skid row connotations. When the aging buildings and their fire
escapes shimmer in the morning light, it's a place of urban beauty,
alluring as an Edward Hopper painting. By Sandee Brawarsky.
