<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4920 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-15 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A CREDIT TO GOVERNOR ALL AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's not bragging about it, but Gov. George W. Bush has spiced
Afro-Texans' first-of-the-new-century Juneteenth jubilee with
something special to eat, sing, dance, parade and orate about.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the emancipation of two plaques commemorating the
Confederacy from the Texas Supreme Court building melded perfectly
with the annual observance of Gen. Gordon Granger's June 19, 1865,
announcement of the emancipation of the slaves in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it wasn't planned that way. But because of the strong
symbolism of the removal of the plaques, one of which contains a
representation of the Confederate battle flag and the other the
seal of the Confederacy, it is hard to believe that it was not
premeditated political scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Bush is not taking credit for the deed. He did not
utter any kind of plaque emancipation proclamation. A Bush
representative said that the decision on the plaques' fate rested
with the General Services Commission. The GSC's executive director
said, however, that his agency was obligated to do whatever the
governor and the Texas Supreme Court told it to do.
</P>
<P>
   It's reasonable, therefore, to assume that the GSC took its
marching orders in the matter of the plaques either directly or
indirectly from the governor. But those orchestrating the Bush
presidential campaign undoubtedly would like to keep the candidate
in a posture of ``plausible deniability.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaques had become a meddlesome issue for Bush. The call for
their removal by the Texas chapter of the NAACP reminded the public
of his evasiveness on the Confederate battle flag issue during the
primary in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   He could not continue to evade the issue in his own state. He
needed to dispose of it to keep it from dogging his heels all the
way to November. So he did the right thing, both in absolute terms
and politically.
</P>
<P>
   Those plaques, which are so insulting to millions of
Afro-Texans, had no place in a place of such exalted significance
to the people of Texas, a building paid for by the taxpayers of the
state.
</P>
<P>
   It well may be that the governor did the right thing for
political reasons alone. But it also could be that he did it just
because he knew it was the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Some Texans, particularly Confederate heritage advocates, have
criticized the way the plaques were removed and new ones _
declaring that the Texas courts dispense ``equal justice ...
regardless of race, creed or color'' _ were substituted for them.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque exchange occurred unannounced last Friday after
working hours. Some see that as sneaking, craven and undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   Actually it was a display of good, pragmatic leadership. Bush
did not want to turn that business into a sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   He must have known that he would catch some grief from the
neo-Confederates, and he decided to weather it, knowing that it
will soon blow over. He has no reason to fear political retaliation
from them because they have nowhere else to go. They surely won't
vote for Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, has to be concerned about independent voters.
With his display of sensitivity to the concerns of
African-Americans, he has indicated that he is not writing them
off.
</P>
<P>
   He can take Texas without the black vote. But he may need some
of it in other states. And he could lose votes among white
independents in the Northeast and on the West Coast by appearing to
write off the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has reached that point in his campaign for
the presidency where he must begin to show that there really is a
compassionate side to his conservatism. He can afford to do that
because he has most of the white conservative voters _ not just the
neo-Cons _ in his hip pocket.
</P>
<P>
   His Juneteenth gesture was a good move in that direction. It was
politically smart. And it was the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
