u s BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-NYT &LR;      06-15 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY AND DE LA HOYA RENEW OLD RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They weighed 75 pounds when they first met. Shane
Mosley was 12 years old, Oscar De La Hoya was 11 and, according to
Mosley, the decision was never in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit him anytime I wanted to with the jab,'' Mosley recalled
during an interview in his downtown hotel suite. ``I beat him, but
that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As amateurs, they boxed about 60 rounds against each other,
developing a rivalry that will culminate Saturday night, when
Mosley and De La Hoya fight for the World Boxing Council
welterweight championship at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting De La Hoya's draw at the box office, promoters for Top
Rank are predicting that pay-per-view sales will be the largest in
history for a nonheavyweight fight. For De La Hoya, it is a chance
to polish his golden-boy image and finally put his haunting Sept.
18 loss to Felix Trinidad behind him.
</P>
<P>
   For Mosley, it is simply an opportunity to ascend to stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for a new champion,'' Mosley said. ``People need to
see just how Sugar Shane executes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley (34-0, 32 knockouts) can become the sixth fighter to win
both the lightweight and welterweight titles. He would join a group
that includes De La Hoya (32-1, 26 knockouts), Roberto Duran,
Pernell Whitaker, Henry Armstrong and Barney Ross.
</P>
<P>
   As a 135-pound lightweight, Mosley defended his title eight
times, winning each by knockout. He vacated the championship last
year and made the leap to the 147-pound welterweight division.
After knockouts of Wilfredo Rivera and Willie Wise, Mosley moved
into position for a reunion with De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting De La Hoya gives me a comfort level because we know
each other so well,'' Mosley said. ``A lot of other fighters have
gotten in the ring with him and get hit a couple of times and they
go, `Oh, wow,' and they start doubting themselves. With me, I know
what to expect. I know what I'm up against.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley has been staggered, but never knocked to the canvas in
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to their amateur days, he believes, his jabs are still
quicker and stronger than De La Hoya's. ``I can cover over the top
of his jab with mine,'' Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya politely disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's seen everything, he hasn't felt it,'' De La Hoya said.
``He's had 34 fights, but he doesn't have that kind of experience
to know how it feels to be hit by someone who can punch as hard as
me. I don't know how he's going to react, but it's an issue with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley and De La Hoya last met in the ring during sparring
sessions as they both prepared for the 1992 Olympics, where De La
Hoya won the gold medal at 132 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a jab contest between me and him,'' Mosley said. ``I
landed a lot of jabs and overhand rights. Oscar did what he does
best, throw a lot of combinations and left hooks.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya said, ``If he's going to use that fight there, he's
really in trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1542EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CYCLING-ARMSTRONG-NYT     06-15 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-ARMSTRONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG IS GETTING AHEAD OF HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong, who last summer capped an amazing recovery from
cancer by winning the Tour de France, the world's most prestigious
and difficult bicycle race, is a bit concerned about his physical
condition. He says he feels so sharp that he may be ready too soon
for this year's tour, from July 1-23.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my training and racing this year has been geared to the
tour,'' Armstrong said Wednesday night in a telephone interview
from his spring and summer home in Nice, France. ``I'm satisfied
with what I've done. In fact, maybe I'm a little ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in such good condition, you can't use it in
training or races to show off your strength. You can't constantly
go deep and try to be extraordinary all the time, or you'll break
down your form.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Armstrong, a 28-year-old Texan, and his U.S.
Postal Service team completed the Tour Dauphine Libere, eight days
through the French Alps with considerable climbing. His teammate
Tyler Hamilton won. Armstrong finished third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the same race last year,'' Armstrong said, ``and didn't
feel nearly as good as I did this year. So this told me that I'm
either stronger than I was last year or I'm too far ahead of
schedule now. I don't know. I have to be careful not to be ready
too quick.''
</P>
<P>
   That Armstrong is even riding is remarkable. Less than three
years ago, testicular cancer that had spread to his abdomen, lungs
and brain was diagnosed; doctors gave him less than a 50-50 chance
to recover. He not only recovered, but he also rode better than
ever. He said his health is fine now, and the slight concussion he
sustained a month ago in a training crash had done nothing except
persuade him to wear his helmet whenever he rides.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, back home in Austin, he spent much of his time with
his foundation spreading awareness of cancer. With Sally Jenkins,
he also wrote an autobiography, ``It's Not About the Bike: My
Journey Back to Life'' (Putnam). It was sixth among nonfiction
books on last Sunday's New York Times best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the defense of his Tour de France title, although his
human-interest drama has been overshadowed by the drug problems
that have haunted this race in recent years. Cycling officials are
suspending riders for two weeks if their red blood cell count
exceeds 50 percent, saying it may indicate the use of EPO, a
potentially life-threatening drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need a test,'' Armstrong said, ``but it needs to be
solid and fair. I hate to think we could have false positives and
see our sport thrown back into all that baloney again. There's not
nearly as much of that stuff used as people are led to believe.
From all my experience on all the teams I've been on, this is
overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, the percentage of red blood cells fluctuates
drastically according to the effort you put in. Mine is generally
43 or 44 percent, but if I train for three or four weeks at
altitude it could go up to 50 percent. So there's a problem
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's support staff is in place. At his three-bedroom home
in Nice, a mile uphill from the Mediterranean, he has his wife,
Kristin, and their 8-month-old son, Luke, who has started to crawl.
He says nothing is bothering him, including the pressure on a
defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   Does he expect to win the tour?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be disappointed if I don't,'' he said, ``but I don't know
if that means I expect to win. I certainly expect to be a factor.
In the tour, the strongest man almost always wins, and I felt I was
the strongest last year. When the race was in its hardest moments,
I felt I was there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4926 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-RACE-MEATPLANT-ART-6T     06-15 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-MEAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 AT A SLAUGHTERHOUSE, SOME THINGS NEVER DIE 
</HEADLINE>
 PLANT-ART-6TAKES-NYT   (Sixth in series)  
 (For release Friday, June 16)  
(EDS: Since Sunday, June 4, and continuing for six weeks, The New
York Times has been publishing a series of articles, ``How Race Is
Lived in America.'' The series is the outcome of a yearlong effort
by a team of Times reporters to capture some of the voices of
ordinary people and some of the troubling issues that Americans
continue to face. These stories, two or three each week, will be
approximately 6,000 words. The News Service will move each story in
advance, and an abridged version will also move, at approximately
3,000 words. They will move in the ``a'' news category and will
carry a slug of the form BC-RACE-SLUG-NYT. Because the articles are
organized into chapters, papers with severe space restraints may
choose to spread a single article over several days. Please see
RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-NYT for a detailed list, or call 888-346-9867
or 212-556-1927.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT601-606 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAR HEEL, N.C. _ It must have been 1 o'clock. That's when the
white man usually comes out of his glass office and stands on the
scaffolding above the factory floor. He stood with his palms on the
rails, his elbows out. He looked like a tower guard up there or a
border patrol agent. He stood with his head cocked.
</P>
<P>
   One o'clock means it is getting near the end of the workday.
Quota has to be met and the workload doubles. The conveyor belt
always overflows with meat around 1 o'clock. So the workers double
their pace, hacking pork from shoulder bones with a driven
single-mindedness. They stare blankly, like mules in blinders, as
the butchered slabs pass by.
</P>
<P>
   It is called the picnic line: 18 workers lined up on both sides
of a belt, carving meat from bone. Up to 16 million shoulders a
year come down that line here at Smithfield Packing Co., the
largest pork production plant in the world. That works out to about
32,000 a shift, 63 a minute, one every 17 seconds for each worker
for eight and a half hours a day. The first time you stare down at
that belt you know your body is going to give in way before the
machine ever will.
</P>
<P>
   On this day the boss saw something he didn't like. He climbed
down and approached the picnic line from behind. He leaned into the
ear of a broad-shouldered black man. He had been riding him all
day, and the day before. The boss bawled him out good this time,
but no one heard what was said. The roar of the machinery was too
ferocious for that. Still, everyone knew what was expected. They
worked harder.
</P>
<P>
   The white man stood and watched for the next two hours as the
blacks worked in their groups and the Mexicans in theirs. He stood
there with his head cocked.
</P>
<P>
   At shift change the black man walked away, hosed himself down
and turned in his knives. Then he let go. He threatened to murder
the boss. He promised to quit. He said he was losing his mind,
which made for good comedy, since he was standing near a conveyor
chain of severed hogs' heads, their mouths yoked open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who that cracker think he is?'' the black man wanted to know.
There were enough hogs, he said, ``not to worry about no fleck of
meat being left on the bone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep treating me like a Mexican and I'll beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   The boss walked by just then and the black man lowered his head.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GETS THE DIRTY JOBS
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you learn in the hog plant is the value of a
sharp knife. The second thing you learn is that you don't want to
work with a knife. Finally you learn that not everyone has to work
with a knife. Whites, blacks, American Indians and Mexicans, they
all have their separate stations.
</P>
<P>
   The few whites on the payroll tend to be mechanics or
supervisors. As for the Indians, a handful are supervisors; others
tend to get clean menial jobs like warehouse work. With few
exceptions, that leaves the blacks and Mexicans with the dirty jobs
at the factory, one of the only places within 50 miles in this
muddy corner of North Carolina where a person might make more than
$8 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   While Smithfield's profits nearly doubled in the past year,
wages have remained flat. So a lot of Americans here have quit and
a lot of Mexicans have been hired to take their places. But more
than management, the workers see one another as the problem, and
they see the competition in skin tones.
</P>
<P>
   The locker rooms are self-segregated and so is the cafeteria.
The enmity spills out into the towns. The races generally keep to
themselves. Along Interstate 95 there are four tumbledown bars, one
for each color: white, black, red and brown.
</P>
<P>
   Language is also a divider. There are English and Spanish lines
at the Social Security office and in the waiting rooms of the
county health clinics. This means that different groups don't
really understand one another and tend to be suspicious of what
they do know.
</P>
<P>
   You begin to understand these things the minute you apply for
the job.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOD AND BURNOUT
</P>
<P>
   ``Treat the meat like you going to eat it yourself,'' the hiring
manager told the 30 new employees, most of them down on their luck
and hungry for work. The Smithfield plant will take just about any
man or woman with a pulse and a sparkling urine sample. This
reporter was hired using his own name and acknowledged that he was
currently employed but was not asked where and did not say.
</P>
<P>
   Slaughtering swine is repetitive, brutish work, so grueling that
three weeks on the factory floor leave no doubt in your mind about
why the turnover is 100 percent. Five thousand quit and five
thousand are hired every year. You hear people say, They don't kill
pigs in the plant, they kill people.
</P>
<P>
   So desperate is the company for workers, its recruiters comb the
streets of New York's immigrant communities, personnel staff
members say, and word of mouth has reached Mexico and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The company even procures criminals. Several at the morning
orientation were inmates on work release in green uniforms, bused
in from the county prison.
</P>
<P>
   The new workers were given a safety speech and tax papers, shown
a promotional video and informed that there was enough methane,
ammonia and chlorine at the plant to kill every living thing here
in Bladen County. Of the 30 new employees, the black women were
assigned to the chitterlings room, where they would scrape feces
and worms from intestines. The black men were sent to the
butchering floor. The two free white men and the Indian were given
jobs making boxes. And most of the Mexicans, whose orientation was
given in Spanish, were assigned knife work, cutting sides of pork
into smaller and smaller products.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
