<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUDERANCH-HORSES-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SADDLE TO SPA, DUDE RANCH HAS IT ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAVONNA MAY-MONS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pulling up to the main house of Southern Cross Ranch, dust
flying up like a storm cloud behind the minivan, I feel like I'm
coming home to grandma's house. On the back porch a German shepherd
snoozes. It glances up at me as I open the screen door and enter
the kitchen, then closes its eyes once more and continues its nap.
</P>
<P>
   Before closing the door, I take a deep breath, inhaling not only
the clean, crisp Georgia air, but also the surrounding vision:
lush, green grass; 10 or so dogs lying in the shade; the horses and
cattle; twin reindeer statues on the lawn; and the fresh dust
settling from our trip. A sense of calm overcomes me, even though I
feel a wave of excitement over the adventure I'm about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   You see, unless you count the time I sat on a pony's back and
was led around in circles at a carnival years ago, I've never
ridden a horse. I'd chosen my destination, Southern Cross Ranch in
Georgia, specifically to learn to ride _ but without having to
rough it.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Cross Ranch, a new breed of dude ranch that combines a
working ranch with the Southern comfort of a bed-and-breakfast inn,
sits on 200 acres deep in Georgia's cattle country. The ranch is in
Madison, smack dab in the middle of the Antebellum Trail, a stretch
covering such small towns as Athens, Watkinsville, Madison,
Eatonton, Milledgeville, Old Clinton and Macon that represent the
historic significance of the Old South. Madison, for instance, was
one of the few towns left unburned during General Sherman's rampage
through Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   German native Inge Wendling began construction on the ranch
after years as a successful horse breeder in Indiana. The ranch,
with room for 50 guests, opened in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The 12,000-square-foot Southern antebellum mansion has rooms
with names like Mint Julep, General Lee, Scarlett O'Hara, Navaho
and Painted Desert. The mixed themes reflect Wendling's attempt to
mix Southern gentility with the rugged West.
</P>
<P>
   She has succeeded. My comfortable room had a king-size bed, TV
and VCR, and private bath with a whirlpool _ a feature that was
particularly welcome after my first few encounters with a horse.
</P>
<P>
   And, pampering aside, I'd come to learn how to ride.
</P>
<P>
   I'd come to the right place. New riders weren't thrown into the
woods alone, which suited me just fine. A guide accompanied me on
my first few rides, after which I rode with other guests. Our rides
on the wooded trails ranged from peaceful to exciting with the
surrounding trees providing ample shade; the trails are so varied
and the ranch so large that we could ride for hours without leaving
the property.
</P>
<P>
   And we learned more than just how to sit in the saddle. Each
guest was responsible for getting his or her horse out of the pen,
brushing it, hosing it down, cleaning its hoofs and putting on its
saddle and bridle. The same was done when you returned to the
stable. Newcomers, like me, were instructed how to do this properly
and, needless to say, breaking a sweat was involved.
</P>
<P>
   But it was well worth it. Even my horse's numerous attempts to
assassinate me didn't ruin my extraordinary experience.
</P>
<P>
   My horse's name was Bear _ an apt name for the medium-sized
brown horse with a white patch on its nose, who seemed out to get
me from the moment he laid eyes on me. Maybe I'm exaggerating a
bit, but after he bolted into the woods with me hanging onto the
saddle for dear life, I got the impression that he didn't care for
me too much. Most guests rode the same horse throughout their stay;
I tried to get rid of Bear, with no luck.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my Bear troubles, the other guests and I quickly fell
into an agreeable routine.
</P>
<P>
   My days usually began with an 8 a.m. breakfast, followed by an
hourlong trail ride. Next came nap time followed by lunch, another
horse ride, more napping and dinner. If I had the energy, I could
take a dip in the pool or soak in the hot tub behind the house,
play on the trampoline out back, or challenge another guest to a
game of horseshoes. Most nights were spent chitchatting with other
guests and watching videos.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
