r t BC-DUDERANCH-HORSES-2ndT     06-15 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUDERANCH-HORSES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: and watching videos. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps because we all were enticed by the horses, the guests
proved to be an amiable group who got to know each other quickly; I
came alone but I didn't get lonely. My fellow guests, including a
group of German men and women, a family of three, two couples and
three college students, mingled in the game room and the den. We
all ate together, enjoying plentiful meals such as lasagna and
fried chicken, prepared by a private chef.
</P>
<P>
   Three days of sleeping late, watching shows I don't have time to
catch at home, gorging myself on food and riding a horse for four
hours a day made the time go quickly. All too soon, I was eating my
last meal at the Southern Cross.
</P>
<P>
   I finished my breakfast of fruit, eggs, sausage and orange juice
and said goodbye to the guests and my host. As I rode off in the
ranch's courtesy van, I looked back and sighed, feeling rested in
body and mind.
</P>
<P>
   I may have been going home, but I had fond memories of long, hot
baths, lazy mornings, yummy food _ and yes, even Bear.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   If You Go
</P>
<P>
   The rooms: The 14 rooms at Southern Cross Ranch are rated on a
five-level system, ranging from $275 to $375 and up for a
three-night stay. More expensive rooms may include a fireplace,
whirlpool tub or hot tub, and vaulted ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Rates include twice-daily horseback rides, mountain-bike use,
game-room privileges, access to video selection, three meals a day,
snacks and non-alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   To do: Beginners can take an hourlong riding lesson for $25.
Most guests take a morning ride after breakfast, then lounge
around. The ranch has a few mountain bikes, but guests who want to
ensure usage should bring their own. Guests are free to hike on the
property.
</P>
<P>
   Off-the-ranch options include a group trip to Hard Labor Creek
Park for an 8.8-mile trail hike. The park is Georgia's largest at
5,800 acres and offers camping, hiking, fishing, trail riding and
an 18-hole golf course. Another option is a tour of historic
Madison, ``The Town Sherman Refused to Burn,'' where guests can
shop at numerous antique, craft and Civil War artifact boutiques.
Lake Oconee is a few miles away and offers 19,000 acres of good
fishing. Guests with a car can take day trips to either Atlanta
(one hour north) or Augusta (one hour east).
</P>
<P>
   Information: Southern Cross Ranch, (706) 342-8027;
www.southcross.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ranch Web sites
</P>
<P>
   Trolling for a dude ranch experience? Here are some helpful Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   www.ranchweb.com: A comprehensive Web site for people serious
about finding the right ranching vacation. Ranches are listed by
state, travel category (professional chef, golf, kids, etc.) and
type (lodge, dude ranch, family ranch, etc.). Visitors may also
browse ranch reviews and join discussion boards.
</P>
<P>
   www.duderanches.com: An easy-to-navigate site that shows ranches
by state or by using an interactive map. Contact information is
listed for each ranch. The site's top-rated ranches are listed
under Favorite Ranches.
</P>
<P>
   adventurequest.com: Offers a wide assortment of adventure
vacations, from hiking to windsurfing. More than 50 horseback
riding adventures are featured. Adventurequest.com lists a
description of the trip, cost and difficulty level. If you find a
trip you like, simply contact adventure tours for reservations.
</P>
<P>
   gorp.com: Another comprehensive adventure vacation Web site,
Gorp.com allows you to search for ranch vacations by state,
departure date and activity (biking, cattle drives, etc.). You can
make reservations online. Listings include a brief description of
the ranch and price range.
</P>
<P>
   _
