<HEADER>
A4939 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COW-PARADE-PROFILE-AR     06-15 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COW-PARADE-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOCKED FROM PARLIAMENT, SHE TURNED TO ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOYCE WADLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I've painted four cows,'' Edwina Sandys, the artist
and sculptor, is saying, of _ oh, why bother trying to stop
ourselves; if you've been walking around town you can see it's
going to be a very silly day _ her current cowmission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first was for the New York Public Library; it's called the
Moobile Library. I have another cow for the SoHo and TriBeCa
Partnerships. Then Peter Price, the head of Avenue magazine, asked
me to do one for EdificeRex, the other for the magazine.
`Cowmoonication' and `Herd on the Avenue.' He's going to put them
in the Met Life building.''
</P>
<P>
   A little defensive here, in that brisk, British accent you
expect when dealing with a granddaughter of Winston Churchill. But
wry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to spend my life with cows, only one cow leads
to another.''
</P>
<P>
   Cows to our left, cows to our right: Cow Parade 2000 begins
Thursday, with 500 life-size cow sculptures (Holsteins) around town
through summer.
</P>
<P>
   Enter also, Edwina Sandys (pronounced SANDS), who despite her
concern about her reputation knows a good deal about fun.
</P>
<P>
   Witty _ that's the word often used for her work. A small
sculpture, titled ``Marriage Bed,'' with a doll's bed that's half
nails, half roses. Sandys also does sculpture on a large scale. Her
15-foot piece, ``Child,'' is in front of the U.N. International
School. ``Christa,'' her sculpture of a female Jesus on the cross,
made her the center of controversy in the early '80s. She has also
done a sculpture from a section of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very attractive, very intelligent and very daring,''
says Hans Janitschek, a correspondent for the Austrian paper Kronen
Zeitung, who met Sandys at the Ritz Hotel in London in 1972, when
he was secretary general of the Socialist International and she a
Conservative, and they nonetheless became close friends. ``You
always had the feeling she was up to something, and she was. And
whether she has money or not, she will always manage. She has the
ability to live in a castle like a big star or in a studio, which
she did in New York, ordering from a Chinese restaurant around the
corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Some colors pop, Sandys says. Orange and blue, also red and
green. In addition, red is her primary color. Her hair is red. The
linen shirt she's wearing over black tights and a black T-shirt is
red. You enter Sandy's spectacular SoHo two-floor loft into a red
alcove. If you stay for a few hours, bothering her with personal
questions as she paints her cows _ Sandys is too polite to say it's
time to leave _ you will see the deep red bathroom. Sandy's second
husband, the architect Richard Kaplan, who works as an
administrator of his family's J.M. Kaplan Fund, designed the
apartment. Sandys, who came to New York after her divorce in the
'70s, is able to support herself with her work, but not, she
concedes cheerfully, in this style.
</P>
<P>
   There are things Sandys does not like speaking about: her
grandfather, who died when she was 23; the death of her mother,
Diana, Churchill's eldest daughter, who committed suicide when
Sandys was 24. ``They say there is no such thing as bad
publicity,'' she says, half to herself toward the end of the
interview, in the tone of one who is having doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Sandys' father was Lord Duncan Sandys, a British cabinet
minister; she was presented to Queen Elizabeth as a debutante.
Always artistic, Sandys worked briefly as an assistant to a
dressmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Career plans?
</P>
<P>
   ``I only knew that I wanted to marry, and um, I would like to
marry an ambassador so I could be an ambassadress. So I could have
a public life in some way. I assumed I would have an interesting
life through a man. That's the way it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandys married Piers Dixon, the son of the British ambassador to
France, at 21, had two sons, then, still in her 20s, decided to run
for a seat in Parliament. She gave that up when supporters of her
husband, who was also planning a run, told her that wouldn't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told him they were interested in couples only,'' Sandys
says. ``They said it was as if they were having a big party and had
hired a butler and a cook, and at the last moment the cook did not
turn up. They said, `Tell your wife to get off the bus.' So I got
off the bus. And into painting. And then we got a divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy's wrote a novel, moved to Tuscany, Italy, where she had a
home, then, running out of money, sold the house and came to New
York. There will be a show at Egizio's Project in SoHo in November.
She is also finishing a book called ``Penelope in Belgravia'' _
paintings she did in the '70s to which she has added a story line.
``Sometimes I feel like doing something totally outrageous,'' the
married and wealthy heroine says. Was the heroine she? Perhaps a
bit, she'll say.
</P>
<P>
   As for how she met her present husband, it's one personal story
in which she delights: She needed a lift to the Hamptons, and he
arrived to drive her out, bringing her the gift of a red rose
tucked into a lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fell in love that instant.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later comes a call, regarding Winston Churchill. ``Hey,
you asked me to tell you something about my grandfather: He liked
cows. That might be your final shot. He had a herd of, I think,
belted Galloways. For aesthetic purposes, he liked the way they
looked against the hillside.''
</P>
<P>
   Any other memories?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now don't delve too much. And don't forget Egizio's Project;
that's where I'll be in the fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
