<SLUG> BC-GORE-COELHO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COELHO QUITS AS GORE'S CAMPAIGN CHAIRMAN, CITING HEALTH REASONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT9 and 10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tony Coelho has resigned as chairman of Vice
President Al Gore's presidential campaign for health reasons, the
Gore campaign announced Thursday. He will be replaced by Commerce
Secretary William Daley, several campaign officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The call I made to the vice president last night informing him
of my doctor's advice is one of the most difficult calls I have
ever had to make,'' Coelho said in a statement released by Gore
headquarters in Nashville, Tenn. ``My doctors have told me that I
need to slow down, eat better and travel less for a period of time.
Unfortunately, none of this advice is consistent with the rigors of
chairing a presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho, whose 58th birthday is Thursday, was hospitalized
earlier this week with an inflamed colon. His departure has nothing
to do with a continuing criminal inquiry into his role as head of
the U.S. exhibit at the 1998 World Exhibition in Portugal, two
campaign officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore paid a warm tribute to his departing chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Coelho led this campaign to a tremendous victory in the
primaries, and he has put an incredible team in place for the
general election,'' Gore said. ``Tony has been an invaluable friend
and adviser. I look forward to calling upon Tony's counsel and help
once again just as soon as his doctors give me the word.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that Daley would leave the Commerce Department
and take over the helm of the Gore campaign will be made later
Thursday, said a campaign official who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Daley has led the Clinton administration's effort to pass a bill
that would normalize U.S. trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Daley is the brother of Mayor Richard M. Daley of Chicago and
the son of the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, who led Chicago for two
decades and wielded enormous power in the national Democratic Party
until his death in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho served in the House of Representatives from 1978 to 1989,
representing part of California's Central Valley and earning a
reputation as a highly effective fund-raiser for Democratic
candidates. He joined the Gore campaign in May 1999 at a time when
it was struggling with out-of-control spending.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department inspector general inquiry had found
questionable spending surrounding the U.S. exhibit in Portugal's
World Exhibition. It found that Expo officials had violated federal
rules by hiring Coelho's niece. A Portuguese bank also made a
$300,000 loan to Coelho for a private foundation to build a
memorial at the fair.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley M. Brand, Coelho's lawyer, said his client's reasons for
quitting had nothing to do with the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is health,'' Brand said. ``It's the kind of issue where he
has been told he can't travel, he has to restrict his diet. He is
not the kind of guy who can operate in a job with those kinds of
restrictions and feel comfortable that he is doing 100 percent.
That's really what has brought this about, nothing else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
