<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SHAFT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-15 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAFT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHAFT': HE'S STILL RISKING HIS LIFE FOR HIS BROTHER, MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's unusual for a movie to stack the deck with a fistful of
jokers, but the new version of ``Shaft'' _ part remake and part
sequel _ does just that. Here, John Shaft is not a complicated man.
He's not even as complicated as the second-rate score, which has
more wah-wah pedal guitar effects than the ``Shaft'' marathon TNT
ran a couple of nights ago. (It's as if the composer, David Arnold,
were trying to show he's ecologically minded, since he recycles
Isaac Hayes' triumphant ``Theme From `Shaft''' throughout the
movie.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the always dependable and indomitable Samuel
L. Jackson as John Shaft, nephew of the seminal free-lance crime
fighter in the 1971 original, is unmistakably the star. His
sharpshooter's timing and saucer-eyed self-awareness has found a
home: He's doing Samuel L. Jackson again, only this time he's
called Shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Shaft is a Manhattan police detective when first introduced, and
he makes more entrances in this picture than Joan Crawford had in
her entire career. For about a third of its running time, ``Shaft''
is basically a runway show, and not for Eleganza this time. The
hero is done up in Giorgio Armani's trademark sleekness, and he
wears it well, though he dresses like R. Kelly. When Shaft verbally
smacks down a colleague (Daniel Von Bergen) who brags about the
four-bedroom house he bought in Long Island, it's an example of the
pot calling the kettle extravagant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaft'' may be the most unrepentantly politically incorrect
movie since the glory days of ``The French Connection.'' When Shaft
is ready to go to work in one of several shootouts _ some of the
most primitively staged gunplay since the Republic western serials
of the 1940s _ he cocks a shotgun and cracks, ``It's Giuliani
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that lack of sensitivity may come from the writer
Richard Price, who contributed the character of the drug kingpin
Peoples Hernandez. As Peoples, the skillful and talented Jeffrey
Wright steals the movie, though it's petty larceny, to be sure.
Peoples is a trash-talking, violent exemplar of the id. His
peculiar enunciation leads one to believe he has burned the roof of
his mouth. ``Ju god a bin'ness car?'' he says, and we know he means
``You got a business card?''
</P>
<P>
   The picture wants to trade on the not-so-subtle differences
between stereotype and archetype, and it breaks a sweat trying to
shatter them. In that way, laboring to find its own politics in the
naive but powerful way the original did, ``Shaft'' becomes the
United Nations of misanthropy. It has not only Peoples Hernandez,
but also a wealthy, heartless WASP racist, Walter Wade Jr.
(Christian Bale).
</P>
<P>
   Wade sets the picture into motion when he beats a young black
man (Mekhi Phifer) to death, then beats the rap by fleeing the
country. Shaft becomes a ``black private dick'' and leaves the
police force to bring Wade to justice, flinging his shield at the
judge who sets Wade free on bail.
</P>
<P>
   Like the original, ``Shaft'' becomes a woman-in-jeopardy movie.
Diane (Toni Colette), a waitress, witnesses the assault and
disappears. Shaft and his friend Detective Carmen Vasquez (Vanessa
Williams) set out to track her down. Peoples and Wade join forces,
though the spectacle of these two battling for onscreen primacy _
the chilly, brittle Wade and the florid, sly Peoples _ is not
unlike a death match between Luciano Pavarotti and Placido Domingo
for the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to remember a movie so unapologetically flamboyant as
``Shaft,'' with two major villains, Bale and Wright, as well as a
star who welds the mismatched pieces together through sheer
presence. Jackson uses the intense, deliberate concentration of a
Baptist preacher, even on a laugh line. Every dialogue exchange is
a baptism by fire, and the hero is as much fun to watch as the
villain.
</P>
<P>
   Though saucy and upbeat, he's judgmental; the fact that no one
understands him but his woman is not an issue this time around,
because he doesn't have one. Except for a sex scene in the opening
with nothing but torsos _ a scene cut so quickly it almost seems
subliminal and you may not be sure if Shaft is in it _ the movie
has no romance.
</P>
<P>
   The one area in which the original ``Shaft'' succeeded is that
it explicitly portrayed black men as sexual beings in a way they
had never been onscreen before. Though an outrageous flirt, the
nouveau Shaft has more affection for his wardrobe than anything
else. It would be way too retro to have Shaft carry on with the
ladies as if it were still the '70s, but it would be nice if he at
least had a steady girlfriend. He's very close to the kind of guy
Sidney Poitier (and Eddie Murphy in the ``Beverly Hills Cops''
movies) often played who strode into a situation, saved the day and
left alone.
</P>
<P>
   For filmgoers, especially African-American filmgoers, of a
certain generation, it's tough to stop thinking of ``Shaft'' as
something that belongs to them. Yes, ``Shaft'' has to be different,
if only because the remake simply couldn't generate the same
visceral impact as the original. Simply by changing the color
scheme of a shopworn genre, film noir, it made a political
statement. And adding elements of New York cultural history, like
basing the villain Bumpy Jonas on a real-life racketeer, Bumpy
Johnson, gave it whispers of confidence in the black audience's
pride in allusions to many sides of its history. There's no way the
new ``Shaft'' can still have the same giddy shock of the new.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Shaft'' is aware of the racial politics of this new
era. The scene that incites Wade to violence features a comeback by
his victim that's a sure-fire pleaser, though it also make it clear
that no one wins in such confrontations. ``Too black for the
uniform, too blue for the brothers'' is the reason Jackson's Shaft
gives his uncle (the original Shaft, Richard Roundtree, cooler and
silkier than ever; it's a crime he's not used more) for leaving the
force.
</P>
<P>
   The politics seem glib here, more cynical than in any
blaxploitation-era movie, and by the end Shaft has turned into a
vigilante. With plot points cribbed from the history of the black
action film, from ``Gordon's War'' to ``New Jack City,'' ``Shaft''
is pasted together like a ransom note.
</P>
<P>
   This may be the first movie that runs under two hours and yet
has no attention span: characters are abandoned and picked up;
narrative threads dissolve before your very eyes, no doubt because
of the backstage battles.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that the director John Singleton and his co-producer,
Scott Rudin, squabbled like Peoples and Wade. Though ``Shaft'' will
probably score at the box office, it will be a cheap, opportunistic
victory.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Singleton; written by Richard Price, Singleton
and Shane Salerno, based on a story by Singleton and Salerno and
the novel ``Shaft,'' by Ernest Tidyman; director of photography,
Donald E. Thorin; edited by John Bloom and Antonia Van Drimmelen;
music by David Arnold and Isaac Hayes; production designer,
Patrizia von Brandenstein; produced by Scott Rudin and Singleton;
released by Paramount Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Samuel L. Jackson (John Shaft), Vanessa Williams
(Detective Carmen Vasquez), Jeffrey Wright (Peoples Hernandez),
Christian Bale (Walter Wade Jr.), Busta Rhymes (Rasaan), Dan Hedaya
(Jack Roselli), Toni Collette (Diane Palmieri), Richard Roundtree
(Uncle John Shaft), Ruben Santiago-Hudson (Jimmy Groves), Daniel
Von Bergen (Lieutenant Kearney) and Mekhi Phifer (Trey Howard). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaft'' is rated is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes multiple scenes of gunplay,
beatings and lots of profanity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
