<P>
   GORE-STAFF (Cincinnati) _ Commerce Secretary William Daley
replaces Tony Coehlo as chairman of Vice President Al Gore's
presidential campaign. Coehlo, 58, cites health problems for his
departure. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTION (Houston) _ The lone eyewitness in the murder
trial of Gary Graham speaks publicly for the first time about why
she has never wavered in her testimony that Graham killed a man
outside a Houston market 19 years ago. Graham, 36, who has
steadfastly maintained his innocence, is scheduled to be executed
later this month. By SALATHEIA BRYANT.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTION-PSYCHOLOGIST (Austin, Texas) _ Walter Quijano, the
former psychologist for the Texas prison system, talks about what
it is like to be in the middle of the maelstrom over Texas
executions. Quijano's testimony about predicting future violence of
convicts and how race relates to violence has prompted state
officials to challenge his credibility in all cases in which he has
testified. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BONFIRE (College Station, Texas) _ Texas A&AMP;M President Ray
Bowen plans to reveal Friday whether the school will continue its
traditional Aggie Bonfire. The collapse of the bonfire last fall
killed 12 people. By JOHN WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   ROTHKO-CHAPEL (Houston) _ The Rothko Chapel was commissioned by
visionary art patrons John and Dominique de Menil and named for
American artist Mark Rothko, whose 14 giant canvases define its
meditative interior. It has been one of Houston's most famous
international destinations since its dedication in February 1971,
and the compelling building is set to reopen Saturday after an
extensive renovation. By PATRICIA C. JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RENO-DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno
weighs into the controversy over whether death row inmates have
gotten fair trials, saying some of them have been assigned bad
lawyers who failed to take advantage of DNA evidence. ``In too many
instances'' defendants are denied good lawyers who can ``properly''
represent them, Reno says at her weekly news conference. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Why isn't Hillary Clinton doing
better against a Republican opponent so obscure that 64 percent of
New Yorkers in a recent survey didn't know anything about him? In
the Senate race, she's in a dead heat with U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio.
Whatever happened to that familiar axiom, you can't beat somebody
with nobody? Maybe it is being trumped by another axiom: People
don't vote FOR candidates - they vote AGAINST them. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
