<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4962 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-VOYEUR-TV0616-COX     06-15 1864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOYEUR-TV0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peep shows
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We've become a nation of peeping Toms. We like
to watch, and we especially like to watch real people in dangerous,
pathetic, embarrassing or scandalous situations.
</P>
<P>
   A young woman tells Jerry Springer her boyfriend is cheating on
her, and Springer gleefully reveals the man is sleeping with her
mother. A restaurant worker spits into a plateful of food and
serves it to a customer as viewers yell ``eeeeeeew!'' But they
remain transfixed. Pets attack, toddlers crash into trees with
salad bowls on their heads. On and on we watch.
</P>
<P>
   We peep into private homes, island campsites, studio
confessionals and any other place human nature is on display. Those
of us who aren't actually peeping are hoping to be peeped at. For
many people today, reality _ in the form of births, birthdays,
weddings, anniversaries, even funerals _ doesn't exist without
video images. We're voyeurs on one side of the window;
exhibitionists on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, 18 million people watched ``Survivor,'' the latest in
a long line of voyeuristic TV shows dating back to 1948 when Allen
Funt flipped on his ``Candid Camera,'' and 1956 when housewives
sobbed out their woes in exchange for applause and prizes on
``Queen for a Day.'' The biggest phenomenon on TV this year is
``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire,'' which lets us groan or cheer,
cluck or complain while watching ordinary folks answer (or fail to
answer) an array of trivial questions.
</P>
<P>
   And coming soon will be the Orwellian ``Big Brother'' on CBS, a
summer series that will give peepers the chance to see a houseful
of strangers coping with life under the microscope of dozens of
hidden cameras. It's a mainstream version of MTV's strangely sturdy
``Real World,'' a modest cable show that was considered innovative
when it debuted in 1992. Now it's considered rather passe with no
prize money, no eating of rats, no struggles to survive.
</P>
<P>
   What does all this so-called reality say about us as a national
crop of couch potatoes? Maybe something, maybe nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the attraction of these programs is the hope of
watching something violent or sexual,'' says Deborah Peel,
president of the Texas Society of Psychiatric Physicians and a
psychoanalyst in private practice. ``They're not set up to show
tenderness or altruism. They're designed to promote friction,
tension and bad behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But Art Farley, a psychoanalyst who practices and teaches in
Austin and Houston, thinks the desire to watch the trials and
tribulations of others is little more than innate curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much like watching soap operas,'' Farley says. ``It
gives people the opportunity to live through other people's lives,
and they find that enormously satisfying. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways these shows are a little like a conflict-laden
dream, a window into our unconscious. The more real they are, even
though they may be bad TV, the more easily you can vicariously live
through these people. It's human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   But if we're watching soap operas, talk shows and reality shows
to feel good about our own less scandalous lives or to feel
superior to the exposed sufferers, is that a good use of our
entertainment time?
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be an outlet for various aggressive or hostile
fantasies,'' Peel says. ``But voyeurism is very passive. You watch;
you don't act. Some things you watch on TV are beautiful or
meaningful, but this real stuff is hardly art. It just takes you
away from acting on your own life.
</P>
<P>
   NATURE OF THE BEAST
</P>
<P>
   Of course, television by its definition is voyeuristic, as are
other forms of dramatic entertainment. The audience sits and
watches. Theatergoers watch actors on a stage, who pretend nobody's
watching. Movies take it a step further, with the action tossed up
on a huge screen in front of an audience sitting in the dark. But
television has that added element of privacy that takes voyeurism
to another level. If you're watching something awful, nobody has to
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voyeurism and TV are so perfectly meant to be together that
the miracle isn't that it's happening now,'' says Robert Thompson,
director of Syracuse University's Center for the Study of Popular
Television. ``The miracle is we've had the taste or discretion to
wait this long. There's just an innate something wired into people.
It's the thing that makes us look into medicine cabinets in other
people's houses or not hang up the extension phone when we hear
someone talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there may be a survival element to the penchant to
snoop, the ability to find out a person's vulnerability in order to
conquer and thrive.
</P>
<P>
   But if all this snooping is so natural, why are we often ashamed
of it? More than 23 million people tuned into Fox's ``Who Wants to
Marry a Multimillionaire,'' yet it was hard to find anyone who
wasn't copping an attitude about it: ``I can't believe you watched
that! I flipped through it for a few seconds, but that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   So, where did those 23 million people come from? We're not
proud, but we're watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day before that show was on was Valentine's Day, and I ate
a whole box of chocolates,'' confessed Thompson. ``I insulted my
own dignity, but it felt so good going down. Watching
`Multimillionaire' was stupid, a waste of two hours on one level.
But the feeling of your jaw dropping lower and lower is a
surprisingly pleasant feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW LOW WILL WE GO?
</P>
<P>
   TV trends don't usually start strong and then weaken. They tend
to become more and more extreme, and the ``Web cam'' sites that
stream video over the Internet are perhaps the most bizarre aspect
of reality pon, D.C., resident Jennifer Ringley go about her daily
life (including changing her clothes and taking a shower) can pay a
subscription fee for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wanting to be watched by other people sounds empty and hollow
to me,'' says Peel. ``These people might want to think about
getting some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Television hasn't gone as far as jennicam yet, but it might
someday. Sitcoms used to be mild and sweet; now they're crude and
caustic. Dramas used to be thoughtful if slightly melodramatic; now
they're fast-paced and gritty. On ``ER,'' people bleed profusely
and vomit. Just as it takes more graphic sex and violence to
appease moviegoers now than it did in the 1950s, it will take even
more shocking reality to keep viewers ogling.
</P>
<P>
   Watching people search for love on ``The Dating Game'' and vie
for big bucks on ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' seemed harmless
enough _ until the two shows evolved into ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire.'' And we all know the low point TV reached when
Darva and Rick said ``I do.'' If it takes eating rats to keep
people riveted to ``Survivor,'' will the folks on ``Big Brother''
feel compelled to show us their bathroom habits?
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect we're going to see a spiral of extremes,'' Thompson
says. ``Although they certainly speak to our less noble instincts,
I think they're going to be the next big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Caveat emptor. Television is in the business of grabbing
eyeballs and selling ads, and network executives will do pretty
much whatever it takes to do that. ``When Animals Attack'' and
``World's Scariest Police Videos'' are proof positive.
</P>
<P>
   WHOM THEY'RE AFTER
</P>
<P>
   The networks don't want just any old eyeballs. They want young,
well-to-do eyeballs, and they've found them in the new reality
shows. CBS has been saddled with an audience of viewers primarily
over 50 for decades, but now it has ``Survivor'' and is eagerly
awaiting the birth of ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept of adventure is very much in fashion with
the younger generation,'' says David Poltrack, CBS's guru of
ratings and research. ``There's been a lot of young, 18- to
34-year-old viewers for 'Survivor.' They also tend to be in the
upper-income brackets, college-educated and slightly more female.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Big Brother'' attracts the same clientele as MTV's ``Real
World,'' more men and even younger viewers will watch. ``Real
World,'' which began its ninth season Tuesday, is enormously
appealing to young people because it validates their lives with the
status of a TV show. It takes their problems, mostly
relationship-oriented, and turns them into high drama and grand
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of danger and disaster is part of the appeal of
reality shows. But the mass consumption of human beings for the
purpose of entertainment can destroy lives, a threat that was
explored in the movies ``The Truman Show'' and ``EDtv.'' One of the
contestants in the European version of ``Survivor'' committed
suicide after being voted out of the tribe on national television.
Programmers may figure if it doesn't happen on camera, it's OK.
</P>
<P>
   Real on-air disaster is not very likely because the reality is
manipulated for TV. Clearly nobody on ``Survivor'' is going to
starve to death or die from a snakebite. Camera crews and producers
are lurking behind every palm tree. And reality is altered by
virtue of turning on the camera. Are the subjects really ignoring
the camera? We don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about these shows is totally contrived,'' says
Thompson. ``They put people in contrived situations and record
them. The only thing real is that we're seeing previously
noncelebrity characters trying to become famous and win money.
Viewers know this, but they don't care. They've seen so much TV and
heard so many experts pontificating about it that they're
absolutely savvy to the manipulation of the media.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet we watch. Like rubber-necking drivers slowing down to
peek at a bloody accident, we're unable to turn away.
</P>
<P>
   THE EVOLUTION OF REALITY TELEVISION . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Candid Camera'' (1948-90) _ Smile! You're on ``Candid
Camera.'' The phrase is part of the national vernacular. The
prime-time show ``caught people in the act of being themselves.''
Conceived and hosted by Allen Funt, each episode captured scenes on
hidden camera _ a mailbox talked to a surprised letter-dropper, a
mechanic opened a woman's car hood to check the oil and found no
engine, teen-agers combed their elaborate coifs in a high-school
bathroom, a cop directed traffic to his own imaginary music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Queen for a Day'' (1956-70) _ A bizarre daytime game show
during which four or five women competed to see whose sob story
spawned the most applause from the studio audience. The woman who
boosted the meter the highest won a cheesy-looking crown and
whatever such as nuclear proliferation and less serious subjects
such as cross-dressing. Donahue sacrificed his dignity when he
appeared in a dress for that one, but he remained popular until
``Oprah'' knocked him off. ``Donahue'' is the granddaddy of
confessional daytime talkers, sowing the seeds for more extreme
confessionals such as ``Sally Jessy Raphael,'' ``Jenny Jones,''
``Jerry Springer'' and ``Ricki Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An American Family'' (1973) _ The forerunner of peeping Tom
documentaries, this landmark PBS program sent cameras to the home
of the Loud family in Santa Barbara, Calif., and spent seven months
chronicling Bill and Pat and their five chil
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
