<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-FANTASIA0616-C     06-15 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FANTASIA0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `''Fantasia''/2000' lacks the luster of classic original
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Walt Disney envisioned ``Fantasia'' as a concert
film with a perpetually changing repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our intention to make a new version of ``Fantasia''
every year,'' Disney said in 1941, a year after the film's original
release. ``Its pattern is very flexible and fun to work with _ not
really a concert, not a vaudeville or a revue, but a grand mixture
of comedy, fantasy, ballet, drama, impressionism, color, sound and
epic fury.''
</P>
<P>
   The original ``Fantasia'' is a masterpiece of animation, but
Disney's bold experiment in sight and sound was one of his rare
financial failures. The film reportedly didn't turn a profit until
its 1956 re-release, followed by successful reissues in 1969, 1977
and 1990. It has since become one of the studio's most popular
home-video titles.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years later, Walt Disney's dream has finally come to
fruition.
</P>
<P>
   Having premiered on Jan. 1 exclusively in Imax theaters, where
it set box-office records, ``Fantasia''/2000 opens today in
standard 35mm format for a limited four-week engagement. The film
features seven new visual interpretations of classical music
selections, along with the return of Mickey Mouse in ``The
Sorcerer's Apprentice.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter piece was the genesis for the original ``Fantasia''
and it remains an animation milestone. In comparison, the rest of
the updated program comes up short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasia''/2000's marriage of classical music and animated
images offers nothing as grand as its forebear. The pieces on the
whole are entertaining and beautifully rendered, but none are as
charming as the original's ``Dance of the Hours,'' with its dancing
hippos and alligators, nor as stunning as the dark, terrifying ``A
Night on Bald Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Running 46 minutes less than the two-hour original, the
lightweight collection appears more geared to children's short
attention spans than to elevating animation to high art.
</P>
<P>
   Musical selections by such composers as Ludwig Van Beethoven,
Igor Stravinsky, Dmitri Shostakovich and George Gershwin are
performed by the Chicago Symphony Orchestra, conducted by James
Levine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasia 2000'' opens with Beethoven's ``Symphony No. 5,''
accompanied by colorful, butterfly-like triangles that move in time
with the familiar notes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Martin welcomes viewers in the first of six host segments
that also feature Quincy Jones, Bette Midler, James Earl Jones,
Penn &AMP; Teller and Angela Lansbury.
</P>
<P>
   Next is the most visually impressive piece of the new works,
featuring a pod of computer-animated whales that miraculously take
flight to Ottorino Respighi's ``Pines of Rome.'' The lovely
10-minute segment brings to mind the marine-life paintings of
Wyland.
</P>
<P>
   Caricaturist Al Hirshfeld's line drawings inspire a stylized
view of 1930s New York City, set to Gershwin's ``Rhapsody in
Blue.'' The free-flowing lines and monochrome backgrounds have a
bouncy look, but the segment's humor falls flat.
</P>
<P>
   Shostakovich's ``Piano Concerto No. 2 ``provides the backdrop
for Hans Christian Anderson's classic fairy tale, ``The Steadfast
Tin Soldier.'' Though visually dynamic, the computer-animated
segment's sharply angled characters pale next to those in the ``Toy
Story ``movies.
</P>
<P>
   A goofy-looking flamingo twirling a yo-yo to Camille
Saint-Saens' ``Carnival of the Animals'' provides much-needed comic
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Following the digitally restored Mickey Mouse classic, which has
a much richer look than the new material, Donald Duck gets his due
_ loading animals two-by-two onto Noah's Ark in a fun and clever
rendition of Edward Elgar's march, ``Pomp and Circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasia 2000 ``concludes with a beautiful but self-important
piece about death and rebirth set to Stravinsky's powerful
``Firebird Suite.'' The title creature, which bursts with flaming
wings from a volcano, recalls the Chernobog from ``A Night on Bald
Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Disney's dream is realized, it misses his guiding hand.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
