<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-ROTHKO-CHAPEL-2TAKES-     06-15 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROTHKO-CHAPEL-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ROTHKO CHAPEL REOPENING AFTER RENOVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PATRICIA C. JOHNSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The buff brick structure sits quietly on a grassy
corner, unassuming and tranquil. You might drive right past unless
you've been there before.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, though, it becomes an oasis.
</P>
<P>
   The Rothko Chapel offers an escape from the heat and hustle of
Houston, from the cacophony of cars and visual stimuli that
threaten to overwhelm.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by lawns and old live oaks, fronted by a pool of
water with Barnett Newman's Broken Obelisk as sentinel, the compact
enclosure gives respite to the tired of mind and soul.
</P>
<P>
   The chapel was commissioned by visionary art patrons John and
Dominique de Menil and named for American artist Mark Rothko, whose
14 giant canvases define its meditative interior. It has been one
of Houston's most famous international destinations since its
dedication in February 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The octagonal chapel is a unique site where modern art,
architecture, spirituality and a gentle, potent humanist activism
coexist. It is open to weddings and memorial services, to symposia,
international colloquia and private contemplation. It is the source
of the prestigious Rothko Chapel Awards for the Commitment to Truth
and Freedom, initiated in 1981, and the Oscar Romero Award, begun
in 1986, which recognize individuals, unknown or famous, who battle
for human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months ago, the chapel closed its doors when problems
that have dogged it since the opening were exacerbated by a new
one.
</P>
<P>
   Lighting had been an issue from the beginning. Rothko wanted a
skylight but underestimated the intensity of the Texas sun, which
blasted the interior. The baffle added to soften and diffuse the
light was never satisfactory. The air-conditioning system was
antiquated.
</P>
<P>
   When cracks appeared on the north wall and widened almost enough
to see outside, it became obvious that serious foundation problems
existed, too. Meanwhile, the fragile paintings, which had last been
conserved in the mid-1980s, were removed to the nearby Menil
Collection conservation lab for a thorough checkup.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the chapel will reopen after a $1.8 million
</P>
<P>
   restoration overseen by McReynolds Architects of Houston that
has
</P>
<P>
   renewed it from top to bottom, inside and out.
</P>
<P>
   A new skylight with ultraviolet glass has been installed. The
baffle, which hung just beneath it, has been replaced to fit inside
the skylight's edges. The result is a rim of light that is diffused
gently down the walls and through the space.
</P>
<P>
   The doors were enlarged so the paintings, the largest of which
measures just under 25 feet high, may be moved in and out without
having to open the skylight, as was necessary in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The foyer was modified to create a climate-control chamber,
allowing a new energy management system to neutralize hot, humid
air from outside before it enters the chapel proper. To accommodate
the system, the entry ceiling was dropped six feet _ from 18 feet
to 12 _ after much debate.
</P>
<P>
   The fear was that the lower ceiling might seem oppressive. It
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   A new foundation was laid. Over the years, the chapel had sunk
nearly two inches. The oak trees along Sul Ross have absorbed
increasing amounts of moisture as they have matured, so the ground
there dries faster than on the opposite side of the chapel. The
solution was to sink the foundation piers deeper, from 20 feet to
55 feet (twice the height of the building).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Menil Collection conservator Carol Mancusi-Ungaro and
Mellon Fellow Pia Gottschaller studied the huge, delicate paintings
inch by inch. Pronounced unfaded and healthy, they were the last,
central component of the chapel's renewal, installed on resurfaced
and repainted walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will just open quietly,'' said Suna Umari, a native of
Lebanon and the chapel's executive director since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The de Menils originally conceived Rothko Chapel in 1964 as a
Catholic chapel to be affiliated with the nearby University of St.
Thomas, where the couple were significant patrons. However, the
university _ already wary of the high profile that art had on
campus _ determined that ``responsibility for the works of art and
making them available to the public would be too great a burden.''
So wrote historian Susan Barnes in The Rothko Chapel, An Act of
Faith.
</P>
<P>
   Because it was never intended to be an independent entity, in
1969 the de Menils proposed to donate the chapel to the ecumenical
Institute of Religion and Human Development instead. The institute,
which is located in Houston's Texas Medical Center and devoted
toclinical aspects of pastoral training, accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that association was severed, as well, in October 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty months after its public dedication, the chapel was reborn
as an autonomous body. The charter mandates that the chapel offer a
place of worship, meditation and prayer, where people may gather
and explore spiritual bonds, discuss human problems, share a
spiritual experience.
</P>
<P>
   With financial support from the Menil Foundation and others, the
Rothko Chapel became the world's ``first broadly ecumenical center,
a holy place open to all religions and belonging to none,'' Barnes
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   There are 16 members on its varied board of directors, currently
chaired by Ben F. Love, former chairman of Texas Commerce Bank (now
Chase Texas). The annual budget is approximately $500,000. That
figure comprises operating expenses and about $130,000 to cover
commitments made by Dominique de Menil, who died in late 1997.
These include lifetime support for Father Andre Scrima, a Catholic
priest in his late 60s who lives in Romania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominique collected remarkable people, you know,'' Umari said,
``people like Father Scrima, who have wonderful talents and gifts
but have no means of support.''
</P>
<P>
   The chapel's $11 million endowment also funds the $20,000 Oscar
Romero Award, given periodically. But the $10,000 Rothko Chapel
Award was personally funded by Dominique de Menil and will be
discontinued, Umari said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raising money to cover the renovation is the first priority of
the chapel. Initial efforts have raised $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   The chapel's integration of art and architecture is
unparalleled.
</P>
<P>
   The Sistine Chapel, inconceivable without Michelangelo's
majestic
</P>
<P>
   frescoes, was designed and built 20 years before Pope Julius II
</P>
<P>
   commissioned its famed ceiling paintings. So, too, the Chapel of
the Rosary in Vence, France, existed before Henri Matisse was
commissioned to design its interior _ everything from the altar,
the crucifix and the vestments to the stained-glass windows and
drawings on the tile walls.
</P>
<P>
   Rothko not only created the work that hangs inside the Rothko
Chapel, he designed the space, too.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOUSTON: x x x the space, too. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Menils hired Phillip Johnson for the project in 1964. The
choice of this patrician architect seemed a natural since he had
designed the Menil home in River Oaks and the University of St.
Thomas campus However, Johnson's drawings were amended _ or
rejected outright _ by Rothko until, as Dominique de Menil
gracefully phrased it, ``the great architect bowed out to the great
artist.'' Houston architects Howard Barnstone and Eugene Aubry
completed the design as the painter demanded, and the patrons
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   (The lengthy, often acrimonious debate between Rothko and
Johnson is amply described in Barnes' history and also in Sheldon
Nodelman's The Rothko Chapel Paintings: Origins, Structure,
Meaning.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rothko worked on the 14 paintings, including three
triptychs for the east, north and west walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude, on every level of experience and meaning, of
the task in which you have involved me, exceeds all my
preconceptions,'' Rothko wrote to the de Menils two years into the
project. ``It is teaching me to extend myself beyond what I thought
was possible for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Born in Latvia in 1903, Rothko was a leading member of the
American Abstract Expressionists and renowned for his paintings of
luminous rectangles of color that seemed to float on the surface.
The chapel's paintings are the culmination of a successful career
fraught, as well, with self-doubt and depression. Rothko killed
himself in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The monumental, seemingly monochromatic paintings are
unprecedented in his oeuvre. In a Manhattan studio that held a
full-scale mock-up of the chapel, including the skylight, Rothko
began to work on the paintings in summer 1964, shortly after
receiving the commission. He finished by mid-April 1967. The
project completely absorbed him. He calibrated every detail of tone
and surface, experimented with media, and obsessed about the
paintings' precise placement in the architecture he had designed
for them. These ``paintings of silence,'' as Dominique de Menil
called them, create the chapel's interior space.
</P>
<P>
   John de Menil once described them as being the color of wine and
blood.
</P>
<P>
   But color is subjective and fugitive; color memory even more so.
</P>
<P>
   Mancusi-Ungaro tells of one visitor who recalls the paintings as
being vivid red.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, seven of the paintings are black rectangles painted on
dark maroon grounds, the so-called ``black-form paintings.'' The
other seven are a deep plum. The artist blended egg, dry pigment,
oil paint and dammar resins, among other materials, then applied
the mix to the canvas in skinlike veils over rectangular forms
sketched in charcoal.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking with earlier work, Rothko eliminated his characteristic
brushy surfaces and any suggestion of form. He created instead
sheer expanses of color and remarkably luminous, if flat, surfaces,
suggesting immeasurable depths.
</P>
<P>
   Devoid of recognizable shapes, the paintings can confound
viewers who are accustomed to entering more traditional chapels
adorned with images.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some _ with huge Rothkos on all sides _ have asked where
the paintings are.
</P>
<P>
   But Rothko's chapel and paintings demand to be sensed almost
through the skin, not looked at like objects. Perhaps spiritual
things and places are meant to be discovered _ revealed _ and need
not trumpet their arrival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
