<HEADLINE>
`BOYS AND GIRLS': CUTE BUT UM, LIKE, A REAL CONTROL FREAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're still disconsolate over the demise of ``Beverly Hills
90210,'' then ``Boys and Girls'' may be the movie for you. I don't
mean the early, cheesy Shannen Doherty ``90210,'' mind you, or the
sleazy. soap-operatic Dylan-in-distress middle years. What this
feeble, harmless romantic comedy calls to mind is an extra-long
episode from one of the show's interminable final seasons, in which
the cast seemed to change every week and nobody could remember if
Donna was still a virgin or not, because nobody _ not the audience,
not the writers, not even the long-suffering David _ cared.
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Prinze Jr., who specializes in anodyne romantic comedies
with defiantly forgettable titles, is a nice-looking young actor
with a winning, gentlemanly manner _ kind of like Ricky Nelson
without the smoldering eroticism. His natural demeanor is so
pleasant and untroubled that the screenwriters, a duo called the
Drews, and the director, Robert Iscove _ also responsible for
``She's All That,'' Prinze's first star vehicle _ have had to labor
mightily to drum up enough emotional complication to eke out a
90-minute movie. Well, not all that mightily. Prinze does appear
briefly in braces, in a team-mascot gopher head and in an
unflattering modified Dutch-boy haircut, but the idea that his
character could be at all troubled, lonely or neurotic is a conceit
the movie can't possibly sustain.
</P>
<P>
   Prinze plays Ryan, a Berkeley engineering major (hey, stop
snickering) whose best (and apparently only) friends are his comic
room-mate sidekick (Jason Biggs) and the girl he really loves even
though he can't admit it. Her name is Jennifer, she's played by
Claire Forlani, and the big joke is that while Ryan's an uptight
control freak who insists on planning everything, Jennifer is a
wild, spontaneous, free spirit who lives in and for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The moment seems to drag on forever. The best thing that can be
said about ``Boys and Girls'' is that it is studiously inoffensive.
But this means that every time a potentially interesting
complication arises _ an inkling of sexual confusion, a situation
that might lead to hurt feelings, a funny joke _ the movie bolts
like a panicky colt, or like Ryan, who keeps remembering that he
has studying to do.
</P>
<P>
   I saw ``Boys and Girls'' at a sneak preview packed with eager
members of its target audience. After about 30 minutes, many of
them seemed to wish they'd stayed home to study. ``I never thought
I could feel ripped off by a movie I saw for free,'' one young man
remarked on his way out. He was the voice of his generation, or at
least of the mob of his peers who had, during Ryan's big emotional
speech about love, trust and fidelity, howled with derisive
laughter at Prinze's furrowing brow and downturned mouth. They may
have been disappointed, but I, at least, was able to leave the
theater with new-found respect for America's often maligned and
misunderstood youth.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BOYS AND GIRLS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Robert Iscove; written by the Drews; director of
photography, Ralf Bode; edited by Casey O Rohrs; music by Stewart
Copeland; production designer, Marcia Hinds-Johnson; produced by
Jay Cohen, Lee Gottsegen and Murray Schisgal; released by Dimension
Films.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Freddie Prinze, Jr. (Ryan), Claire Forlani (Jennifer),
Jason Biggs (Hunter), Amanda Detmer (Amy), Alyson Hannigan (Betty),
Monica Arnold (Katie), Heather Donahue (Megan), Lisa Eichhorn
(Shuttle Passenger), Raquel Beaudene (Young Jennifer) and Brendon
Ryan Barret (Young Ryan).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys and Girls'' is rated PG-13 (parents strongly cautioned).
It has some mild profanity, a mild sex scene, and some mildly
off-color jokes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0112 </DOCNO>
