<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TIPPI-HITCHCOCK0616-C     06-15 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIPPI-HITCHCOCK0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From `Birds' to beasts
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tippi Hedren lives among 60 big cats and two
African elephants, but that makes a sort of sense: Being a movie
star is fine preparation for a life with wild animals. Or vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   It was all a long time ago, nearly 40 years, but Hedren is still
happy to talk about her tumultuous professional and personal
relationship with Alfred Hitchcock, the subject of the eighth
annual American Movie Classics Film Preservation Weekend on the
cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Hedren starred in two films for Hitchcock: ``The Birds,'' which
was very popular at the time, and ``Marnie,'' which wasn't, but
which has gained stature over the years. After she split with
Hitchcock, she made ``A Countess from Hong Kong,'' Charlie
Chaplin's last movie, and ``The Harrad Experiment'' with her
daughter, Melanie Griffith. And then . . . silence.
</P>
<P>
   She owes her portion of fame, as well as the silence that
followed, to Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed a personal contract with Hitch for seven years,'' she
says via phone from Shambala, her animal preserve in California.
``The only other actress he ever had under personal contract was
Vera Miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock had seen Hedren in a TV commercial and was struck by
her patrician blond beauty, something for which he always had a
weakness _ Grace Kelly, Eva Marie Saint, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was rather amusing that I was being likened to
Grace Kelly. I had enough assurance that I wasn't insulted by being
associated with someone else. I'm my own woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedren's memories of Hitchcock are of a ferociously articulate
man, painstaking in his explanations of what a particular scene
needed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was wonderful with me; he was not only my director, he was
my drama coach. It was fabulous to have that kind of in-depth
direction, but I'm sure I needed it; ``The Birds ``was my first
movie. I had done a tremendous number of commercials, but that is
not the same as becoming a character. I was technically educated
about cameras but not about acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very psychological director. It could be maddening at
some points. I didn't even realize what was happening; he'd know
which buttons to push to get a response out of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other times, I pulled things out of my own experience. When my
horse died in ``Marnie,'' I went right back to when my dog Corky
died when I was a child. Corky was a little terrier who died of
distemper because my parents didn't have enough money to take the
animals for shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedren still marvels at the amount of preparation Hitchcock did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had me sit in on meetings with everyone from the cameraman
to (costume designer) Edith Head, to editing and set decorating. It
was really incredible. We would talk about the script and the
character so much that by the time we got to the filming, it was
very clear what was needed. He rarely did more than three takes on
most of the scenes. Sometimes, he would go with the first take.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of its complicated special effects, ``The Birds'' was an
extremely arduous production experience, and after Grace Kelly
flirted with the idea of making a comeback on ``Marnie,'' Hitchcock
again turned to Hedren.
</P>
<P>
   It was on that picture that Hedren rebelled against what she
regarded as Hitchcock's increasing mania about her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possessiveness that the man was perpetrating upon me was
suffocating. He was so controlling _ suffocating really is the best
word. He didn't want me as a mistress, it wasn't that; he just
didn't want me to be with anyone else. Dating was a big problem.
Remember, I already had a child, I was my own woman, and if you're
going to be Svengali, you'd better choose somebody that doesn't
have any life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get out of it. I did it myself. `I can't go on like
this,' I told him, `I have to get out.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `I'll ruin your career,' and he did.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next four years, Hedren got her $600 a week and
basically didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What hurt the most was that (French director Francois)
Truffaut wanted me for a picture, and Hitch said I wasn't
available. It was so hurtful I could hardly stand to hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he gave my contract to Universal, and they wanted me to
do some TV show, and I said I didn't want to do that. And they
said, `We'll drop your contract.' And I put out my hand and said,
`Will you shake on that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hedren runs Shambala, a game preserve that grew out of
``Roar,'' a barely released film she made with her then-husband and
her daughter in the late '70s that took years to complete but
spawned a passionate love of wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity helps some in fund-raising, but in other ways it
hurts _ people think we're rich, which isn't the case. Some people
say, `Let her daughter support her.' That goes over real well. But
the celebrity makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Shambala is spread across 75 acres in Southern California and
has a monthly overhead of $75,000, but as far as Hedren is
concerned, it has been far more rewarding than the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the financial burdens weren't so horrendous, I'd be the
luckiest woman in the world. We have private parties on the
weekend. We have a fantastically wonderful safari tent that's
decorated to the nines, gourmet dinners served on a wonderful
inch-and-a-half-thick glass dining table with crystal and china.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's paradise out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
