w e BC-IVOR-JIM-CARREY-IN-ME     06-15 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JIM-CARREY-IN-ME-MYSELF-AND-IRENE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TWO FACES OF JIM CARREY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Jim Carrey in
scenes from ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Maybe if he made less money. Maybe if his face wasn't
perpetually contorted into some impossible grimace. Maybe if he
displayed fewer teeth.
 &HT;    Maybe then Jim Carrey would get the kind of respect Hollywood
normally accords any actor whose box-office receipts are a billion
and rising.
 &HT;    Outdrawing Hollywood's top male stars hasn't worked. Neither has
playing it straight, more or less, in bravura performances for
world-class directors in Peter Weir's ``The Truman Show'' (l998)
and Milos Forman's ``Man On The Moon'' (l999).
 &HT;    Oh, sure, those performances brought him a pair of Golden Globes
from the Hollywood Foreign Press, but nobody really counts those.
What matters is the Academy Award, and in the Oscar stakes Carrey
is left at the starting gate time after time.
 &HT;    Like his idol Jerry Lewis, who was never taken seriously by
anyone except the unfathomable French, Carrey has ruled the box
office but still struggled to be seen as anything more than a guy
making faces.
 &HT;    ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' which will open June 23, may be more of
the same. In it Carrey tackles the kind of all-stops-out, ``look,
Ma, no hands'' steamroller of a part that actors' dreams are made
of, playing split personalities trapped within a single body.
 &HT;    The catch: The movie is the latest opus from Peter and Bobby
Farrelly, who were responsible _ and we use the word loosely _ for
``Dumb and Dumber'' (1994) and ``There's Something About Mary''
(l998), which together earned more than $500 million worldwide.
 &HT;    Carrey's performance as Charlie, a mild-mannered police officer
whose subconscious bubbles to the surface in the form of Hank, his
violent, abrasive alter ego _ think Dirty Harry on steroids _ is a
remarkable one, even if it happens in the kind of lowbrow,
anything-for-a-laugh comedy that made Carrey Hollywood's
least-respected superstar.
 &HT;    ``This is our take on `The Three Faces of Eve,''' Peter Farrelly
says, ``except we call it `The Two Faces of Barney Fife,''' after
the beleaguered deputy played by Don Knotts on television's ``The
Andy Griffith Show.''
 &HT;    ``It's an extremely demanding role,'' Farrelly adds, ``because
Jim had no props or make-up to clearly delineate between the two
characters. It's not an easy thing to do. He uses voice changes,
but mostly body language and mannerisms.''
 &HT;    The film is also a love triangle, as Charlie and Hank vie for
the affections of Irene, a woman on the lam who likes them both.
The role is played by Renee Zellweger, who is currently Carrey's
offscreen love interest as well.
 &HT;    Zellweger, who earned her stripes opposite Tom Cruise in ``Jerry
Maguire'' (1996), thinks Carrey ranks with Hollywood's best actors.
 &HT;    ``Jim is a genius,'' she says. ``I've never seen anybody do what
he can do. We'd perform a scene, and in the next instant he'd be
somebody completely different, completely unrecognizable. It was
kind of scary, because his eyes were even different.
 &HT;    ``It was magical to see what he could do.''
 &HT;    In promoting ``Man on the Moon,'' in which he played the bizarre
comic Andy Kaufman, Carrey indulged in some wild, Kaufmanesque
antics. This time around, he's relaxed, even mellow in a T-shirt,
sports jacket and short-cropped hair. Even the mention of his
second consecutive failure to be nominated for an Oscar, despite
most critics' considering him a shoo-in, doesn't get him riled.
 &HT;    ``They're bastards,'' he says of the Academy, ``but you know
I've got to be careful about what I say.
 &HT;    ``Please say I was being facetious,'' he adds quickly, ``because
sometimes these jokes don't translate directly.
 &HT;    ``I understand the Academy, and their experience of me over five
movies was as a crazy persona,'' he says more seriously. ``Over two
films, they're not going to bend that far. I'll accept (the Oscar)
from my seat by the time I get it. I'll have to get somebody to go
up there as I slobber over myself.
 &HT;    ``But I swear to God I don't sweat those things,'' he concludes.
``It would be ungrateful. I have a great life. After all, I'm able
to work with Peter Weir and Milos Forman.''
 &HT;    And with Zellweger, of course. Carrey _ who is divorced from
actress Lauren Holly, whom he met while shooting ``Dumb and
Dumber'' _ says that there are no marriage plans. He also denies
rumors that Zellweger, who is currently shooting ``Bridget Jones's
Diary'' in England, is pregnant.
 &HT;    He will, however, admit that they're more than just good
friends.
 &HT;    ``I will say we had the most wonderful old-fashioned,
tremendously
something-you-dream-about-happening-that-never-happens-anymore
courtship,'' Carrey says. ``We're having a great time. She's a gem
of a human being, and one of the best actresses I've ever seen in
my life. That's why I wanted her in my movie _ not to go after her
but to learn from her.
 &HT;    ``She's a great person, and is what she seems to be,'' the
comedian says. ``She makes me laugh. She's a bashful person, but
very funny.''
 &HT;    Next up for the funnyman is a straight role in ``The Phone
Booth'' for director Joel Schumacher. The story, described as a
Hitchcockian thriller, is about a man who answers a pay phone on a
crowded New York street and is told he will die if he hangs up.
 &HT;    Plans for him to star in a remake of the Danny Kaye film ``The
Secret Life of Walter Mitty'' (1947) are on hold, though Carrey
would seem to be an absolute natural for that one.
 &HT;    ``It's a cool story,'' he admits, ``but I need to see a script
before going ahead.''
 &HT;    After multiple ups and downs, personally and professionally,
Carrey says he is now comfortable with his life.
 &HT;    ``It's never been about money,'' he says. ``It was where you are
when you get that money.
 &HT;    ``The big change in my life is that everybody knows me now,''
Carrey continues. ``It makes you self-conscious. Yet my life is
getting simpler and simpler, thanks to a lot of people who remind
me that, if you lose the menial things in life, you lose your pride
and your joy.
 &HT;    ``When I first got famous,'' he recalls, ``I bought into the
philosophy that you should hire people because you can. I wanted to
be Bruce Wayne.
 &HT;    ``Now I enjoy washing my own cape.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
