<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5007 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-15 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOLKS LOVE HER OR LOATHE HER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Why isn't Hillary Clinton mopping up the floor with
her rookie Republican opponent, a young congressman so obscure that
64 percent of New Yorkers in a recent survey didn't know anything
about him?
</P>
<P>
   She's virtually tied with Rep. Rick Lazio, who hastily entered
the New York Senate race only in May as a fall-back candidate after
the Republicans' first choice, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to that familiar axiom, you can't beat
somebody with nobody? Clearly, Clinton is a Somebody. And so far,
Lazio is a Nobody.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times/CBS Poll conducted June 4-10 showed the first
lady with the support of 44 percent of likely voters compared with
39 percent for Lazio, a statistically insignificant difference.
This is essentially the same standoff that polls matching Clinton
with Giuliani had registered for months.
</P>
<P>
   Although 45 percent of those surveyed said they had a favorable
impression of the first lady, she has been unable to attract a
simple majority in any poll the past year despite diligent
statewide campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   And that leads to a second, contradictory axiom.
</P>
<P>
   People seldom vote FOR a candidate on individual merit. They
vote AGAINST a candidate they don't like, making that person's
opponent an incidental beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to measure the true extent of the hostility
toward the first lady that has slopped over from disgust over her
husband's misdeeds. But it is clearly a factor. The recent poll
shows 31 percent of those surveyed had an unfavorable opinion of
her. She is unlikely to sway those folks. Her negatives, like those
of her husband, are frozen in partisan cement.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, hardly open-minded observers, make much of her
inability to break through to 50 percent support. At the same time,
however, the 40ish support she does have seems consistently solid,
which as a base is not bad this early in a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the snarling attitude that always assumes the worst
of her is the view of conservative commentator George Will, who
scoffed on ABC-TV last weekend at the self-deprecating witticisms
she made a recent New York Legislative Correspondents Association
dinner in Albany. She isn't known for a sense of humor; so her
performance was a breakthrough of sorts. With her carpetbag and her
photographic poses in a Yankees cap, she was a surprising hit.
Lazio showed up at the dinner but refused to make a speech.
</P>
<P>
   The cynical journalistic crowd loved her jokes, but not Will,
whose heart permanently belongs to Ronald Reagan. Will grumped
irrelevantly that she now had more experience as a stand-up comic
than she had in public office, mocking the inconvenient fact that
as first lady she was involved in serious public policy debates and
carried out many official duties. ``So maybe she ought to
reconsider what she's running for,'' he said. Then he sourly added
that if the Mets had beaten the Yankees recently, she would have
changed hats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has no hope of winning over the Wills of the world. So
what she must do _ and is doing _ is go after the 24 percent who
are still undecided about her. This is no small task since it is a
mystery how anybody in this polarized era could have remained
neutral until now on the subject of the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, on the other hand, is still a blank page. He has spent
his House career being all things to all people, voting sometimes
with conservative Speaker Newt Gingrich, sometimes with Republican
moderates. Only 26 percent of those surveyed viewed him favorably,
but the whopping 64 percent who said they don't know anything about
him constitute both an opportunity and a potential problem.
</P>
<P>
   They can be cranked up or turned off. It is up to Lazio to
capture them and Clinton to lure them away.
</P>
<P>
   Both are bent to their task. Lazio is riding a bus around the
state, but it lacks the originality and personal touch that Sen.
John McCain brought to his Straight Talk Express. The first lady is
everywhere, marching in parades, giving interviews, dropping in on
ordinary folks.
</P>
<P>
   Barring some enormous verbal gaffe, none of this will hurt. How
much it actually helps this summer until voters begin to focus on
politics in the fall is open to debate.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran pollsters of both parties complain that nobody is even
paying attention to the presidential contests yet, let alone to
local sideshows like congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   But early positioning can ultimately influence public opinion.
Is this to be a referendum on her fame, or on his obscurity?
</P>
<P>
   The first lady is trying to paint Lazio as a right-wing radical,
which he does not seem to be. He is trying to return the favor,
portraying her as a left-wing radical, which she is not.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully by autumn they will both have that stuff out of their
systems and can get down to the real business of the campaign,
which is the clash of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
