<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5008 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-OPEN-MONTGOMERIE-     06-15 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-MONTGOMERIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MORE SEASONED MONTGOMERIE RETURNS WITH REALISTIC APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHELLE SMITH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Colin Montgomerie always seems to come
into the U.S. Open as one of the favorites. He has yet to walk away
with a win.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 Open at Pebble Beach, his first U.S. Open, may have
been as close as he's come. Montgomerie went into the clubhouse as
the leader with a final-round 70 to finish at even-par in ungodly
conditions and then accepted congratulations from Jack Nicklaus on
his first Open win, which is golf's equivalent of a papal blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit, I thought at that stage when I finished that
round _ I holed a very good putt at the last, about a 5-footer left
to right _ that I holed that putt to win,'' Montgomerie said
Wednesday. ``I felt that putt was to win the tournament. And as it
turned out, it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Tom Kite _ who was 3-over after just three holes _
rallied to pick up six strokes and the victory. Jeff Sluman
finished second at 1-under.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, 36, is a star, and a very rich man, thanks to the
European Tour, where he has won twice in nine tries this year. But
he joins a list of the game's biggest names (including David Duval,
Phil Mickelson and Jesper Parnevik) who have never won a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be honest. It's not a normal golf tournament, so
everyone feels that way and I'm no different,'' Montgomerie said.
``I've had a reasonable career and haven't won a major, so, yes,
there's slightly more pressure on the situation. But it won't
affect me in any way, shape or form in my lifestyle or life if I do
happen to win a major. I would like to do it, but if I don't, well,
I've had a good run, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie has a hostile history with Northern California
galleries. At the 1998 Open at the Olympic Club, Montgomerie was
flustered and angry by the remarks from the crowd. It was getting
so bad at one point that Montgomerie turned to confront his verbal
attackers and fellow players denounced the behavior of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   While not addressing the issue of the galleries specifically,
Montgomerie thinks he's become tougher as the years wear on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through enough to learn, hopefully, and to be able
to cope with any situation that's thrown against me here and for
the ages to come,'' he said. ``I feel that my character is a lot
tougher than it was before and I'm as determined as ever. I just
hope that lady luck throws in a shot or two to my side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
