<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TITAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-15 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TITAN A.E': MAY A SLIGHTLY DIFFERENT FORCE BE WITH YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A brash young space traveler with festering father-son issues,
his tart-tongued female colleague and a crew of oddly shaped
intergalactic creatures: If the basic ingredients of Don Bluth and
Gary Goldman's ambitious animated film ``Titan A.E.'' sound awfully
familiar, it's because in some ways this handsomely designed
intergalactic adventure could be described as Son of ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   But in many other respects the movie is not a George Lucas
imitation. Its guiding concept imagines the human race literally
lost in the stars and scattered about the universe in ``drifter
colonies'' after an alien invasion in the 31st century has
destroyed the planet. Even then the survivors and their descendants
are pursued by the aliens who drove them from their homes. Huddled
in their enclaves, these refugees hoard useless earthly bric-a-brac
that reminds them of their home. (``A.E.'' stands for ``After
Earth.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Titan A.E.'' goes only so far in implying a multi-species
equality. Without designating a hierarchy it suggests that humans
are still superior to almost everyone else. That's why their
enemies, the Drej, are determined to chase them to the ends of the
universe if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Then why, given the movie's poignant notion of humans as
intergalactic exiles, does so much of ``Titan A.E.'' feel
emotionally flat and mechanically tossed off? Despite some gorgeous
sequences, including one set in a lake of glowing hydrogen
``trees,'' ``Titan A.E.'' is bland. Although crammed with action,
little of it produces roller-coaster thrills of adventure and
self-discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem may have to do with our ever loftier
technological expectations of science fiction movies in the
post-``Star Wars'' era, and ``Titan A.E.'s'' animation techniques
are certainly innovative. The two-dimensional figures interact
seamlessly with three-dimensional computer-generated surroundings
that are richly colored and loaded with intriguing gadgetry. But
when thrust into complex environments that cry out for real human
figures, the animated characters tend to seem smaller than life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titan A.E.'' has problems in pacing, storytelling and
character definition. In striving to be all things to all
generations, the screenplay, adapted from a story by Hans Bauer and
Randall McCormick, vacillates uneasily between the fluff of
Saturday morning cartoons and fairly sophisticated wisecracking.
Although the action sequences are lively, they zip by too fast to
build up much cliffhanging excitement.
</P>
<P>
   When we first meet the movie's hero, Cale (Matt Damon), he is a
towheaded little boy whose father, a military scientist, is racing
against time to complete a secret operation, the Titan Project,
that could save humanity from extinction. Earth is about to be
destroyed by the Drej, a race of soulless aliens described as
``pure energy,'' who swarm in shape-shifting formations of
laser-blue lights and speak in mechanized, metallic mumbo jumbo.
</P>
<P>
   As the end of the world looms, Cale's father bids a hasty
farewell to his son before shipping him off to safety. Although the
boy is desperate to remain, his father is firm about his having to
leave and promises that one day they will be reunited. In a parting
gesture he gives his son a magic ring that he says will protect him
from harm.
</P>
<P>
   The story leaps ahead more than a decade. Cale is now a
rebellious teen-age dock worker at a space station that resembles a
grungy junkyard of rusting outmoded machinery. Seething because he
believes his father abandoned him, he has little regard for
humanity. But his feelings suddenly change when he discovers that
the ring his father left him contains a genetically encoded map to
guide him to the Titan, a spaceship designed to save humanity and
concealed somewhere in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   With Korso (Bill Pullman), the space captain of the spaceship
Valkyrie and an old acquaintance of his father's, Cale embarks on
this ultimate treasure hunt. In close pursuit are the Drej, who
know of the Titan's existence and are waiting for Cale to lead them
to it. As the code is deciphered step by step, the predictable
space battles erupt, and two of Cale's fellow treasure hunters
reveal a treacherous side.
</P>
<P>
   One signal that Korso is not entirely a good guy is his red
goatee. Action heroes just don't wear goatees, especially red ones.
Pullman's John Wayne-like vocal swagger is just a little too
exaggerated for comfort. Korso's wily first mate, Preed (Nathan
Lane), is even more suspicious. Haughty and slightly effeminate
with a Vincent Price voice, he conforms to Hollywood's
stereotypical image of the effete villain.
</P>
<P>
   Also on board the Valkyrie is Akima (Drew Barrymore), a curt,
resourceful Eurasian-looking pilot, and a crew that includes the
vessel's eccentric, turtle-like navigator, Gune (John Leguizamo),
and its sour, grumbling weapons specialist, Stith (Janeane
Garofalo).
</P>
<P>
   ``Titan A.E.'' tries to pack so much into 90 minutes that the
characters don't have enough screen time to engage our emotions.
Cale and Akima in particular have all the depth of television
spinoffs of Luke Skywalker and Princess Leia. This is not to say
that ``Titan A.E.'' isn't entertaining in its breezy, mild-mannered
way, only that its mythology and characters barely resonate.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TITAN A.E.'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Don Bluth and Gary Goldman; written by Ben Edlund,
John August and Joss Whedon, based on a story by Hans Bauer and
Randall McCormick; director of animation, Len Simon; music by
Graeme Revell; production designer, Philip A. Cruden; produced by
David Kirschner, Bluth and Goldman; released by 20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Matt Damon (Cale), Bill Pullman (Korso),
John Leguizamo (Gune), Nathan Lane (Preed), Janeane Garofalo
(Stith), Drew Barrymore (Akima), Ron Perlman (Prof. Sam Tucker),
Alex D. Linz (Young Cale), Tone-Loc (Tek) and Jim Breuer (the
Cook).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titan A.E.'' is rated PG (Parental guidance suggested). It
includes action sequences that could frighten very young children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1731EDT &QL; 
