<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-US-0616-COX     06-15 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-US-0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. STILL WITHOUT 'TIMELINE' FOR KOSOVO PEACEKEEPING EFFORT,
OFFICIAL SAYS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By LISA MICHALS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A year after U.S.-led NATO troops liberated Kosovo
from Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic's oppressive government, the
United States is apparently no closer to forming an ``exit
strategy'' for its peacekeeping efforts in the war-torn province, a
top U.S. foreign policy official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not set a timeline to it,'' said Jim O'Brien, special
advisor to the President and Secretary of State for Kosovo and
Dayton Implementation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a solution that is driven by dates,'' he said,
responding to concerns that the United States has become bogged
down in yet another unending peacekeeping effort. ``It is something
that is driven by our interests, and our desire to stay there until
results are achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Those desired results, however, may be too difficult to achieve,
according to O'Brien's fellow panelists at news conference
Thursday. formidable
</P>
<P>
   They said the tasks of nation-building undertaken by the United
Nations _ creating democratic institutions, a self-sufficient
economy and a peaceful multi-ethnic society _ could be a formidable
challenge for the international community.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, U.N. officials and peacekeeping forces find themselves
maintaining security in a region that has never known multi-ethnic
cooperation, and perhaps never will. Just as in Cyprus and Korea,
blue-hatted peacekeepers and a de-militarized zone (DMZ) could
become perpetual fixtures in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States and our European allies will need to be
present in Kosovo for a very, very long time,'' said Ivo Daalder,
senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, a Washington think
tank.
</P>
<P>
   According to O'Brien, ongoing U.S. participation in Kosovo is
justified by America's duty to stand up for ``what is right,'' as
well as ``strategic interests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balkans are at the heart of the central question about the
future of Europe,'' he said ``As we recognized wisely after the
second world war, Europe coalesces around American leadership and
presence on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States last spring led a devastating 78-day NATO air
war against Yugoslavia, which beat back the Serb army and allowed
hundreds of thousands of Kosovar Albanians to return to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, steady progress has been made in rebuilding Kosovo.
An economy based on the Deutch mark is beginning to function, a
central bank and judicial system have recently been established and
efforts are being made to re-welcome minority groups such as the
Roma (gypsies) back into the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the panelists said deep-rooted ethnic conflicts cannot be
painted over with a fresh coat of new institutions and
international aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot enforce peace,'' said Dan Goure, senior fellow at
the Washington-based Center for Strategic and International
Studies. ``You can restrain violence, but you cannot prevent it.''
</P>
<P>
   Daalder agreed, adding, ``What we can and must insist upon is
that if you are a Serb or an Albanian, there should be no reason
for you not to be able to walk down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   (Lisa Michals' E-mail address is: lmichals(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
