<HEADER>
A5013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JESUS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-15 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JESUS' SON': TRAVELS WITH A STONED CANDIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: ``Jesus' Son'' was shown as part of this year's New
Directors/New Films Series. Here are excerpts from A.O. Scott's
review, which appeared in The New York Times on April 7.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Jesus' Son,'' Alison Maclean's scruffy, likable new film
adapted from a book of linked short stories by Denis Johnson,
follows the adventures of a young man known only by a nickname that
can't be printed in this newspaper. He acquires this sobriquet _
the initials are F.H. _ because of his almost miraculous propensity
to screw things up, to bring bad luck on himself and those around
him.
</P>
<P>
   But as incarnated first in Johnson's dreamy, neo-beatnik prose
and now in Billy Crudup's transcendent goofing, F.H. retains a
curious aura of innocence. He's like Candide strung out on every
drug he can find, or an itinerant holy man hitchhiking across the
Midwest in wet, filthy hipster hand-me-downs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the pleasures of ``Jesus' Son'' is watching a filmmaker
take risks and discover new resources of style. True to her source,
Maclean tells the young man's story in a looping, absent-minded
manner, skittering ahead and then scrambling backward to fill in
forgotten details.
</P>
<P>
   Her decision to string together a series of self-contained
vignettes could have resulted in meandering tedium, but she manages
to find a loose, improvisatory rhythm that matches Johnson's
discursive riffing, and that gives her scenes a keen edge of
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Her use of Johnson's own words in the voice-over narration works
less well. Some of his breathless beatnik invocations of the beauty
of the universe lose their innocence on the journey from page to
soundtrack and come across as more fussy than inspired.
</P>
<P>
   The film is fragmentary and episodic, but its first two
sections, set mostly in the brown wintriness of Iowa in 1971,
achieve a tattered narrative unity, thanks to the hero's on-again,
off-again obsession with a doomy, passionate young woman named
Michelle (Samantha Morton).
</P>
<P>
   As their relationship ambles along on its inevitable course from
stoner comedy to junkie tragedy, our hero encounters a succession
of memorably messed-up characters, including Wayne (Denis Leary),
who sucks spilled booze out of a cocktail napkin and smashes the
walls of his own house to find copper wire to sell for scrap, and
Georgie (Jack Black), a hospital orderly who is either a gifted
healer or a dangerous psychopath.
</P>
<P>
   Georgie figures in the film's most memorable sequence, a set
piece shot in the hallucinatory fluorescence of a late-night
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A man wanders in off the street with a hunting knife sticking
out of his eye. ``Patient complains of a knife in his eye,'' the
intake nurse dutifully reports, and later she asks the man, who was
stabbed by his wife, if he wants the hospital staff to call the
police. ``Only if I die,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of surrealist deadpan humor, visual and verbal,
pervades ``Jesus' Son.'' The movie may remind you, in style and
subject, of Gus Van Sant's ``Drugstore Cowboy,'' which similarly
imagined the early 1970s as the golden age of American junkiedom
and was suffused with a rough, dreamy masculine lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   Van Sant's film featured William S. Burroughs as its household
saint of pharmacological enlightenment. For her part Maclean trots
out Dennis Hopper, once the Lord Byron of the drug culture and now
its Ancient Mariner, for a cameo as a scary guy our young friend
meets in rehab.
</P>
<P>
   As it follows F.H. into recovery, the film loses momentum. The
last section is devoted to his new life, post-Michelle, in Arizona.
He has a job at a treatment center for disturbed and disabled
patients, a new love (Holly Hunter) and a voyeuristic devotion to a
Mennonite housewife.
</P>
<P>
   But these details, bereft of the desperate energy of need that
had propelled the movie, feel small and anecdotal. It's not that
``Jesus' Son'' romanticizes drug use; on the contrary, it rubs our
faces in the tawdry emptiness of an addict's days. But if drugs
wreck _ and sometimes take _ the lives of F.H. and his misfit
tribe, they also make them interesting, vivid and oddly beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   These words also apply to Crudup and Morton, whose chemistry (so
to speak) keeps the film from nodding off into feckless hustler
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Crudup plays a lost, irresponsible and stupid young man with
discipline and intelligence, using every muscle in his face to
suggest the unreachable emotion and the accidental goodness of his
character. His F.H. is authentically creepy and unexpectedly
charming. If you saw him on the street, you wouldn't know whether
to cross to the other side, give him a quarter or take him home
with you.
</P>
<P>
   Morton, nominated for an Oscar for her portrayal of the mute
laundress in Woody Allen's ``Sweet and Lowdown,'' is just as
fierce, sweet and angry here, and without much more to say. She
inspires her errant knight to fantasies of rescue and saves this
movie from its own self-destructive impulses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-HEROIN-NYT &LR;      06-15 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-HEROIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEROIN-RELATED DEATHS IN BRITAIN AND IRELAND LINKED TO BACTERIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Officials investigating the mysterious deaths of 35
heroin addicts in England, Scotland and Ireland in the last two
months said Thursday that the cause was a strain of clostridium, a
bacterium usually found in soil or dust.
</P>
<P>
   The clostridium strain, known as Clostridium novyi Type A, is
well known as a cause of severe infection in farm animals and can
lead to a bovine illness known as Black Disease, which kills off
flesh, turning it black. It rarely infects humans, though it is
said to have been responsible for outbreaks of gangrene among
soldiers in the First and Second World Wars.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the heroin users, the bacterium is most likely
coming from a particular batch of heroin contaminated with dirt
harboring clostridium spores, officials said. When the users
dissolve the heroin in citric acid and inject it into their
muscles, generally because their veins have collapsed from repeated
abuse, the injection kills off surrounding tissue, forming a
perfect breeding ground for the bacterium. The first symptom of the
illness is a severe infection at the site of the injection, leading
to massive localized swelling and gaping abscesses.
</P>
<P>
   The illness is treatable at this early stage, with huge doses of
antibiotics and the surgical removal of the dead tissue at the site
of the infection. But left untreated, the bacterium then releases
powerful toxins into the body, causing a huge increase in white
blood cell counts and kidney and liver malfunctions. Patients who
have reached this stage have died of heart failure within 48 hours
or so.
</P>
<P>
   Of more than 70 reported cases, in Glasgow, Edinburgh,
Manchester, Liverpool and other cities, about half the victims have
died.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that it was impossible to tell which batch of
heroin was responsible, or at what point on the usual heroin route,
from West Asia to Britain, the drug had been contaminated. They
also said they did not know how much was still out on the streets.
In Glasgow, police announced that a special unit set up to
investigate the outbreak had made 11 arrests.
</P>
<P>
   But even though they now know what is causing the illness,
doctors said that there is still no cure once the toxins enter the
bloodstream. They stressed that addicts should smoke heroin, not
inject it. Dr. Jai Lingappa, an investigator with the U.S. Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta, said that studies
were continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking forward to the results of culturing the heroin
under a variety of conditions to see if we can isolate it and other
bacteria,'' Lingappa told reporters in Glasgow. ``We also want to
learn more about why these people became sick and others didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1739EDT &QL; 
