<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Very warm and more humid air will spill into the Middle Atlantic
and Northeastern states Friday. Partly sunny skies will combine
with breezes from the southwest that warm as they descend the
Appalachians raising temperatures above seasonal levels. A few
thunderstorms are will form in the afternoon in the Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Many showers and thunderstorms, some of which will be strong
with heavy rain, will develop from the Great Lakes to the central
Mississippi Valley Thursday as a cold front sweeps to the east.
Behind this front, cooler air will move south from Canada, dropping
readings into the 50s and 60s in the northern and central Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The record warmth will abate slightly in the West as cooler
onshore breezes develop along the central California coastline.
Interior deserts and valleys will remain hot, however.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: BREAKING RECORDS
</P>
<P>
   Many summer hot spells are accompanied by the setting of daily
temperature records. Much less common are all-time records that are
set when the heat exceeds that of any previous day measured at a
given location. Rarer still are all-time state records that occur
when the temperature is higher than has been measured at any
official site in a state. On Wednesday, an all-time record was set
at San Jose, Calif. when the mercury touched 109 degrees. The
California state record remains 134 degrees at Death Valley, which
has stood since July 10, 1913.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
