<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: You could call it another reinvention
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore's presidential campaign is getting a new chairman. Tony
Coelho is quitting for health reasons, and William Daley is
stepping down as commerce secretary to take over. It's the second
makeover in a year of Gore's high command. Coelho, an ex-California
congressman, was hospitalized this week with an inflamed colon and
said he's been having epileptic seizures. Daley, considered one of
the most politically savvy members of President Clinton's Cabinet,
is a son of the late Chicago Mayor Richard J. Daley and brother of
current Mayor Richard M. Daley.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY TO ABLE THE DISABLED
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush proposed spending $880 million over five years
for technology development to ease the challenges facing the
disabled and helping them work from home. Speaking today at a
disabled-friendly company in Portland, Maine, Bush said: ``People
with disabilities confront hardship every day of their lives. To me
that leaves our society with a simple choice: whether to add to
that hardship or to try to lessen it.'' The candidate's father,
former President George Bush, signed the Americans with
Disabilities Act in July 1990.
</P>
<P>
   UPPING THE ANTE
</P>
<P>
   Doubling the size of his original plan, Al Gore today promised
$500 billion in tax relief over 10 years to help middle-class
Americans pay for tuition, buy health insurance and save for
retirement. He had outlined most of his tax relief plans during the
primary season, estimating their cost at no more than $250 billion
over 10 years. But as prow to be fathers. I know I did,'' the
screen says, crediting the quote to the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND THE IMPORTANCE OF WEALTH
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is giving a double meaning to his current three-week
``prosperity tour,'' collecting a cool million at two dinners on
Manhattan's Upper East Side for the Democratic Party. He stopped
first at the Park Avenue home of financier Alan Patricof, where 40
people paid $12,500 each for a total take of $500,000. At the next
stop, the 90th Street home of Mitchell Blutt, a doctor and venture
capitalist, 50 people paid $10,000 each, also yielding $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   TALL ORDER FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   A pro-choice stand on abortion may not be Pennsylvania Gov. Tom
Ridge's only big obstacle for the Republican vice presidential
nomination; another could be the fact that he himself is too big.
The buzz in GOP circles, according to the New York Post, is that
when focus groups see video of Ridge with George W. Bush, the
pairing flops because the 6-foot-3, massively built Ridge seems to
overpower the slim Bush, whose height is 6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   NOT A HAPPY PLACE , BUT THE MONEY'S GOOD
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has some reasons to avoid Massachusetts. He
resoundingly lost the Republican primary there, and he's likely to
lose there again in the fall. And the Texan makes no secret of his
disdain for the elite atmosphere he encountered at Harvard Business
School. All of which might make Bush's stop in Boston tonight seem
odd, if it weren't for one fact: Massachusetts is a tempting place
for Republicans to raise money, appealing to Boston business
leaders and the booming high-tech industry. Bush is expected to
bring in $1 million at a $20,000-a-couple event.
</P>
<P>
   VEEP CHANCES GONE WITH NUCLEAR SECRETS?
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists and friends of Bill Richardson are
worried that the flak and finger pointing over sky-high gas prices
and lost nuclear secrets from the Los Alamos nuclear weapons lab
could doom the energy secretary's prospects of becoming Al Gore's
running mate. Controversy is hardly what presidential candidates
look for in a No. 2, especially Gore, already weighed down by the
baggage of campaign fund-raising allegations and President
Clinton's scandals. But Gore is not discussing whether Richardson's
troubles would disqualify him.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT PART OF NO _
</P>
<P>
   John McCain's Michigan backers apparently haven't heard him say
repeatedly he has no interest in being tapped for George W. Bush's
presidential ticket. In fact, they put in orders for 500
Bush-McCain bumper stickers after McCain's Michigan campaign office
announced by e-mail that they were available. State Sen. John
Schwarz, who had headed McCain's Michigan campaign, said he paid
for them himself because he's convinced that having McCain on the
ticket will help the GOP win in November _ and that ``it will be
kind of fun'' if they start showing up.
</P>
<P>
   FORGET THE GLITZ , HIRE MORE BOUNCERS
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about violence between rumbling Reform Party factions
and protesters at the convention in Long Beach, Calif., organizers
say they've increased the security budget by as much as 15 percent.
Reform Party official Cedric Scofield cited tough-talking e-mails
between supporters of presidential contender Pat Buchanan and party
founder Ross Perot. And National Chairman Gerry Moan said the party
had received threatening messages from militant groups opposed to
Buchanan. He said he's increased the security budget by nixing
other expenditures _ including for a fancy stage design.
</P>
<P>
   OUT TO GET THE PARTY-SWITCHER
</P>
<P>
   A conservative group that does not have to disclose its donors
set up 50 electronic billboards in Rep. Michael Forbes' Suffolk
County district that show the newly minted Democrat with ex-House
Speaker Newt Gingrich. The Republican Majority Issues Committee
also is sending out 20,000 fliers to Democratic houses on eastern
Long Island touting Forbes' votes for impeachment and school prayer
and against abortion. Forbes became a Democrat last summer,
accusing GOP House leaders of being too extreme, and Republicans
have tabbed him their No. 1 target for defeat in November.
</P>
<P>
   SILENT PARTNER BEHIND THE SCENES
</P>
<P>
   By most outward signs, former President George Bush has
maintained a cautious distance from George W. Bush's quest for the
White House, seldom making joint appearances with his son and
rarely commenting on the election. But behind the scenes, Bush the
elder is anything but remote. The New York Times reports that he
regularly exchanges phone calls or e-mails with about a half-dozen
senior officials in the campaign, and his chief of staff, Jean
Becker, is on the phone with Karl Rove, the chief campaign
strategist, almost every day.
</P>
<P>
   RAISING FUNDS _ THAT'S WHAT HE DOES
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising for the Democratic National Convention in Los
Angeles will intensify in the coming weeks, Terry McAuliffe, the
convention committee's new the factions that have developed within
the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   MOOLAH IN VERMONT
</P>
<P>
   Under Vermont's new state law providing public financing for
statewide campaigns, Anthony Pollina, a Progressive Party candidate
for governor, announced that he has just qualified for nearly
$300,000 in state money, more than the incumbent Democratic
governor, Howard Dean, will get. Pollina had only to raise
contributions of $50 or less from 1,500 Vermont voters around the
state. Some of his donations were as small as 50 cents. The
contributions had to amount to at least $35,000, and to be gathered
from February to July. The state will now give him enough public
money to reach a $300,000 total campaign budget.
</P>
<P>
   HOW ABOUT YOU _ BETTER OR WORSE?
</P>
<P>
   When Al Gore kicked off his current ``Progress and Prosperity
Tour'' this week, he recycled a version of Ronald Reagan's famous
question, asking voters: `
</P>
</TEXT>
