<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOYS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOYS AND GIRLS,' RETREAD OF CLASSIC `WHEN HARRY MET SALLY,' GOES
FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C-  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ``Clueless'' turned Jane Austen's ``Emma'' into high school
hijinks and Baz Lurman's ``Romeo + Juliet'' put Shakespeare in the
mouths of babes, who'd have thought such recycling would get so out
of hand?
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``Boys and Girls,'' a ``When Harry Met Sally ... ''
for the college set. My, how the classics have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Prinze Jr. is geeky, socially maladroit Ryan, who hides
his good looks behind an aggressively nerdy haircut and a pair of
Clark Kent glasses. Nervous, careful, haplessly applying logic and
reason to an unreasonable world, he keeps crossing paths with
kooky, confident Jennifer (Claire Forlani of ``Meet Joe Black''), a
talky, gawky beauty who makes Ryan bristle with every spontaneous
outburst.
</P>
<P>
   The mixture is combustible, or so the film would have us
believe, but there are no sparks behind the wan verbal fireworks,
no character behind the caricatures.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, director Robert Iscove turned ``She's All That,'' a
teen knockoff of ``Pygmalion,'' also starring Prinze, into a
surprise hit. The story wasn't much to speak of, but the film
bubbled with energy thanks to a swirl of bright characters around
the charismatic leads and a delightful step-perfect dance number
that popped out of nowhere to pick up the picture's spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Iscove, a former choreographer, remembered that dance number and
this time uses it to even greater effect. Shy, stiff Ryan flails
around, intently trying to pick up the rhythm of a group dance,
while goosey Jennifer leaps right in.
</P>
<P>
   The energy is infectious and by the end of the number the
mismatched couple is grooving to the same beat. In one spirited
scene, Iscove exemplifies what the wordy script insistently
verbalizes, but once off the dance floor the film slips back into
its dull inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Biggs (``American Pie'') marvelously underplays his part
as Ryan's roommate, a pathological liar who remakes his identity
every few minutes and freely dispenses useless romantic advice, but
otherwise the film lacks a social world for the flirting best
friends their nervous mating dance.
</P>
<P>
   Left with little more than a series of conversations where the
best friends and would-be lovers talk around the issue so much they
wear a hole in the film, ``Boys and Girls'' is finally beholden to
the dialogue. The screenwriters ``The Drews'' haven't the deftness
or invention to pull it off. Prinze and Forlani coast on charisma
alone, but even their charms can't coax magic from the prosaic
dialogue and romantic cliches that clog this listless comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Boys and Girls. Directed by Robert Iscove. Screenplay by The
Drews. Cast: Freddie Prinze Jr., Claire Forlani, Jason Biggs,
Amanda Detmer, Heather Donahue, Alyson Hannigan. Dimension Films.
97 minutes. Rated R for sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
