r e BC-TREK-STAN-LEE-ON-THE-     06-15 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-STAN-LEE-ON-THE-7TH-PORTAL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAN LEE SPINS A NEW WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of comic-book
writer Stan Lee surrounded by some of the characters he created.) 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    ``I'm going to try to put you on speaker phone,'' Stan Lee says.
``If I lose you, I'll call back and we'll try it again.''
 &HT;    It's an amusing moment. Lee is the legendary creator of such
comic-book superheroes as the X-Men, Spider-Man and the Fantastic
Four. These days, he's also an Internet titan.
 &HT;    And he can't master a speaker phone.
 &HT;    ``I'm the worst guy in the world with things that are
technical,'' he says, laughing across the telephone line from his
office in Encino, Calif. ``You know something? I bought my wife a
new car, and it's got 8,000 buttons to push _ I can't figure any of
it out.
 &HT;    ``I drive an '87,'' he adds. ``There are a couple of buttons,
and I know what they are and what they do. I think things can get
too technical.''
 &HT;    Technological difficulties resolved, Lee launches into
conversation about the goings-on at Stan Lee Media and Marvel
Comics. There's the big-screen version of ``The X-Men'' to discuss,
as well as ``The 7th Portal'' and Lee's shocking deal to pen comics
for Marvel's archrival, DC Comics.
 &HT;    ``I don't know if the Marvel diehards have calmed down yet,''
Lee says of that last development. ``What I'm going to do is write
the DC characters _ Wonder Woman, Flash, Green Lantern, Batman,
about a dozen of them _ as if they'd never been created.
 &HT;    ``It'll be as if I thought of a guy called Superman,'' Lee
explains. ``He won't necessarily be from Krypton and won't
necessarily be a reporter. I'm going to take it from scratch and
see what I'd do with him.
 &HT;    ``I may make one of the men a girl or make one of the people a
black man,'' he says. ``I'm free to do it any way I want. But I'm
not trying to set up a whole new series. I'm only doing one of each
_ what DC does after that is up to them.''
 &HT;    The first Lee-DC collaboration, featuring Wonder Woman, will hit
comic-book stores by year's end, with subsequent books out every
other month.
 &HT;    But anyone eager to see Lee's latest work doesn't need to wait _
just hop onto the Web and visit www.stanlee.net. There you'll
encounter Vendetta, Krog, Thunderer and the other heroes and
nasties who seek to control the universe in ``The 7th Portal.''
 &HT;    Launched in February, ``7th Portal'' runs in five-minute,
biweekly installments.
 &HT;    ``Each episode is getting better and better,'' Lee says. ``It's
a learning process for us. I didn't foresee the Internet, but I
will tell you now it's a certainty that the Internet will be the
greatest, most all-consuming, all-pervasive entertainment medium
the world has ever known.''
 &HT;    At the expense of comic books?
 &HT;    ``I don't think so,'' Lee replies. ``I think people, especially
young people, are always going to love reading a story on paper.
They love turning the pages, seeing full color, having little books
that you can roll up and put in your pocket, that you can share
with friends or collect.''
 &HT;    Besides, comic books are invaluable sources of material for
animated Saturday-morning television shows, live-action series and
feature films. The latest example is the big-screen production
``X-Men,'' directed by Bryan Singer and starring Patrick Stewart,
Ian McKellen, Halle Berry and Anna Paquin, among others.
 &HT;    ``I've not seen the movie yet,'' says Lee, who makes a quick
walk-on in the July 14 release, ``but Bryan is an incredibly
intelligent director and a dedicated one. I have to feel he's going
to put a certain amount of intelligence into this movie that'll
make it palatable not just to the comic book's fans, but to the
general audience.''
 &HT;    Numerous other films based on Marvel comic books loom on the
horizon. Among them is ``Spider-Man,'' to be directed by Sam Raimi,
as well as a ``Blade'' sequel, ``The Silver Surfer,'' ``The
Fantastic Four'' and a computer-generated ``The Incredible Hulk.''
 &HT;    And then there are Lee's more recent creations, who are also on
their way to the big screen.
 &HT;    ``You know Mark Canton, the producer who did `Batman,' `Men in
Black' and so forth?'' Lee says excitedly. ``He's here in my office
right now, and he's going to do a movie of `The 7th Portal.' It's
going to be a big-budget motion picture done by a guy who produces
the biggest of the big. I'm so thrilled I can't begin to tell
you.''
 &HT;    As if all that weren't enough, Lee and company are creating
original Internet adventures _ look for ``The Accuser'' and
``Lumina,'' not to mention ``The Backstreet Boys'' _ and readying a
newfangled Mighty Mouse. They're also involved in designing a ``7th
Portal'' ride for Paramount Parks.
 &HT;    Most men Lee's age _ he's 77 _ are heading for the golf courses,
recalling former glories or fretting about meeting the Grim Reaper.
Lee, however, says that he simply doesn't have time for such
thoughts.
 &HT;    ``I wouldn't dare die,'' he says. ``There's just too much
unfinished work here.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The 7th Portal,'' consult the
Stan Lee Web site at www.stanlee.net. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
