<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE'S LABOUR'S' NOT UP TO BRANAGH'S OR THE BARD'S USUAL HIGH
STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B+  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone wandering into ``Love's Labour's Lost'' with high
expectations is probably in for a big disappointment. Kenneth
Branagh's fourth Shakespeare adaptation is neither a tour-de-force
like his ``Henry V'' and ``Much Ado About Nothing,'' nor is it an
eye-filling starfest like his shot-in-70mm ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a slight, whimsical version of one of the Bard's lesser,
least performed comedies, not very convincingly updated to 1939 and
goosed up with some broad comic effects and a series campy
production numbers featuring songs by such '30s tunesmiths as
George Gershwin, Cole Porter and Jerome Kern.
</P>
<P>
   It's never hugely engaging and it's instantly forgettable, but
it has a certain goofy charm, the language is always glorious and
generally well spoken, the musical numbers are enjoyably
choreographed, and it's mercifully brief _ at 93 minutes, probably
the shortest of all Shakespeare movies.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's plot has to do with the complications that ensue
when the King of Navarre (Alessandro Nivola) and his three best
friends (Matthew Lillard, Adrian Lester and Branagh) make a pact to
eschew wine, women and song so they can devote themselves to a
three-year campaign of non-stop meditation and study.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner do they take their oath than the beautiful Princess of
France (Alicia Silverstone) pops into the castle with her three
attendants (Natascha McElhone, Carmen Ejogo and Emily Mortimer) for
a lengthy visit. As each of the eight characters finds an
attractive partner, the guys' pact becomes very hard to keep.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, bard of Avon or no, this is all about as profound
as a re-run of ``Love American Style.'' The reason that the lesser
Shakespeare plays are so infrequently performed is that they don't
hold up dramatically. It's ultimately boring to watch a bunch of
people standing around the stage endlessly gushing about how much
they love someone.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th century update helps a bit, but not much. Branagh has
devised a cute '30s-style newsreel that bridges several of his
scenes nicely, but the Ruritanian setting clashes rather glaringly
with the text (the historical Kingdom of Navarre was in northern
Spain) and the added pre-WWII political background is basically
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the actors are attractive and marginally appealing, and
the language has its own power and momentum, even if the context is
so empty and uninvolving that it's easy to nod off and miss a good
deal of it. Branagh has one particularly moving speech about the
transforming power of love that's stirring enough to bring tears to
the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   And Branagh's biggest gamble _ the '30s songs and Busby
Berkeley-like production numbers _ actually works. They may make
Shakespeare purists want to throw rocks at the movie, but they
perfectly counterpoint the play's sappy sensibility, and they offer
a regular fix of music and color. Frankly, I'd hate to sit through
this movie without them.
</P>
<P>
   Love's Labour's Lost. Directed and written by Kenneth Branagh.
Cast: Kenneth Branagh, Alicia Silverstone, Alessandro Nivola,
Natascha McElhone, Adrian Lester, Nathan Lane. Miramax. 93 minutes.
Rated PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
