<SLUG> BC-THESTREETCOM-DAGEN-STREET </SLUG>
  
 BEWARE OF SHRINKAGE WHEN JUMPING INTO HOLDRs  
 (Financial Commentary)  
 (Editors: Please note disclosure at end.)  
 By DAGEN McDOWELL   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When people talk about a shrinking investment, they
usually mean they're losing money. Merrill Lynch's HOLDRs are
giving an altogether new definition to that phrase.
</P>
<P>
   These baskets, which trade on the American Stock Exchange, all
start out with 20 stocks. But with mergers and acquisitions, stocks
can leave the portfolio and HOLDRs, by their very nature, will
never add new ones as replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine sector HOLDRs, four of them now have fewer than 20
stocks. And all the HOLDRs are less than a year old.
</P>
<P>
   For prospective and current owners of these portfolios, you
should know that you get a very concentrated basket of stocks that
can become more and more concentrated with age. Not only do these
mergers expose your HOLDRs to potentially greater volatility, the
tax consequences of these mergers and acquisitions might hurt, too.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, Merrill Lynch's HOLDRs are fixed portfolios
of 20 stocks that can be bought and sold just like stocks. They can
only be purchased in 100-share increments, or round lots, so they
are not exactly for the small investor.
</P>
<P>
   These baskets cover emerging, volatile sectors, like
business-to-business and Internet Infrastructure, and more
established areas like Pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   They give you an easy way to buy a small basket of stocks with
one purchase. So, rather than paying 20 commissions to buy 20
stocks, you pay one commission to buy one security.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you actually own all the underlying stocks in the
portfolio and can redeem HOLDRs shares for the underlying stocks.
(That exercise can only be done in 100-share increments and costs
$10 per 100 shares, with the fees going to the HOLDRs trustee, Bank
of New York.)
</P>
<P>
   However, these are fixed, unmanaged baskets of stocks that don't
track well-known indexes, which continually replenish their stock
makeup. HOLDRs are concentrated at birth and can become even less
diversified as time goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to mergers and acquisitions, three of the existing HOLDRs
_ the Internet, Pharmaceutical and Internet Infrastructure baskets
_ now only have 19 stocks. The B2B, or Internet
business-to-business, HOLDRs portfolio only has 18 stocks. Future
transactions could reduce the number of stocks in other HOLDRs as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet HOLDRs basket now holds 19 stocks after the merger
of EarthLink and MindSpring earlier this year. (America Online as a
holding probably won't be affected by its merger with Time Warner.)
</P>
<P>
   The Pharmaceutical HOLDRs lost Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn when it merged
with Monsanto to become Pharmacia.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Infrastructure portfolio has one less stock
following VeriSign's acquisition of Network Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The B2B HOLDRs has 18 stocks since SBC Communications acquired
Sterling Commerce and Kana Communications acquired Silknet
Software.
</P>
<P>
   When these mergers and acquisitions occur, a stock might leave
the basket. But since you officially own every stock in the
portfolio, you'll receive your due as a shareholder in any company
that's being acquired. You'll get the appropriate amount of cash or
stock; it will just show up in your brokerage account.
</P>
<P>
   When SBC bought Sterling Commerce in an all-cash deal, B2B
owners got that money in their accounts. When Kana acquired
Silknet, the B2B basket only had one share of Silknet stock. Owners
of that HOLDR got 1.66 shares of Kana stock distributed to them for
every 100 shares of the B2B basket they held.
</P>
<P>
   If a company in one of the HOLDRs spins off a piece of itself to
the public, you'll also see those shares in your brokerage account.
For example, Hewlett-Packard, one of the stocks in the Internet
Architecture HOLDRs, spun off Agilent Technologies. For every share
of H-P, investors got 0.3814 shares of Agilent. For every 100
shares of the Internet Architecture basket you owned, you got 2.67
shares of Agilent in your account.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all this activity can also mean taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The federal income-tax laws treat owners of the HOLDRs as
directly owning the underlying securities. The HOLDRs will not
result in any federal tax consequences separate from the tax
consequences associated with the ownership of the underlying
securities, says each HOLDRs prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   The tax treatment of each merger or acquisition depends on how
the underlying issuer is treating it. You could end up paying
ordinary income or capital gains taxes depending on how each deal
is structured.
</P>
<P>
   The shrinkage issue is only going to become more apparent. Two
proposed transactions, if they get done, will reduce the stocks in
the Telecom HOLDRs.
</P>
<P>
   Brace yourself.
</P>
<P>
   A FULL MAILBOX
</P>
<P>
   Also prepare yourself for a deluge of mail if you own several of
the HOLDRs baskets. If you buy just one, you technically own each
and every stock in that basket. And you will get an annual report
from every company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I currently own some Telecom HOLDRs shares and previously
owned some Biotech shares for a short time,'' wrote reader John
Baycich. ``I received an annual report and proxy card for every
company in the HOLDRs. The mailman was not pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine the amount of mail you would get if you owned
four or five of these baskets?
</P>
<P>
   (Dagen McDowell is a senior writer for TheStreet.com. Send your
questions and comments to deardagen(at)thestreet.com, and please
include your full name. Dear Dagen aims to provide general fund
information. Under no circumstances does the information in this
column represent a recommendation to buy or sell funds or other
securities.)
</P>
<P>
   Distributed by New York Times Special Features
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
