<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TITAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORY LOST IN SPACE IN ACTION-PACKED `TITAN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B   
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disney doesn't merely dominate the world of animated features,
it literally controls the market, and decades of attempts by rival
studios have done little to ease the monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox is cagily targeting two audiences with ``Titan
A.E.,'' families looking for wholesome fare and techno-fans who
seek out anything science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Equal parts space-age Bible story, mythological quest and
old-fashioned space opera, it's an attempt to recapture the
zeitgeist of ``Star Wars'' with the limitless possibilities of
animation, polished up with glitzy computer-generated sequences and
paced at warp speed. But can it overcome the presumption that
animated features are simply long cartoons for kids?
</P>
<P>
   Set a thousand years in the future, in a galaxy where Earth has
been reduced to charcoal and humans are scattered cosmic castaways,
bitter orphan Cale (Matt Damon) shuns his own kind like lepers and
ekes out a living as a space age hard hat on a rough deep space
outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Hot-shot mercenary Captain Corso (Bill Pullman), a growling Han
Solo to this surly Luke Skywalker, hijacks him for a mission to
save what's left of mankind. Cale holds the secret to finding a
futuristic Noah's Ark called the Titan, a ship created by Cale's
father and sent into the far reaches of space.
</P>
<P>
   The glowing blue race of baddies known as the Drej, creatures of
pure energy who splintered the Earth 15 years earlier with their
crystalline Death Star, are also hunting Cale to finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   Cale escapes an assassination attempt in a breakneck chase and
flirts with Corso's curvy, big-eyed, butt-kicking pilot Akima (Drew
Barrymore), an idealistic freedom fighter who breaks through his
shell of indifference and helps him discover his inner hero and
fulfill his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't any surprises in terms of the story, a throwback to
the same cliffhanger adventures and pulp sci-fi that inspired
``Star Wars,'' and the script suffers from flat stock characters
and a supporting cast of second fiddle alien types defined less by
personality than attitude and smart ass quips. But the appeal of
space opera is not drama but the spectacle and directors Don Bluth
and Gary Goldman deliver.
</P>
<P>
   The film navigates through magnificent spacescapes, intricately
designed colonies made of jury-rigged astral junk, and an ice field
where the giant floating crystals crash and shatter as ships play
hide and seek, going the asteroid scene of ``The Empire Strikes
Back'' one better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titan A.E.'' packs spectacular imagery and high-energy action
in a tight 90 minutes and drives it a ripping pace. It moves so
fast you almost forget it the leaves characters in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   Titan A.E. Directed by Don Bluth and Gary Goldman. Screenplay by
John August, Joss Whedon, Ben Edlund and Randall McCormick. Voice
cast: Matt Damon, Drew Barrymore, Bill Pullman, Nathan Lane, John
Leguizamo, Janeane Garofalo. 20th Century Fox. 90 minutes. Rated PG
for action violence, mild sensuality and brief language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5029 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-OPEN-SANCHEZ-HNS &LR;      06-15 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-SANCHEZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAND OF OPPORTUNITY FOUND ON THE GOLF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Javier Sanchez still doesn't seem real.
Even after a 20-minute conversation, I consider him a work of
fiction, a character invented by the USGA to prove that golf really
and truly can belong to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez sneaked across the Mexican border 24 years ago, because
he believed that washing dishes in a San Francisco-area restaurant
could be the start of something big. He was 17, and he had grown up
on a farm without electricity, running water or neighbors _ unless
you counted the people 2 miles away. To go to school, he commuted
more than an hour each way on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is teeing off in his fifth U.S. Open, at one of the
most opulent resorts in the world. Children ride horses here, too,
but somehow it's not the same.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez was 21 when he picked up a golf club for the first time.
At the same age, Tiger Woods had won the Masters. He had
commercials on every television network. Sanchez didn't even know
that golf was on TV.
</P>
<P>
   His introduction to the game came totally by chance. He was on
his third job in the States, cooking in a restaurant, when his
bosses decided to take over the restaurant at the Palo Alto
Municipal Golf Course. That job led to another, with the grounds
crew, and his friends at the course told him that he should try the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I got some (used) clubs, a bag, and I used to go to the
driving range and not even hit a ball but just watch people
swing,'' he told a news conference this week. ``And later on, when
everybody kind of would leave, I kind of started imitating. And
then I started hitting the ball up in the air and fell in love with
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, that should have been the beginning of a lovely
hobby, not a new career. But Sanchez already had made a habit of
ignoring boundaries. He came to the States with a green card
``borrowed'' from another Mexican man for $50. His uncle drove him
across the border that night and told him not to say anything when
they showed the document to immigration officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I couldn't say anything,'' Sanchez said, ``because
I couldn't speak English.''
</P>
<P>
   He learned quickly and well. He has public-speaking skills that
elude most natives. He also has an immigrant's prodigious work
ethic, which helped him make the huge leap from dishwashing to
professional golf.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Pollex, an instructor at Palo Alto Municipal, gave him some
lessons, and he practiced a lot after his shift with the grounds
crew. Sanchez may be the most distinguished graduate of golfing
night school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to putt with the lights on the parking lot; they'd
shine on the putting green,'' he said. ``I used to play there until
9 or 10. And I put in a lot of hard work. Like I said, working hard
for me is not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   His life in Mexico had been much harder. Even at minimum wage,
he felt obliged to send money back to his parents, Bruno and
Rosario. They now live in Redwood City, barely two hours' drive
from this weekend's Open. Sanchez doesn't expect them to come to
the tournament, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know anything about golf,'' he said. ``I took them
out on a course and tried to explain, but they don't understand how
the score is kept or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the family, he said, never balked when he decided to turn
professional in 1990, at age 31. His friends, who understood golf,
thought he had gone around the dreamer's bend.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Sanchez had married an American woman (he is now
divorced and remarried) and become a citizen. He had succeeded as
an amateur golfer, but his first few years as a pro were bound to
be lean. And they were. His first year, playing in golf's version
of the minor leagues, he made about $14,000. He spent $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he couldn't get past the PGA qualifying school,
but he did start to make some money. He had moved to Georgia, where
some Atlanta lawyers befriended him and became his sponsors. He no
longer stays in the cheapest hotels. He says that, in his best
years, he makes about $70,000 to $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   In four trips to the U.S. Open, Sanchez has made the cut once,
finishing in a tie for 90th in 1996. He still hopes to make the PGA
Tour, at age 41. It seems unlikely, but why shouldn't Sanchez
believe? He left reality in the dust a long time ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
