<HEADLINE>
`BIOGRAPHY': THE LIFE OF SAM PHILLIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Broadcast notes follow first review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The photograph, taken in 1956, is an icon of American pop music
history. Four young men are gathered around a piano in a simple
recording studio. Struggle, success and bitter disappointment lay
ahead for all of them. At that moment, though, they shared raw
talent, buckets of hope and Sam Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips _ just out of camera range that night in his Sun
Records studio in Memphis _ had orchestrated the publicity shot
just as he had organized the early careers of the four young men:
Jerry Lee Lewis, Carl Perkins, Johnny Cash and Elvis Presley. By
1956 Elvis had already graduated from Phillips' limited orbit, as
the others were soon to do.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, the biggest Sun star of that moment, had been making a
record that day, with Lewis playing backup piano. When Elvis
dropped by, Phillips, ever the quick-thinking promoter, first
summoned Cash, then called a newspaper, requesting a photographer
and reporter, who dubbed the group the Million-Dollar Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a moment, four men noodling around with songs they
all knew, hymns mostly. Then, like Phillips' time of great
influence, it was over. But that time is worth remembering. And
it's done particularly well in the documentary ``Sam Phillips: The
Man Who Invented Rock 'n' Roll,'' which A&AMP;E is offering on Sunday
night under its ``Biography'' banner.
</P>
<P>
   The film _ written by the rock historian Peter Guralnick and
directed by Morgan Neville _ is filled with the sounds of Phillips'
America: generous samples of gospel, country music and early rock.
And it's filled with the sound of Phillips, still going strong and
looking amazingly youthful well into his 70s. ``Nobody knows more
about sound than me,'' he proclaims.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, at age 27, Phillips, an Alabama native who had become a
Memphis radio personality, opened his studio as a sideline. He
began recording black Southern musicians, including the bluesmen
B.B. King and Howlin' Wolf, for established record companies. A
group called Jackie Brentson and His Delta Cats, including a young
Ike Turner on piano, brought Phillips a hard-driving rhythm tune
called ``Rocket 88.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, was that what I was looking for,'' Phillips says,
recalling how he marveled at ``the force that was in that thing.''
Today ``Rocket 88'' is widely regarded as the first rock 'n' roll
record. Phillips may not have invented it, but he had the sense to
package it, and soon he was selling it under his own label, too.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first Sun hits was ``Just Walking in the Rain''
(1953), recorded by Johnny Bragg and the Prisonaires, inmates at
the Tennessee State Penitentiary. (The tune was later covered by
white artists like Johnnie Ray.) The scene of the hulking Bragg,
standing now in the rusting ruins of his old cellblock singing his
song with an expression of ultimate bliss, is unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed _ everything _ in '53 when a 19-year-old
Elvis Presley walked into the Sun studio asking to make a record as
a birthday gift for his mother. Phillips' employees told the boss
about this ``white boy with a Negro sound.'' You know the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips began promoting other white artists, Roy Orbison and
Charlie Rich among them. But there was only one Elvis, and after
releasing his first five records, Phillips released Elvis, selling
his contract to RCA for $35,000. His canny investments set him up
for life. But his moment was over. Today he runs a string of radio
stations and happily wallows in the role of rock patriarch.
</P>
<P>
   The film assembles a roster of performers and former staff
members, all of whom say they're glad their lives were touched by
the ebullient Phillips. ``I kind of think of Memphis as the Emerald
City,'' says Jack Clement, a Sun producer, ``the Emerald City of
rock 'n' roll at least. And that could make Sam the Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   `DEADLOCKED': OVERWROUGHT, YET SATISFYING
</P>
<P>
   ``Deadlocked'' (8 p.m. Sunday on TNT) gives Charles Dutton a
chance to build a head of steam, progressing from regret to anger
to a rage of Vesuvian proportions. He takes the viewer with him on
this journey, and if he is lustily chewing the scenery by the
film's climax, you may be ready to offer him another helping.
Although nothing else in the production is quite up to the level of
Dutton's affecting performance, the drama succeeds, at least by the
flexible standards of the made-for-television movie.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton plays Jacob Doyle, a retired corrections officer whose
son, Demond (Jo D. Jonz), has just been convicted of a brutal rape
and murder. Ned Stark (David Caruso) successfully prosecuted the
case, but that took no particular effort. The white victim was
found dead in her husband's office; DNA tests showed that she had
had sex with Demond, a black former gang member and petty criminal,
who refuses to say a word in his own defense.
</P>
<P>
   The final matter of business before the jury is consideration of
the death penalty. Jacob has come to court to beg for his son's
life, maintaining, despite the evidence, that Demond is the victim
of a system that discriminates by race and class. Jacob starts
meekly, but when he realizes the futility of his words, he pulls
out two pistols and starts firing. His ear bleeding from a court
officer's return fire, Jacob herds Demond, the jurors and the dead
woman's husband into the jury room and demands to see Ned.
</P>
<P>
   When Jacob declares to Ned, ``I'm the father that made the boy
you convicted,'' Dutton manages to make Jacob an overwhelmingly
sympathetic character. When he gives Ned 24 hours to find evidence
that will free Demond, and Ned agrees, you can't help rooting for
them.
</P>
<P>
   When the film, directed by Michael Watkins from a script by
David Rosenfelt and Erik Jendresen, moves beyond the unbearably
tense jury room, it sometimes feels like an episode of some generic
crime series. The latter part of the story depends on some turns
that you will probably see coming, even as they test credibility to
the breaking point. And the plot's overwrought conclusion is the
kind of smokescreen that covers a hasty retreat. Still, Dutton
leaves you satisfied, even after the smoke clears.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BIOGRAPHY'
</P>
<P>
   Sam Phillips: The Man Who Invented Rock 'n' Roll'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   Written by Peter Guralnick and directed by Morgan Neville.
Neville and Guralnick producers; Andrew Tilles, supervising
producer; Helen Hood Scheer, associate producer; Shaun Peterson,
editor; Craig Spirko, director of photography. Produced for A&AMP;E by
Peter Jones Productions. Peter Jones and Jerry Schilling, executive
producers; CarolAnne Dolan, A&AMP;E executive producer; Billy Bob
Thornton, narrator.
</P>
</TEXT>
