<HEADLINE>
FCC REPORTEDLY SET TO APPROVE BELL ATLANTIC, GTE MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Stock prices in this story are not up to the moment.) 
 By TIM ARANGO   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal regulators are set to give their blessing to
the planned merger of Bell Atlantic and Irving, Texas-based GTE,
creating the largest local phone company in the country, the
Washington Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, four of the five commissioners on the
Federal Communications Commission indicated Wednesday that they
would support the deal. The anticipated merger was announced two
years ago. A decision could come as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, which will be called Verizon
Communications, would control about 63 million telephone lines in
31 states, approximately one-third of the total lines in the United
States. The deal will add GTE's 4 million wireless customers to
Verizon Wireless, the venture formed last year by New York-based
Bell Atlantic and Britain's Vodafone AirTouch, which is already the
nation's largest wireless operator.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will have a market capitalization of close
to $150 billion, with $60 billion in revenue, while employing
260,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic closed Wednesday at 57 3/8, up 1 15/16, while GTE
was flat at 68 3/4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
