<HEADER>
A5048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      06-15 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A RESEMBLANCE? IT'S ONLY NATURAL
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sunshine,'' the family saga by the Hungarian filmmaker
Istvan Szabo that opened in New York last Friday, the actresses
Jennifer Ehle and Rosemary Harris play the same character at two
different stages in her life. Ehle is the young, rebellious Valerie
Sonnenschein, who marries her cousin Ignatz (Ralph Fiennes) in the
twilight years of the Austro-Hungarian Empire; Harris is the mature
Valerie, who survives both the death camps of World War II and the
Stalinist repression of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   It's a smooth transition, made smoother by the fact that Ehle is
Harris' daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done it twice, actually,'' Harris said in the Upper East
Side apartment that serves as the family pied-a-terre in New York
City (home base is North Carolina, where Harris' husband, the
novelist John Ehle, was raised). ``The first time was `The Camomile
Lawn,' a lovely British television series that Sir Peter Hall
directed,'' Harris said. ``He chose Jennifer for the bulk of the
story. I think there were seven episodes, and she was in six of
them. But the last one jumped to 40 years later when the survivors
from World War II met at a funeral, and Jennifer's was one of the
surviving characters. And Peter Hall asked me if I would be
Jennifer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to be riding on her coattails a lot,'' said Harris of
her daughter, who won a Tony Award this month for her performance
in ``The Real Thing'' _ thus beating out her mother, who had been
nominated for her role in ``Waiting in the Wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris added: ``When Ralph and Istvan were talking about
casting, apparently, as Jennifer explained it to me the other day,
Ralph said, `Well, I know an actress who would be right for the
older Valerie,' and Istvan said, `Well, I've seen a girl who I
think should play the younger Valerie.' And then by chance they put
the two pieces together and said, `Well, isn't that a funny thing _
they're mother and daughter.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to Jennifer, `Should we sit down and talk about it?'
and she said, `Oh, no _ do you think we should?' I said, `No, if we
don't know each other pretty well by now, nobody knows us better
than we do.' I didn't watch any film clips of her performance. I
knew with `Sunshine' she would be playing from her own personality,
so we didn't discuss it too deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the great figures of the London and New York stage, whose
lengthy resume includes Laurence Olivier's legendary 1963 ``Uncle
Vanya'' and her own Tony for the original 1966 production of ``A
Lion in Winter,'' Harris has been mysteriously neglected by the
cinema. ``I've never played a really big part in a movie,'' she
said. ``I think it would be lovely to go in every day and, like
threading beads on a string, to gradually let your part grow, like
one does in the theater. But so far, I've not been offered a part
that was more than a few scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say I feel more at home on the stage, partly because
of the text _ you get a bigger lump to grab hold of. I jokingly
said once I was like an animal that had evolved: I've grown gills
for the stage; I breathe in a different way. I am in my element, my
own element, when I'm on the stage. I'm in a slightly different
element when I'm in a film.''
</P>
<P>
   RUTHLESS BUT DEADPAN
</P>
<P>
   Although he appeared in only nine episodes, Patrick Warburton
will forever be associated with ``Seinfeld'': the 6-foot-3-inch,
broad-shouldered actor played David Puddy, the massively impassive
boyfriend of Elaine (Julia Louis-Dreyfus). Warburton plays a very
different character in ``The Woman Chaser,'' an independent feature
adapted by the first-time filmmaker Robinson Devor from a neglected
pulp novel by Charles Willeford.
</P>
<P>
   As Richard Hudson, a used-car dealer in 1960s Los Angeles, he's
a ruthless manipulator who suddenly discovers his artistic calling.
He has to make a movie to show the world what he's learned about
it. ``I thought the whole story was intriguing _ you've got a guy
who does some pretty reprehensible things, but there's not a total
lack of empathy for this character,'' Warburton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His way of dealing with people is so wrong sometimes,'' the
actor added. ``But I thought if we were able to approach this in
the right way, it could be a very humorous story. I've read `spoof'
in some critiques, but I've never thought of this being a spoof.
When I read this I thought it could work on all sorts of different
levels. I think we accomplished some of that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear the word deadpan a lot,'' he said in regard to his
sober style of comic acting. ``I'm not sure exactly what it means
other than the fact that I know when I look at something and I find
it funny, that I really think the approach has got to be one of an
earnest, honest take on something. You let the viewer find the
humor. You don't spell it out. Otherwise it's just not funny. Puddy
is not a joke to Puddy, and Richard Hudson is not a joke to Richard
Hudson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved Jerry Lewis when I was growing up,'' Warburton said by
way of explaining a gift for comedy not always evident in men of
his size. ``I was a bit of a little freak. My parents sent me to an
all-boys Catholic prep school in Anaheim, and I had to take a bus
for a full half-hour each way. You were either an academic or a
football player, and I was neither. Sophomore year, I weighed 105
pounds; I was the littlest kid in the whole school, and I had big
old Coke-bottle glasses. I am absolutely blind. I'm farsighted, and
I am cross-sighted, and I have a huge astigmatism. I had to rely on
having something of a sense of humor just to survive life at the
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
