<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-RURAL-HOSPITALS-0616-     06-15 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RURAL-HOSPITALS-0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL TO AID RURAL HOSPITALS HAS BIPARTISAN SUPPORT
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Hoping to avert a wave of rural hospital closings
across the country, a bipartisan group of lawmakers Thursday
proposed increasing those hospital's Medicare payments.
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ sponsored in the House by Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla.,
and in the Senate by Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D. _ is a response to
reductions in Medicare payments resulting from the 1997 Balanced
Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balanced Budget Act was important ... but many of us
concluded that we went too far,'' in reducing payments to rural
hospitals, Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers noted many rural hospitals, defined as those with 100
beds or fewer in rural areas, are in financial trouble and are
cutting services _ and in some cases closing _ because of Medicare
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These hospitals are tightening their belts and rural Americans
are feeling the pain,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, a
cosponsor of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Rural Research Program at the University
of North Carolina at Chapel Hill indicated that 182 rural hospitals
have reduced their size to fewer than 15 beds in order to take part
in Medicare's Critical Access Hospital program, which pays slightly
higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of closing, they're taking this new program,'' said
Thomas C. Ricketts III, director of the university's rural health
research program.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad noted that many rural hospitals may have a patient
population that is 70 percent to 80 percent Medicare-eligible.
</P>
<P>
   When those hospitals' Medicare payments are reduced, it affects
their financial margins because rural hospitals receive
substantially less money than urban hospitals for the same
services, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Medicare payments for treating simple pneumonia in
North Dakota are $4,259 compared to $8,564 in New York City.
Payments for treating heart failure are $3,980 in North Dakota and
$8,004 in New York, Conrad said.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing payments to rural hospitals is a matter of fairness
and economic necessity, lawmakers from rural areas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elderly people in rural America pay the same Medicare taxes as
anyone else,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa. ``There is no reason
they should be discriminated against.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Fay, vice president of Province Health Care, which owns 17
rural hospitals and manages 48 others, said rural hospitals are
crucial to the welfare of their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the hospital is gone ... and their health care system has
melted down, communities have a difficult time recruiting new
industries,'' Fay said.
</P>
<P>
   Donna M. Williams, executive vice president of the National
Rural Health Association, said increased Medicare payments are
essential to the health of rural hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rural residents ... have the right to care no matter where
they choose to live,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors hope to attach the bill to any major proposal to reform
Medicare or offer seniors prescription drug benefit. For rural
hospitals, it would rescind a provision in the 1997 law that
reduced inflationary adjustments in Medicare payments by 1.1
percent through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Other provision in the bill would provide rural hospitals:
</P>
<P>
   _ Up to $5 million in low-interest federal loans to update their
buildings and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grants up to $50,000 to help rural hospitals install new
computer technology systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Higher payments to hospitals with at least a 60 percent
Medicare caseload or are in geographically isolated areas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increased payments for lab services to facilities with fewer
than 15 beds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the web:
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Foley: www.house.gov/foley
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kent Conrad: www.senate.gov/(tilde)conrad
</P>
<P>
   National Rural Health Association: www.nrharural.org
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
