<HEADER>
A5060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-15 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   by JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNEXPECTED MAN NOW EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's been on and off more times than Dame Edna's wig,
but the long-awaited production of ``The Unexpected Man,'' by
Yasmina Reza, who won a Tony Award for ``Art,'' is apparently
coming to fruition, and with an impressive cast to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Performances of the two-hander, about a pair of strangers
meeting on a train, are to begin on Oct. 11 at the Promenade
Theater. Eileen Atkins will play the female lead, a literary fan,
as she did in London, where she won an Olivier Award. Opposite her
is another famous face long absent from an American stage, Alan
Bates. Bates, who won a Tony in 1973 in ``Butley,'' will play a
writer with a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   The production, which played in London in 1998 with Michael
Gambon as the writer, will again be directed by Matthew Warchus
(``True West''), who also directed ``Art'' on Broadway and in the
West End.
</P>
<P>
   The production had been rumored to be coming to New York several
times since, most recently for a January run at the Gramercy
Theater. But that fell through after a suitable male lead could not
be found. This time, however, Julian Schlossberg, a producer, says
everything is a go. ``We're very excited,'' he said. ``Our hats are
over the windmill.''
</P>
<P>
   SIGNING THE STARS
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With summer vacations looming, several of next year's
big musicals have been looking to signing their leading men.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list are the producers of ``The Producers,'' the
musical adaptation of Mel Brooks' 1968 film satire about a pair of
hapless Broadway schemers. Nathan Lane played the deranged producer
Max Bialystock (Zero Mostel in the movie) in early readings and is
still the leading candidate for that part. For his sidekick, Leo
Bloom, the accountant turned producer played by Gene Wilder in the
film, producers are pursuing Matthew Broderick.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the production team who spoke on condition of
anonymity said the two actors were the leading choices for the
roles but stressed that no deals had been signed.
</P>
<P>
   The musical, with a score by Brooks and a book by him and Thomas
Meehan, is expected to try out in Chicago early next year before a
spring opening on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, after several days of rumors, the producers of
``Seussical,'' the Dr. Seuss musical, were ready to confirm that
David Shiner had been cast in the prime role of the Cat in the Hat.
Shiner is probably best known to audiences as the clowning foil of
Bill Irwin in Broadway runs of ``Fool Moon'' in 1993, 1995 and
1998. The role of the Cat, who acts as the musical's narrator, was
something of a surprise for Shiner, who said he had auditioned on a
lark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never done a musical before,'' he said, speaking from his
home in Germany. ``So I was very relaxed. I never thought they'd
take me.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they did, so now Shiner is to start vocal lessons.
Rehearsals begin on July 10 for a planned October opening at the
Richard Rodgers Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the biggest guessing game in town is who might be in
the running for ``Oklahoma!,'' the revival that the producer
Cameron Mackintosh says he will bring to Broadway this year _ but
only if he gets the right cast. He and the director Trevor Nunn
have been holding casting calls for male and female leads.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the show were mum on casting, but those in the
know say that Marc Kudisch (the cocaine-sniffing ambisexual in
``The Wild Party'') and, even more enticingly, Harry Connick Jr.,
have been sighted coming and going to audition rooms.
</P>
<P>
   TWO ON BROADWAY?
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nothing is definite, but the Manhattan Theater Club
could soon have two productions on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Already announced is Charles Busch's comedy ``The Tale of the
Allergist's Wife,'' confirmed to open on Broadway on Nov. 2, most
likely at the Barrymore Theater (currently home to ``The Real
Thing''). But there is also talk that ``Proof,'' David Auburn's
drama about a touched mathematician and his daughter, might have a
further life as well. The theater club has already extended its run
at City Center until July 30, but several commercial producers have
inquired about a run at a larger theater, possibly the Walter Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   There is one complication, however. Mary Louise Parker, the star
of ``Proof,'' is listed on promotional material as the star of
``Desire Under the Elms,'' opening at the Roundabout Theater
Company this fall. If ``Proof'' proves to have legs, someone's
plans might have to change.
</P>
<P>
   FILLING SHOES
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Taking on a play like ``True West,'' which calls for
toaster larceny, typewriter demolition and attempted murder, is
never easy for an actor. But that job is even more daunting when
the roles taken over have most recently been filled by Philip
Seymour Hoffman and John C. Reilly, both nominated for Tony Awards
for their performances.
</P>
<P>
   But such is the task at hand for Josh Brolin and Elias Koteas,
accomplished film actors who start their run in ``True West'' on
Wednesday, with Brolin playing Austin, the soft-spoken
screenwriter, and Koteas as Lee, his drifter brother. (The two will
begin switching roles in late July and alternating in early
August.)
</P>
<P>
   Brolin, who began his career in theater and will be seen in this
summer's film thriller ``The Hollow Man,'' said he was eager to be
back onstage. ``I think I wanted to say no, but with this play, how
can you say no?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koteas, who has played memorable roles in ``The Thin Red Line''
and ``Crash,'' among other films, echoed Brolin's sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of searching for something to get myself back
onstage,'' said Koteas, who adds that he is still getting
reacquainted with the stage. ``There's technical stuff, '' he said.
``Getting used to using your voice, your body _ it's different.''
</P>
<P>
   Brolin says that comparisons with their predecessors are natural
but dismisses them with a smile. ``People are going to write about
it because it's easy to write about,'' he said. ``But it's kind of
ridiculous, isn't it? It's like comparative lit, which I always
thought was one of the dumbest classes ever. How do you compare one
piece of art to another? They just are what they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
