<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-RENO-DEATH-PENALTY-HN     06-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RENO ENDORSES DNA TESTING FOR DEATH ROW INMATES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno on Thursday weighed in
on the growing controversy over the death penalty, saying some
death row inmates had bad lawyers who failed to take advantage of
DNA evidence that could have proven their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is very important, critically important, that, not
only do they have access to DNA testing before they get to the
point of being on death row, but that they have access to other
forensic and investigative resources that will permit them to
properly explore their claim of innocence,'' she told her weekly
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people in this country do not have competent counsel
to represent them in capital cases,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Reno declined to say whether she supported some form of
post-conviction DNA testing. ``It's going to depend on the
circumstances,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said her view of the criminal justice
system was changed in 1989 because of her experience in helping
overturn the conviction of an innocent man in Florida when she was
a local prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, then the Dade County state's attorney in Florida, was
asked by the state's governor to re-examine the case of James
Richardson, who had spent 21 years in prison _ five on death row _
for poisoning to death his seven children and a stepchild.Reno
concluded that Richardson had been convicted on perjured testimony
and that investigators had ignored the baby sitter _ who was on
parole at the time of the murders for killing her second husband _
as a possible suspect. A judge set Richardson free on April 15,
1989.``I will never forget turning around and looking over my
shoulder at that man, who walked out of the courthouse free for the
first time in 21 years,'' Reno said. ``And to think that he could
have gone to the electric chair for a crime I did not think he
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   The state of Florida used an electric chair to execute prisoners
but in February switched to lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Two different bills, one sponsored by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, and one sponsored by
Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., would allow convicted prisoners to ask
for DNA tests under certain circumstances in an effort to prove
their innocence. Both bills would apply only to federal crimes.
</P>
<P>
   There has not been a federal execution since 1963, but the
number of people put to death by the states is growing _ more than
620 since 1976, according to the National Institute of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Since the U.S. Supreme Court reinstated the death penalty in
1976, eight prisoners have been freed from death sentences and 87
others from lesser sentences after DNA tests cast doubt on their
convictions, according to the Death Penalty Information Center, a
Washington-based group opposed to capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers and foes of capital punishment say laws are
needed to guarantee that convicts can get DNA tested, even if their
appeals have expired. Such laws would be especially useful to those
convicted before the mid-1990s, when many prosecutors and defense
lawyers began using DNA tests at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she would work with both Hatch and Leahy to reach a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   New York, Illinois and Minnesota are the only states that have
laws specifically allowing inmates to ask judges to order DNA
testing of evidence using technology not available at the time of
trial. In California, the state Senate voted unanimously last month
to allow inmates to seek testing if the relevant evidence or
testing technology were not previously available and to require
officials to retain biological evidence. Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, the expected Republican nominee, said earlier this month
that post-conviction DNA testing should be used when the results
could bear on guilt. But Bush, who supports the death penalty, has
refused to say whether he would support legislation _ either in
Texas or Washington _ to make DNA testing available to inmates who
currently cannot obtain it because of court-imposed time limits on
introducing newly discovered evidence.
</P>
<P>
   These time limits are based on the fact that evidence becomes
less reliable due to the passage of time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
