<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TYCOON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN THE TERRIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The arrest Tuesday of Vladimir Gusinsky, the Russian media
tycoon who owns an independent TV network, radio stations,
newspapers, and magazines, looks like a crude effort to punish or
intimidate critics of President Vladimir Putin's government.
</P>
<P>
   The jailing of Gusinsky and the questionable charges against him
also betoken a political blunder _ either by the so-called power
ministries and by Putin's chief-of-staff, Alexander Voloshin, or by
Putin himself. Commenting from Spain, where he claimed not to have
had advance knowledge of the prosecutor's move against Gusinsky,
Putin termed his arrest ``a dubious present for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of state power to single out for retribution the
oligarch who has been the Kremlin's most damaging critic cast a
pall over Putin's European trip, belying his carefully crafted
image as president of a new Russia founded upon equal justice for
all.
</P>
<P>
   Abroad as in Russia, it is generally understood that the
country's nouveau billionaires had to bend or break the rules of a
game that changed overnight. Indeed, Gusinsky was not one of the
oligarchs who acquired oil fields, refineries, or metallurgical
factories at rigged privatization auctions. Targeting Gusinsky,
said Mikhail Gorbachev, ``smacks of vengeance, to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky's broadcasting and press outlets are known for their
propensity to counter government propaganda about the Kremlin's
brutal war in Chechnya and for overt mockery of Putin and his inner
circle. Journalists and business people have protested the
Kremlin's retaliation, sensing that such a revival of police-state
methods may foreshadow a broader assault on all democratic forces
in Russia. Putin ought to hear from governments in the West that he
cannot have gadflies thrown in jail and hope to belong to the club
of the democracies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
