<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-GAMBLING16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET GAMBLING BILL FULL OF LOOPHOLES, PANEL TOLD
 &HT;    510&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite its name, the ``Internet Gambling
Prohibition Act'' would encourage more people to bet from home, law
enforcement and religious officials told Congress on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, originally intended to stop Internet wagers, has
acquired so many loopholes that ``it does indeed expand gambling,''
Justice Department attorney Kevin DiGregory told the House Commerce
subcommittee on telecommunications, trade and consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is a Trojan horse for the horse racing, dog racing,
``sports fantasy'' and jai alai companies,'' the Rev. Louis
Sheldon, chairman of the Traditional Values Coalition, told the
panel.
</P>
<P>
   State lottery officials also opposed the bill, saying it would
block online lottery ticket sales even while allowing other kinds
of gambling. ``State lotteries would be put at a competitive
disadvantage to other participants in the industry,'' said Greg
Ziemak, president of the North American Association of State and
Provincial Lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton administration officials, state lottery
representatives and religious conservatives now ganging up on it,
the once-popular bill faces an uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   The measure got off to a strong start last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., introduced it in response to complaints
that online gambling could encourage children to place bets, feed
the addictions of compulsive gamblers and create new opportunities
for fraud by unregulated casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Operators of Las Vegas casinos, fearing online competition, also
wanted Congress to stop Internet gambling. Sports officials, both
at the college and professional levels, joined the chorus calling
for curbs, saying the lure of Internet betting could overwhelm
young athletes.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, online gambling already is banned by a long-standing
federal law that prohibits the use of wires to transmit bets across
state lines. But most online gambling sites operate outside U.S.
borders, beyond the reach of the law.
</P>
<P>
   This legislation would cut off those offshore casinos by
blocking their access to Internet service providers in the United
States. Under the bill, if a state or federal law enforcement
agency were to notify a service provider of a gambling operation,
whether foreign or domestic, the provider would be required to take
down the Web site within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved the legislation by unanimous consent last
November. In April, the House Judiciary Committee approved it,
21-8.
</P>
<P>
   But as the bill's fine print started getting closer inspection,
its progress has slowed in the House. At Thursday's hearing,
testimony called attention to the bill's exemptions for Internet
betting on horse racing, dog racing and jai alai.
</P>
<P>
   Those ``loopholes'' are ``so big you could drive a truck through
them,'' said Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said several states now allow ``account wagering'' on
dog and horse races. In those states, residents can register
themselves to place bets by telephone. Under the proposed
legislation, subscribers could bet over the Internet too.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said racing officials would have no reliable way of
knowing who was opening an account on the Internet. For example, an
out-of-state teenager could open an account, pretending to be an
in-state adult.
</P>
<P>
   State officials fear that while dog and horse tracks would be
getting richer through the Internet, they would be losing business
because the law would block states selling lottery tickets on line.
</P>
<P>
   Though no state currently offers online gambling, ``there are
states who feel that there may come a time when their governments
feel it is appropriate to offer such games,'' Ziemak said. ``We are
united in the belief that the federal government has no place in
determining the way in which state lotteries operate.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Commerce Committee, which claimed jurisdiction because
the measure deals with Internet service providers, has until June
23 to amend the bill or pass it along for a floor vote.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the concerns raised about betting on horse races,
Eshoo, who represents the Silicon Valley, said she objects to
turning Internet companies into a watchdogs. She warned the bill
could place ``an inappropriate burden on high-tech companies.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   The Thoroughbred Owners and Breeders Association, www.toba.org
</P>
<P>
   The National Collegiate Athletic Association, www.ncaa.org
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
