<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THEATER BUFFS, CLICK HERE
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning there was research, some legal work and in some
cases a lot of restoration. The result is a niche and a Web site:
www.broadwayarchive.com, which specializes in theatrical
productions made for television. Gathered together they make an
unusual outcropping in the home video sea.
</P>
<P>
   At present about 40 productions are available on videocassette
at the site, most of them from PBS. Swoosie Kurtz and Geraldine
Fitzgerald star in Eugene O'Neill's ``Ah, Wilderness!'' (1976);
Blythe Danner and Frank Langella in Tennessee Williams'
``Eccentricities of a Nightingale'' (1976); Irene Worth in Samuel
Beckett's ``Happy Days'' (1980); Dustin Hoffman and Eileen Brennan
in Maxwell Anderson's ``The Star Wagon'' (1966); James Earl Jones
and Raul Julia in ``King Lear'' (1974).
</P>
<P>
   Productions to be added go back to the Dupont Show of the Month
and the Kraft Television Theater in the '50s and '60s: George C.
Scott and Agnes Moorehead in ``A Tale of Two Cities'' (1958); Lee
J. Cobb and Eli Wallach in ``Don Quixote'' (1959); Julie Harris and
E.G. Marshall in ``The Night of the Storm'' (1961); Laurence
Olivier, Judith Anderson, Hume Cronyn and Jessica Tandy in ``The
Moon and Sixpence'' (1961).
</P>
<P>
   To start such a collection one negotiates for rights and goes
digging for the material, wherever it has landed over the years.
``Basically, they were rotting in warehouses,'' said Andrew
Barrett, a vice president of the Broadway Theater Archive, which
began looking for the productions in 1996 in broadcasters' vaults,
libraries, museums and other likely spots.
</P>
<P>
   And there are hundreds more out there to be found. The owners
include estates, production companies and various individuals.
About 70 broadcasts have come from WNET. Barrett said that owners
have been cooperative. ``They realize that no one else is doing
this, and their stuff would be lost forever,'' he said.
Information: (800) 422-2827.
</P>
<P>
   POOH-BAHS RETURN
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know the old-fashioned answer to that question,'' said
Mike Leigh, whose film ``Topsy-Turvy,'' nominated for four Academy
Awards, is to be released Tuesday on tape and DVD by USA Home
Entertainment. The question was how he feels about the film on
video. ``Basically I hope that anybody who sees it has a pretty big
screen.''
</P>
<P>
   The big, colorful film about the difficult and sometimes
hilarious relationship between the librettist William Schwenck
Gilbert and the composer Arthur Sullivan was a departure for Leigh,
noted for small and highly original urban dramas. ``On a level of
naughtiness and anarchy, I was attracted by the sheer unlikelihood
of me doing such a project,'' he said from London.
</P>
<P>
   But there were fundamental connections. ``The main subject of
the film is one I endlessly come back to, which is the tension
between what we are and what we pretend to be, the mask,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reflections like these make good additions to director's
commentaries on DVD, particularly when the director is as
expressive as Leigh. One day he will make a commentary, he said,
but there is none on the disc available next week.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   SWEET AND LOWDOWN
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen's film lives a jazz lover's fantasy: to step back
into the '30s and find out what the near-greats were like. And so
we have Emmet Ray (Sean Penn), a guitarist with just enough talent
to get away with his hubris and selfishness. ``I like women, but
they gotta have their place,'' says Emmet. His girlfriend, Hattie
(Samantha Morton), literally never says a word. But ``Allen's
tone,'' Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``is too genial,
despite the character's obvious dark side, to allow Emmet much
weight.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77; DVD, $29.95. 95 minutes.
Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: June 20.
</P>
<P>
   ANNA AND THE KING
</P>
<P>
   It's unfair to ask this film to be what it isn't, but one still
misses Yul Brynner, Deborah Kerr and the music in ``The King and
I.'' Jodie Foster and Chow Yun-Fat occupy the roles of the
schoolteacher and the Siamese king who sent for her to teach his 58
children. In place of music, Andrew Tennant's adaptation of the
diaries of Anna Leonowens relies on grand settings and a
multicultural sensitivity that put the pair at loggerheads over
political and cultural issues. But ``without any real sparks
between the main characters, `Anna and the King' unfolds like an
exotic historical diorama with dramatic vignettes thrown in for
spice'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Fox. $107.37; DVD not yet available. 147 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: June 20.
</P>
<P>
   THE EMPEROR AND THE ASSASSIN
</P>
<P>
   Compared with other Chen Kaige films (``Farewell, My
Concubine,'' for example, or ``Temptress Moon''), this one, about
China's first emperor, Ying Zheng (Li Xuejian), clanks along as a
relatively conventional blood-soaked narrative of back-stabbing
imperial politics and mass slaughter. Eventually the emperor's
betrayal of his lover and brilliant strategic ally (Gong Li) leaves
him friendless and standing alone. One may wonder whether it is a
disguised parable about the failed ambitions of Mao's Cultural
Revolution, but with its action, pomp, suds and moralizing, ``the
movie conveys the sweep of history with a capital H'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $29.95. 160 minutes.
Mandarin with English subtitles. R.
</P>
<P>
   ALL I WANNA DO
</P>
<P>
   In 1963 the students at Godard's boarding school include the
promiscuous girl (Monica Keena), the angry rich one (Kirsten Dunst)
and the bulimic one (Heather Matarazzo). Odette (Gaby Hoffman)
arrives with her horse and a way with snappy sayings that leads one
classmate to predict that she will become ``a speechwriter or a
demagogue.'' When a merger with a boys' school threatens, the girls
fight for the school's identity. That leads to girl-power melodrama
and bratty farce, but ``the ungainliness is part of the film's
charm'' (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $32.99. 94 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   WITNESS PROTECTION. When the petty mobster Bobby Batton (Tom
Sizemore) gets caught cheating on his bosses and is ordered killed,
he decides to rat on them to the authorities. That lands him, his
wife (Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio) and children (Shawn Hatosy and
Skye McCole Bartusiak) in a duplex apartment where they are taught
how to live in the federal witness-protection program by a U.S.
marshall (Steve Beck). They have a lot to learn, especially the
arrogant Bobby, and, Ron Wertheimer wrote in the New York Times,
the ``process of forced metamorphosis is both fascinating and
frightening.'' 1999. HBO $79.99; DVD, $19.98. 101 minutes. Closed
captioned. Release date: June 13.
</P>
<P>
   POETRY IN MOTION and IMAGINE THE SOUND. Two films by Ron Mann
explore Beat writers and '60s avant-garde jazz musicians. Charles
Bukowski, Amiri Baraka, William S. Burroughs, John Cage, Allen
Ginsberg and Robert Creely, among others, appear in ``Poetry in
Motion'' (1982, 90 minutes). Cecil Taylor, Archie Shepp, Bill Dixon
and Paul Bley are featured in ``Imagine the Sound'' (1981, 90
minutes). Home Vision. $19.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   THE MORPH FILES. Peter Lord, a founder of Aardman Animations and
co-director with Nick Park (``Wallace and Gromit'') of the upcoming
film ``Chicken Run,'' helped create the British claymation and
computer animation series about Morph, an ever-changing character
who inhabits a desktop world and lives in a box. 1999. BBC Video.
Three cassettes, $9.98 each. 45 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
