<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-DEFENSE-3     06-15 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-DEFENSE-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. REITERATES OBJECTIONS TO ISRAELI MILITARY SALE TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ U.S. diplomats met with Israeli military officials
Thursday to reiterate their objections to the sale of an airborne
radar system to China, participants in the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans also pressed for consultations before Israel
offers advanced weaponry to other countries ``of concern'' to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli officials reacted testily to the request, fearing
that the United States was in effect asking for veto power over
Israel's arm sales. And some of the U.S. officials appeared
exasperated by what they see as Israeli unwillingness to
acknowledge growing concern about tension in the China Straits and
about the potential exposure of U.S. forces there.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats from both sides said they welcomed the effort to
tamp down a simmering dispute that has prompted one key Congressman
to threaten to cut military aid here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are both trying to find a way to resolve a disagreement,
though our view still is that they should cancel the sale,'' a
State Department official said after the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. delegation presented a list of 27 ``countries of
concern,'' including China and India, another important Israeli
arms client, where Washington wants formal consultations before
Israel negotiates arms sales, even if the weapons do not
incorporate U.S. technology.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing technical sophistication of Israel's homegrown
defense systems prompted this unusual request, U.S. officials said.
``This is a special relationship, with special obligations on both
sides,'' a U.S. official said. The U.S. delegation was headed by
Eric Newsome, chief of the State Department's Bureau of
Political-Military Affairs, and included several high-ranking
Pentagon officials and Martin Indyk, the U.S. ambassador to Israel.
Amos Yaron, the defense ministry's director-general, led the
Israeli side.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Israel has resisted the intensifying U.S. pressure to
rescind the agreement to supply China with the $250 million worth
of a early-warning radar and communications system. Mounted in a
refurbished Ilyushin-76 transport parked on the periphery of Tel
Aviv's Ben Gurion International Airport, the airborne surveillance
center is just weeks away from its final test flights, officials
close to the project said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., who heads the House subcommittee
that oversees foreign aid appropriations, vowed earlier this week
to slice $250 million from next year's planned $1.92 billion
military package for Israel if the sale is concluded.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would drop his objection if Defense Secretary William
Cohen testifies that the sale would not jeopardize U.S. national
security. That is a difficult proposition for Cohen, who forcefully
stated in recent visits to Israel that the radar system would
greatly heighten the risks faced by U.S. forces in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright strongly objected to the
threatened cut in aid. ``I want to make it clear that although the
United States has real concerns about the proposed Israeli sale of
Phalcon aircraft to China, and we are discussing the matter with
the Israeli government, we do not believe that linking this issue
to our assistance to Israel is the way to proceed,'' she said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Backing down somewhat, Callahan is now advocating a delay in the
disbursement of Israel's military aid until the sale is either
canceled by the Barak government or blessed by the Clinton
administration. A prolonged delay would disrupt Israeli defense
plans and cost the country upwards of $50 million in interest
earnings. That is because under an arrangement extended to no other
U.S. aid recipient, Israel traditionally receives its annual
military assistance disbursement up front, as a lump sum deposited
in an interest-bearing account at the start of the fiscal year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
