<SLUG> BC-BORDER-JUDGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWMAKERS SEEK MORE BORDER JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling a backlog of narcotics and immigration
cases in federal courts a crisis, a bipartisan group of senators
from Southwest border states have introduced legislation that would
create 13 new judgeships in Arizona, California, New Mexico and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These courts are the front line of the drug war,'' said Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas. ``We cannot tolerate a lack of
judicial resources in our fight against the drug trade.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a Democrat, said ``federal
courts along the U.S.-Mexico border are simply overwhelmed with
pending drug cases.''
</P>
<P>
   She said additional judges would result in ``more trials, more
convictions and a safer border.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, federal judges from border states traveled to
Washington to press lawmakers for more resources. They noted the
five U.S. judicial districts along the U.S.-Mexico border handle 26
percent of all federal criminal court cases filed.
</P>
<P>
   They also noted that criminal cases along the border skyrocketed
125 percent from 1994 to 1998, but court staffing increased by only
30 percent during that time, according to records kept by the
administrative office of the U.S. Courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to go to war, you need certain troops,'' U.S.
District Judge George Kazen of Laredo, Texas, told a news
conference in May.
</P>
<P>
   Edward C. Prado, a U.S. district judge in San Antonio, said the
onslaught of cases filed by agents with the Border Patrol, Customs
Service, Drug Enforcement Administration and the Immigration and
Naturalization Service has stuffed dockets all along the Rio
Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Prado said two San Antonio judges are dispatched to Del Rio,
Texas, each month because there is no full-time judge there.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, sponsored by Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., and
Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., includes eight permanent judgeships
(three in the southern district of California, one in New Mexico,
and four in Texas) and five temporary judgeships (three in Arizona,
one in California, three in Arizona, and one in New Mexico).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
