u i BC-GERMANY-RUSSIA-630&AMP;AD     06-15 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-RUSSIA-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN WARNS GERMAN BUSINESS LEADERS THAT U.S. COULD SPUR NEW ARMS
RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ President Vladimir Putin of Russia proposed Thursday
that his country be placed at the heart of Europe's defenses
against missile attack. Putin warned that a proposed U.S. missile
defense system would lead to a ``very dangerous'' arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to several hundred German business leaders in this
capital that long stood at the epicenter of the Cold War, Putin
sought to portray Russia as a natural ally of Germany and the new
Europe while depicting the United States as insensitive to European
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cooperation could take the form of building a nonstrategic
missile defense system reliably covering all of Europe from the
Atlantic to the Urals,'' Putin said on the second day of a
three-day visit here. ``We think this is all possible technically
and technologically. All we need is the political will.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time that the Russian president has taken
up the idea of using Russian anti-missile systems to protect
Europe. But the setting in Germany, the country at the continent's
center and the one whose modern history has been most troubled by
where its strategic allegiances should lie, gave his words an added
edge.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the Russians appear to be proposing the use of
``theater'' anti-missile systems allowed under the Antiballistic
Missile Treaty of 1972 to shoot down short- and medium-range
missiles that threaten Europe. The Russians say they are developing
technology that could down missile-bearing rockets in the boost
phase.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is skeptical of the idea. But Putin is aware
that his proposal buttresses what appears to be a central strategic
aim, driving a wedge between Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, like other European countries, has expressed
ambivalence about the proposed U.S. system, which is widely seen
here as an unproven weapon against an unlikely enemy and one that
would undermine what the Germans call the ``architecture of
disarmament.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now no risk of all-out war in Europe,'' Putin said.
``But that is no reason for complacency.'' He added that the
proposed U.S. system ``would be a blow, especially in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Because such a U.S. system would in part depend on equipment
placed in Europe, the consequences would be particularly serious,
Putin continued, noting that Russia would have no choice but to
regard such equipment as ``directed against Russia'' and would
respond ``in an appropriate way.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would NATO then do?'' he asked. ``Would Russia respond?
And what's that called? It's called a new arms race. We think that
is very dangerous. Can we find a way out? I am sure we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's German hosts appeared mildly taken aback by the
provocative tone of the speech that was delivered shortly after
Putin's first meeting with Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. Aides to
Schroeder hastily called an unscheduled briefing for early Friday,
but the purpose of the session was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The German government has been relentlessly upbeat in its
assessment of Putin, who spent five years in Germany as a KGB spy.
And Germany has described relations between the two countries as a
``strategic partnership.'' After their first meeting, but before
Putin's speech, Schroeder praised the Russian's ``open-minded
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Putin also attacked the eastward expansion of
NATO, a project that Germany favors. He said such expansion would
not strengthen European security and would prompt the question of
why is NATO moving toward our frontiers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have the right to think of our security?'' Putin added.
``We have not only the right, but a duty, for the sake of the
security of all. Because if a country like Russia felt itself to be
in danger, it would destabilize the situation both in Europe and
across the world.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a recent speech in Germany, President Clinton suggested that
eventual Russian membership in NATO should not be excluded, and
Putin has in the past entertained that notion as conceivable.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian clearly senses that European unease over the
U.S. missile plan has presented him an unusual opportunity, and he
is probing European uncertainty wherever possible. The best
alternative to NATO, he said Thursday, is to develop the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe into the basis
for regional stability.
</P>
<P>
   Between his talks with German officials, Putin talked by
telephone to President Jacques Chirac of France. A spokesman for
the Kremlin said the two agreed that the ABM Treaty, signed by
Washington and Moscow, should be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration wants the treaty amended to allow the
deployment of 100 interceptors and a battle-management radar system
in Alaska that would act as a shield against a possible attack from
countries like Iraq and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders of Russia and France,'' the Kremlin spokesman
reported, ``noted with pleasure the closeness of their positions on
questions of strategic stability, confirming as well the necessity
of preserving and strengthening the Antiballistic Missile Treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany has also expressed concern over any dismantling or
change to the treaty, but has made clear that the U.S. plans will
not be allowed to affect the ``cohesion'' of the alliance. The
German commitment to NATO, seen as the guarantor of its postwar
revival and reconstruction, is deep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
