<SLUG> BC-FILM-SHAFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON IS PURE PLEASURE IN `SHAFT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B-  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best thing about the 1971 blaxploitation classic, ``Shaft''
_ in fact, the only truly good thing _ was Isaac Hayes'
Oscar-winning music. And, happily, the producers of this remake
have been smart enough to realize this fact and to recreate that
score virtually intact.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's other big plus is Samuel L. Jackson, who has about
10 times the sassy charisma of the original's star, Richard
Roundtree. In his first solo above-the-title starring vehicle, he's
endlessly fun to watch: to the extent that this could well end up
being his defining role.
</P>
<P>
   So this big-budget effort to revive the dubious esthetics of the
extinct action genre of the early '70s essentially works _ even
though the script is a complete mess and John Singleton's direction
is often clumsy and heavy-handed to an annoying degree.
</P>
<P>
   The story follows the adventures of the original John Shaft's
nephew (Jackson), a highly unorthodox New York City detective
obsessed with an arrogant white racist (Christian Bale) who
callously murdered an innocent young black man but walked because
of the wealth and influence of his real estate magnate father.
</P>
<P>
   The main plot-thread has Shaft and the yuppie scumbag playing a
cat-and-mouse game with each other as they're both on the trail of
a panicky bartender (Toni Collette) who witnessed the murder,
fingered the villain for Shaft, but then disappeared into the night
before she could testify against him.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-movie, however, the script shifts its focus to Shaft's
conflict with a Dominican drug lord (Jeffrey Wright, of
``Basquiat'') _ a decision reportedly made in the editing room
because Singleton liked Wright's performance so much he decided to
emphasize it at the expense of Bale and what was supposed to be an
extended cameo by Roundtree.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's work is indeed humorous and clever, but this second-act
detour throws the movie way off balance. And by the time we get to
the inevitable, final-act shootout, the script has thrown in yet
another pair of villains _ two crooked Keystone Kops _ to create a
bewildering labyrinth of thinly motivated, often tedious subplots.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Shaft'' also suffers from Singleton's morbid view of
race relations and eagerness to exploit the race card. His white
characters are all as consistently evil and homicidally bigoted as
they were in his ``Rosewood.'' The worst thing Shaft can think of
to say about the Bale character is to call him ``a white boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still and all, the movie powers along on the strength of
Jackson's funny, foul-mouthed, tough-guy charm. His character _
with his demonic look, flowing leather trench coat, vigilante
sensibility and flamboyant resignations from the police force _ may
be an utter absurdity, but Jackson is always pure pleasure to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the music. In an era in which movies are invariably
crammed full of inappropriate pop songs in hopes of selling tons of
soundtrack albums, it's gratifying to have a film with a consistent
score that counterpoints the mood and visual style, provides a
stirring theme and is virtually a character of the movie _ perhaps
even the most important character.
</P>
<P>
   Shaft. Directed by John Singleton. Screenplay by Richard Price,
John Singleton and Shane Salerno. Cast: Samuel L. Jackson, Vanessa
Williams, Jeffrey Wright, Christian Bale, Toni Collette. Paramount.
95 minutes. Rated R for language and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0173 </DOCNO>
