<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-HITTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX HITTING IN A SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jimy Williams was standing behind his desk in the
manager's office at Yankee Stadium, searching for answers. For one
of the few times in his tenure as Red Sox manager, Williams seemed
publicly frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had chances with the right people up,'' said Williams of
yet another wasted opportunity by his team. ``And balls were hit
hard, but they were caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have been unable to hit for the last few weeks.
Doldrums have slowed their bats tremendously. This is a profound
hitting slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hit balls . . . close games,'' said Williams, free
associating. ``We hit balls pretty good . . . hit 'em with guys in
motion.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no answers to team-wide slumps. Do you break out of
slumps with bunts and going to the opposite field? Or do you try to
smash out of slumps with free swings and long drives? Or do you
just wait for the law of averages to finally arrive in Boston?
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, in New York, Williams had gone the tried-and-true
approach. The manager attempted to create runs by sending his
runners, by playing hit-and-run, by not sitting back and waiting
for the big hit which, like warm air, has yet to arrive in Boston
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put 'em in motion,'' the manager said. ``You've got to
believe in your hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, for example, Williams had sent Jose
Offerman running with Trot Nixon at the plate with the Sox
trailing, 1-0. Nixon absolutely smashed the ball but his drive was
caught at the knees by right fielder Paul O'Neill. A few feet
either way, and the Red Sox might have had a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit the balls pretty good with guys in motion,'' Williams
said again.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the sixth, the game still 1-0, Williams sent Darren
Lewis off from first on another hit-and-run with Jason Varitek at
the plate. Once again, a Red Sox hitter absolutely smashed the ball
as Varitek drove a liner to center. But Bernie Williams slid in to
make the catch at his knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balls were hit hard,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   No difference. These Red Sox of late can't score.
</P>
<P>
   It is bizarre. Few Red Sox fans of any age, from 20 to 120, can
recall a Boston team of any era that could not hit. Just as few Red
Sox fans of any age can recall a Boston staff that pitched as well
as this Red Sox staff. Life is upside down in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And the frustration builds. ``Everybody is trying too hard to
take too much on himself,'' said first baseman/DH Brian Daubach
who, like Carl Everett, failed to come through against a struggling
Roger Clemens with the bases loaded in the first. ``That's for sure
what I'm doing. We're all trying too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   A big hit by either Daubach or Everett effectively would have
ended that game, given that Pedro Martinez was pitching. Neither
delivered, and the Red Sox were forced to try and claw and scratch
their way to a win when a big hit would have made the task much
easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, but we played hard and we played well,'' said
Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, big hits have been so rare in the last few weeks that a
first-and-third situation for the Red Sox is troublesome. The bases
loaded with one out? Dire straits. And the bases loaded with none
out _ baseball's most pleasant prospect _ is an absolutely
catastrophic prospect for a Boston team that is not hitting,
particularly in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit the ball hard (Wednesday),'' said Nixon, ``but
sometimes we're all trying too hard with guys in scoring position
and we're trying to do too much in one at-bat. You're going to hit
those ruts during the season and you just hope there aren't too
many of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But this rut is so deep that Red Sox fans are mystified. Each
night on TV, Red Sox fans see highlights of bases-clearing doubles
in other games, 13-10 final scores, and endless talk about a
juiced-up baseball or the sorry lot of major league pitching. And
yet virtually every pitcher facing the Red Sox seems to throw like
Cy Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of opportunities to put a few runs up,'' said
Garciaparra, who accounted for the only Red Sox run Wednesday the
only sure way Boston seemingly can score the last few weeks _ with
a home run. But, once again, the Red Sox didn't take advantage of
those chances.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, for the umpteenth time, outstanding pitching was
squandered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DAVIS-SEA-PAINTINGS-N     06-15 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-SEA-PAINTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO A QUAINT FISHING PORT CAME A JAZZY CITY BOY, LURED BY THE
LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At first look, the quaint fishing port of Gloucester,
Mass., seems an unlikely hangout for the jazzy city painter Stuart
Davis (1894-1964). But Davis loved the place, with its
sea-brightened light, its rocky coast, its maritime activity and
its art colony goings-on.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Davis, these attributes lured well-known painters over
the years, including Winslow Homer, William Morris Hunt and Frank
Duveneck in the late 19th century, and Edward Hopper, John Sloan,
Childe Hassam, William Glackens and Milton Avery in the 20th.
</P>
<P>
   Gloucester, Davis wrote in his 1945 autobiography, was the place
he had been looking for: ``It had the brilliant light of
Provincetown, but with the important additions of topographical
severity and the architectural beauties of the Gloucester schooner.
I wandered over the rocks, moors and docks with a sketching easel,
large canvases and a pack on my back, looking for things to
paint.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis had been drawn to Gloucester by Sloan, a friend of his
family, and spent almost every summer there from 1915 to 1934. He
first went with his mother, Helen, a sculptor, and his brother,
Wyatt. In 1925 his parents acquired a house, and Davis _ by then
very much part of the summer scene _ set up his painting studio in
it. Did Gloucester and its well-worn motifs play a role in the
lively and innovative American Cubist style that Davis eventually
developed? No doubt about it, as evidenced by ``Stuart Davis in
Gloucester,'' a show of some 45 oils, watercolors and drawings at
the National Academy of Design, organized by the Cape Ann
Historical Association with the art critic Karen Wilkin as curator.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he got to Gloucester, however, Davis had already
been hit with Armory shock, caused by the big-bang 1913 show in New
York that gave American innocents their first real experience of
European modernist art. As a matter of fact, Davis, who worked at
cartooning and illustrating while studying with the Ashcan painter
Robert Henri, exhibited no fewer than five watercolors at the
Armory Show (priced at $100 each). They were animatedly realistic,
but when he saw them in context, he decided he had to think in more
progressive terms. He turned to the Fauvist and Cubist modes he saw
there for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Among the standout early works he did in his summer place is a
reductive Fauvish landscape, ``Hillside Near Gloucester''
(1915-16). A crisp tree with a pale lavender trunk next to a large
aquamarine rock is set against a bright lavender-blue sky that
Matisse himself would not have scorned. In paintings like ``Rocky
Neck, Gloucester'' and ``Airview'' (both 1916), Davis seems to be
trying his hand at Cubist structure, piling together the geometric
shapes of houses and buildings and pushing their landscapes into
planar thrusts.
</P>
<P>
   In his efforts to become a ``modernist'' painter, Davis tried a
number of styles, producing work far more experimental than that of
his fellow artists. Much of it was cued by the European
avant-gardists he had admired at the Armory show, like van Gogh,
Matisse and Picasso. But though he didn't turn away from the
picturesque themes offered by Gloucester, Wilkin points out in her
``Stuart Davis in Gloucester,'' a book accompanying the show, he
often applied the Modernist notions he saw at the Armory show to
subjects more in line with the gritty philosophy of Henri and the
Ashcan School: backyards, sheds and outhouses, and working
streetscapes with garages, gas pumps and cars.
</P>
<P>
   An example of Davis' more mundane interests is the painting
``Coal Derrick'' (1916), a view of the harbor divided in the middle
by a long, ungainly black apparatus used to hoist coal from ships.
It sits in the water close to a harbor shoreline tightly packed
with a Cubist jumble of houses, while flattened fingers of land jut
out from another angle.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Multiple Views'' (1918), he makes an awkward pass at an
important Cubist notion, that of simultaneity. A number of separate
Gloucester vignettes are compressed into one painting: houses,
figures, the facade of a garage, a tree, a tower, landscape
elements and less readable forms, all on a flat surface plane.
Crude as it is, the work anticipates his later, stylized landscapes
like ``Report From Rockport'' (1940; not in the show) that meld
abstract and semi-abstract bits and pieces into a busy, complex
whole whose colors dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the paintings of the early 1920s seem to flounder,
suffering from Davis' laborious attempts to go further with Cubism.
``Garden Scene'' (1921), painted in muddy colors, is a rambling
collection of flattened, largely geometric shapes in search of a
composition. But by the mid-1920s, his work had lightened up. He
was beginning to hit his stride, as evidenced in the sprightly
watercolor ``Gas Pumps'' (1925).
</P>
<P>
   A jaunty red caricature of a pump with price (was gasoline ever
really 36 cents a gallon?) is poised on the edge of a heavily
stylized harbor scene with boats and sea gulls, the sea conveyed by
a set of straight horizontal lines. The scene, anchored at either
end by the pump and a buoylike form, is partially framed within a
linear trapezoid, in turn enclosed by a more irregular geometric
outline. It's a slight drawing, but it anticipates the later work
for which Davis is celebrated: the snappy compositions _ tied
together by ingenious linearities _ cued by neon signs, billboards,
rushing traffic, the beat of jazz and other elements by which he so
deftly conveyed the cacophony of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the later paintings in the show already illustrate the
bouncy, energetic shorthand that characterizes Davis' mature
styles, among them ``Sail Loft'' (1933), an intricate canvas in
which stylized parts of boats, wharves, water, fishing shacks, rope
and other nautical mementos are strategically melded in a tightly
designed composition. By this time, Davis had already established a
reputation with his first abstract paintings, the influential
``Eggbeater'' series of 1927.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition includes a number of black-and-white drawings
that reveal how cleverly Davis plotted the schematics of his work,
and a post-Gloucester oil or two to show that he used motifs from
the fishing port long after his close association with the place
was over.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Gloucester played a role in his work, as did his other
environments, especially New York City, providing a special light,
evocative motifs and particular spaces. Yet as Wilkin herself
suggests, Davis' art has more to do with his own genius _ his gift
for paring line and shape to essences and uniting them with
scintillating color _ than with any special place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuart Davis in Gloucester'' remains at the National Academy
of Design, 1083 Fifth Ave., at 90th Street, (212) 369-4880, through
July 30. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
