<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5080 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-WOMEN-0615-COX     06-15 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-WOMEN-0615-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE'S EFFORTS TO REACH OUT TO WOMEN NO ACCIDENT
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) Politics
categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCRANTON, Pa. _ Vice President Al Gore's so-called ``progress
and prosperity'' tour has taken on the same ``family friendly''
tone that has characterized nearly every facet of his presidential
campaign in recent weeks, a reflection of the importance he and his
strategists have placed on winning the vote of women this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than the board room economics of world trade, Gore is
focusing more on what he describes as the ``kitchen table''
economics of working families: affordable health care, pre-school
and after-school programs, quality education and protected
retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident. Women constitute 53 percent of the nation's
voting population, and in the last two presidential contests, women
have given the Democratic nominee, Bill Clinton, his winning edge.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, though, Gore has trailed Texas Gov. George
W. Bush, the likely GOP presidential nominee, in various national
polls. And most troubling to the Gore campaign is that in many of
those polls, the vice president has trailed Bush among women,
sometimes by as much as 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's performance among women recently prompted a stern warning
from prominent Democratic pollster Celinda Lake: ``A Democratic
presidential nominee cannot win without the support of women.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest Washington Post-ABC Poll, which was published this
week, Gore ran roughly even with Bush among women, 48 percent to 46
percent, hardly enough to overcome Bush's lead among men, 51
percent to 43 percent, in the Post-ABC survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polls are just moving pictures,'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane
said Wednesday, as the vice president's ``prosperity'' tour entered
its second day. ``But to the degree that they are moving, they are
moving in the right direction. By this fall, we're confident that
women will recognize which presidential candidate is making
proposals relevant to their daily lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is counting on winning ovebout being
compassionate won't do anything,'' she said with a reference to
Bush's signature campaign slogan of ``compassionate conservatism.''
The vice president is ``promising things that are going to help me
where I live,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   McGregor was impressed after watching Gore in a 90-minute
televised forum sponsored Monday night by Oxygen, the new cable
television network developed by Oprah Winfrey and devoted to
women's issues. ``He was really honest and understanding,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions from a studio audience of 150 women,
Gore repeated many of his family-oriented proposals, rarely
contrasting himself with Bush, with one major exception: Gore's own
support for abortion rights, coupled with a pledge to appoint
Supreme Court justices he believes agree with the constitutional
right to privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue in the forefront of this year's debate in
this presidential election,'' Gore said, ``and let me just state
clearly again: I support a woman's right to choose. My opponent
does not.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore avoided any mention of abortion during his visit to
Pennsylvania on Wednesday. But he could not avoid a local
controversy over his pro-choice position. His scheduled appearance
at Scranton's Mercy Hospital was cancelled at the last minute after
Bishop James C. Timlin said he opposed allowing him to speak at the
Catholic facility. Gore appeared instead at the offices of Allied
Services, a not-for-profit company that specializes in
rehabilitation and nursing home care.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen promoted the Trenton, N.J., event Monday as: ``Al Gore
gets in touch with his feminine side.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, Gore has attempted to get in touch with the
``feminine side'' of American politics almost since the beginning
of his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination. And it
has only intensified in the year since his eight-months-pregnant
daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, introduced him at his official
kick-off.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Gore and his wife, Tipper, joined talk show host
Rosie O'Donnell at a midtown Manhattan day care center where the
vice president played in the sandbox and sang his ABC's with 3- and
4-year olds.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, he made an impromptu stop at another daycare
center his motorcade passed enroute from the local pharmacy to his
health care forum.
</P>
<P>
   Gore noticed the crowd of children with crayon-scrawled
``Welcome to Scranton'' signs and stopped to chat with them for
about 10 minutes as Gore campaign film crews recorded the event,
possibly for the ``family issues'' campaign ads to be aired in the
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a president who understands what these kids need,''
said Dottie Shoemaker, an assistant teacher and cook at the United
Way-run center, which cares for 84 children ranging from 9 months
to 10 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore has a problem in his efforts to connect with women that
Clinton never had, namely George W. Bush. Bush split the women's
vote in defeating Texas Gov. Ann Richards in 1994, then won 65
percent of that vote in his landslide re-election in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   GOP pollster Linda Divall said the governor has been able to
close the so-called gender gap by talking about issues that have
traditionally benefitted Democrats _ education, health care and
Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   At the mid-day forum on health care Wednesday, Gore called for
the creation of a Health Care Trust Fund as a first step toward
universal health care coverage for Americans. Gore's plan calls for
first extending coverage to children, then to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   He also underscored his desire to set aside Medicare funds so
they cannot be used for purposes other than the federal health
insurance program for 40 million elderly and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gore is scheduled to visit Cincinnati, where he is
expected to outline tax cuts targeted to middle-class working
families _ ``tax cuts to let families live their values _ to help
you save for college, pay for health insurance and build additional
security for your retirement,'' he said in the speech Tuesday
kicking off his ``prosperity'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
