<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SENIORITIS16-COX     06-15 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORITIS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. COMMISSION TO STUDY 'SENIORITIS' IN HIGH SCHOOLS
 &HT;    380&AMP;adds
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard Riley created a
national commission Thursday to conduct a $1.1 million, year-long
study of ``senioritis'' _ the malaise that leads students to slack
off in their final year of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many of our high school seniors are checking out once they
have filled out their college application or received an early
acceptance notice from college,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that helps explain why, among those graduates who go on
to college, one-third have to take remedial courses and one-fourth
never earn a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students who aren't college-bound often drift through their
entire senior year with no sense of direction,'' Riley continued.
``These young people really do have a serious case of the 'who
cares?' syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   He announced his action to more than 1,500 high school educators
and other participants in his department's conference on
``reinventing high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the audience nodded with recognition. In interviews
afterwards, several admitted the syndrome was common when they were
in school. That may be why many parents and teachers tolerate it,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of seniors, they start to fade out about
February,'' said Delores(cq) Brown of the Prince Georges Public
Schools in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have all their graduation credits, they're tired, and
they're ready to move on to the next phase in their life,'' she
said. ``It's very hard for the kids to stay focused when the
returns are intangible. Maybe more courses should be required.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few educators bristled at Riley's generalizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of kids study harder in the last two years,'' said Myra
Ross of Amherst Regional High School in Massachusetts. ``Once they
figure out the reasons for studying hard, they find focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul Patton of Kentucky will head the panel, officially
named the Commission on the High School Senior Year. Its mission
will be to find ways to transform a year-long wait for the senior
prom and graduation ceremony into a year of educational activities
_ possibly including internships, service projects or advanced
study _ that help students move more smoothly into college, work
and adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Riley said that later this month he will name two vice chairs
and the rest of the commissioners, who are to include four students
and four members of Congress, as well as teachers, administrators,
university presidents, youth experts and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Patton said the commission will conduct studies; hold hearings
this fall for experts, students and recent graduates; issue an
interim report in December; hold more hearings, and issue a final
report next June.
</P>
<P>
   Riley has raised $740,000 of the $1.1 million budget. That
includes $400,000 from the Charles Stewart Mott Foundation of
Flint, Mich., $250,000 from the Education Department, $50,000 from
the Carnegie Corporation of New York and $40,000 from the Woodrow
Wilson National Fellowship Foundation of Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Patton, a former chairman of the Education Commission of the
States, said two incidents impelled him to take on the challenge of
finding ways to make the last year of high school more productive:
</P>
<P>
   _ His daughter Bambi taught him that reluctant students can be
motivated. When he and his wife informed Bambi that they had
received a notice that she was failing in high school, she asked
him, ``Dad, if I make the dean's list, will you get me a
Corvette?'' Figuring she couldn't, he took up the offer; she made
the dean's list, and he bought Bambi the car.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Kentucky, which uses test scores to evaluate the success of
its schools, scores rose for high schools when the tests that had
been given to laid-back seniors were instead given to strivers in
their junior year.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some educators at the conference blamed senioritis on the
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We start immunizing them against senioritis in February, when
we talk to the seniors in small groups and warn them not to get on
cruise control,'' said Matt Bugg, principal of the high school in
LaQuinta, Calif. ``If they get their (college) acceptance letter
and go on auto-pilot, we remind them that a lot of colleges will
surprise them and withdraw the offer if their grades drop in the
last semester.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said that schools need to offer the students more
than one last school year consisting of seven periods a day, five
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some of our teachers stationed at the local community
college, so kids in 11th and 12th grade can take a mix of college
and high-school courses, if that's what prepares them for what they
want next in life,'' said Terry Peluso, an assistant superintendent
for instruction at Campbell Union High School in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   School-to-Work officials in Washington said the biggest recent
study of what high school seniors think about school is a survey of
8,663 Colorado seniors that was released last year by that state's
Schools-to-Careers program.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how often they were bored in class, 66 percent said
``most'' or ``half'' of the time, 33 percent said ``once in a
while,'' and 1 percent said ``never.''
</P>
<P>
   They said they most strongly motivated when they were interested
in the subject (96 percent), liked the teacher (79), had a
knowledgeable teacher (78) or saw how the class related to their
career interests (62).
</P>
<P>
   They said they are most interested in classes that involve
active, hands-on chances to apply a lesson (74 percent), watching
videos (68 percent) or solving real-life problems (61 percent).
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   Education Department _ www.ed.gov
</P>
<P>
   Colorado high school senior survey:
www.stw.ed.gov/Database/Subject2.cfm?RECNO &QC; 4332
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
