<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ARAFAT _ WASHINGTON _ Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
arrives here today for a one-day meeting with President Clinton and
quite possibly with a sense of urgency toward completing the
``Palestinian track'' of the Middle East peace process with Israel
following the sudden death of Syrian President Hafez Assad.
Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 6 p.m. EDT on the NYT wire in (I)
International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-US _ WASHINGTON _ A year after NATO troops liberated the
war-torn Yugoslav province from Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic's
oppressive government, experts say Kosovo's instability threatens
to derail implementation of the entire Dayton Peace Accords.
Developing. (Michals, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EDT on the NYT wire in (I)
International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LOSALAMOS-SCENE _ SANTA FE, N.M. _ The mood in Los Alamos is
about as black as the charred remains of homes. The city that's
always considered itself elite is reeling under a spy scandal at
the prestigious lab, which employs most everyone in this company
town, a wildfire that swept through and destroyed half the homes,
and now some missing top-secret data. Talking to townspeople,
scientists, and others for a scene piece. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 50.
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-REHEARING _ ATLANTA _ Attorneys for Elian Gonzalez's Miami
relatives said at a rambling news briefing that they have met the
deadline to file a petition for a rehearing of their case in the
battle to keep the 6-year-old Cuban boy in this country. The
request for a rehearing before all 12 judges of the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta was sent to the court overnight
and was expected to arrive later Thursday, attorneys for the family
said. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GORE-COELHO _ CINCINNATI - Vice President Al Gore's campaign
underwent its second major shakeup Thursday with the resignation of
Tony Coelho from the top spot. Coelho, who has been dogged by
ethical questions, stepped down for health reasons. His replacement
will be Commerce Secretary William Daley, who will leave his
Clinton cabinet post to direct the Gore presidential campaign
during the final six months of the contest. With comments from
Gore, Coelho and Bush campaign reaction. (Shepard, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-GAMBLING _ WASHINGTON _ Amid the many issues competing
for attention in Congress's busy schedule, one bill given a good
chance of passing would ban Internet gambling. The bill is
supported by conservatives who oppose gambling on moral grounds,
liberals who say it hurts the poor, and the politically generous
domestic gaming industry. (Geewax, Cox News Service). 28.
</P>
<P>
   RURAL-HOSPITALS _ WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan group of lawmakers
unveil a bill to require that Medicare reimbursements to rural
hospitals keep up with inflation. (Lipman, Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORITIS _ WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard Riley on
Thursday announces creation of a national, blue-ribbon commission
to study senioritis, the mysterious malaise that hits hard in the
last year of high school for students who have finished their
required courses and passed their exit exam. Three foundations are
chipping in to help taxpayers finance the commission, which will be
headed by Kentucky Gov. Paul Patton, and will study ``how to make
the last years of high school, especially the senior year, more
productive, and how to improve transitions to college and the adult
world.'' We'll seek comments from students and teachers among the
1,400 participants who hear the announcement at a conference here
on ``reinventing high schools.'' You may want to seek local
reaction as well. (Mollison, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   ECSTASY _ WASHINGTON House Judiciary Committee is holding a
hearing on illegal importation and trafficking of ecstasy. (ODell,
Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-EDUCATION _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton hosts a
White House strategy session Thursday on Improving Hispanic student
achievement. (Garcia, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   PYRAMID _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ To his business peers, Bill Caudell
is a visionary who created a website that would make thousands
rich, and provide charity to children's programs. To his admirers,
Caudell is a mystical, spiritual man. But to police and state
lawyers, Caudell is a con-man who used smarts, spirituality and
salesmanship to create the what investigators believe is the
largest Internet hoax ever: an international pyramid scheme that
swindled $18 million from 60,000 people in just eight months. State
lawyers will argue for a permanent, statewide ban of th company
June 20 in Palm Beach County Circuit Court. Takeout from court
papers on the case. (Mossman, Palm Beach Post). 85. WITH GRAPHICS
AND PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   PEDESTRIANS _ You think it's dangerous driving in Florida, try
walking. Five of the nation's 10 most dangerous metropolitan areas
for pedestrians are in Florida, including Palm Beach County, which
ranked seventh in a study released Thursday. The reason is suburban
sprawl, said the study by the Surface Transportation Policy
Projeer. But friends who e-mail me on a regular basis and have
access to a wide range of useless information have shared with me
some little known facts from 14th century England. (Ernest Murray
is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Jaime is a carpenter from
Veracruz, working during the week as a framer for a local builder.
He's been here a year, and his wife and two children still live in
Mexico. Jaime lives with a roommate in a tiny frame home down a
pothole-pitted dirt driv appear as the mouse arrow moves around the
image of the artwork. The museum also now features a Dell learning
lab, offering access to the site and a way to correspond online
with the curator and artists. (Gee, Austin American-Statesman).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-NET _ The Internet is changing the way we listen to music,
but it's also affecting the way musicians and the recording
industry are marketing and selling their products. The ChangeMusic
Atlanta festival, in town this weekend, explores the possibilities
of new technology. We talk to CMJ founder Bobby Haber about the
changes afoot and profile a local band and manager who believe the
Internet is replacing the bar circuit as the launch pad of choice
for new artists. (SHarrison, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND _ Phil Kloer's weekly TV viewing guide for the
weekend. Sunday is Father's Day and the conventional TV wisdom is
that the medium's portrayal of dads is a classic case of reverse
evolution, from Ward Cleaver to Homer Simpson _ Father Knows Best
to Father Knows Squat. There's some truth in that but there's more.
Actually, TV's portrayal of fathers today is richly diverse, from
loving, anxiety-riddled Andy Sipowicz (Dennis Franz) on ``NYPD
Blue'' to struggling , deeply flawed Jake Manning (Jeffrey
Nordling(CQ)) on ``Once and Again.'' Ray Barone on ``Everybody
Loves Raymond'' is a weak but caring dad while Ken Titus on
``Titus'' is strong and uncaring. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BOYSGIRLS _ Review of ``Boys and Girls'', with Freddie
Prinze Jr. in another twentysomething epic. Grade: C. (StMurray,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-PARADISE _ Review of ``The Color Of Paradise.'' Iranian
film about blind boy. Grade: A. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-HONOR _ Review of ``Return with Honor.'' Good, solid
documentary about Vietnam and POWs. Grade: A. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 19.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SHAFT _ Review of ``Shaft,'' with Samuel L. Jackson in
the redo as the original John Shaft's nephew. ETA: Tuesday
afternoon. Grade: B-. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-TITAN _ Review of ``Titan A.E.,'' animated sci-fi. Grade:
C-. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 11.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-WOMEN _ Review of ``81/2 Women.'' Peter Greenaway's
really gone off his rocker. Grade: D. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-FANTASIA _ Review of the redone Fantasia. Some of the
animation can't live up to the standard of Toy Story 2. B-.
(Larsen, Dayton Daily News). 15. MOVED.
</P>
