<SLUG> BC-HONDA-HOOT0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's all about riding Wild mountain ride
 &HT;    By David Tulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A hazy sun peeked through fingers of fog from Black
Mountain tickling the Blue Ridge Parkway. The road ahead invited us
to test its smooth, wide asphalt bent merrily around forested
hillsides. When I spotted my riding partners disappearing in a full
lean around the next curve, it dawned on me what the Honda Hoot in
Asheville, N.C., was all about. Riding.
</P>
<P>
   While the springtime gathering in Daytona Beach is about seeing
and being seen in bumper-to-bumper traffic rumbling loudly down
Fla. A1A, its northern counterpart in the lush Appalachians is
about riding challenging roads and smelling pines and damp leaves,
with cool mountain breezes cleansing your thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   The South's two biggest motorcycling events couldn't be more
different. What started out six years ago as a brand-specific
gathering of Honda machinery has evolved into a general celebration
of motorcycling.
</P>
<P>
   This year, most major motorcycle manufacturers are joining the
party for a week of riding, seminars and old-fashioned Southern
hospitality Wednesday through June 24.
</P>
<P>
   Even America's venerable Harley-Davidson line participated last
year, offering test rides on its sporty Buell motorcycles just
steps away from rivals BMW, Honda, Kawasaki, Suzuki, Victory and
Yamaha.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the twisty mountain roads, downtown Asheville's laid
back charm is part of the lure for riders. And local business
owners are more than happy to welcome the 10,000 riders who drop an
estimated $7.5 million on lodging, sightseeing and retail
purchases, according to the city's Convention and Visitor's Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown streets are wall-to-wall motorcycles, hundreds of
chromed cruisers sharing parking spots with gaggles of tourers and
flocks of sport bikes.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on their immaculate yellow 1997 six-cylinder Honda
Valkyrie, a pair of newlyweds in their 30s from Williamsburg, Va.,
took in the Haywood Street scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daytona was our first motorcycle event together, but it's not
a riding experience,'' said Gary Williams.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Colleen, added, ``Daytona is one big people party, and
we're too old for that kind of partying.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple also owns a 1995 Harley cruiser. ``We can wear
leather or shorts, it doesn't matter to us. And we belong to both
HOG (Harley Owners Group) and HRCA (Honda Rider's Club of America)
so we're not snobs. The Hoot is about riding,'' said Gary Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, to learn the latest trends in motorcycling, you first
had to crank up your scooter for the scenic, but wet, 25-minute
ride from downtown Asheville to Windy Gap.
</P>
<P>
   Curious llamas looked up from their corral as a hundred
motorcyclists listened to the motorcycle industry lunch ride at
Freedom Escape Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motorcycling is enjoying its biggest and best success we've
ever had. There's an incredible increase in young riders, off-road
riders, and we're paying attention to female riders, and the rapid
growth in their numbers as well,'' said Gary Christopher, Honda's
senior manager for motorcycle press.
</P>
<P>
   Kawasaki's Mel Moore summed things up by saying, ``These are the
golden years of motorcycling, so enjoy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
