<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL `GYPSIES' CREATE MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Titan A.E.'' blasts off this weekend from movie theaters
around the country, with an often-striking blend of 2-D animated
characters and gorgeous 3-D computer-generated backdrops.
</P>
<P>
   The film, produced and directed by veterans Don Bluth and Gary
Goldman, is far from perfect, with a disjointed plot that doesn't
always make sense. But it's a fun ride. Its look was enlivened by a
team of self-described ``digital gypsies'' headed by two veterans
of George Lucas' operations, using remarkably inexpensive
technology to quickly craft some of its most eye-popping scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The two, David Dozoretz and Paul Martin Smith of Persistence of
Vision Digital Entertainment, had key roles on ``Star Wars: Episode
1 _ The Phantom Menace,'' as previsualization effects supervisor
and editor, respectively. They'll begin work any day now on the
next episode of ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   But between those two sagas, they got a call from 20th Century
Fox to create the ``wake angels'' and ``ice crystals'' scenes, and
to finish a third, the ``gas trees.''
</P>
<P>
   The three scenes, all stunning, were surprisingly created using
mostly off-the-shelf software and Apple Powerbook laptop computers.
And they did it fast, creating 124 effects shots in a
breathtakingly brief 58 days, which may be a world land speed
record for such normally time-gulping work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardware we used was pretty interesting,'' said Dozoretz.
``It wasn't $3 million of Unix(-based mainframe computers). We did
a lot of work on Powerbooks. You can spend half a million dollars
for all these huge servers, or you can buy 10 Macs.''
</P>
<P>
   That fast-and-cheap approach makes the results particularly
remarkable (and remarkably inexpensive), pointing once again to
where filmmaking is headed, even in one of its most tech-dependent
areas. Dozoretz, for one, is excited about the prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' Dozoretz said. ``This digital revolution
is so fabulous. You're not just editing shots any more, you're
editing stuff in the shots. The digital revolution is as big to
film as sound was. We're changing from a photographic medium to a
painterly medium.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the film's Web site, at www.afterearth.com, is
handsomely and interestingly done, with Quicktime movies of
interviews with a number of the film's principals, and clever use
of sound among other features. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Surfing Mars
</P>
<P>
   The initials in ``Titan A.E.'' stand for ``After Earth,'' for
what happens after our home planet is destroyed by an alien
species. On a somewhat less dramatic scale, NASA is planning
another kind of ``After Earth,'' sending a manned expedition to
Mars by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many challenges in that expedition will be
communication. And among the people trying to figure out how to
make it all work is Vint Cerf, the one-time UCLA researcher who
co-wrote and continues to tend the TCP/IP protocols that make the
Internet function.
</P>
<P>
   Cerf, speaking recently to the Internet Society's Los Angeles
chapter (he's the international chairman), talked a bit about the
challenges of keeping people in touch when it takes 40 minutes to
say hello.
</P>
<P>
   Cerf, now with MCI-Worldcom, is working with Mars mission
planners at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in La Canada Flintridge.
And he has found the challenges of communicating with a future Mars
team go far beyond just those 40-minute delays caused by distance.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest complication is that the two planets are moving at
different speeds, he said. That enormously complicates
communication basics like data transmission rates and error
checking. And of course things like solar flares, and even the sun
itself, can interfere, making only one-way or no transmission
possible at some periods.
</P>
<P>
   So Cerf and the JPL are busy constructing an interplanetary
Internet, with a first-ever standardized communication system that
will be on all future space missions as they head into the void.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Network being created at JPL is ``the gateway to the
Mars frontier,'' Cerf said. ``We hope as each mission is launched,
we'll be able to assemble another leg of the network. We are
definitely going to have a two-planet Internet by 2008. The
Internet Society's motto is, 'The Internet is for everyone, even
martians.'''
</P>
<P>
   Want more information? Go to www.gip.org or www.ipnsig.org. You
can also look at the presentation slides Cerf used in his
wide-ranging talk at isoc.org/internet.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information on
the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail him
at davidbloomearthlink.net or call (818) 713-3678. This column and
related material can also be found all week at www.dailynews.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
