<SLUG> BC-CAR-ERNHARDT0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hot ticket: 8th title pursuit
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dale Earnhardt has slipped quietly into the No. 2 spot
in the Winston Cup standings, but his legion of fans has been
anything but silent.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt backers began lighting up the switchboard at Atlanta
Motor Speedway on Monday, one day after the 49-year-old veteran
finished second at Michigan Speedway. The race moved Earnhardt to
the runner-up position in points, 98 behind leader Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Intimidator'' is tied with Richard Petty for the most
Winston Cup championships with seven each. And AMS is the site of
the final event of the season, the NAPA 500 on Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   So, some Earnhardt fans are planning far in advance for the
possible historic moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we've had some calls from the Earnhardt fans _ people who
haven't been here in a few years,'' said Ed Clark, AMS president
and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are milestones in any sport,'' Clark said, ``but if Dale
could win an eighth championship, it would be a major milestone for
his career and the sport as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cup schedule has not reached the halfway point yet,
but the 15th of 34 races will be Sunday's Pocono 500. Unlike the
past several years, Earnhardt has been consistent all season.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt has finished in the top 10 in 11 races and in the top
three in six races. His lone victory of the season was by a couple
of inches over Labonte in the first Atlanta race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a few years ago, people would tell you (an eighth title)
would never happen,'' Clark said. ``But you can never rule out a
competitor like Dale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has got some good cars to work with this year, and I think
that his back problems _ which required offseason surgery _ were
bothering him more than he let on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like he is feeling better,'' Clark said. ``He looks
like his old self. Whatever it is, the fire is back in Dale again.
</P>
<P>
   As always, when Earnhardt is in the championship race, the
residual effect is felt all over NASCAR, especially at the ticket
booth.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Page, president and general manger of Sears Point Raceway,
said he noticed an increase in Earnhardt fans calling about next
weekend's event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime Earnhardt is doing well, fans seem to come out of the
woodwork to support him,'' Page said. ``And if he continues to do
well and stay in the points race, it will generate a ton of
attention for the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
