<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-COELHO-0616-RESE     06-15 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-COELHO-0616-RESEND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COELHO RESIGNS AS GORE CAMPAIGN CHIEF; DALEY NAMED
 &HT;    740&AMP;add
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Vice President Al Gore's campaign underwent its
second major makeover in a year Thursday when Tony Coelho resigned
as chairman for health reasons and was replaced by Commerce
Secretary William Daley.
</P>
<P>
   The affect of the change at the top of the Gore campaign was not
immediately apparent, but comes at a crucial time. With only five
months remaining before the general election, Republican rival
George W. Bush, the governor of Texas, stubbornly holds a slight
lead in the polls and the Democratic vice president is searching
for a coherent campaign message.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore is losing an effective strategist in Coelho, he also
is free of further political embarrassment over a government ethics
investigation of his outgoing campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   And in Daley, he has a seasoned political operative with
experience in four presidential campaigns and a household name in
the crucial electoral state of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton always respected his (Daley's) political
judgment,'' said Frank Greer, who was President Clinton's chief
media consultant in 1992. ``In fact, I was surprised he (Daley)
didn't run the reelection campaign (in 1996). He understands the
modern political campaign, much more than Tony ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley, 51, a banker and lawyer by trade, came to Clinton's
assistance in the dark days of the 1992 New Hampshire primary amid
news reports of Clinton's marital infidelity, his avoidance of
military service during the Vietnam War and drug experimentation as
a Rhodes Scholar in England.
</P>
<P>
   Daley ran the 1996 Democratic National Convention in Chicago.
Most recently, he was one of the major forces behind the
administration's push for normalized trade relations with China.
The measure passed the House and awaits Senate action.
</P>
<P>
   He also is the brother of Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley and son
of the legendary city boss, Mayor Richard J. Daley. His first
exposure to presidential politics was as a teenager at the 1960
convention that nominated John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, widely regarded as the most politically savvy of Clinton
cabinet members, will officially assume his campaign post July 15,
just weeks before the national conventions of both parties. But he
plans meetings with Gore strategists this weekend in Washington
before visiting the Gore campaign headquarters in Nashville next
week.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate announcement from the White House on a
replacement for Daley in the final seven months of the Clinton
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of Coelho's resignation drew a surprisingly
partisan response from the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish (Coelho) well and hope his health improves,'' said
Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes. ``I wonder whether naming a new
chairman involves yet another reinvention of the Gore campaign.
Which Vice President Gore will campaign next week?''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho, 58, hospitalized in Virginia since Monday night with
diverticulitis, an inflammation of the intestine, issued a
statement saying he was stepping down from the Gore campaign on the
advice of his doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctors have told me that I need to slow down, eat better
and travel less for a period of time,'' his statement said.
``Unfortunately, none of this advice is consistent with the rigors
of chairing a presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   In a subsequent telephone interview with The Associated Press,
Coelho also disclosed that his doctors had warned that seizures
from the epilepsy he has suffered from most of his life could
increase in frequency with the pace of the upcoming general
election.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign announced Coelho's resignation in a prepared
statement as the vice president flew from New York to a
family-owned food wholesaler in the Cincinnati area to promote tax
cuts targeted to middle class families as part of his ``progress
and prosperity'' tour of battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   Later, with Daley at his side, the noticeably upbeat vice
president met with reporters in the wholesaler's warehouse to
discuss what impact Coelho's departure and Daley's arrival will
have on his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Coelho led this campaign to a tremendous victory in the
primaries, and he has put an incredible team in place for the
general election,'' Gore said. As for Daley, ``he has done an
outstanding job in everything he has done,'' Gore added. ``I'm
thrilled that he has agreed to take over the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he did not anticipate any other major changes in his
campaign organization.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story can end here. Optional add follows &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coelho notified Gore of his decision to step down during a
telephone conversation late Wednesday. Gore then consulted by
telephone with his wife Tipper, who was campaigning in Florida,
before calling Daley shortly after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Daley joked that he initially thought the vice president was
calling about being his running mate. He said he eagerly accepted
the chairmanship because ``it is the most important election that
most of us have been involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho took control of the Gore campaign in May 1999, bringing
political focus and fiscal discipline to a bloated and spendthrift
organization. With primary rival Bill Bradley showing surprising
strength in the Democratic contest, Coelho engineered a crucial
early endorsement of Gore by the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Gore chose Coelho after extensive consultations with
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho oversaw the tactical move of the Gore campaign from
Washington to Nashville last fall and helped hone the attacks that
quickly ended Bradley's dreams of upsetting the vice president in
the Democratic presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   But with his political skills, Coelho also brought controversy.
He had resigned from a California congressional seat in 1989 amid
charges that he had failed to disclose a $50,000 loan he had
received from a Beverly Hills savings and loan association.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Congress, he became wealthy as a Wall Street and
Washington consultant and as a member of scores of corporations. He
was the chief Democratic strategist in the 1994 election that led
to the first Republican majority in the House of Representatives in
four decades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Coelho served as the American ambassador to the the
1998 World Exposition in Portugal. But earlier this year, he became
the focus of a government investigation stemming from a State
Department audit that questioned his handling of the finances
related to the Exposition.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Coelho's ethical problems was a concern in
relation to his campaign against Bush, Gore replied, ``Not in the
least.'' And the vice president declined to respond to Bush's
prediction, made two weeks ago, that the Gore campaign would
eventually ``dump'' Coelho.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment on that, nor would I dignify that with a
comment,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
