<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-EDUCATION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ANNOUNCES GRANTS TO CLOSE HISPANIC EDUCATION GAP
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton announced more grants Thursday to
help close a long-standing shortfall in educational achievement
among Hispanic students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of gaps that we all want to close. Most
of them are narrowing, but we've still got a lot of work to do,''
Clinton told legislators and educators attending a Session on
Improving Hispanic Student Achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic Education Action Plan program will be increased by
$436 million to support academic programs, student services and
faculty development for Hispanic students, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the funds would address several goals over 10
years:
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrolling children in quality early childhood programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Improving proficiency in English.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing test scores.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing high school graduation rates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doubling college graduation rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closing this achievement gap is a challenge that may seem
daunting now, but it will seem inevitable once we do it,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, addressing the one-day session at the
White House via satellite from New York, also announced that
federal agencies, corporations and non-profit groups would jointly
provide outreach programs and technical assistance to Hispanic
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never be satisfied with a Hispanic dropout rate that
hovers around 30 percent. We have to do better,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the partnership, to be called the 2010 Alliance,
``is designed to to remind the nation of these goals, and to spur
commitments at every level of government in the private sector to
help meet them.''
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Council of Economic Advisers released at the
conference says the high school completion rate for Hispanics is 63
percent compared with 88 percent for whites and African Americans.
That gap ``must decrease,'' said panelists, ``in order for
Hispanics to compete in the global economy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the session, panelists broke into groups to discuss Clinton's
plan to improve all levels of education, from preschool through
college, among Hispanic students. Higher achievement levels can be
obtained by tackling the problem at the grass roots, said
panelists.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
