<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-GUERIN-BOS &LR;      06-15 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-GUERIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME WORSE THAN EVER IN YEARS AFTER MURDER OF IRISH CRUSADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Four years ago, Veronica Guerin, a reporter whose work
shone a relentless light on this country's burgeoning underworld,
was shot dead as she sat in her car at a traffic light, and Ireland
was changed utterly.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, organized crime was all but ignored and gangland
leaders operated with relative impunity. But while laws aimed at
the underworld have been toughened and those who murdered Guerin
have been brought to justice, the problems she exposed have only
gotten worse. Ireland is awash in drugs, and organized crime,
despite unprecedented pressure by police, has never been more
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Guerin has been forgotten. With the fourth
anniversary of her murder upcoming June 26, a memorial to her was
recently unveiled on the campus of Trinity College. Last month,
during a conference in Boston, the Vienna-based International Press
Institute honored Guerin. And Friday, a film based on the last few
years of her life, ``When the Sky Falls,'' opens in Dublin and
London.
</P>
<P>
   But in the four years since her murder, the number of heroin
addicts in Dublin has nearly doubled to about 13,000, health
officials say. Drug pushers have slashed the price of heroin and
junkies can get a fix for about $5, the cheapest in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Junkies walk the streets aimlessly or lounge bleary-eyed in the
city's parks and public places. One day last week, a couple of
addicts lay passed out, in an unconscious embrace, on a bench
outside the gleaming Financial Services center at the mouth of the
River Liffey, a temple to Ireland's booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Guerin, 38 at the time of her death, exposed the venality of
Dublin's gangsters, the obscene profits they were making by turning
one generation after another into heroin-addicted zombies, and the
seeming inability of the Irish authorities to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   For that she was first shot in the leg as a warning, then, when
she wouldn't back off, assassinated. In response to the public
outrage at her murder, which cost Ireland its most courageous
reporter and a 6-year-old boy his mother, the government passed
sweeping laws allowing authorities to seize the assets of anyone
who cannot explain where he got his money.
</P>
<P>
   The Garda Siochana, Ireland's national police force, carried out
the biggest criminal investigation in the history of the Irish
Republic, which led to the arrest and conviction of several men who
carried out her murder.
</P>
<P>
   The underworld leader who allegedly ordered her murder, John
Gilligan, will soon go on trial, and there seems little doubt that
he will spend the rest of his life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the war over Northern Ireland winds down, the battle
over the lucrative narcotics trade has heated up. Police resources
that used to be spent on anti-terrorism are now devoted to
combating drugs. But it is a Sisyphean task. Many Irish gangsters
have simply picked up and moved to the Netherlands, where the use
of some narcotics is decriminalized, and police are not as
aggressive in going after drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cusack, who covers law enforcement for The Irish Times, said
the laws created after Guerin's murder have helped the police seize
more than $20 million in criminal assets, but haven't curtailed the
influence of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now just an offshore outpost of a European criminal
problem,'' said Cusack.
</P>
<P>
   The gangsters who killed Guerin hoped they would silence other
reporters as well. To some extent, they have, said Emily O'Reilly,
who wrote a book about the murder and its aftermath. Guerin was
famous for confronting criminals face-to-face. No one has done that
since, said O'Reilly, who says such restraint is a sign of prudent,
not frightened, journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Her book, ``The Life and Death of a Crime Reporter,'' was
critical of Guerin for taking what O'Reilly considered unnecessary
risks and personalizing journalistic attacks on reputed criminals.
But O'Reilly reserved special condemnation for Guerin's editors at
the Sunday Independent, whom O'Reilly accuses of not doing enough
to dissuade Guerin from risking her life even as they failed to buy
her a life insurance policy. The newspaper eventually gave Guerin's
husband a large lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Guerin was killed, her replacement, Liz Allen,
scaled a fence to confront Gilligan's wife at home, and he later
called Allen to deny involvement in the murder. O'Reilly said Allen
has since been advised by her editors not to engage in the kind of
confrontations that made Guerin famous.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Kealy, the Sunday Independent's deputy editor and news
editor, denied that he or other editors had ordered Allen to steer
clear of criminals. But he acknowledged that Guerin's murder, which
he and others thought unimaginable before it happened, changed the
way editors assess the risks to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were careful with Veronica,'' Kealy insisted. ``And there
are things we can do to protect Liz.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Guerin felt the need to confront criminals in person
to get their side of the story is that Ireland's strict libel laws
make it legally risky to cast aspersions in print, even on
gangsters. There has been no political groundswell to change the
laws, Cusack argues, because they benefit politicians who do not
have to worry about scrutiny of their personal lives or of the
widespread corruption now plaguing the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the new movie and the renewed focus on Guerin's life have
encouraged antidrug activists in some of Dublin's poorest
neighborhoods. At a special screening of the film, Sadie Grace, who
coordinates the Dublin Citywide Antidrugs Campaign, asked for a
moment's silence to remember Guerin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children are being killed on a weekly basis here and
nobody cares,'' said Grace. ``If the government cared the way
Veronica Guerin cared, we wouldn't be having the deaths we're
having.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggie O'Kane, a reporter for The Guardian, a leading British
newspaper, does not think that the authorities' inability to curb
the kind of crime that Guerin put in the spotlight is a slight to
her memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just read the autobiography of Martha Gellhorn, who was
Ernest Hemingway's companion, and it made me think of Veronica,''
O'Kane said. ``When she was in her 80s, Gellhorn pondered her own
legacy, concluding that while maybe not one word she wrote had made
any difference, that was nothing to regret. Her duty, she said, was
to try to make a difference. And Veronica tried. God knows,
Veronica tried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
