<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-NKOREA-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK FROM NORTH, SOUTH KOREAN LEADER SAYS `NEW DAY IS BEGINNING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SKOREA-NKOREA-ASSESS, SKOREA-NKOREA-REACT) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ In a triumphant return home from his summit
meeting with North Korea, President Kim Dae-jung on Thursday told
jubilant South Koreans that ``a new day is beginning'' for their
divided nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Pyongyang, I realized Pyongyang is our land.
People in Pyongyang are our people. And they have deep-rooted love
for their southern compatriots,'' the South Korean president said
in an address at the airport as he returned from three days of
talks with his North Korean counterpart, Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the juncture of opening a new chapter in our
history, putting an end to 55 years of division and hostility,''
Kim Dae-jung told the thousands of children and officials who
turned out to give him a hero's welcome.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, the president's motorcade drove past cheering
crowds, as tens of thousands of colorful balloons were released
into the skies over downtown Seoul. As the limousines moved through
the city, many South Koreans sang ``Our Wish Is Unification,'' a
song popular on both sides of the two nations' heavily fortified
border.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the two leaders also sang the song at a
lavish banquet while joining hands.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving home, the South Korean leader tried to calm
concerns among his allies in Washington and Tokyo that security
concerns had been ignored during the talks. During his speech at
the airport, Kim Dae-jung said that he and Kim Jung Il had indeed
had frank discussions on sensitive security issues, including the
North's nuclear and missile programs as well as the 37,000 U.S.
soldiers stationed in the South.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean president did not describe in detail what he
and the North Korean had had said about the issues, which were not
mentioned in their final agreement signed on Wednesday. He only
said their talks had been frank and productive.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Dialogue was very useful, and I was able to confirm that there
are things that have a bright prospect for resolution,'' the South
Korean president said. He added that they also talked about South
Korea's controversial National Security Law, which is frequently
used to crack down on leftists and North Korean sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   The accord, which produced a common agenda for national
reconciliation and _ theoretically _ eventual reunification, will
of course face many obstacles before it is implemented. Still, the
agreement was widely praised Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in the case of the collapse of the Berlin Wall, the
agreement constitutes a major change toward peace,'' said Japan's
prime minister, Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   China, communist North Korea's one remaining true ally, also
hailed the accord in unusually strong terms. ``The Chinese side has
positively rejoiced over the success of the summit and wishes to
extend its congratulations,'' said Zhu Bangzao, a foreign ministry
spokesman in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States, which has continued to station troops in
South Korea to defend against attack from the north, was
considerably more guarded in its praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, a reduction in tensions is important, but on the
specific issue of possible missile threats, I haven't seen nor
heard of anything in the summit that negates that,'' said Richard
Boucher, the State Department spokesman. The Clinton
administration, citing the potential threat from North Korea's long
range ballistic missile program, has proposed developing an
anti-missile shield to guard against what it considers ``rogue
states'' like North Korea, Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian Foreign Ministry had nothing but praise Thursday
on the outcome of the summit. The two Koreas ``will have to do a
great deal of difficult work to overcome the mutual prejudice and
mistrust that had been accumulating for decades,'' a ministry
statement said. ``Russia intends to make an active contribution to
this process.'' And, in fact, President Vladimir Putin is to make
the first visit by a Russian president to North Korea this year,
probably in July.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The final accord also included agreements on family reunions,
political prisoners, and a common pledge not to engage in offensive
military operations against each other. And the two sides covered
other things as well, like rail connections, hotlines between
leaders, offices in each other's capitals and joint economic
development projects.
</P>
<P>
   While the two countries have agreed to many things in the past,
it has never been done at the level of a summit meeting _ and never
with such apparent goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with a surprise greeting at the Pyongyang airport by
the 58-year-old Kim Jong Il, the meetings between the two men
seemed to evolve into a rolling, emotional getting-to-know you
party. So warm were the currents between them by the end that the
two men embraced firmly on the tarmac just before the visiting
leader boarded his return flight home.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean president's wife, Lee Hee-ho, wept as she
followed behind her 75-year-old husband to the departing plane
while thousands of official greeters waved pink paper flowers,
copies of the Kim Jong Ilia, a specially cultivated azalea that is
the North Korean dictator's trademark.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite the goodwill, hard questions over the implementation of
the agreement are expected to emerge in the coming days. But few in
Seoul seem likely to forget the extraordinary distance traveled in
the short time since secret talks began between the two sides in
Beijing in April. So completely had their history of war and
hostile ideologies separated them, in fact, that even the Korean
language they both use had evolved in ways that made it difficult
to draft talking papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so exciting that I am sort of floating right now,'' said
Chang Ching-wee, a political scientist at Yonsei University. ``It
is difficult to think.''
</P>
<P>
   But Park then quickly grew sober and spoke of the difficult work
ahead that will be required to transform the diplomatic feats of
Pyongyang into lasting political achievements. ``It will take time
and continuous effort to implement what these two gentlemen have
agreed upon. Everyone is excited because this was so unexpected,
but there will be surely be difficulties ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials speaking off the record, and others who
watch relations between the two Koreas closely say that a rough
sequence of events has already been outlined, and that many of the
ideas emerged in rough form in six or more secret talks held before
the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong to look at what just happened as
ceremonial,'' said one senior South Korean official. ``But many
points were worked on beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   He indicated that for each side to secure the other's
confidence, North Korea would make possible dramatic reunions for a
symbolic but significant number of the nearly 2 million South
Korean families which have lost contact with their relatives in the
north since the end of the Korean War in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   The South, meanwhile, will extend millions of dollars worth of
financial assistance to the North, whose collapsing barter economy
has suffered repeated famines in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Only after these steps have been reached will serious talks
begin on security issues, and a visit to Seoul by Kim Jong Il,
which is seen as am important gauge here of his commitment to
further progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hunch is that the two sides will work on the family issue
with the International Red Cross, and at least 100 families will be
brought together,'' said Park Young Ho, director of the Center for
North Korean Social and Human Rights. ``The north will also
probably cooperate in establishing lists of survivors. The
groundwork for all of this has already been laid, I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Many will also be watching for signs that North Korea is sharing
the news of these recent events in a more generous and
straightforward way than it has in the past, including during the
summit, when Kim Dae Jung's words were not broadcast to the
communist nation.
</P>
<P>
   This task will pose special challenges for a totalitarian
leadership whose censorship and manipulation of information is
extreme even by communist standards. According to South Korean
officials, Kim Jong Il himself has only spoken on the air in his
country once or twice at most since taking power after his father's
death in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many experts said there were reasons to hope that the
previously little known leader's self-assured performance during
the summit will encourage further confidence building and
moderation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had a real purchase on the strength of the hold the
regime has on its people,'' said Leon V. Sigal, a North Korea
expert at the Social Science Research Council in New York. ``All
this speaks of a lot of self-confidence which may mean they are
ready to begin doing things a bit differently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
