<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Friday, June 16, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Michael McGarr at the the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   LAKER-MANIA _ (Los Angeles) The excitement of having a potential
champion team crowned Friday night has everyone in a tizzy. For the
first time in nearly 15 years, sports-minded Angelenos might be
able to hold their heads high. Laker mania even upset Dodger fans
earlier in the week: During the 7th inning stretch, they all ran to
TVs to catch the Lakers' score. By Jason Kandel. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DNC-MONEY (Los Angeles) _ An update on the fund-raising for the
Democratic National Convention. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   WIRETAP-DRUGDEALS (Los Angeles) _ Saying Los Angeles County
prosecutors broke wiretap laws, a federal judge said he will
consider whether to order retrials for two drug dealers because
they were not notified of eavesdropping by the police. The judge
also said in a preliminary ruling that the Los Angeles County
District Attorney's Office violated his previous order to notify
all defendants of wiretaps. By Troy Anderson. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   RAPPER-CONVICTION (Los Angeles) _ A jury has convicted rapper
Stanley Howse of ``Bone Thugs-N-Harmony'' of assault with a
semiautomatic firearm, and being an ex-convict with a gun. Howse
faces a maximum prison term of 19 years and eight months.
Sentencing is set for July 14. By Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD-REORG (Los Angeles) _ In a key step toward reorganizing
Los Angeles Unified School District, officials announce the 11
educators picked to lead the new miniature districts within the
sprawling school system. Most of the new ``local superintendents''
are longtime LAUSD administrators, some of whom already hold jobs
quite similar to their new gigs. By David R. Baker. (Will move in
the ``n'' California state news file.)
</P>
<P>
