<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBF-FINALS-KOBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE BRYANT FINDS HIS TRIDE IN OT THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The game was in overtime. The Lakers had just
lost Shaquille O'Neal to fouls. The capacity crowd at Conseco
Fieldhouse sensed that it was time, at last, for their Pacers to
pull it out.
</P>
<P>
   There was someone else who had other ideas. As Shaq took his
seat on the bench, 21-year-old Kobe Bryant, who pushes the
definition of precocious to the max, chatted up teammate Brian Shaw
during a break in the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this situation, Jordan wouldn't let his team lose,'' Bryant
told Shaw amid all the clamor. ``Why should I let this team lose?''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant scored 6 of his 28 points in the final 2:33, including
the clincher with 5.9 seconds left, to give the Lakers a 120-118
victory and a 3-1 lead in the NBA Finals. Los Angeles can clinch
its first title in 12 years with a victory Friday night in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Hoop historians may well look back on Wednesday's OT epic and
see it as a watershed moment in Bryant's young career. He's
completing his fourth NBA season and, with his compelling
performance Wednesday, is again eliciting comparisons to Michael
Jordan. He uses the same phrases (``my thought process was . . .
''). He makes the same gestures, such as the open hands out in a
calming maneuver. He plays a similar game, from the slashing, to
the top-of-the-key shots, to the hesitation jumpers in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't there yet, but the more we see, the more we think he's
got a chance.
</P>
<P>
   As he dropped two long jumpers, made the clincher on a
where-did-he-come-from? second chancer and, let's not forget, came
up with a huge block on Austin Croshere, his veteran teammate (and
former Jordan running mate) Ron Harper looked on in equal parts
admiration and wonder. Had he seen this before?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just oohing and aahing,'' Harper said. ``He is who he
is, a kid who loves the game and is happy to do his thing. He would
tell you, I was just having fun. That's fun to him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely the way Bryant described his feelings after the
big OT performance.
</P>
<P>
   This is fun for him. It's a moment he's been preparing for since
he started playing the game in Italy as the son of ex-NBA player
Joe Bryant. It's almost been scripted since then. He entered the
NBA after high school, already mature beyond his years because of
his European upbringing and family background. He ended up going to
the Lakers via trade in a deal that may well go down as one of
general manager Jerry West's best and boldest.
</P>
<P>
   And through some roller-coaster times, ranging from playoff
upheavals to coaching changes to spats with Shaq, it all has come
together this year. He's a consensus All-Star, a consensus
All-Defensive team performer, and, as we saw Wednesday, more than
capable of carrying a team when the need arises.
</P>
<P>
   After O'Neal fouled out, LA coach Phil Jackson, who knows a
thing or two about Jordan, called for his spread offense, which
basically gives Bryant the ball as well as the green light. That
was all Kobe needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had that look in his eye that he was not going to be
denied,'' Shaw said. ``He is not affected by pressure at all. Not
at all. He is in attack mode all the time. We knew one thing. We
knew he wasn't going to pass, so it was good to get out of his
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Pacers figured that out and, eventually, made
Bryant give up the ball after he drained the two long jumpers. That
enabled him to sneak out from under the backboard to retrieve
Shaw's errant shot and coax in a reverse layup. It was his fourth
hoop of the overtime and capped a remarkable stretch in which the
Lakers converted on all eight possessions. By the time Reggie
Miller's potential winner bounced away, it was almost forgotten
that he had gone 47 minutes on a bum left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' saluted Larry Bird Thursday, himself no
stranger to such heroics. ``Every shot was, you know, all net. I
mean, it wasn't even close. He made big play after big play. I
thought Reggie came back and made some big plays, but we knew Kobe
was going to take over. It's just that we didn't stop him. And it
was awesome. I mean, he really played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant has been making a slow but steady case as the logical Air
Apparent since arriving in the NBA. Thursday, former Nets coach
John Calipari, who drafted Kerry Kittles instead of Bryant,
recalled seeing a talented kid with boundless promise during a New
Jersey workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners couldn't believe I was even considering Kobe,''
said Calipari, who had the eighth pick. ``My feeling was that he
and Kerry would be about the same for the first couple years, but
after that, this kid could be off the charts in five years. Kerry
was a safer pick. Plus, Kobe had never been through adversity and
this was, after all, New Jersey. And we were worried we'd be able
to keep him. His agent didn't want him there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant ended up going 13th in the 1996 draft to Charlotte who,
in an arranged deal, then sent him to the Lakers for Vlade Divac.
Less than one month later, O'Neal signed as a free agent with the
Lakers and the seeds were sown. But it was not until the arrival of
Jackson, Jordan's old coach, that Bryant, Shaq, and the Lakers got
it all together. Jackson encouraged Bryant to be more selfless, to
trust his teammates, to try and not do everything. Bryant ended up
leading the Lakers in assists and steals and was second in scoring,
rebounding, and minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson referred Thursday to the challenge of trying to keep
Bryant's ``impulsivity'' in check. At the same time, the coach also
knew when it was time to loosen the reins and, in that regard, he
and Bryant were on the same page in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   As they broke from a discussion following O'Neal's departure,
the two made eye contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had already said, `OK, OK,' '' Jackson said. ``That was
basically our check-off signal.''
</P>
<P>
   That also was the signal that every NBA team is going to see
more often in the coming years. As dominating as Shaq is and will
continue to be, it's terrifying to think of where Bryant might be
headed. He gave us all a sneak preview in Game 4. And, just like
Mike, he finished what he started.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
