<SLUG> BC-CALIF-PIZZA-NYT8 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7  
 THE INVESTOR TASTE TEST: A DESIGNER PIZZA OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 18)  
 By   SANA9   SIWOLOP10   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philly &UR; 11 &LR;  cheese steak. Thai chicken with roasted peanuts and
ginger sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Purists may cringe, but these are the kinds of toppings that
California Pizza Kitchen sprinkles over its paper-thin crusts, to
the delight of new-wave pizza fans in 21 states.
</P>
<P>
   While the designer pies have won a following, the question of
whether investors will develop a similar taste will be answered
only in July, when the chain, based in Los Angeles, is expected to
go public.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the company had not set a price for its offering
or announced how many shares would be available. According to its
prospectus, it wants to use the proceeds to pay back about $40
million in bank debt and to buy back some of its $45.4 million of
preferred stock.
</P>
<P>
   The chain has had a mixed record since a pair of lawyers, Larry
S. Flax and Richard L. Rosenfield &UR; 12 &LR; , founded it 15 years ago.
During its first seven years, it had a relatively low-key growth
plan, gradually opening 23 restaurants. But in 1992, Pepsico bought
a controlling interest, and California Pizza binged &UR; 13 &LR; , opening 60
outlets in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that under Pepsico's stewardship, the chain showed
little aptitude for picking viable locations or maintaining
quality. In 1996, sales actually declined at restaurants open at
least a year. That year, Pepsico decided to focus on its soft-drink
business, and in 1997 Bruckmann &UR; 14 &LR; , Rosser &UR; 15 &LR; , Sherrill &AMP;
Co &UR; 16 &LR; ., a New York investment firm, bought a 67.4 percent stake,
which is now down to 39.5 percent. The founders remain co-chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   After Pepsico's departure, the company closed 16 of the 60
restaurants it built in its fast-expansion days. It has since
followed a conservative growth plan and now has 100 restaurants to
its name, 74 of them company-owned. It has upgraded food quality
while keeping high service standards, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   California Pizza is part of what the industry calls the
casual-dining category _ a segment whose sales are expected to grow
8.7 percent a year over the next five years, according to
Technomic &UR; 17 &LR; , a Chicago consulting firm, versus just 5.7 percent
for the overall industry.
</P>
<P>
   Some of California Pizza's recent figures have been strong.
Sales at company-owned restaurants grew 6.1 percent in 1998, 4.1
percent in 1999 and 6.8 percent during the first three months of
2000. That compares with just 0.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers impress Ron Paul, president of Technomic &UR; 17 &LR; ,
because the casual-dining segment considers annual growth of 2 to 3
percent as ``pretty good.'' He also likes that the average check
for California Pizza customers is just $10.50; he thinks
casual-dining customers see $10-and-under bills as good value.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is not the hottest market in which to sell
restaurant shares. The Standard &AMP; Poor's restaurants index is down
20 percent over the last 12 months. The new-issue market itself is
rife with postponements and cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   California Pizza reported total debt of $40.1 million on April
2. Last year, earnings fell 48.6 percent, to $5.4 million, while
overall sales grew 7.2 percent, to $1.79 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While it is evident that premium pizza is not merely a fad, Phil
Lempert &UR; 18 &LR; , the editor of the Lempert &UR; 18 &LR;  Report, an industry
newsletter in Santa Monica, Calif., said California Pizza would
have to spend heavily on advertising to remind the public that it
also has other items on its menu.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Randall Hiatt &UR; 19 &LR; , a consultant at Fessel &UR; 20 &LR; 
International in Irvine &UR; 21 &LR; , Calif., question whether California
Pizza can expand effectively outside its Western base. He wonders
if the chain is now growing too slowly. While investors have
punished restaurant companies that expanded too quickly in the
mid-1990s &UR; 22 &LR; , he thinks they are now rewarding those that are
pursuing sustained growth, like the Cheesecake Factory and P.F.
Chang's &UR; 23 &LR;  China Bistro, whose numbers of outlets are growing at
least 15 to 20 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   California Pizza has opened only 10 company-owned restaurants
since the beginning of 1998; four are under construction. ``I don't
think the market will sustain low growth in this industry,''
Hiatt &UR; 19 &LR;  said. ``I think the company is going to have to expand
geographically.''(BOX) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
