<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ATET-MEDIONE-BOS &LR;      06-15 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATET-MEDIONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T SEALS $44 BILLION DEAL FOR MEDIONE GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Thursday officially closed its $44 billion acquisition of
MediaOne Group, cementing the revamped Ma Bell's new role as the
nation's largest cable television provider, with 16 million
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's filing of closing papers in a Delaware court also makes
it instantly Massachusetts' dominant provider of cable TV and
high-speed Internet access, and clears the way for it to buy cable
franchises in Boston and 38 suburbs from Cablevision and heavily
upgrade them for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne's cable customers in 175 Bay State communities and its
155,000 RoadRunner high-speed Internet access customers in
Massachusetts and New Hampshire can expect to see new ``AT&AMP;T
Cable'' and ``AT&AMP;T Broadband'' logos on their bills and trucks
within two or three months.
</P>
<P>
   Closing the MediaOne deal _ which will require AT&AMP;T to sell off
major US cable interests within 12 months _ was the main condition
before it could complete its deal to buy the Greater Boston
Cablevision franchises, which have lagged far behind MediaOne in
rolling out broadband-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the way is clear for AT&AMP;T to move forward with that
acquisition,'' said MediaOne spokesman Richard D. Jenkinson. AT&AMP;T
expects to take over the Cablevision franchises by the end of this
year, as part of a complex swap of systems in New York and
Massachusetts and cash payments.
</P>
<P>
   The MediaOne deal is a key element of AT&AMP;T's $100 billion-plus
move into owning cable systems across the United States as part of
a master strategy of using upgraded cable lines to provide
telephone and Internet service across much of the country, with
major clusters in Boston, Chicago, and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has also bought Charter Communications franchises in 53
Worcester-area communities, and with the Cablevision deal closed
will have franchises in 267 of the Bay State's 351 cities and
towns.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen M. Connolly, an AT&AMP;T spokeswoman, said ``there might be
some minimal shifts of individuals'' in Massachusetts who work for
AT&AMP;T and MediaOne, but overall the company expects to add many new
jobs here selling AT&AMP;T-branded telephone service over upgraded
MediaOne franchises. AT&AMP;T's cable and broadband operations are
based in suburban Denver.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T officials had said they did not expect to close the deal
until early August, after the expiration of a period during which
Time Warner Entertainment _ in which MediaOne holds a 25.5 percent
stake _ could have vetoed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   A Time Warner spokesman confirmed his company blessed the
closing but would not comment on whether that was any part of an
overall deal to resolve several nettlesome disputes between AT&AMP;T
and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T officials have been hoping to reach a deal to offer their
phone service over Time Warner lines, perhaps in exchange for
selling the minority stake MediaOne holds in Time Warner
Entertainment and offering access to America Online _ which is
buying Time Warner _ on its cable modem services.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the Federal Communications Commission's approval
of the deal, within a year AT&AMP;T must either divest MediaOne's Time
Warner stake, or AT&AMP;T programming interests including Liberty
Media, or interests in cable systems serving 9.7 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has made no comment on which option it will pursue and has
suggested it could meet the FCC's mandate with a step short of an
outright sale of the programming interests or by persuading the FCC
it overestimated AT&AMP;T's influence in cable systems in which it
holds a minority interest.
</P>
<P>
   Based on AT&AMP;T's Wednesday closing price, the MediaOne
acquisition is now valued at about $44 billion, down sharply from
the $58 billion price tag when the deal was announced last year,
because of the swoon in AT&AMP;T shares since then.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly said MediaOne shareholders can choose to receive either
95 shares of AT&AMP;T for every 100 shares they own plus $36.27 a share
in cash, or $85 a share in cash, or 149.12 shares of AT&AMP;T for every
100 MediaOne shares they own.
</P>
<P>
   However, the latter two options are subject to pro-ration,
depending on how many people want stock and how many people want
cash. The actual amount of stock and cash people receive depends on
how many people choose what option, with AT&AMP;T setting an overall
package of 606 million shares of AT&AMP;T common stock and $23 billion
in cash to buy MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   ``If every MediaOne shareholder says, `I want $85,' that will
never happen,'' Connolly said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York Stock Exchange trading Thursday, AT&AMP;T shares closed
at $34.1875, up 68.75 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
