<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5117 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SKOREA-NKOREA-CHINA-3     06-15 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-NKOREA-CHINA-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREA RAPPROCHEMENT SEEN AS VICTORY FOR CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sidebar with SKOREA-NKOREA) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Perhaps no outside country has more to gain from peace
on the Korean peninsula than China. And so, as the leaders of North
and South Korea ended their three-day summit meeting with an
agreement and a hug, Chinese officials were understandably elated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese side believes that the summit has produced
important results and is a major event of historic significance,''
said Zhu Bangzao, the Foreign Ministry spokesman. ``It will make a
valuable contribution to the maintenance of peace and stability on
the Korean peninsula. The Chinese side is heartily pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the meeting in Pyongyang in many ways represented a
triumph of Chinese diplomacy, said diplomats and policy experts,
because China _ the only major power to have longstanding
diplomatic relations with both sides _ was instrumental in bringing
the Koreas together.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Korea had to decide it wanted to do this,'' said Zhang
Xiaojin, a professor of international relations at People's
University in Beijing. ``But compared with other countries, China
had an important role.''
</P>
<P>
   China shares a long border and an even longer communist
brotherhood with North Korea. It fought alongside North Korea in
the Korean War of 1950-53, and for the last decade, since the fall
of the Soviet Union, it has been North Korea's only significant
ally.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, with its pursuit of economic reform and
foreign investment, China has cultivated increasingly close
political relations as well as a brisk trade with South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that China has had relatively stable diplomatic ties to
both states since it established relations with South Korea in 1992
has required a delicate balancing act and forced upon China a
certain sense of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, China has fretted about the possibility of
armed conflict on the peninsula and about the dire condition of the
North Korean economy _ which has prompted hundreds of thousands of
North Koreans to flee illegally into China.
</P>
<P>
   David Shambaugh, director of the China Policy Program at George
Washington University, said, ``China's first goal is not to have an
imploding North Korea at its border, and everything else works
backwards from that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To that end, China has supplied North Korea with food and fuel
during its severe food shortages of the last six years. Chinese
diplomats have long encouraged North Korea to follow in China's
footsteps: adopting outward-looking reforms in order to revive its
moribund economy.
</P>
<P>
   Until several months ago, that advice seemed to be falling
mostly on deaf ears, with North Korea's leader, Kim Jong Il,
rebuffing numerous invitations to visit Beijing. In private,
Chinese officials often expressed frustration with Kim.
</P>
<P>
   But the momentum shifted dramatically this spring as North Korea
made overtures to a number of Western nations, establishing
diplomatic ties with Italy and Australia. And just weeks ago, Kim
made the long-awaited visit to China. It was his first official
trip abroad since he became his country's leader after his father's
death in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Kim spent three days in Beijing, meeting with Chinese leaders
and touring some of China's most successful high-tech enterprises.
He told Chinese officials that he was impressed with the country's
rapid economic development, commenting that he hardly recognized
Beijing from his last visit, 17 years earlier. He indicated that he
planned to follow the Chinese model.
</P>
<P>
   But the summit meeting this week, with the two Korean leaders
clearly getting along well together, was perhaps more successful
than the Chinese could have dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the Chinese government was happy because North
Korea has been in a very deep economic crisis, and this kind of
friendly dialogue may lead to more support from South Korea _ and
that puts less pressure on China,'' said Professor Zhang.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy experts added that the subtle Chinese diplomacy
that culminated in the summit might also have reset the
geopolitical balance in northeast Asia, diminishing the role of the
United States in particular. China had long feared, they said, that
a reunified Korea might be dominated by the South, an ally of the
United States for more than 50 years, and thus tied into the U.S.
defense structure, putting U.S. weapons directly on the Chinese
border. But that seems less likely now.
</P>
<P>
   By cultivating strong relationships with both North and South,
``China has brought both parties under their tutelage,'' said
Shambaugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have co-opted South Korea and maneuvered the U.S. pretty
much out of this chapter,'' he said. ``Seoul looks as much to
Beijing now for guidance as to the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   In officials statements, China _ whose stated policy is never to
meddle in the affairs of other countries _ took no credit for the
outcome. And in the many official accounts and commentaries in the
state media Thursday, enthusiasm was tempered by the awareness that
nothing on the divided peninsula is likely to be simple.
</P>
<P>
   The ``historic handshake'' created ``favorable conditions for
the peace and stability of the Korean peninsula and Northeast Asia,
as well as the peace and stability of the world at large,'' said an
article in Thursday's People's Daily, the official Communist Party
newspaper. ``The world welcomed the historic handshake of the
Korean nations. Of course there is still a lot to do afterward, and
the two sides should continue to make an effort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1921EDT &QL; 
