<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEARCH-FUNDING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE SIXTH IN FEDERAL R&AMP;D FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER WALSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fueled by medical and graduate reserch programs,
Massachussetts received the sixth-highest amount of federal
research and development funds in 1998, according to a study
released Thursday by the Rand Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachussetts, you have one of the premier medical
research units in the Boston/Cambridge area,'' said Donna Fossum,
senior policy analyst for the report.
</P>
<P>
   California topped the list, with more than $14 billion in
federal money for research and development,followed by Maryland,
Virginia, Georgia, and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Massachussetts was awarded $3.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   When research dollars are broken down by population, Washington,
D.C., ranks first with $5,139 per person, while Massachussetts
comes in fifth with $587 per person.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have are not only university- and college-based
graduate research programs, you have institutions that do nothing
but graduate work and medical research,'' Fossum said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the research and development money goes into
university programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The research and development portfolio encompasses the safety
of food to preserving wildlife to national security to going to the
moon,'' Fossum said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a migratory bird station in Maine is reflected in
the state's No. 46 ranking, while forestry research is a major
contributor to New Hampshire's No. 33 standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a state in this country that isn't playing a
critical role,'' Fossum said. ``It matters to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire has the only laboratory in the country for
researching theeffects of cold weather on the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's high north. Where else can you study this kind of
activity?'' Fossum asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
