<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-BIGDIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES $8.5B CAP ON BIG DIG FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Delivering a formal slap in the face to
Massachusetts' ``Big Dig'' and its hosts, the US Senate Thursday
voted to deny paying any more of the $8.5 billion in federal funds
approved for it until government and project leaders sign an
agreement promising never to ask for any more cash for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The voice vote was largely symbolic, because state and project
officials had already agreed to a cap of $8.549 billion in federal
assitance for the project, whose cost has spiraled from $2.6
billion in 1985 to $13.6 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   That deal will be cemented Friday, when Massachusetts Turnpike
Authority Chairman Andrew S. Natsios will hand-deliver to the US
Department of Transportation a signed document agreeing to the cap
and several other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, in fact, what the senator's amendment says, and what we
agreed to when we testified before the senator's committee,'' said
Turnpike Authority spokesman Joe Landolfi, referring to Senator
John McCain, a vociferous Big Dig critic and author of the measure
capping funds for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in no way going to impact the construction of the
project,'' Landolfi said.
</P>
<P>
   The formal language means it would be far more difficult to
squeeze more cash out of the federal government for the massive
highway remodeling project should the need and the political will
to do it surface.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts lawmakers don't expect to ask for more money for
the project, given the negative publicity associated with the cost
overruns. ``They know we can't go to the well again,'' said an aide
to Senator Edward M. Kennedy, Democrat of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The signed agreement also locks in the Turnpike Authority to the
$8.549 billion in federal aid, of which $5 billion has been spent.
But the McCain amendment, if it bacame law, would further hamstring
the state in requesting more help down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Turnpike Authority was hoping that the signed agreement
would dissuade McCain, a Republican from Arizona, from inserting
the language into the Senate Transportation Appropriations bill.
``It obviously, for some reason, did not,'' Landolfi said.
</P>
<P>
   But ``we can live with it,'' he added. ``We agree with the
cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Language similar to McCain's amendment is in the House version
of the transportation funding bill. But the language does not block
all the Big Dig money pending a signed agreement, said Karin
Walser, an aide to Representative J. Joseph Moakley, Democrat of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's going to become law, it will have to happen in
conference,'' when House and Senate negotiators work out a
compromise version of the bill, Walser said.
</P>
<P>
   The funding limit is part of a 12-point Project Partnership
Agreement Natsios will bring to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement includes a commitment by Big Dig officials that
the controverial project will not siphon money away from other
transportation needs in the state.
</P>
<P>
   That element also requires a separate agreement between the
state and 13 regional planning boards on funding for non-Big Dig
transportation projects. The last of these sub-agreements was
reached Thursday, said Luisa Paiewonsky, director of planning for
the Massachusetts Highway Department.
</P>
<P>
   The state also agrees in the Natsios document to submit detailed
financial updates to the Federal Highway Administration every six
months, and to provide extensive data and records to outside
monitoring agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to provide timely access to Big Dig records and
employees could result in a withdrawal of funding, under the
agreement being delivered Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios will also deliver an update on Big Dig's financial plan,
reporting that the cost overrun on the project is $1.84 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That number shows that the federal government was closer to the
truth. On Feb. 1, Big Dig officials acknowledged that they had $1.4
billion in cost overruns. A separate audit by the federal
government put the number at between $1.7 billion and $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Former Big Dig chief James J. Kerasiotes was fired earlier this
year over the finance debacle, and replaced by Natsios.
</P>
<P>
   McCain held hearings on the Big Dig project last month, lashing
out at Big Dig officials, private contractors, and government
authorities for their ``complete and utter failure'' in handling
the project's fiscal crisis. He warned then that the project could
end up costing as much as $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project has suffered from gross mismanagement and what
appears to have been a complete lack of critical federal oversight.
It has experienced billions of dollars in cost overruns,'' McCain
said in submitting his amendment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not my intention to stop the Boston project,'' McCain
said. ``The project should be completed as quickly and as fiscally
responsibly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain acknowledged that the officials involved had agreed to
the $8.549 billion cap in the hearings. But ``if it isn't in a
statute or in writing, then where is it?'' the senator asked. ``The
answer, of course, is that it doesn't currently exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts delegation was at a loss to explain why McCain
would insist on the amendment when the formal agreement was about
to be signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew this was in the works,'' said a staffer to a
Massachusetts lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator McCain's amendment is a non-issue,'' said Kyle
Sullivan, an aide to Senator John Kerry,
</P>
<P>
   McCain aide Pia Pialorsi seemed surprised when told of the odd
timing of the amendment and of Natsios's plan to deliver the signed
agreement. But ``it's just to put it in the law,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5125 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AFGHAN-MINES-ART-(TRI     06-15 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-MINES-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEGACY OF LAND MINES LEAVES DAILY REMINDERS OF DECADES OF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY BEARAK  (ART ADV: Photos NYT5-6 were sent June 12 to NYT
photo clients. A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANDAHAR, Afghanistan _ The tour through the minefield began
near one of the main roads, among the houses where the little
children were playing.
</P>
<P>
   Mohid Hashim, who leads a mine-clearing team, shouted at the
youngsters in Pashto, ``Hey, don't you know that red flag means
it's dangerous here?''
</P>
<P>
   The children scurried away, but as always they would meander
back. Housing is impossibly scarce here in war-devastated Kandahar,
the second-largest of this nation's cities. Several families have
taken shelter surrounded by the rubble of what is called Minefield
179, willing to risk the explosives buried in their new backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Afghanistan, one of the world's most enduring battlegrounds, is
also among its most booby-trapped landscapes. It has an estimated 5
million to 7 million of the deadly devices concealed in the rocky
soil _ about one for every three of the nation's people.
</P>
<P>
   But in a place where even a scrap of good news has become as
rare as a peaceful summer, there is some cause for thanks. A
mine-clearing operation, perhaps the largest in the world, has in
10 years managed to reduce the number of maiming explosions by
half. Each day now, only 10 to 12 people make a misstep that blows
them apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we are still scared of explosions, but I have eight
children, and a father cannot keep that many small ones from
running around,'' said Abdul Nabi, a poor laborer who has built a
home in the minefield from stony debris and cornstalks.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He had come out of his dark hovel into the fierce light. Two of
his youngsters had been traipsing among the piles of crushed brick,
chasing each other through a labyrinth of jagged half walls. About
15 yards from his door, a man in a hard white helmet was doing the
tedious work of ``de-mining,'' carefully probing and digging.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The father did not want to be harshly judged. This is
Afghanistan, he explained, and there have been 21 straight years of
war. Many of the ordinary rules of rational behavior have by
necessity been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged defensively. ``Where else is there for us to live?''
he said. ``As they started clearing the mines, people began moving
in. We have a good space here.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``de-miners'' work for a variety of international charities
under the auspices of the United Nations. There are 4,800 people
involved, split into teams throughout the country. In 10 years,
more than 1 million explosive devices have been safely exploded or
dismantled, said Richard D. Kelly, who manages the program.
</P>
<P>
   Minefield 179, about the size of a football field, is among the
last contaminated grounds within Kandahar itself. Excavation at the
site has been going for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 11 mines have been unearthed, as well as 80 ``UXOs,''
shorthand for ``unexploded ordinance'' that includes rockets, bombs
and grenades. Some 30,000 metal fragments have also been found.
Those objects further slow the monotonous work, since each one has
to be uncovered carefully to be sure that it is not deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Sattar is a merchant of some means, but even he decided to
accept the risks of living in the minefield. His family owned
property within No. 179. He rebuilt his house in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He answered a knock on his handsomely painted front door. ``Yes,
there is some danger, but it does not bother me,'' he said with
more nonchalance than bravado. ``The U.N. found a mine under the
corner of our house some time back, and the other day they found
another one about 20 yards from here. But soon all the mines will
be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his five children stood with him. Just a few feet away,
on the other side of a brick wall, one of the men in helmets was
busy ferreting through the unpredictable soil.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all up to Allah,'' Sattar said of the danger. ``You must
have faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Afghanistan is not alone in its land mine infestation,
though it is surely among the most afflicted. Estimating global
numbers is very difficult, but Angola, Cambodia, Iraq and Egypt
also finish near the top of most lists.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, large numbers are not as important as strategic
location: how many people live near the minefield, how much fertile
land is unusable.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet Union invaded Afghanistan in 1979, and driving it out
took a decade. The Soviet troops were orderly in configuring their
minefields, forming broad protective arcs around key roads, cities
and dams. The groups of Afghan mujahedeen, who battled each other
after defeating the Soviet army, were more haphazard with their
placements _ indeed often random.
</P>
<P>
   They all used the gamut of insidious devices. Fragmentation
mines leapt into the air, spraying a thousand steel splinters like
little daggers. Blast mines tore off limbs while propelling dirt,
gravel and bone fragments into the fresh wounds. Triggering
mechanisms were often disguised as a pen or a pack of a popular
brand of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 most countries in the world signed a treaty renouncing
use of antipersonnel mines, although those not signing included the
United States, China and Russia. President Clinton pledged to join
the majority by 2006, giving Washington time to develop
alternatives to what is considered an important defensive weapon.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Military observers say that a modest amount of mine installation
continues in Afghanistan as the Taliban, who control most of the
country, try to complete their conquest of a well-armed opposition.
But most devices in the ground are the afterlife of earlier
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of them ban-the-mines people,'' said Ross
Chamberlain, an Australian explosives expert who had joined the
walk through No. 179. ``If someone's coming to attack your house,
you've got a right to defend yourself any way you can. But do it
right. If you've put mines in, it's your job then to take them
out.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The men now taking them out in Afghanistan are local people,
hired at a starting salary of $100 a month. This is a top wage
these days, but the work is perilous, and there is no glamour to it
_ no cinematic images of a heavily perspiring man snipping colored
wires. The main danger comes from the boredom of sifting through
dirt.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, five de-miners have been killed in
Afghanistan. ``One was sheer stupidity,'' said Chamberlain. ``The
guy hit an anti-tank mine with a pick. Just a mess. It took 40
minutes to gather up the pieces, and they still haven't found his
helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The tour continued. Minefields 178 and 180 looked a lot like No.
179. Minefield 232 was at the edge of the city in an open field
with wheat planted nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The final stop was Kandahar's main hospital, back toward the
center of town. In some cities, finding the recent victim of a land
mine explosion might be catch as catch can, but the overcrowded
wards here almost always have someone newly mutilated.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, there were two, and the one who was awake was named
Abdul Khaliq. He was 14 and scrawny, lying in a corner bed near a
window.
</P>
<P>
   His left leg had been gone for two weeks. A bulky white bandage
covered the stump, and every now and then he rubbed it with his
fingers. His right leg and thighs and chest had also been hurt, but
the most striking thing about him was the stunned look in his eyes,
as if he was frozen in that instant he heard the blast and flipped
into the air.
</P>
<P>
   It had happened as he ran up a small hill outside of the city,
chasing friends over familiar ground. For years, they had crossed
that terrain. Nothing before had ever exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing,'' he said weakly. ``We were playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
