<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SENATE-BIGDIG-BOS &LR;      06-15 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-BIGDIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES $8.5B CAP ON BIG DIG FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Delivering a formal slap in the face to
Massachusetts' ``Big Dig'' and its hosts, the US Senate Thursday
voted to deny paying any more of the $8.5 billion in federal funds
approved for it until government and project leaders sign an
agreement promising never to ask for any more cash for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The voice vote was largely symbolic, because state and project
officials had already agreed to a cap of $8.549 billion in federal
assitance for the project, whose cost has spiraled from $2.6
billion in 1985 to $13.6 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   That deal will be cemented Friday, when Massachusetts Turnpike
Authority Chairman Andrew S. Natsios will hand-deliver to the US
Department of Transportation a signed document agreeing to the cap
and several other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, in fact, what the senator's amendment says, and what we
agreed to when we testified before the senator's committee,'' said
Turnpike Authority spokesman Joe Landolfi, referring to Senator
John McCain, a vociferous Big Dig critic and author of the measure
capping funds for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in no way going to impact the construction of the
project,'' Landolfi said.
</P>
<P>
   The formal language means it would be far more difficult to
squeeze more cash out of the federal government for the massive
highway remodeling project should the need and the political will
to do it surface.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts lawmakers don't expect to ask for more money for
the project, given the negative publicity associated with the cost
overruns. ``They know we can't go to the well again,'' said an aide
to Senator Edward M. Kennedy, Democrat of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The signed agreement also locks in the Turnpike Authority to the
$8.549 billion in federal aid, of which $5 billion has been spent.
But the McCain amendment, if it bacame law, would further hamstring
the state in requesting more help down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Turnpike Authority was hoping that the signed agreement
would dissuade McCain, a Republican from Arizona, from inserting
the language into the Senate Transportation Appropriations bill.
``It obviously, for some reason, did not,'' Landolfi said.
</P>
<P>
   But ``we can live with it,'' he added. ``We agree with the
cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Language similar to McCain's amendment is in the House version
of the transportation funding bill. But the language does not block
all the Big Dig money pending a signed agreement, said Karin
Walser, an aide to Representative J. Joseph Moakley, Democrat of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's going to become law, it will have to happen in
conference,'' when House and Senate negotiators work out a
compromise version of the bill, Walser said.
</P>
<P>
   The funding limit is part of a 12-point Project Partnership
Agreement Natsios will bring to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement includes a commitment by Big Dig officials that
the controverial project will not siphon money away from other
transportation needs in the state.
</P>
<P>
   That element also requires a separate agreement between the
state and 13 regional planning boards on funding for non-Big Dig
transportation projects. The last of these sub-agreements was
reached Thursday, said Luisa Paiewonsky, director of planning for
the Massachusetts Highway Department.
</P>
<P>
   The state also agrees in the Natsios document to submit detailed
financial updates to the Federal Highway Administration every six
months, and to provide extensive data and records to outside
monitoring agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to provide timely access to Big Dig records and
employees could result in a withdrawal of funding, under the
agreement being delivered Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios will also deliver an update on Big Dig's financial plan,
reporting that the cost overrun on the project is $1.84 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That number shows that the federal government was closer to the
truth. On Feb. 1, Big Dig officials acknowledged that they had $1.4
billion in cost overruns. A separate audit by the federal
government put the number at between $1.7 billion and $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Former Big Dig chief James J. Kerasiotes was fired earlier this
year over the finance debacle, and replaced by Natsios.
</P>
<P>
   McCain held hearings on the Big Dig project last month, lashing
out at Big Dig officials, private contractors, and government
authorities for their ``complete and utter failure'' in handling
the project's fiscal crisis. He warned then that the project could
end up costing as much as $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project has suffered from gross mismanagement and what
appears to have been a complete lack of critical federal oversight.
It has experienced billions of dollars in cost overruns,'' McCain
said in submitting his amendment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not my intention to stop the Boston project,'' McCain
said. ``The project should be completed as quickly and as fiscally
responsibly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain acknowledged that the officials involved had agreed to
the $8.549 billion cap in the hearings. But ``if it isn't in a
statute or in writing, then where is it?'' the senator asked. ``The
answer, of course, is that it doesn't currently exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts delegation was at a loss to explain why McCain
would insist on the amendment when the formal agreement was about
to be signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew this was in the works,'' said a staffer to a
Massachusetts lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator McCain's amendment is a non-issue,'' said Kyle
Sullivan, an aide to Senator John Kerry,
</P>
<P>
   McCain aide Pia Pialorsi seemed surprised when told of the odd
timing of the amendment and of Natsios's plan to deliver the signed
agreement. But ``it's just to put it in the law,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
