<HEADER>
A5129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BACKSTREET-LUPUS-NYTR     06-15 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKSTREET-LUPUS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKSTREET BOY PLANS LUPUS BENEFIT TO HONOR HIS SISTER'S MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL DEYOUNG   
 The Gainesville Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just because you're one of the biggest pop stars in the world,
with millions of dollars in the bank and millions of adolescent
fans hanging your picture on the wall, doesn't mean you're not a
human being with a loving family. Some things still hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Howie Dorough of the Backstreet Boys is living proof.
</P>
<P>
   Dorough's sister Caroline Cochran died almost two years ago of
complications from lupus, a disease that attacks the body's immune
system. ``She was 37 and the mother of two kids,'' Dorough, a
native of Orlando, Fla., said in a telephone interview. ``It's
something that's affected my family and our lives quite a bit,
seeing her go through this for 13 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorough, 26, who lives with his family in Orlando, has organized
a benefit concert June 25 at the Universal Citywalk complex in
Orlando. ``The Backstreet Boys do a lot of charity work,'' he said,
mentioning the Elton John AIDS Foundation and Sting's Rainforest
Foundation International. ``I started talking with my family: Why
don't we just set up our own foundation and hopefully raise
awareness?''
</P>
<P>
   Dorough's sister Angie Herring, who runs his fan club, is
organizing the benefit, which includes an auction, to raise money
for lupus research and education, and financial aid for patients
who cannot afford treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Dorough will perform ``Fly to Heaven,'' an original song about
Caroline Cochran, with another sister, Pollyanna. ``I've called a
lot of friends of mine in the industry, and sent out a lot of
invites, and we're hoping to get a lot of responses back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. McLean, another Backstreet Boy, will probably be there,
Dorough said. Confirmed performers include the Nelson twins,
Deborah Gibson and the actor Sherman Helmsley of ``The
Jeffersons,'' who's planning a stand-up comedy routine. Tickets for
the event, which will take place at the Groove nightclub, are $75
and $200.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities including Mariah Carey, Shania Twain and Shaquille
O'Neal have donated personal items for the auction, as have Donough
and his fellow band members.
</P>
<P>
   Recording of the third Backstreet Boys album begins in Los
Angeles next month; Dorough and his band mates have been
collaborating with writers including Dianne Warren and Babyface.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months, the Backstreet Boys' sales records have
been eclipsed by fellow teen-age pop acts 'N Sync and Britney
Spears.
</P>
<P>
   Dorough said the band isn't worried. ``We really try to
concentrate on just making good music for our fans and having the
respect of the industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try not to get too caught up at all in the sales and
everything. It's always thrown in our face, but there's enough out
there for everybody. And everybody has their time.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album should be out by Christmas. Meanwhile, Dorough has
a benefit to plan, and his sister's memory to honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never think it's going to take somebody out of your
life,'' he said. ``In the back of our minds, we thought it was just
one of these diseases that you could live with. Some people can
live with it for a long time, and some people it hits really
quickly, and all of a sudden they die.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
