u e BC-HITECH-ARTMUSEUM0616-     06-15 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITECH-ARTMUSEUM0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S(eeing more deeply into the art and history of South Africa
 &HT;    By Robert W. Gee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Curators at the Austin Museum of Art wanted to
create a virtual tour on the Web of their new exhibit, ``Liberated
Voices: Contemporary Art From South Africa,'' and some folks at
Dell Computer Corp. came up with a clever solution.
</P>
<P>
   Using Flash technology, the museum's Web site (www.amoa.org)
features images of two of the exhibit's works that, as the user
moves the mouse arrow around the images, project captions of
additional information about the art or about South African history
as it relates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's figuring out a way of communicating with people not just
in the traditional sense,'' said Ashley Blake, spokeswoman for
Dell.
</P>
<P>
   The museum calls the technology X-Ray Artvision, and plans to
expand it to future exhibitions. ``This is an educator's dream,''
said Katy Hernandez-Cowles, head of education at the museum.
``We're kind of expanding the education of this exhibit beyond the
gallery walls and beyond the county and state.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials are encouraging area school teachers to use the
Web site in the classroom as an introduction before coming in to
see the works in person.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, an underwriter of the exhibit, which is on display until
Aug. 13, also provided computers at the museum for visitors to
access the redesigned Web site, which includes links to South
African newspapers and the Museum for African Art in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is also facilitating e-mail dialogue between museum
patrons and some of the African artists.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
