<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5133 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MUSIC-NET16-COX     06-15 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-NET16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Artists, industry pros in town to discuss music, Net impact
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the kind of statistic that is keeping music industry
leaders awake at night: A survey out this week found that 38
percent of Internet users _ 35 million Americans _ have downloaded
music from the Internet, yet only 2 percent said they paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey of 2,503 Americans, by the Pew Internet &AMP;
American Life Project, has deepened fears of the Recording Industry
Association of America and such artists as Metallica and Dr. Dre,
who have criticized users of Napster and other software programs
designed to share music files online.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some artists _ notably struggling bands having a hard time
breaking through _ are cheering such findings, noting they point up
new ways that the Internet is changing not only how we listen to
music, but how musicians get the word out to potential fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another marketing tool,'' says Atlanta-based band manager
and promoter Wayne Briggs. ``Everyone loves to discover. That's one
thing that's really cool about the Internet _ you can go there and
discover something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Briggs is one of a handful of music industry experts who will
converge on Atlanta this weekend for the ChangeMusic Atlanta
conference and music festival.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is sponsored by CMJ, the publisher of CMJ New
Music Report, a weekly publication that provides airplay data and
new music news and reviews to radio programmers and music industry
professionals. It was first published in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day event, which opens today, is expected to draw more
than 600 artists and music industry professionals to explore the
impact and possibilities of new technology in the music business.
Thousands more will likely attend the musical performances taking
place in 18 venues across Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participants will be less well-known artists for whom
the Internet is proving to be an effective new way to get the word
out.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: El Pus, a hip-hop-infused Atlanta alternative
rock band managed by Briggs, whose Web site (www.elpus.com) has
helped generate local buzz about the band. Briggs reports that a
number of fans have come to shows after checking out the Web site
and hearing the tracks available there.
</P>
<P>
   Local musician Lee Cuthbert, who maintains the Web site for her
band, Gentle Readers (www.gentlereaders.com), has also discovered
that an online presence has several advantages. ``The biggest
benefit for us has been the dates page'' listing upcoming shows,
she says. ``We have a mailing list with a few hundred names on it,
but those folks sometimes trash their e-mail or lose their
postcard, but they can always find the latest show info.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites may have other advantages, Cuthbert says. They can be
fun, in a way that a public relations agency or record label might
not encourage. For instance, Cuthbert's comments on the band's
photos and the disclaimer at the bottom of the dates page _ ``all
Gentle Readers' shows are guaranteed to be spoken word, modern
dance and puppet-free'' _ liven up a visit to her band's site.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet presence alone isn't going to bring success. While
the Gentle Readers' site is a helpful tool, for instance, the band
doesn't always benefit monetarily. ``We don't sell much merchandise
off the Web,'' Cuthbert notes. ``Our label sells more than we do
electronically, but that has been the least utilized part of our
site.''
</P>
<P>
   CMJ founder and CEO Robert Haber adds that while the Internet is
proving to be yet another way for launching a band, ``there's
nothing that's ever going to replace a band touring, marketing and
promoting on the road. The Internet in and of itself will never
break a band.''
</P>
<P>
   The ChangeMusic festival, sponsored by Haber's company, is an
outgrowth of the CMJ Music Marathon _ an annual New York showcase
and music industry gathering, which celebrates its 20th anniversary
this fall. Organizers decided to expand the reach of the Music
Marathon this year by providing several regional events. Atlanta is
the first stop; S, to the $250 premium pass, which includes the
opening night party, performances and events. For daytime events
and panels, passes start at $95. For more info, see the CMJ Web
site (www.cmj.com) or call 1-877-633-7848.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
