<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-WEEKEND16-COX     06-15 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giving dads their due
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday is Father's Day, and the conventional TV wisdom is that
the medium's portrayal of dads is a classic case of reverse
evolution, from Ward Cleaver to Homer Simpson _ Father Knows Best
to Father Knows Squat.
</P>
<P>
   There's some truth in that, but there's more. Actually, TV's
portrayal of fathers today is richly diverse, from loving,
anxiety-riddled Andy Sipowicz (Dennis Franz) on ``NYPD Blue'' to
struggling , deeply flawed Jake Manning (Jeffrey Nordling) on
``Once and Again.'' Ray Barone (Ray Romano) on ``Everybody Loves
Raymond'' is a weak but caring dad, while Ken Titus (Stacy Keach)
on ``Titus'' is strong and uncaring.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Hal (Bryan Cranston), the 40-going-on-14 dad on
``Malcolm in the Middle.'' That's Hal of the hairiest back on the
planet, disco dude on roller skates, who can't quite decide whether
he's disciplinarian or enabler to his sons' antics.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's hilarious rerun (8:30 p.m. on Fox), Hal skips work,
gets the boys to bug out from school, and they all play hooky at a
stock car race. The final scene, with Hal returning home thinking
he's fooled wife Lois (Jane Kaczmarek), is priceless.
</P>
<P>
   Also of note for dads:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Story of Fathers and Sons'' (8 p.m. Saturday on ABC) _ A
rerun from last Father's Day, this special looks at the joys and
sorrows of fathers and sons, with testimony from Los Angeles Lakers
star Shaquille O'Neal, teen heartthrob Zachery Ty Bryan and actor
Edward James Olmos.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sporting Lawns'' (9 p.m. Sunday on HGTV) _ If you're a dad
whose theme song is ``I fought the lawn, and the lawn won,'' check
out this special that combines lawn care and sports. It looks at
groundskeepers and their equipment at baseball and football
stadiums and golf courses like Pebble Beach in California.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Man Show'' (10 p.m. Sunday on Comedy Central) _ This is
the second-season premiere of this sketch show for frat boys and
those who wish they still were _ wildly uneven, occasionally
hilarious and always politically incorrect and testosterone-addled.
Sunday, the boys go to a professional wrestling school and offer
the usual quotient of breast and flatulence jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Today
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Piano Grand!: A Smithsonian Celebration'' (8 p.m. on
WPBA/Channel 30) _ Billy Joel hosts this special noting the more or
less 300th anniversary of the invention of the piano.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The 2000 Alma Awards'' (9 p.m. on ABC) _ For these Latin
American entertainment awards, all eyes will be on Jennifer Lopez
and Christina Aguilera, who share entertainer of the year honors
(along with Ricky Martin). But also deserving of your attention is
the deliriously versatile Ian Gomez, who's honored for appearing on
three series simultaneously: ``The Drew Carey Show,'' ``Norm'' and
``Felicity,'' where his character, Javier, ended the season with a
gay wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Croc Week'' (8 p.m. on Animal Planet) _ Cable channel Animal
Planet's breakout star, Steve Irwin, is the focus of a week of
specials. Australian ``Crocodile Hunter'' Irwin, whose fearless
and/or insane approach to handling crocodiles and snakes in the
wild has been spoofed by ``Saturday Night Live'' and ``South
Park,'' is known for his catch phrases ``Crikey!'' and ``Holy
Smokes, that was close!'' First up tonight: ``Spitting Cobras'' at
8 and ``Crocodile Hunter's Wildest Home Videos'' at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Birds'' (8 p.m. Friday on American Movie Classics) _ AMC
kicks off a weekend of Alfred Hitchcock flicks with this 1963
classic about feathered fiends.
</P>
<P>
   Other Hitch highlights on AMC:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Notorious'' (2 p.m. Saturday) _ Several critics pointed out
similarities between the plot of ``Mission Impossible: 2'' and that
of this 1946 movie, in which Cary Grant sends his beloved, Ingrid
Bergman, off to seduce and betray the ex-Nazi (Claude Raines) he's
trying to capture. But Grant doesn't do many flying kicks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Vertigo'' (8 p.m. Saturday) _ Nothing is as it seems in what
many buffs consider Hitch's best: James Stewart tries to mold Kim
Novak into his lost love in what might be called ``Pygmalion'' in
hell.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Psycho'' (10:30 p.m. Saturday) _ It's impossible now to
re-create what audiences first felt in 1960 when Janet Leigh took
her famous shower.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rear Window'' (8 p.m. Sunday) _ Stewart again, in a
wheelchair, with Grace Kelly in the blonde role and a very scary
Raymond Burr as the heavy. Even heavier are the sexual subtexts of
Stewart's voyeurism and Kelly's frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
