<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MEAT-PLANT (Tar Heel, N.C.) _ The first thing you learn at
the Smithfield hog plant here is the value of a sharp knife. The
second thing you learn is that not everyone has to work with a
knife. Whites, blacks, American Indians and Mexicans, they all have
their separate stations, but it is blacks and Mexicans that are
left to battle over the dirty jobs at the factory, one of the only
places within a 50-mile radius in this muddy corner of North
Carolina where a person might make more than $8 an hour. While
Smithfield's profits nearly doubled over the past year, wages have
remained flat. So a lot of Americans have quit and a lot of
Mexicans have been hired to take their places. But the workers see
one another, more than management, as the problem, and they see the
competition in skin tones. By Charlie LeDuff.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT601-606.
</P>
<P>
   (Full and abridged versions have moved in ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead stories:
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT (Lincoln, Neb.) _ Pockets of extraordinary drought, by
some measures the worst in a century, have struck farms and homes
in parts of the South and the Plains. In Florida, alligators are
roaming out of lake and ponds that have all but disappeared. In
southeast Louisiana, rice crops and drinking wells are being ruined
by salt water that has seeped into the parched aquifer. In West
Texas, ranchers are selling off goats and sheep as the grasslands
dry up. In Georgia, the red soil is baked hard as concrete. By Jo
Thomas. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA (Seoul, South Korea) _ In a triumphant return home
from his summit meeting with North Korea, President Kim Dae Jung
tells jubilant South Koreans that ``a new day is beginning'' for
their divided nation. By Howard W. French. (The story has moved in
``i'' news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars inside: SKOREA-NKOREA-ASSESS, SKOREA-NKORA-REACT,
SKOREA-NKOREA-CHINA.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ADVISER (Washington) _ Arrayed behind George W. Bush as he
unveiled his nuclear policy initiative last month were two former
secretaries of state, two former national security advisers and a
former secretary of defense. But once Bush left the stage, the
foreign policy expert who fielded questions on the specifics of the
Texas governor's proposal was 45-year-old Condoleezza Rice, a black
college professor who is tutoring a presidential candidate who
concedes that he has much to learn about the world. By Elaine
Sciolino. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
2,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-MINES (Kandahar, Afghanistan) _ Afghanistan, one of the
world's most enduring battlegrounds, is also among its most
booby-trapped landscapes. It has an estimated 5 million to 7
million of the deadly devices concealed in the rocky soil _ about
one for every three of the nation's people. A mine-clearing
operation has in 10 years managed to reduce the number of maiming
explosions by half. Each day now, only 10 to 12 people make a
misstep that blows them apart. By Barry Bearak. (The story has
moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map and photos NYT5-6.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Russia President Vladimir Putin says
that Russian prosecutors have gone ``too far'' in arresting and
jailing the owner of Russia's largest independent media company
which had been critical of the government. ``I personally believe
that this is excessive,'' Putin said during his state visit to
Berlin. ``I think it should have been possible to handle this
without an arrest.'' Putin's remarks were the first time that he
has criticized the detention of Vladimir Gusinsky, the owner of
Russia's largest media company. By Michael R. Gordon. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMAKERS-EFFICIENCY (Undated) _ Productivity has improved
across the U.S. auto industry in recent years. While the Ford plant
in Atlanta ranked as No. 1, the biggest overall efficiency gains
last year took place at General Motors, which was once known for
inefficiency. By Keith Bradsher. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in
``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-JONES (Undated) _ Robert Trent Jones, the golf architect
who designed or remodeled more than 500 courses, and who once made
a hole in one to justify his redesign of a hole, died Wednesday
night at his home in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. He was 93. Jones, who
had been in poor health since having a stroke last summer, had
retired to Florida, but for most of his career he worked out of
offices in Montclair, N.J. By Dave Anderson. (Scheduled to move by
8 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
