<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5141 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-BOS &LR;      06-15 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALEY TAKES OVER FOR AILING COELHO AS GORE CAMPAIGN CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tony Coelho resigned as chairman of Al Gore's
presidential campaign Thursday, giving the vice president a welcome
opportunity to bring in Commerce Secretary William Daley to run his
fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise resignation of Coelho, who cited health reasons, is
the latest sign of turmoil at Gore campaign headquarters, which
made a ballyhooed move from Washington to Nashville after stumbling
last year, and will now be working under its third leadership team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if this is yet another effort of the Gore campaign to
reinvent itself,'' said Karen Hughes, communications director for
Republican candidate George W. Bush. ``Which Vice President Gore
will campaign next week?''
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic operatives were more sanguine about the sudden
turn of events, saying that Daley shared many of Coelho's
strengths, and few of the former chairman's weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Though Coelho is credited with reviving and honing the Gore
campaign operation after joining it in May 1999 _ so that it
soundly whipped challenger Bill Bradley in the Democratic primaries
_ he made enemies in the process and was forced by ethical
questions to maintain a low public profile.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Coelho has came under fire as the Gore campaign seemed
to lose some of the discipline and vigor with which it had
dispatched Bradley, and Bush climbed in the public opinion polls.
Foes sniped at Coelho for an imperious style, and there were
reports that he was tired and looking for a face-saving exit.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, an experienced political hand who Gore has long wanted to
bring into the campaign, was rumored to be Coelho's successor. No
action was taken, however, until Coelho checked into a hospital in
suburban Virginia this week for treatment of abdominal pain.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho said Thursday that an attack of diverticulitis, an
inflammation of the large intenstine, and a series of epileptic
episodes forced him to submit his resignation. ``My doctors have
told me that I need to slow down, eat better and travel less for a
period of time,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, none of this advice is
consistent with the rigors of chairing a presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho, 58, who has important ties to congressional Democrats
and party fund-raisers, will remain as an adviser to the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho's attorney, Stan Brand, said Thursday that a Justice
Department ethics investigation of Coelho's handling of funds when
he representing the United States in a 1998 trade fair in Lisbon
had ``nothing to do with his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation is where it was. It is ongoing. There has
been no change in status or circumstance,'' Brand said.
</P>
<P>
   As a Commerce secretary, longtime Democratic pol, and son of a
legendary Chicago mayor, Daley has his own extensive ties to the US
business, political and fund-raising communities. He shares
Coelho's decisive style and, not having to worry about ethical
questions, will be freer to represent the campaign on television.
</P>
<P>
   Daley ``has a very, very good political mind. Very good
instincts,'' a former associate said. ``He is a very good
strategist. Very decisive. Very confident. Very, very solid.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Gore who wooed the Commerce secretary, and Daley who
played hard to get, the associate said. ``It was definitely them
coming to him. If your last name is Daley, that is how you work.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had asked Daley to chair his campaign last year, but Daley
turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   Daley is the 51-year-old son of the late Chicago Mayor Richard
J. Daley and brother of the current mayor, Richard M. Daley. He is
a trusted adviser of President Clinton and played the lead role in
winning approval of the North American Free Trade Agreement in
1993; in hosting the 1996 Democratic National Convention in
Chicago; and in shepherding through legislation to normalize trade
relations with China this year.
</P>
<P>
   Daley has advised Gore that the path to victory lies in steady
hard work and progress, not dramatic flailing. ``Hit singles,'' he
has told the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the campaign is in very good shape. We have to
implement the game plan laid out,'' Daley said after flying in from
Washington to join Gore at a campaign stop in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are talking about some of the people in Democratic
circles who have established themselves as a sage, steady
strategist,'' said Charles A. Baker, a veteran Massachusetts
political operative with ties to the Gore campaign, ``on anyone's
list Bill Daley is on the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chairman will inherit from Coelho a smoother-running,
better-funded campaign whose message, fund-raising and targeting
operations are in the hands of veteran Democratic operatives like
Carter Eskew, Bob Shrum, Michael Whouley, Tad Devine, and Donna
Brazile.
</P>
<P>
   Though there may be additional personnel changes as Daley brings
on his own talent, no one in Nashville expects a purge. Longtime
Gore aides like Peter Knight and Roy Neel are expected to retain,
if not increase, their access to the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy coming in is a very good thing,'' said one top-ranking
campaign official. ``As he steps into Tony's shoes, the important
thing to remember is that we have built a campaign that is ready to
move into the fall at full speed. This was a very easy decision for
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican campaign operatives, however, said Daley's arrival
was a sign that Clinton White House and national Democratic
officials were increasingly worried about Gore's lackluster spring,
planning for the August convention, and their ability to beat Bush
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho's departure ``might indicate that a lot of people in the
administration are worried about the direction of the Gore
campaign,'' said Hughes. She said the Bush campaign, despite its
problems in the Republican primaries, has not faced any major staff
shake-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, visiting Boston Thursday, said Daley ``seems like a pretty
darn efficient fella,'' but that candidates make the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking at an appearance with Daley at a wholesale food
market in Cincinnati, said: ``Bill Daley has done an outstanding
job as commerce secretary; he has done an outstanding job in
everything he has done. I'm thrilled that he has agreed to take
over the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe staff reporter Anne E. Kornblut contributed to this report
from Boston. Wire service material was used in its preparation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
