<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     06-15 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `BIG MOMMA'S HOUSE,' starring Martin Lawrence. Directed by Raja
Gosnell (PG-13, 97 minutes). This fitfully amusing film, starring
the comic whirligig Lawrence, could best be described as
``Stakeout'' goes ghetto, with a touch of ``Tootsie'' for flava _
er, flavor. Lawrence plays Malcolm, an FBI agent with a penchant
for doing undercover work in full body makeup. Here he impersonates
Big Momma, a stubborn old Southern woman. Why? Big Momma's
granddaughter is on the run because her ex-boyfriend, Lester, a
murderous bank robber, has escaped from prison. Malcolm believes he
can use her to get to Lester. This isn't much of a movie; it looks
like a series of baseball card shots and may have the worst rhythms
ever in a film directed by a former editor (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `DINOSAUR,' with the voices of D.B. Sweeney, Alfre Woodard and
Ossie Davis. Directed by Ralph Zondag and Eric Leighton (PG, 90
minutes). Reputedly the most expensive animated feature ever made,
Disney's showcase of computer animation technology begins with a
breathtaking sequence, a visual and sonic extravaganza that the
rest of the movie never quite lives up to. The story, of a young
dinosaur raised by lemurs who must lead a herd of his fellow
reptiles to safety after an asteroid strikes the earth, is cobbled
together from other Disney plots. But the effects _ the dinosaurs'
movements and their nearly seamless insertion into real locations _
will impress skeptical grown-ups. More important, the film, in
spite of some potentially upsetting scenes of carnivorous mayhem,
will delight children and whet their desire for the inevitable
tie-in merchandise (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `FANTASIA/2000,' with James Levine and the Chicago Symphony
Orchestra. Various directors (G, 75 minutes). The millennial
version of Disney's 1940 groundbreaking fusion of animation and
classical music includes seven new segments and keeps one from the
original film (the wonderful ``Sorcerer's Apprentice,'' starring
Mickey Mouse). ``Fantasia/2000'' is more backward-looking than
futuristic. The two best segments are ``Rhapsody in Blue,'' a witty
Manhattan-in-the-Jazz-Age homage to the caricaturist Al Hirschfeld
set to the music of Gershwin, and the finale (set to Stravinsky's
``Firebird'' Suite), in which a cometlike sprite whooshes around
the globe explosively creating, destroying and renewing the
planet's life forms. Celebrity introductions lend the film the feel
of a deluxe corporate promotion. At the Sony Imax Theater, Broadway
at 68th Street (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `FREQUENCY,' starring Dennis Quaid and Jim Caviezel. Directed by
Gregory Hoblit (PG-13, 100 minutes). ``Back to the Future'' meets
``Field of Dreams'' meets ``It's a Wonderful Life'' meets ``The
Sixth Sense'' in this entertaining but shamelessly sentimental
supernatural soap opera with a macho heart. Caviezel is a morose
young policeman who contacts his dead father, a heroic firefighter,
on a ham radio and contrives to save him from the accident that
cost him his life. From here, the two collaborate on changing other
aspects of the past and on catching a serial killer. There are
enough testosterone tears to soak Shea Stadium (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `GLADIATOR,' starring Russell Crowe, Joaquin Phoenix, Connie
Nielsen, Richard Harris and Oliver Reed. Directed by Ridley Scott
(R, 150 minutes). This movie is the answer to a question no one
bothered to ask: what would happen if someone decided to film the
imminent extreme football league as if it were a Chanel commercial?
Scott subjects action-packed bouts of mayhem and decapitation in
the Roman Colosseum to his glossy, inhuman directing style; it is
admirable but repellent. As the noble Roman general who ends up
fighting for his life, Crowe gives a performance with ball-of-fire
intensity, suffused with a movie star's impatience. He holds the
movie together, such as it is (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `GONE IN 60 SECONDS,' starring Nicolas Cage, Giovanni Ribisi,
Angelina Jolie, Robert Duvall and Christopher Eccelston. Directed
by Dominic Sena (PG-13, 119 minutes). A remake of a movie so
insubstantial that its title seems to refer the length of time it
would linger in a viewer's memory. Cage, who has gone prematurely
blond, is the world's best car thief. He is dragged out of his
apparently lucrative go-cart business and returns to auto theft to
save the life of his brother (Giovanni Ribisi). With a magnetic
cast of crooks and cops, it's mindless hot-rodding entertainment, a
film so glossy and impersonal that you will sympathize more with
the cars than the people (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   `HAMLET,' starring Ethan Hawke and Liev Schreiber. Directed by
Michael Almereyda (R, 112 minutes). Almereyda has rooted his
voluptuous and rewarding new adaptation of Shakespeare's play in
today's Manhattan. The city's contradictions of beauty and squalor
give the movie a sense of place, and New York becomes a complex
character in this vital and sharply intelligent film. Often shaded
in lush, soothing hues of blue, ``Hamlet'' exudes an intoxicating
masochism in which half the cast is battling despondency and the
other half has the glint of imminent insanity. Here the melancholy
of Hamlet (Hawke) over the death of his father is almost a state of
grace: It gives him a sense of purpose that the other characters
lack. The director's rigorous trimming has a boldness and vivacity
that make this version exhilarating while leaving Shakespeare's
language and intent intact (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `HIGH FIDELITY,' starring John Cusack, Jill Peterson, Iben
Hjejle and Joan Cusack. Directed by Stephen Frears (R, 107
minutes). Although its setting has been moved from London to
Chicago, the screen adaptation of Nick Hornby's best-selling 1995
novel is wonderfully true to the spirit of the book. Cusack has one
of his juiciest roles in Rob, a 30-something record store manager
and vinyl fanatic sorting through the ``Top 5'' breakups in his
disastrous romantic history while trying to salvage his latest
relationship. The movie hilariously captures the mind-set of
not-so-young men for whom pop music is a kind of religion and hip
musical taste an ultimate measure of a person's worth (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `LOVE'S LABOUR'S LOST,' starring Kenneth Branagh, Nathan Lane,
Matthew Lillard, Alessandro Nivola and Alicia Silverstone. Directed
by Branagh (PG, 95 minutes). Branagh has decided, for no particular
reason, to festoon an early Shakespeare comedy with classic show
tunes and classic Technicolor movie-musical cinematography. His
cast consists mainly of attractive young movie actors, most of whom
are not terribly adept at singing, dancing or reciting Shakespeare.
But the stumbling amateurism is not without charm. Branagh throws
it all together with the gusto of a man playing a tuba with a bass
drum strapped to his back while his pet monkey leaps around with a
squeeze box. It's not art exactly, or even music, but it's
occasionally entertaining, albeit in an annoying kind of way
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `M:I-2,' starring Tom Cruise, Thandie Newton and Anthony
Hopkins. Directed by John Woo (PG-13, 120 minutes). Cruise returns
as the daredevil secret agent Ethan Hunt in Woo's loud, flashy,
incoherent new blockbuster. The film is jampacked with movie
references _ to Hitchcock, to the first ``Mission: Impossible''
movie and to Woo's earlier, and superior, Hong Kong action films _
but it's at once overheated and flat. The plot, involving killer
viruses, is baffling rather than twisty. The introduction of a love
interest ( Newton) who also happens to be the bad guy's
ex-girlfriend adds an element of melodrama that's more grating than
affecting. Some good car chases and explosions, though (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `SHANGHAI NOON,' starring Jackie Chan and Owen Wilson. Directed
by Tom Dey (PG-13, 110 minutes). Chan is one of the great physical
comedians, and this martial arts western spoof is a high-spirited,
marvelously silly showcase for his talents. Chan plays Chon Wang,
an Imperial Guard dispatched from Beijing to the Old West to rescue
a princess played by Lucy Liu. But the heart of the movie is the
interplay between Chan and Wilson, who depicts his inept outlaw
sidekick with goofy, spacey charm. After the glum bullying of
``Gladiator'' and the noisy bombast of ``M:I-2,'' it's refreshing
to see a movie so good-natured, so confident in its ability to
provoke not queasy awe or numb exhaustion, but pure delight
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `SMALL TIME CROOKS,' starring Woody Allen and Tracey Ullman.
Directed and written by Allen (PG, 95 minutes). The sweet, funny
wisp of a movie starts out as a parody of ``Big Deal on Madonna
Street,'' then turns into a child's-eye ``Bonfire of the Vanities''
before returning to its original mode as a caper comedy. Allen and
Ullman are Ray and Frenchy Winkler, an inept thief and ex-con and
his upwardly mobile wife, whose cookie business takes off and
allows her to indulge her dream of being a Park Avenue hostess. If
the movie suffers severely from attention deficit disorder, the
jokes are funny (but mild) and the screwball comic tone is
impeccably sustained. Ullman (putting on her Fern Rosenthal voice)
and Elaine May (as Frenchy's dimwitted cousin) are delightfully
goofy (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `SUNSHINE,' starring Ralph Fiennes, Rachel Weisz, Jennifer Ehle,
Rosemary Harris and James Frian. Directed by Istvan Szabo (R, 180
minutes). In Szabo's tale of 20th-century Hungarian history,
Fiennes plays three members of a wealthy Jewish Budapest family _
grandfather, father and son _ who endure the corruption of the
Austro-Hungarian empire, the viciousness of fascism and the
brutality of Communism. Fiennes' performances, and those of Ehle
and Harris (playing the same character at different stages of life)
help save the film from melodramatic excess. Even though much of
the story is crudely told, ``Sunshine'' is nonetheless a serious,
humane and thought-provoking attempt to make sense of complicated
and painful historical experiences (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `U-571,' starring Matthew McConaughey, Bill Paxton, Jon Bon
Jovi, David Keith and Harvey Keitel. Directed by Jonathan Mostow
(PG-13, 120 minutes). Mostow, whose previous film, ``Breakdown,''
was a marvel of B-picture minimalism, shifts from the wide-open
spaces to the cramped interior of a World War II submarine movie.
McConaughey, whose knotted-with-unease face makes it look as if he
were cramming for finals, is part of a secret mission to capture a
Nazi code-encryption machine and get it back to the Allies. He and
his crew have to do so on a Nazi U-boat they have hijacked. Mostow
does a fine job of building tension, given that he is working in a
minor genre whose climactic notes you will know if you have ever
seen a movie set on a sub (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `THE VIRGIN SUICIDES,' starring Kirsten Dunst, James Woods and
Kathleen Turner. Directed by Sofia Coppola (R, 97 minutes).
Coppola's directorial debut, adapted from Jeffrey Eugenides' 1993
novel about the self-destruction of five sisters in a 1970s
Michigan suburb, shows her to be a filmmaker with fine visual and
emotional instincts, adept at matching the book's hypnotic, sensual
black humor. The movie's best moments have an inspired feeling of
playfulness and freedom matched by Dunst's smart, beguiling
performance as Lux Lisbon, whose sexual awakening propels her and
her sisters to their doom. But despite Coppola's keen instincts,
and the beautifully understated acting of Woods and Turner as the
Lisbon parents, ``The Virgin Suicides'' is marred by the
self-conscious aestheticism and emotional detachment of its source
(Scott).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
