<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREANS VIEW PACT WITH JOY, RELIEF AND CAUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sidebar with SKOREA-NKOREA) 
 By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ From farmers tilling rice paddies to
workers in neckties walking busily through high-rise office
buildings, South Koreans were both elated and relieved _ and a bit
wary _ Thursday as their president brought back promises of peace
and reconciliation from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week, I saw things happen that I never imagined would
take place,'' said Kim Bok-young, 50, who runs his own business
selling children's clothes, as he waited for a cab in downtown
Seoul. ``In our hearts, I think we have already achieved
reunification.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing that sentiment was Jang Young-joo, a 47-year-old
government worker who was holding a South Korean flag in front of
City Hall in a crowd of hundreds trying to catch a glimpse of
President Kim Dae-jung's motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the negative feelings are gone, and now I want
reunification as soon as possible,'' Jang said. ``We're brothers
and sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   For the younger generation of South Koreans, recent images of
North Koreans broadcast on televisions across the nation were
enough to dispel negative stereotypes ingrained since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, I was taught that North Koreans were
strange,'' said Kim Jung-joon, a 22-year-old medical student, as he
sat in a Starbucks coffee shop in Seoul, preparing for final exams.
``But after seeing them on TV, they weren't as weird as I
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a nation with old memories of the Korean War and fresh
scars of a devastating economic crisis, the prospect of ties with
North Korea seemed both daunting and outright scary.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling out weeds from her rice paddy in Pyongtaek, a city some
40 miles south of Seoul, Kim Ok &UR; - &LR; su, 75, let out a deep breath
when asked how she felt about the possibility of reunification or
expanded exchanges with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know much, but I think there will be many difficulties
after reunification, and lots of money we'd have to spend,'' Kim
said shyly, as she wiped away sweat from her forehead. ``My
youngest boy lost his job after the IMF,'' she added, alluding to
the economic crisis that broke out in late 1997, causing South
Korea to turn to the International Monetary Fund for emergency
loans. ``He still hasn't found a job.''
</P>
<P>
   The discussion about North Korea led Kim to reminisce about the
Korean War, which started 50 years ago. The memories may have
become hazy, but judging from her expression, they are still
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commies came to our village with guns and took our food
and wouldn't even let us leave our lights on at night,'' she said.
``They killed a lot of people here. Just thinking about commies
makes me shudder.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopping for a cold drink and a cigarette at a grocery store
less than a mile away from Kim's rice paddy, Song Yoon-sup, a
36-year-old truck driver, said he felt awkward and worried because
of the enormous changes that took place over the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until just recently, we were cursing North Korea and vowing to
defeat them,'' Song said. ``And all of a sudden, we're calling Kim
Jong Il `chairman,''' a reference to the North Korean leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does all of the change mean that two of our countrymen would
have to feed one North Korean,'' he wondered, ``or does it mean
increasing their productivity by transforming them to become
capitalists?''
</P>
<P>
   Such harsh realists were not difficult to find back in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Keun-hong, a business consultant wearing a pressed linen
suit and a smart hairdo, was in no hurry to see North and South
Korea unite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope reunification does not happen until 15 to 20 years
later, and even then, I hope only a partial reunion would happen,''
said Kim, 29. ``I am still suspicious of their theatrics, and the
financial costs would be hard to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   But many ordinary South Koreans clearly felt that the first step
had been taken on the path toward a brighter future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we were able to open our hearts and talk with
each other is incredible,'' said Kim Bok Young, the owner of the
children's clothing company. ``Now it's time to tackle the
objectives one at a time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
