<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-ART-     06-15 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIA AND ERITREA MOVE TOWARD TRUCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Fighting between Ethiopian and Eritrean
soldiers paused Thursday as ministers from both nations prepared to
sign a preliminary cease-fire on Sunday that would involve yet
another role for United Nations peacekeepers in a conflict in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the two-year war _ which has cost tens of thousands of
lives _ seems decisively closer to an end. Thursday top ministers
from each nation were preparing to travel back to Algeria to sign
the document brokered there by the Organization for African Unity
over the last two weeks. On Wednesday night, a final hurdle was
cleared when Ethiopia accepted the plan, which Eritrea approved
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Outside officials said they were cautiously optimistic that this
was the first concrete step toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than a simple `OK, we will not shoot,''' said a
senior administration official in the United States, which was
deeply involved in negotiating the deal. ``It's a very solid
foundation to deal with remaining issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that in signing this they are
committing to resolving these issues politically and peacefully and
not through the barrel of a gun,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for an immediate cease-fire and the creation of a
15-mile buffer zone, outside the range of most artillery fire, to
be patrolled by U.N. peacekeepers. That buffer zone would be
entirely in Eritrean territory, reflecting the gains Ethiopia won
on the ground in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said the signing would be only the first step
toward a resolution of the conflict. The heart of the final deal is
an independent commission to establish the border between the two
nations officially, a complicated process involving century-old
colonial treaties that are far from clear. Disagreement over who
owned what, in fact, set off the war in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a question of what will happen in the next weeks
or months, in the time between the signing and the arrival of the
first peacekeepers. Ethiopian forces will remain on Eritrean
territory until then _ and for two weeks afterward _ and no one
rules out further skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from both sides, however, said Thursday that they
would respect the cease-fire and that they would now turn their
attention to the demarcation of their 620-mile border. The issue
may be particularly important to Eritrea because Ethiopian troops
have not only pushed it out of the disputed areas but now occupy
land that unquestionably belongs to Eritrea.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Territorial gains mean nothing,'' said Yemane Ghebremeskel, a
spokesman for the Eritrean president, Isaias Afwerki.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopian officials, denying that their losses were huge, cast
the war as a protection of their sovereignty, which they say
Eritrea violated by moving troops into several areas along the
border it claimed as its own in May 1998. Selome Taddesse, a
spokeswoman for Ethiopia's prime minister, Meles Zenawi, said she
believed it would be proved that the territory belonged to
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident we have nothing to lose,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war began, Ethiopia and Eritrea had been allies, with
growing economies and a close friendship with many Western nations,
the United States chief among them. In 1993, Eritrea, for a
generation the northernmost province of Ethiopia, won its
independence, though the new border between them was never
officially marked off.
</P>
<P>
   A series of border skirmishes escalated quickly into full-scale
warfare, with long lines of trenches, tanks, artillery bombardments
and air raids. In the process two nations considered to be the most
stable on the Horn of Africa _ in the same region as Sudan and
Somalia, in a near-constant state of war _ were also thrown into
disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from both nations, as well as Western countries
looking to restore that stability, say they hope they can begin to
concentrate again on developing their now-demolished economies.
</P>
<P>
   One major issue outstanding is exactly what role the United
Nations will play and when. A U.N. spokeswoman, Marie Okabe, said a
three-member planning team was expected to go Algeria this weekend
to begin preparations for the deployment of peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, the Security Council has not decided whether to
actually send them. So there are no estimates of when they could
go, from which countries and in what numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement comes at an awkward time for U.N. peacekeeping
operations in Africa, only weeks after dozens of peacekeepers were
kidnapped in Sierra Leone. That debacle has cast doubt on a planned
operation for Congo, in which 5,537 peacekeepers and observers have
been approved to shore up a shaky peace deal among six nations
fighting there.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials said, however, that the peacekeeping operation
in Ethiopia and Eritrea would be far more straightforward:
peacekeepers could be deployed along a clearly established front
line between opposing armies that have largely fought by the
generally accepted rules of war. There are none of the irregular
forces or renegade rebel troops that can make peacekeeping
operations far more complicated, uncertain and treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very different operation,'' the U.S. official said.
``But obviously the parties are going to have to live up their
agreement. And there is no justifiable reason for guns to be fired
once this agreement is signed.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the vague language of the preliminary peace agreement,
there are already differing interpretations in how each side views
the peacekeepers' role. Taddesse said the peacekeepers must be
confined to the buffer zone in Eritrea. Ghebremeskel, the Eritrean
spokesman, said he understood that peacekeepers were to patrol both
sides of the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
