<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING INCIDENT DELAYS U.N. VERIFICATION OF ISRAELI EXIT FROM
LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United Nations is hoping to finish up the
job of verifying that Israel has withdrawn from southern Lebanon,
but its work was frustrated Thursday when Israeli soldiers fired
shots near a U.N. team visiting one of the last remaining unchecked
border sites.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli authorities expressed regret over the incident, which
forced the postponement of an expected announcement here that the
border verification was complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it was a stupid mistake and let's get on with the
verification tomorrow,'' said a U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard. He
and other officials expressed confidence that the tortuous task
could be completed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Four shots were fired into the air and a fifth into the ground,
just yards from the deputy commander of the U.N. peacekeeping
contingent in southern Lebanon. The shots forced the inspection
team, consisting of U.N. and Lebanese military officials, to
retreat from the immediate area.
</P>
<P>
   Confirmation that Israel has left southern Lebanon would allow
the United Nations to start deploying its own peacekeepers on the
border and give the signal for the Lebanese government to reassert
its authority in southern Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
