<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5160 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-15 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: House of Clinton a House Divided? 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Friends of  &UR; Bill &LR;  and  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR;  told U.S. News &AMP; World
Report that if the Mrs. is elected to the Senate, Socks the cat
will live with her in Washington, and Buddy the dog will stay with
Bill Clinton at his museum and library in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave the New York house empty during the week, but
presumably all animals and adults would weekend in the new love
nest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Celine Dion &LR; , who is pregnant, provides all the medical
details of her in-vitro fertilization in People magazine, which
reports that 18 eggs were harvested; that three, fertilized, were
transferred to her uterus; and that she weighs 115 pounds and wears
a size 2 dress. ``I share my whole life with the audience,'' says
Dion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FOR POP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sourcebooks Inc. has sent word of what it calls ``the
quintessential Father's Day gift,'' a book called ``We Interrupt
This Broadcast: The Events That Stopped Our Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest edition of the book and CD compilation includes ``the
unprecedented media coverage of President Clinton's impeachment;
the horrifying audio clips of the Columbine High School tragedy;
the sudden death of  &UR; John F. Kennedy Jr. &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   And have a wonderful day with Dad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HARDBALL FROM TALK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Boss, the menswear company whose clothes are worn in the
new Miramax movie ``Hamlet,'' was all set to throw a
half-million-dollar party with Miramax to celebrate the movie's
opening when Talk magazine, the publishing arm of the studio
stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Boss President  &UR; Marty Staff &LR;  told the menswear journal DNR that
Talk objected to the party unless Boss launched an ad campaign in
Talk magazine. ``As far as I know,'' said Staff, ``that's
unethical. A half-million-dollar party became a $15,000 dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk publisher  &UR; Ron Galotti &LR;  said the decision to put the kibosh
on the party was made by Miramax. ``Good for us. . . . Marty should
have advertised in Talk. Then he could have had his premiere party.
Fair is for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I was at an awards ceremony with Jon Voight, whose stunning &LR; 
 &UR; daughter Angelina Jolie I've known since she was an infant. I &LR; 
 &UR; snuck up, grabbed her, turned to Jon and said, `Is this your &LR; 
 &UR; nightmare?' and he went pale and muttered, `Oh my God, yes.' '' &LR;
</P>
