<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ADVANCES APPEALS COURT FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: ``findings'' in 9th graf is cq) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Continuing the battle of the briefs, Microsoft told
the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit on
Thursday that it should ignore a government brief asking it not to
begin work on the company's antitrust appeal until the Supreme
Court decides whether to take it.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, the 19 state attorneys general who are
their partners, and the trial judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson, are
all working to move Microsoft's appeal directly to the Supreme
Court, under an obscure law known as the Expediting Act. But the
company wants its case heard first by the Court of Appeals, which
ruled in its favor in a previous case.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-page brief filed Thursday afternoon in response to a
government filing on Wednesday, Microsoft raised a potentially
important argument: it asserted that the states are not covered by
the Expediting Act, which allows direct appeal of significant
antitrust cases ``in which the United States is the complainant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and the states dispute that
interpretation, but all parties acknowledge that they are debating
an unsettled area of the law with no direct precedents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a court ruling in Microsoft's favor on this point would
damage the direct-appeal effort, probably ensuring that the appeals
of the federal and state cases against Microsoft would be heard by
the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   That court has shown that it is eager to take the appeal, and
analysts say they believe that Microsoft's chances would be better
there.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department declined to respond to Microsoft's brief
Thursday, though it remains possible _ even likely, given the legal
maneuvers of the last week _ that the department will file its own
brief on the subject later.
</P>
<P>
   But the department already addressed the issue of the Expediting
Act at length in a brief filed with Jackson on Tuesday. In that
brief, and in Microsoft's offering Thursday, both sides extracted
isolated moments or statements from the long antitrust trial to
support the view that the two cases should or should not remain
joined for appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The state and federal cases were researched and prepared
separately but filed jointly and consolidated for trial. The brief
filed by the Justice Department on Tuesday noted that at the start
of the antitrust trial, Microsoft ``called consolidation
`unquestionably appropriate' because of `the same factual and legal
theories' that `go to the very heart' of both suits.''
</P>
<P>
   It added that Jackson ``entered a single findings of fact, a
single set of conclusions of law and a single final judgment in the
case.'' Jackson ordered a breakup of Microsoft and restrictions on
its conduct last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's brief notes that the states asked for the right
to conduct separate cross-examinations during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear which court will settle the debate. But the
Court of Appeals may already have its own opinion. When the judges
decided on Tuesday that the full court, not the usual three-judge
panel, would hear the case, they issued two separate orders, one
for the Justice Department and the other for the states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
