<HEADER>
A5166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MURDOCH-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      06-15 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH'S NEWS CORP. BRANCHING OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAUL HANSELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. been left behind in the digital
age?
</P>
<P>
   After an early and expensive Web fiasco, the company, which owns
Fox television, Twentieth Century Fox, HarperCollins and a
worldwide collection of other media assets, has kept a low profile
on the Internet. Murdoch has publicly criticized the pending sale
of Time Warner to America Online and has said that Internet
companies are valued far too highly for News Corp. to consider a
similar merger.
</P>
<P>
   But since the AOL-Time Warner linkup, Murdoch has been working
feverishly to put in place a huge media-technology deal of his own
that will answer questions about his digital strategy.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Friday, News Corp. will file with the Securities and
Exchange Commission to sell shares in a new company holding all the
interests in satellite television that it has been building up over
the last decade _ including the vast Star system in Asia, BSkyB in
Britain, and stakes in other systems in Europe and Latin America
that collectively reach 100 million homes in 60 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect the new company, which will use some variation
of the Sky name, to be valued at more than $40 billion, almost as
much as the parent company. With the company expected to raise
perhaps $5 billion, it will be the largest media offering in
history.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly the sort of financial engineering that has been
the hallmark of the News Corp. But what does satellite television
have to do with the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Everything, in the News Corp.'s view. As Internet connections
become faster, people will gravitate to video content rather than
just words and pictures, it figures. More important, now that cable
and satellite systems are moving to digital transmission, the
channel-changing box is turning into a specialized computer that
can deliver interactive information games and shopping over the
television screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average household spends seven hours in front of the
television,'' said Peter Chernin, the president of News Corp.
``Imagine what we can do if we change the relationship from one way
to two way.'' (Murdoch, the 68-year-old chairman, declined to be
interviewed, citing his treatment for prostate cancer.)
</P>
<P>
   The set-top box could also become the hub of a network linking
other household devices from telephones to power meters, especially
for homes without a computer. By creating Sky and using the money
from the offering to deploy those boxes rapidly around the world,
News Corp. hopes to head off other competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for many homes outside the United States, that box may
be the only computer in a household and could be the hub that links
to other household devices, from telephones to electric meters,
each of which could generate fees for the box's owner. So News
Corp. has realized that its television business can be transformed
into something that is as much a technology network, if it moves
fast enough. It is talking about bringing in a technology company,
like Microsoft or a wireless telephone player, as a major investor
in Sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving from a television world to a multimedia world in
which we can create an array of content services and applications,
for satellite, wireless and other platforms,'' said Chase Carey,
the co-chief operating officer of News Corp., who become president
and chief executive of Sky, based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another motive for the creation of Sky, one that
has little to do with new technology and everything to with the
panic of television programmers during the two days last month when
Time Warner pulled Disney's ABC off its cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a world moving to five, six seven major media companies,
you don't want to be in a position where you have to count on
others,'' said Chernin, ``You need to have enough marketplace
dominance that people are forced to deal with you.''
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. itself had to enlist the help of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani to get Time Warner Cable to carry the Fox News Channel in
New York. While News Corp. does not have any cable or satellite
distribution of its own in the United States, it hopes that Sky's
dominance of television distribution outside of the United States
will give it increased bargaining clout with the media companies
here.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not to say that News Corp. plans to keep Sky out of
the United States. It has tried and failed several times to build
or buy a satellite broadcasting system here.
</P>
<P>
   If Sky's shares are valued as high as the company hopes,
analysts say it will try to use that stock to buy EchoStar
Communications Corp. or DirecTV, the most valuable asset in General
Motors' Hughes Communications unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``By setting up a financial vehicle for its satellite assets,
News Corp. will have a means of using a high-multiple currency to
make acquisitions, and GM Hughes is a natural target,'' said Ed
Hatch, a media analyst at SG Cowen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there was speculation a few months ago that Murdoch was
considering a bid for General Motors solely to get at DirecTV. The
car business, presumably, he would jettison as an unneeded
byproduct.
</P>
<P>
   Chernin declined to comment on the GM talk but he hardly
disclaimed interest in DirecTV. News Corp., he said, has long
believed that owning content like programming and distribution like
satellite systems is equally important.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are great arguments and debates about whether content is
king or distribution is king,'' Chernin said. ``At the end of the
day, scale is king. If you can spread your costs over a large base,
you can outbid your competitors for programming and other assets
you want to buy.'' (In England, this week, News Corp. exercised the
power of its scale, when BSkyB won the rights to the top soccer
league, bidding 1.1 billion pounds.)
</P>
<P>
   But Chernin said Sky would have a strong business even without a
satellite company here. It will have a toehold in interactive
television in the United States through its 20 percent stake in the
soon-to-be-merged TV Guide Gemstar. TV Guide magazine still has 10
million subscribers, but the company is now focused on producing
electronic program guides used on set top boxes to select from the
hundreds of available channels.
</P>
<P>
   Even outside the United States, News Corp. will face a
considerable challenge tying together its holdings. The only part
of the Sky empire it owns outright is Star in Asia. The rest are a
collection of partnerships, but Carey insists that in most
countries News Corp. has effective management control, despite the
ownership stakes of local partners.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MURDOCH-INTERNET-2NDT     06-15 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH-INTERNET-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: partners.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meanwhile, News Corp. has been negotiating, so far
unsuccessfully, to bring more partners into Sky in other regions.
Jean-Marie Messier, the chief executive of Vivendi, has publicly
expressed interest in linking its 49 percent of Canal Plus,
Europe's largest pay television service, to Sky. But that was
before he began negotiating to buy Seagram and its Universal movie
and music studios. Carey said that News Corp. is not in discussions
with Vivendi.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what is to say that people in any country will want to shop
or read information on a television screen, given the disappointing
results of earlier trials?
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. has been emboldened by the experience of BSkyB, which
made a pre-emptive move to convert its system from analog to
digital signals starting in 1998. By giving away set-top boxes
worth $200, the company converted 3.4 million of its 4.2 million
subscribers to the digital system.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to more channels, BSkyB offers an interactive
television service called Open, with the usual crop of information
pages on news, weather and sports. But use has been far higher than
other such services. Half of the customers use it at least once a
week.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. is hardly alone in betting on the future of media
convergence. America Online is about to introduce its own AOL TV
set-top box. Microsoft has gussied up its WebTV product. In Europe,
moreover, companies are lining up to pay as much as $5 billion for
licenses to offer the next generation of wireless telephone service
called 3G, which is also capable of delivering high-speed data
services.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. has not bid for wireless licensees. But it figures
that Sky's position straddling media and technology will let it cut
deals to merge wireless services with its Sky offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies just bid a lot of money for 3G licenses so
they can compete with four other companies that offer the same
thing,'' Carey said. ``They are going to need to differentiate
their cell phone services and clearly we can bring our brands, our
content and the services we are developing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
