<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SKOREA-NKOREA-ASSESS-     06-15 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-NKOREA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THOUGH HOPEFUL, U.S. OBSERVERS PUZZLED BY NORTH KOREA'S
MOTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SKOREA-NKOREA) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The agreement signed at the summit in Pyongyang on
Wednesday, just days shy of the 50th anniversary of the start of
the Korean War, was brimming with words that heralded the arrival
of peace. Yet the two countries are still technically at war, and
no one wants to raise the question of who would govern a unified
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's prime minister likened the breakthrough to the fall of
the Berlin Wall, yet the DMZ, or demilitarized zone dividing the
two Koreas, remains firmly in place, an ugly barbed-wire scar
running across the Korean Peninsula. There is no popular uprising
against the communist government in the North, and no serious
discussion of removing the hundreds of thousands of troops and a
terrifying concentration of weaponry that line both sides of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, U.S. officials trying Thursday to puzzle their way
through North Korea's apparent, or at least public, change of
attitude said they saw the first real glimmer of hope that one of
the last remnants of the Cold War could gradually erode, and that
North Korea might soon be regarded less as a rogue state and more
like just another failed state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly what's going on is hard to read,'' said Nicholas
Eberstadt, a longtime Korea scholar in Washington. ``Kim Jong Il
proved that he really is a movie-maker, and he made himself the
star,'' Eberstadt said, referring to the North Korean leader's
obsession with the cinema, which once led him to kidnap a South
Korean director and a famous actress to build him a film industry.
</P>
<P>
   But no one in Washington pretends to understand the rest of the
script in Kim's latest production. In meetings at the White House
and the State Department on Thursday, some wondered aloud whether
the sudden emergence of the reclusive North Korean leader was a
one-time anomaly or a radical change of strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Is he prepared to pull his troops back from the demilitarized
zone and dismantle the tens of thousands of mortar and missiles
that could destroy Seoul in an hour? And, if so, should the United
States be ready to talk about pulling its 37,000 troops out of the
Korean Peninsula, as the North has demanded for years? Could a
country whose major export consists of missiles and arms shipped to
the Middle East break himself of the arms trade, or satisfy the
United States that it should be removed from the State Department's
list of terrorist nations?
</P>
<P>
   If it did, the desperately poor country would suddenly be
eligible for aid from the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund. But the aid would inevitably come attached to communications
technology, an influx of foreigners and outside ideas _ all
anathema in a country where radios can only be tuned to the
official government stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly has to be taken as a change in North Korean
tactics in how to engage the world,'' said Robert Gallucci, who
negotiated the 1994 deal with North Korea to freeze its nuclear
program and is now dean of Georgetown University's school of
foreign service. ``Whether it is a strategic change, or whether
this is truly a new North Korean approach to the world, it is
simply too early to know. There is a lot of history here: War,
terrorism, nuclear ambitions, incidents at sea, that suggests the
need for a lot of caution.''
</P>
<P>
   None of those issues were discussed at length at the summit. But
South Korean officials who telephoned Washington on Thursday said
that President Kim Dae-jung had raised the questions of North
Korea's nuclear program and missile exports in his talk with his
North Korean counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   But he did so chiefly to alert him that these issues remain
major stumbling blocks, according to U.S. and South Korean
officials, and he made no effort to address them in a summit that
was mostly about setting a tone of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The full briefing for U.S. officials will come Friday and this
weekend, when South Korea's national security adviser arrives in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   So the Clinton administration Thursday was clearly trying to
balance caution with encouragement for Kim Jong Il, a man until
recently regarded as an Asian Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a good deal of euphoria in the south,'' said one
senior administration official who has been deeply involved in
negotiations with the North for years. ``But is there a change in
the million-man army? In the missile program? In the North's
nuclear ambitions?''
</P>
<P>
   The only conclusion the administration could safely reach, he
said Thursday afternoon, was ``not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of the new opening by the North will be plumbed
repeatedly in the next few months _ by South Korea, Japan and the
United States. The United States has missile talks with the North
that begin in a few weeks. Japan is negotiating a possible
resumption of diplomatic relations _ if it can resolve the issue of
Japanese women believed kidnapped by the North, and the country's
continued harboring of members of the Japanese Red Army terrorist
group. South Korea, once the euphoria dies down, will learn whether
the exchanges of families, the communications links and the
cultural exchanges _ all promised before _ turn into reality.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no question that with this week's summit, the
Clinton administration finds itself at a very different place than
it was six years ago this week. At the time the United States was
about to support sanctions against North Korea for its refusal to
allow inspectors to visit the site of its suspected nuclear weapons
program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was warned by his top military advisers that the North
could make good on its threat that it would respond to the
sanctions by invading the south. Clinton was about to order more
troops to the region, to back up the B-2 bombers he had recently
dispatched to within easy reach of the DMZ.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a policy of rapprochement that the administration entered
reluctantly _ at the urging of Kim Dae-jung when he came to office
two years ago _ has radically changed the atmosphere. The mystery
is whether it has also changed the nature of the North Korean
threat.
</P>
<P>
   The larger North Korea issues for the White House may well fall
to the next president. Al Gore or George W. Bush may have to face
the question of whether there is a justification for keeping U.S.
troops in South Korea if the threat they have deterred since 1953,
when the Korean War came to an uneasy armistice, no longer appears
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   And Gallucci noted Thursday that the decision over whether to
develop and deploy a national missile defense _ a $60 billion
program in which North Korea has long been cited as the most urgent
``rogue state'' threat _ might have to be rethought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have based the logic of the system on the threat from North
Korea, and the assumption that its leaders are not impressed by
ordinary nuclear deterrence,'' the former nuclear weapons
negotiator said. ``If it turns out that we are revising our
thinking about those North Korean leaders, then it suggests that we
might have to reassess the whole plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
