u a BC-RENO-EXECUTIONS-HNS &LR;      06-15 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-EXECUTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO SAYS DEFENDANTS FACING 
DEATH PENALTY DESERVE BETTER LAWYERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno, lending her voice to a
raging national debate over capital punishment, said Thursday that
too many people on trial for their lives have incompetent attorneys
defending them.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, the nation's top prosecutor, called on states to ensure
that defendants _ especially those charged with a capital offense _
receive adequate representation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should not be prosecuted for a capital crime until they
have a lawyer who can properly represent them and they have the
investigative and other resources necessary to properly investigate
the charges against them,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states bear a responsibility in terms of prosecution to
ensure that if they're going to prosecute, they should make sure
that the person being prosecuted has competent counsel. And if the
person can't afford it, that it be provided in real terms, not just
in name.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno called it ``critically important'' that defendants facing
the death penalty have access to all forensic and investigatory
resources that will permit them to pursue their claims of
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is very important that all defendants charged with
crimes that have significant sanctions, that clearly people charged
with a capital crime should have . . . good lawyers who can
properly represent them,'' she said. ``In too many instances in
this country, people charged with capital crimes do not.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno recalled her years as a Miami prosecutor and the day a man
walked through the courtroom after his death sentence had been set
aside and his conviction overturned after spending 21 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never forget turning around and looking over my
shoulder at that man who walked out of the courthouse free for the
first time in 21 years and to think that he could have gone to the
electric chair for a crime I did not think he committed,'' Reno
said. ``We just can't do that. We cannot let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's comments came as national attention has focused on the
death penalty partly because of Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
presidential campaign as well as a recent event in Illinois, a
university study and pending federal legislation critical of
capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who had allowed 131 executions during his 5 { years in
office before granting a 30-day reprieve to a convicted killer June
1 to pursue DNA tests, has campaigned as being tough on criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Gov. George Ryan, a fellow Republican, declared in
February a moratorium on executions in that state. Ryan called for
the halt after the convictions of 13 death-row inmates in Illinois
had been overturned since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Columbia University reported Monday that two-thirds
of all death penalty cases appealed between 1973 and 1995 were
riddled with such serious errors that the verdicts were overturned.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, explaining
the difficulty of finding competent lawyers to handle death-penalty
cases, said the lawyers most likely to accept court appointments to
these trials are the least experienced or least competent. These
attorneys are most likely to have the fewest clients and,
therefore, greater time and inclination to take the low-paying
criminal cases, the group added.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., has proposed legislation that would
require states to create agencies to appoint experienced lawyers
for defendants facing the death penalty and to ensure that these
attorneys are adequately compensated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
