<HEADER>
A5170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUTOMAKERS-EFFICIENCY     06-15 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOMAKERS-EFFICIENCY-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCTIVITY IN U.S.-OWNED AUTO PLANTS IS STEADILY IMPROVING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ford Taurus factory in Atlanta has no air-conditioning to
ward off the sweltering heat of Georgia summer. Its scuffed, black
concrete floors and sooty ceiling beams hold the grit of 53 years
of car-building. While orange robots dodge and weave to weld car
roofs and sides, hundreds of men and women work on the assembly
line. To all appearances, it is an utterly ordinary car factory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Atlanta plant is, in fact, special. According to a
highly regarded annual study released Thursday, the factory is the
most efficient in North America, representing the first time that a
U.S.-owned auto plant has surpassed Japanese-owned factories on
this continent in labor productivity.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, productivity has improved across the U.S.-owned
auto industry in recent years. While a Ford plant ranked as No. 1,
the biggest overall efficiency gains last year took place at
General Motors, once known for inefficiency. Ford is the most
efficient U.S. automaker, although its performance was marginally
worse by some measures last year because of the production of very
big, complicated vehicles like the new Ford Excursion sport
utility.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several years, Detroit automakers have gradually
made up much, though certainly not all, of the productivity gap
between U.S.-owned factories and those owned by the Japanese. They
have done so not primarily through the use of high-tech computers
and robots, although they have integrated such equipment into their
factories, but through improved management and organization,
according to Harbour &AMP; Associates, which issued Thursday's report.
And while Japanese automakers continue to set the standard in
quality, better management is helping Detroit automakers start to
catch up in reliability, too, although precise estimates vary
widely for how much the quality gap has closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of overall performance, not just labor productivity,
they continue to close the gap,'' said Ronald Harbour, the
consulting firm's president. ``But the Japanese are not standing
still and still lead in quality, productivity and manufacturing
cost.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, when competition with Japan bordered on a
national obsession, the productivity gap between U.S. and Japanese
factories, particularly auto factories, was a major preoccupation
for politicians, corporate executives, and investors alike. Ten
years of economic stagnation in Japan and the rise of America's
high-tech industries have pushed auto productivity comparisons out
of the limelight. But while the nation's attention has moved on to
Microsoft and the Internet, much has changed in the nation's auto
factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1980s, there was a widely held, popular view that Japan
represented the economic future,'' said Robert Shapiro, the
undersecretary of commerce for economic affairs. ``Since the 1980s,
the U.S. auto industry has recovered very nicely, and in part that
reflects productivity gains.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, GM, Ford Motor and Chrysler, now a division of
DaimlerChrysler, required more than twice as much labor as their
Japanese competitors to build a car. Today they need 18 to 50
percent more hours of labor in the factory. That is still a hefty
disadvantage, to be sure, but it is manageable because manual labor
now accounts for only a tenth of the cost of a car as other
expenses, like design and engineering, have grown.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's problem is that it has been unable to improve
management practices at all factories. But a few of Detroit's
best-run factories are now as efficient as the Japanese operations
or more so, according to the study by Harbour, a consulting firm in
Troy, Mich., with which the seven leading automakers in North
America share confidential productivity data each year. Auto
factories in Japan are slightly more efficient than Japanese-owned
factories in the United States, because they are closer to some of
their suppliers, but the gap with these factories has narrowed as
well, Harbour said.
</P>
<P>
   The most productive factories are not distinguished by a higher
degree of automation than their competitors. Robots are now
commonplace for physically strenuous or dangerous tasks, but human
beings have proved themselves less expensive for many other tasks.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the most automated assembly plant in North America,
Mitsubishi's mid-size car factory in Normal, Ill., also had some of
the lowest labor productivity last year because so many employees
were constantly required to keep the robots maintained and
repaired, Harbour said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   What really seems to separate the productive factories from
inefficient ones is something more basic than automation, and yet
more complex. ``It's good management,'' Harbour said.
</P>
<P>
   What particularly efficient factories have in common, he said,
is that they seldom shut down their assembly lines in the middle of
a shift, so they rarely require unscheduled overtime to meet
production quotas. American-owned assembly lines suffered frequent
shutdowns until recently, because workers were absent or auto parts
reached the assembly line that were defective or did not fit
together easily. For many years, the assembly lines of
Japanese-owned factories have almost never stopped in the middle of
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Senior managers at Japanese automakers tend to say that high
productivity comes from a constant attention to detail, advice that
U.S. automakers are starting to follow. ``There is no silver
bullet,'' said Daryl Wilson, Toyota's vice president for
manufacturing in Canada. The Toyota Corolla factory in Cambridge,
Ontario, was North America's most efficient in 1998 before being
displaced by Ford's Atlanta factory last year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At Ford's factory in Atlanta, strong labor-management relations
have permitted more attention to detail. Absenteeism is currently
running 3 percent, just half the rate at many factories in Michigan
and Ohio. But the rate used to be 2 percent, and the increase
upsets Steve Trousdale, the chairman of the local unit of the
United Automobile Workers union, who is determined that the Atlanta
factory not be chosen for layoffs in the next recession.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Trousdale sent a strongly worded letter to every union
member. ``Attendance must improve,'' it said. ``If AWOLs go down,
job security goes up,'' the letter continued. ``You must be
responsible and come to work!'' the letter concluded, in bold face,
capital letters printed in extra-large type.
</P>
<P>
   The national leadership of the UAW discourages competition
between union locals for fear that automakers will play them off
against each other. But Trousdale, elected by the workers in
Atlanta, disregards such concerns. ``I've got to look at what is
good for the Atlanta work force,'' he said last month at the
factory. ``I don't really look at what somebody else thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Atlanta factory still has union work rules guaranteeing
that workers with the most seniority receive the easiest jobs, a
system that limits management's flexibility. Japanese automakers,
which are non-union, do not face such rules, and they organize
their employees into more flexible teams that take whatever tasks
most need doing.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Todd Cooper, a 32-year-old worker on the assembly line and a
former electrician on construction sites, has the grueling task of
putting 35-pound dashboards into cars day after day, but said he
accepted the unchanging rhythms of the seniority system. ``I don't
have to work outside in the cold and the rain,'' he said last
month, eating a sandwich from his lunchbox while sitting,
exhausted, on a crate next to the assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Windsor, Ontario, DaimlerChrysler is also paying close
attention to details. Sandra Bouckley, the company's manager of
advanced minivan manufacturing, is trying to change the way her
company prepares for the introduction of a new model.
</P>
<P>
   When Chrysler redid the minivan in 1995, it closed its minivan
factories in Windsor and St. Louis for nearly three months to
replace equipment, losing sales. This year, Bouckley has already
installed much of the new equipment during weekends and by
extending the assembly line so that there is room for old and new
machinery. The Windsor factory will only be closed for two weeks
between models as a result.
</P>
<P>
   That is a big improvement, but Japanese automakers sometimes
change models in a day, by making even more elaborate preparations.
Moreover, DaimlerChrysler will close its St. Louis minivan factory
for seven weeks this summer because the company is not yet able to
change over two factories quickly at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a philosophical, technological deviation from the way
we've always done business, and we decided we'd test it in
Windsor,'' Bouckley said.
</P>
<P>
   GM was the least efficient automaker in North America in
stamping car hoods, doors, roofs and other parts out of big sheets
of steel until Joseph Spielman became GM's vice president for metal
parts stamping in 1994. Now it is the most efficient of the Big
Three in stamping by some productivity measures but trails well
behind Honda and Toyota. Spielman has managed this partly by
standardizing equipment: he reduced the number of sizes of stamping
presses to 57 to just 6, for example.
</P>
<P>
   That made it easier to service the machines and exchange parts
among them, allowing GM to make do with only 200 stamping presses
instead of the 350 it had in 1993. Since each press is as big as a
Boeing 737-300 and carries the same price tag, $32 million, the
investment savings have been huge. But GM has not been able to
reduce employment to match because of its restrictive labor
contracts, Harbour said.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to improve upon Spielman's self-description: ``6 foot
6-1/2 and 250 pounds of romp and stomp.'' But as far as the UAW and
its members were concerned, Spielman had a little too much romp and
stomp until recently. Upset by his demands for better productivity,
workers at a factory in Flint, Mich., launched a strike two years
ago that crippled the automaker's production for two months,
costing it $2 billion in after-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the strike, both sides have been committed
to greater cooperation, and Spielman became an outspoken advocate
of worker involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't me out there with a cattle prod or a whip, it's
people out there saying, ``This is ours, this is our plant,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-collar workers in factories are now in close touch with
white-collar engineers sitting at computers in office buildings.
Workers with questions about blueprints used to be told to mail
letters to the engineers, waiting two weeks or more for a reply.
Since January, workers have been sending e-mail to engineers, using
personal computers in the factories. Spielman requires the
engineers to respond within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   James DeLair, the local union vice president in Flint, said that
the changes have been noticeable. ``There seems to be a whole lot
more interest in what the worker has to say,'' DeLair said. ``The
working relationship, hourly to salaried, could still use
improvement, but upper management wants to make things better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
