<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-DEANWITTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY SELECTS INVESTMENT BANKER TO RUN BROKERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the brokerage business, the climb to the top ranks of
management almost always started from a stockbroker's desk in a
local branch. But, suddenly, the route to the top has been diverted
through business schools and investment bankers' offices on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. said Thursday that it had
chosen John Schaefer, a longtime investment banker to run its
brokerage operation, the second largest in the country. The
appointment came a few months after the biggest brokerage firm,
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., named another former investment banker,
Stanley O'Neal, to run its brokerage network.
</P>
<P>
   Like O'Neal, Schaefer is the first person to hold his new job
who never was a stockbroker. The similarities do not end there:
Both men are 48, and each has a master's degree in business
administration from Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about rewarding the most senior broker any more,''
said Richard Strauss, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``We're
past that stage. It's about getting the most strategic thinker in
place. Things are changing so quickly in the brokerage business,
there's no room for error.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the changes is Internet technology, which
ushered in cheap, online stock trading and led investors to
question why they were paying commissions of $200 or more to place
trades through brokers. Morgan Stanley and Merrill both capitulated
last year and, over the objections of their armies of brokers,
introduced online trading with commissions as low as $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   The integration of new technology into Morgan Stanley's various
businesses has been Schaefer's primary focus as the firm's chief
strategic and administrative officer for the last two years. He
also is the co-chairman of a committee that oversees the firm's
investments in electronic securities exchanges and other areas of
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer, who was not available for comment, succeeds James F.
Higgins as president and chief operating officer of the firm's
private client group. Higgins, 52, is assuming the title of
chairman of the group, which was the Dean Witter brokerage firm
before Dean Witter merged with the Morgan Stanley investment
banking firm in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins, who has run the brokerage operation for 12 years, also
was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer inherits a group of more than 13,000 brokers who have
been wrestling with the merger of self-service investing with their
traditional service of personally advising clients on how to manage
their money. Last year, after operating its online-trading service
as a separate division under the brand name of its Discover credit
card, Morgan Stanley renamed it Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Online
and rolled it in with the rest of the firm's brokerage operations.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley announced that shift with great fanfare, a step
ahead of Merrill Lynch's introduction of online trading, but Morgan
Stanley has guarded information about how well its online service
has been received.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Witter could have had a big head-start online against its
Wall Street competitors. It was the first to experiment with
trading over the Internet when it bought Lombard Brokerage, a small
San Francisco-based online brokerage firm, in 1996 for about $60
million. But Higgins and other Dean Witter executives feared the
reaction of its brokers to the new threat and did not embrace the
new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Roach, who founded Lombard and helped run Dean Witter's
online business until earlier this year, said Schaefer's experience
in dealing with new technology made him an ideal choice to succeed
Higgins. ``He really gets it,'' said Roach, the chief executive of
an Internet startup called eLance.com. ``He's a great leader. He's
absolutely direct. He's opinionated but he listens.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Witter's brokers historically have been less productive
than their competitors at Merrill Lynch and the Salomon Smith
Barney unit of Citigroup, analysts said. Some analysts believe that
lag results in part from Dean Witter's reluctance to open its sales
network to products, such as mutual funds, from other companies.
While other brokerage firms are struggling to get their brokers to
sell their own funds, as many as 70 percent of the funds sold by
Dean Witter brokers are their own funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
