<SLUG> BC-GORE-TAXES-405&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PROPOSES $500 BILLION TAX CUT OVER 10 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCKLAND, Ohio _ Expecting a shower of gold at the end of the
month when new budget surplus estimates are released, Vice
President Al Gore said Thursday that he would offer Americans $500
billion in tax cuts over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The amount is twice what Gore had proposed earlier and half of
what Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, his Republican rival, has
proposed. Gore has been extremely critical of Bush's proposal,
saying the nation cannot afford it and the vital programs and
entitlement benefits would have to be cut to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides said the chief difference between their proposals was
that Gore's tax cuts would be limited primarily to families with
children and aging parents. Bush's income tax cut of $1.3 trillion
over 10 years would apply to people across the board.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is basing his proposal on the expectation that the federal
budget surplus will expand by perhaps $1 trillion. He had already
proposed the broad outlines of most of the tax cuts, but Thursday
he offered estimates of how much money he would devote to each.
</P>
<P>
   In a discussion at a food warehouse here, Gore said his plan
would cover long-term care, college tuition, day care, relief for
parents who stay at home with infants and relief from the so-called
marriage penalty, which has long been proposed by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the $500 billion would include tax-free
retirement accounts to supplement Social Security, the details of
which he said he would discuss next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tax relief package for middle-income families can help to
solve the most important challenges that families face today,''
Gore said. ``This package, big as it is, stands in sharp contrast
to an alternative that would completely eliminate the budget
surplus and threaten the underlying prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   The discussion here in a Cincinnati suburb came on the third day
Gore's ``progress and prosperity tour,'' which is designed to take
the vice president to battleground states and give him a chance to
highlight the booming economy and get some credit for it.
</P>
<P>
   The tour is premised on the Gore campaign's belief that the
economy is the vice president's trump card in the election. He says
the unprecedented growth in the economy has given the nation the
luxury of talking about ``big ideas,'' though on his tour he has
mostly offered new ways of spending the burgeoning surplus rather
than wrestled with philosophical choices.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But he is also proposing ways to make money. At two fund-raisers
in New York on Wednesday night, he gave a mini preview of a speech
on the environment that he plans to make the week after next, when
he will argue, as President Clinton has, that protecting the
environment does not have to mean sacrificing the economy, and that
in fact money can be made off cleaning up the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the third week of this series of speeches, I'm going to be
talking about how we can create millions of good new jobs by
investing in the new technologies that are far more efficient that
will position us to be more competitive, that will put us in first
place in the 21st century in making and selling the kind of
products that people all over the world in crowded, polluted cities
are trying to buy,'' he said to financial donors.
</P>
<P>
   Showing some eagerness on the subject, he brought it up later
and more explicitly to another group of financial donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there has been a kind of massive denial about
it,'' Gore said, ``the opportunities for business and for creating
new jobs and transforming our technological base to create the new
products that the rest of the world is clamoring to buy _ more
efficient engines, better industrial processes, new cars and trucks
_ we ought to be making them and selling them to the rest of the
world, where their desires for a higher standard of living are
climbing rapidly but they're choking on their pollution and the
rest of the world has far worse pollution than anywhere in the
United States outside of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax credits that he outlined Thursday would: make up to
$10,000 in college tuition costs tax deductible; give care-givers a
$3,000 tax credit to help care for elderly parents; provide a tax
credit for after-school programs; make the existing child-care tax
credit refundable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
