<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CBS-SURVIVOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' BREAKS ANOTHER RATINGS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS's enormous summer hit, ``Survivor,'' soared to new ratings
heights Wednesday night, pulling in more viewers than CBS has had
on any Wednesday night since the Nielsen Media Research company
transformed its ratings system in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks of growing ratings persuaded CBS to announce
formally Thursday that it would broadcast ``Survivor II: The
Australian Outback'' in the middle of the coming television season,
starting in January or February.
</P>
<P>
   Given the impact that ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
had on the past television season, when it expanded from a summer
show to a regular-season show, ``Survivor,'' a reality-adventure
series, has the potential to reverse CBS's ratings fortunes,
possibly making the network a contender for overall television
leadership next season.
</P>
<P>
   CBS began asking for participants for the next edition of
``Survivor'' following its broadcast Wednesday night. It also
announced that it would move up the starting date of its follow-up
reality show, ``Big Brother,'' one day, to Wednesday, July 5, at 9
p.m., to take advantage of the big audience flowing out of
``Survivor,'' which will be shown from 8 to 9.
</P>
<P>
   This week, without the impediment of ``Millionaire,'' which ABC
had placed opposite ``Survivor'' during the first two weeks of its
run, ``Survivor'' added about 5 million viewers, for a total of
just over 23 million.
</P>
<P>
   That was about seven million more viewers than NBC attracted
with Game 4 of the National Basketball Association finals Wednesday
night. It was also more viewers than ABC had for any episode of
``Millionaire'' last August, when that show quickly established
itself as a television phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Survivor'' eclipsed viewing levels for one of
CBS's biggest sports events, the National Collegiate Athletic
Association basketball championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, ``Survivor'' proved to be an especially powerful
draw with young viewers, bringing in more viewers between the ages
of 18 and 34 than any series show that played on CBS all last
season.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, a young participant was voted off the island
where the show is being staged. Stacey Stillman, a 27-year-old
lawyer from San Francisco, was eliminated in a vote by her
teammates. In the first two shows, two participants in their '60s
were voted out.
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives predicted Thursday that the show would do even
better as the weeks go on and the countdown to a final survivor
continues. The show is to run through August, with the final
episode coming down to two survivors, one of whom will win $1
million. A winner will be selected by the seven previously rejected
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Like the previous losing contestants, Stillman made numerous
television appearances Thursday, on CBS's ``Early Show'' and on
CNN, Fox News and MSNBC. She also appeared on ``Late Night With
David Letterman'' on CBS Thursday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
