<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5180 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHO LOVES YOU, BASHAR BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to understand Syrian politics today, after Hafez
Assad's death, go to the video store and check out three movies:
``Pinocchio,'' ``The Wizard of Oz'' and ``Godfather II.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinocchio'' is useful because if you believe that Bashar Assad
has, by himself, orchestrated his own smooth succession to his
father, well, then I have some lakeshore property in the Syrian
desert I'd like to sell you. Bashar is Pinocchio; the real question
is who is Gepetto? Who is pulling the strings behind the scene? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, Bashar's only title was head of the Syrian
Computer Society. Within hours after his father's death he was
named the armed forces commander, and the Syrian parliament passed
a law lowering the minimum age of the Syrian president from 40 to
34. Bashar is 34. You have to love that. They didn't bother with 30
or 25, they went right to B-34. Bingo. Who whispered to the
parliament to do that? Bashar alone? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wrong to assume that Bashar is simply a puppet. He
appears more serious than that. But it would be unwise to assume he
is ruling alone. His father met a lot of opposition when he tried
to elevate Bashar earlier. So Bashar needs friends. For the moment
a coalition of Alawite tribal elders, key army officers and his
sister's powerful husband, Gen. Asef Shoukat, seem to have come
together to back him. This means that the real question is not
simply what sort of Syria does Bashar want, but what sort of Syria
do his Gepettos want.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is a coalition of the family, the elders and
the chieftains who have decided that Bashar offers the best vehicle
for survival, because with Bashar they can present a united front
against the great challenges ahead,'' said Rob Satloff, head of the
Washington Institute for Near East Policy. ``He offers the image of
a liberalizer, perhaps enough to keep Syria's Sunni majority from
exploding after the passing of the reviled Hafez, but not one who
will go too far. He offers the image of an economic reformer, who
can entice foreign investment and economic aid, but not one who
will crack down on corruption too harshly. And with Bashar they
have someone who, unlike his father, might actually smile at
Israelis, without giving away anything in substance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to our next film, ``The Wizard of Oz.'' You know the
scene _ the one where Dorothy's house lands on the Wicked Witch and
all the munchkins come out to sing ``Ding, dong, the witch is
dead.'' That is exactly how many Syrians feel today about the end
of Assad's cruel tyranny. Syria's Sunni elite, and the rising new
generation, are hungry to join today's global conversation.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to understand Syria today, study Iran. The Iranian
mullahs kept the lid on almost as tight as Hafez did, but when they
finally had an election 75 percent of Iranians voted for the leader
who wanted to loosen the lid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The single most underestimated force in international affairs
today is what happens _ thanks to globalization _ when we all
increasingly know how everyone else lives. People everywhere start
to demand the same things, and when they can't get them, they get
frustrated. No wonder the Syrian lawmaker Youssef Jedani was quoted
in The New York Times as saying of Bashar: ``There are very high
expectations, because he's young and open and wants to give more
liberty and democracy.'' But Jedani added: ``I think he'll follow
the same rhythm as his father. You can't go fast here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah? There is a lot of repressed energy in Syria, and the
young will not put up with indefinitely from Bashar what they put
up with for so many years from his father. Managing that pent-up
energy may be Bashar's biggest challenge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Provided Bashar survives _ which brings us to ``Godfather II.''
No sooner was Hafez dead than his brother Rifaat, who in 1982 saved
the family's rule by crushing the Muslim fundamentalist uprising in
Hama, claimed Syria's leadership. Rifaat is in exile, but he
controls an Arabic satellite TV station, which he uses to beam
messages into Damascus. Could Bashar ever do to Rifaat what Michael
Corleone did to his brother Fredo when he proved disloyal in
``Godfather II'' _ have one of his thugs take Fredo fishing and
then shoot him in the head? If I were Rifaat, I wouldn't go fishing
with any strangers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
