<HEADER>
A5184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-AD-COLUMN-N     06-15 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: MICROSOFT TRIES A FIRESIDE CHAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The latest installment in Microsoft's campaign to win
the hearts of American consumers is a television commercial titled
``Vision.'' It is the third in a series of commercials in which
Microsoft's leaders describe the company's values and its
importance to the economy. The first began shortly after a federal
judge ruled in April that Microsoft had repeatedly violated the
nation's antitrust laws. The current installment began running
Sunday, four days after the judge ordered that Microsoft be split
in two. Microsoft is appealing both the legal ruling and the
breakup order. The producer of the ad is McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: Bill Gates, Microsoft chairman, is seated,
wearing a thick blue sweater. His hands are folded with one elbow
resting on a table. The setting, at the company studio, is wood
tones and personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Beside Gates on the table are a coffee cup, paper and pen,
carefully placed to look casual. It is as if Gates had just paused
from contemplation for a few words with the camera. As he speaks,
the camera moves closer to him and slightly to his left. His words
are accompanied by the soft strains of an acoustic guitar.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: The commercial consists entirely of Gates speaking
about his company:
</P>
<P>
   ``The next generation of software is being developed right here.
It will understand your voice, anticipate your needs, protect your
privacy and connect you to the Internet wherever you are. It will
help your children learn, and give businesses new tools to succeed
in the coming digital world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been writing great software for the past 25 years. It's
what we're all about. It's our passion, and it always will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best is yet to come.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: Some competitors will cringe at the declaration that
Microsoft products, especially its Windows operating system, are
``great software.'' And whether computers will soon do all that
Gates says is open to question. But how can you argue with vision
and optimism? It has certainly worked for Gates so far.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: The commercial is the equivalent of a ``fireside
chat'' with Gates. He presents the benevolent face of Microsoft _ a
hard-working paragon of American capitalism, laboring daily to make
better software to improve people's lives. It is a visual antidote
to the portrayal of Microsoft in the antitrust trial as a bullying,
arrogant monopolist. No arrogance in this commercial, which even
helpfully identifies Gates, in white letters, as the chairman and
co-founder of Microsoft, in case any Martians are tuning in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-15 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: COSTLY MOVE IN PARIS, BUT TYPICAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, France, Italy, Germany and Russia)  (EDS: medaillons in penultimate graf is cq.) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quirky. Eccentric. Self-assured. Amusing. All over the place.
Modern. Spontaneous. Competitive. Expensive. Charming. Arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the adjectives people use to describe
Jean-Marie Rossi, considered the doyen of Paris antiques dealers.
Rossi is a big man (6-foot-5) with a large personality. After 44
years in business, he recently moved his gallery, Aveline, to the
Place Beauvau on Rue du Faubourg Saint-Honore, across the street
from the Elysee Palace, the home of the presidents of France.
</P>
<P>
   At great expense, he hired a renowned Paris decorator,
Francois-Joseph Graf, to transform two floors of a private house
built in 1771 into a large, spacious, light-filled gallery. He then
installed the antiques himself, creating vignettes with clever
combinations of furniture, paintings, porcelains and objets d'art.
</P>
<P>
   Moving was an expensive gamble for someone at this stage of his
career, but he dismissed such talk. ``I paid for it with one Roy
Lichtenstein painting,'' he said. ``I bought `The Ring' in 1963 for
6,000 francs and sold it for 12 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossi may or may not be the oldest of the great Paris dealers;
nor is his taste the most classical. While he is known, as his
first wife and current gallery director, Barbara Hottinguer, put
it, as an ``extreme connoisseur'' in 18th-century furniture from
France, Italy, Germany and Russia, he sells things from many
periods, specifically from the time of Louis XIII through the 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what's unpredictable _ with life, women, interiors and
objects of art,'' said the dealer, who is married to his fourth
wife, Marie. ``I like Frank Lloyd Wright and Brancusi. I like
whatever is modern for its period. I don't care what century it is
as long as it's original.''
</P>
<P>
   His client list includes Rothschilds, Helene David-Weil, Henry
Kravis, the Getty, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Louvre, the
Musee d'Orsay and the Toledo Museum of Art. The big-name designers
who shop at his gallery include David Mlinaric of London; Alberto
Pinto, Jacques Garcia and Jacques Grange of Paris and David Easton,
Duane Hampton, Juan-Pablo Molyneux and Peter Marino of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also have 40-year-olds buying in the gallery,'' he said.
``Both European and American.'' Rossi insists that his staff treat
everyone with courtesy, so Americans in jeans feel welcome. He does
not want the gallery to be intimidating, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rossi is not like other dealers,'' said Tony Victoria, a New
York dealer specializing in French antiques. ``He's respected
because he puts together modern and antique. He's a flamboyant
figure in a staid world. He has flair. He is always putting wild
modern stuff like Lucite with 18th-century antiques.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria, who recently opened a second, more modestly priced
French antiques shop on Main Street in Bridgehampton, N.Y., added:
``Rossi is no old-fashioned, true-blue,
18th-century-French-furniture dealer, like Jean-Paul Fabre, who is
the touchstone of authenticity in Paris. Rossi has a wide
intellect, but he's equally known for a sense of humor _ and tongue
to match _ which is unknown in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria said his father used to buy from Rossi's partner,
Maurice Aveline. ``When Jean-Marie took over, it got too
stratospherically expensive,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Rossi does have a reputation for very high prices. He would not
disclose them but said he was willing to spend a lot _ perhaps more
than anyone else _ for top merchandise. ``Everyone has taste, but
good taste costs a fortune today,'' he said. ``It's like wine. If
you order the most expensive wine in a restaurant, you normally get
the best. In the 1940s and 1950s you could build great collections
without a lot of money. Now, unfortunately, you need money. In a
way, it's easier when it's expensive. You have less competition.''
</P>
<P>
   His prices are defended by Leon Dalva, a French furniture dealer
in New York. ``There's a small group of us trying to uphold the
standard,'' he said. ``We have competed with Rossi at auction, and
sometimes we dealers fall in love with a thing and feel we have to
have it at any price. People think we always buy cheap and sell
dear. It's not true. French furniture from the 18th century is the
most beautiful furniture anyone has ever made. It's expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalva said he admired Rossi because he also bought ``outlandish,
amazing things from the 19th century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rossi was the first to buy things of that period,'' he said.
``They were not copies of anything, but real 19th-century
originals.''
</P>
<P>
   Didier Aaron, a Paris dealer who has known Rossi for over 40
years, said: ``Like me, he buys whatever he likes. It's not work
for us; it's a passion. It is not a question of price. If you have
good taste, you can buy things from any century or style.''
</P>
<P>
   Khalil Rizk, director of the Chinese Porcelain Co. in New York,
said that Rossi ``is all over the place, but with his eye even
normal pieces seem to take on an aura.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossi also works hard. He is training his 26-year-old daughter,
Marella, in the gallery. After receiving a degree in art history at
the Sorbonne, studying at the Louvre and at Versailles and taking
the Christie's art education course, Rossi began to work at Aveline
a year ago. She has created its Web site (www.Aveline.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``Father goes to Drouot every day,'' she said, referring to the
French auction house. ``Last Sunday, he flew to London for a
Sotheby's furniture sale preview. Three months ago, he bought 10
percent of the Karl Lagerfeld sale in Monaco.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossi, the son of a French mother and an Italian immigrant who
ran a ball-bearings factory, studied law and was certified as a
government notary. It was a gentlemen's profession, but he loved
the world of art and antiques more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 25, I asked Maurice Aveline if I could help him,''
he said. ``He was a well-known dealer. I did administration and
learned how to restore pieces. Eventually I took over.''
</P>
<P>
   Today his inventory is unpredictable. Most classic, perhaps, is
a Louis XVI architect's table stamped by G. Jacob, one of the best
names in 18th-century French furniture. The deceptively plain
mahogany table has a top that tilts up to form a writing surface.
The top is supported by several slim columns designed to hold
oversized portfolios. Some columns have garlands of olive leaves
carved on them. The table looks modern enough for a SoHo loft.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there are a pair of German commodes from
about 1770, highly ornamented, from a chateau in the Duchy of
Limbourg. The demilune commodes are creamy white and decorated with
gilded Corinthian capitals, medaillons, portraits and trellis work.
They are as dazzling as anything from Pavlosk Palace outside St.
Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a very tall, revolving Japanese bookcase made for
the World's Fair in 1867. The columns are faux bamboo wood
decorated with bronze Japanese dragons. ``It would have been the
most modern thing at the fair,'' Rossi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
