</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL ASKS CONGO'S NEIGHBORS TO ASSIST IN ENDING
CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council Thursday urged visiting
ministers from a half-dozen African nations embroiled in the war in
Congo to join in seeking a way out of the desperate conflict that
continues to devastate Africa's largest country.
</P>
<P>
   The message repeated as two days of talks got under way here was
that the United Nations could accomplish nothing to stem such
carnage and alleviate Congo's suffering without active help from
its African neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   France, which holds the council's rotating presidency this
month, circulated a new draft resolution that expressed ``deep
concern'' over the continuing hostilities in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The draft resolution demanded ``the orderly withdrawal of all
foreign forces'' from Congo, with a four-month deadline for Rwanda
and Uganda to pull out their troops, which battered the city of
Kisangani earlier this month in fighting one another. Angola,
Namibia and Zimbabwe have supported Lauren Kabila's government in
Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution welcomed the participation in Thursday's meeting
of a political committee formed under the ceasefire agreement
reached last July in the Zambian capital, Lusaka. Senior officials
at Thursday's session came from Congo, Angola, Rwanda, Uganda,
Zambia and Zimbabwe, as well as two Congolese rebel movements and
the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
   The complexity of achieving any consensus was underscored when
Rwanda's foreign minister, Ande Bumaya, said that Rwandan troops
could not leave without security guarantees that Hutu rebels would
stop using Zaire as a base for attacking his country.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council previously authorized the dispatch of 5,537
peacekeepers to Congo, but there has been a mounting reluctance to
commit them to monitoring a ceasefire that has yet to take hold.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general's special representative to Congo, Kamal
Moranje, told the council Thursday that the troops earmarked for
peacekeeping in the country were not nearly enough, and said an
extra battalion was needed just to prevent new fighting over
Kisanagani. He also proposed extending the date now set for a
peacekeeping contingent to begin deploying in Congo early next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The chief U.S. representative, Richard Holbrooke, who visited
the region five weeks ago with other council representatives, said
there was ``no excuse for what happened in Kisangani,'' where the
latest fighting between Rwandan and Ugandan troops killed at least
160 Congolese civilians and injured another 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting, Holbrooke said, made it more difficult to recruit
peacekeeping forces to go to Congo because the duty had become more
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected writing off Congo as a failed nation. ``States
don't fail,'' Holbrooke said. ``Leaders do.''
</P>
<P>
   In a report to the Security Council last week, Secretary General
Kofi Annan asked council members to make it clear to the warring
parties in Congo ``that their assurances of support for the peace
process and guarantees of security and freedom of movement can no
longer be taken at face value, but must be reflected in their
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan pointed out that one-third of Congo's population, or 16
million people, critically needed food, more than 1.5 million were
displaced and 5 million were completely or partially isolated from
their traditional supply routes. He also referred to a cholera
outbreak and mounting HIV infection rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-OLY-KOREAS-NYT &LR;      06-15 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KOREAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH AND SOUTH KOREA WANT TO MARCH TOGETHER AT SYDNEY GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: also moving in `s' category) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   North and South Korea on Thursday pushed for cooperation on the
athletic level, as well as the political. Both sides are speaking
encouragingly about the possibility of marching together at the
opening ceremonies of the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney,
Australia, on Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for North and South Korea to march under the
Olympic flag, as well as the flags of the two nations, Olympic
officials said. The countries would field separate teams for
competition in Sydney, but they are being encouraged to send a
joint team to the 2001 world table tennis championships in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Un-yong, a member of the International Olympic Committee and
the Parliament from South Korea, proposed the joint march last
month to Juan Antonio Samaranch, president of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   On May 25, after the countries had announced plans for the
landmark summit talks that took place this week, Samaranch wrote to
the presidents of both countries and proposed the Olympic march. He
said it would ``not only contribute to peace in the region but will
also allow joint training and mutual cooperation in many areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the North Korean IOC delegate reacted positively to
the South's suggestion of a unified march into the opening
ceremonies in Sydney. ``I am expecting the joint entrance of the
South and North Korean teams at the Sydney Olympics,'' said Chang
Ung, the IOC delegate from North Korea, was quoted as saying in
South Korean media pool reports.
</P>
<P>
   A show of solidarity in the Olympics would represent a political
victory of sorts for Kim Un Yong, who seeks to succeed Samaranch as
IOC president but received a severe warning from the Olympic
committee last year in the wake of the Salt Lake City bribery
scandal. His son, known as John Kim, has been indicted for
allegedly receiving a sham job paid for by Salt Lake's Olympic
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Talks have been ongoing about the possibility of North Korea
playing host to some matches in the 2002 men's World Cup, scheduled
to be held in Japan and South Korea. The two Koreas fielded a joint
team for the 1991 world table tennis championships.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea boycotted the 1988 Summer Games in Seoul after the
IOC would not agree to its demands to be a co-host of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound of Montreal, the IOC delegate who wrote a book about
the 1988 Seoul Games, said he gave the joint appearance in Sydney
``a fighting chance of happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
