<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VW-CLAY-MODEL-NYT &LR;      06-15 0213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VW-CLAY-MODEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MODEL FROM VW HAS TIRES OF CLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As it asking too much to expect that someone would spend $70,000
to $100,000 for a lump of brown clay with four wheels?
</P>
<P>
   A life-size, two-ton clay model of the Volkswagen New Beetle
(the real thing sells for $16,000 or so) went on the auction block
at Christie's last week.
</P>
<P>
   And it stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few people bid on the clay model, which was part of
Christie's 20th century decorative arts sale, and those bids failed
to reach critical mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a few bids, and they got close to our minimum bid
requirement,'' Margaret Doyle, a Christie's spokeswoman, said.
``But it didn't sell. We are disappointed. A lot of people looked
at it when it was on display in our gallery. It stood out, that's
for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle would not divulge the minimum bid requirement; the sale
catalog listed it at about $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   No full-size clay auto models are known to have been auctioned,
Christie's said. More typically, the clay is reused or destroyed
during the process of measuring for molds used in production.
</P>
<P>
   The clay model will return to the Volkswagen Design Center in
Wolfsburg, Germany, where it was produced in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-L     06-15 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO _ A `VITAMIN' FOR BOXING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Seth Abraham was running the NBA, there's no
doubt - you'd be watching a Lakers-New York Knicks final series
right now. There'd even be a good chance of a Lakers matchup
against the unretired Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson ... don't worry, that would be all worked out
somehow.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Abraham is only the CEO and president of Time
Warner Sports. He just has the last word in what HBO and its
pay-per-view arm TVKO presents in the boxing world.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Oscar De La Hoya and Sugar Shane Mosley will be
hooping it up Saturday night at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing in sports are the elite matchups,'' Abraham
said from his New York office this week before jetting out to L.A.
for the aforementioned superbout. ``Better that the Lakers are in
the NBA Finals than Portland because from a marquee matchup, the
general public wants to see Shaq, not Sabonis. And the public wants
De La Hoya-Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in these elite matchups, and I'll continue to
believe in putting out lots of money so we can use our influence to
make these happen. That's what helps erase some of the problems
that the sport of boxing will always have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sport will always have a common cold with trials and
suspect mandatory title defenses ... there's so much wrong. But HBO
can be the vitamin of boxing, putting on these big fights to better
the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   In some corners, Abraham and HBO have become more than a remedy
but are viewed as part of the illness.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, who has already fought 15 times on HBO cards, is
under contract to the premium pay channel through 2001. Last week,
the network signed Felix Trinidad, who defeated De La Hoya for his
title this year, to a long-term deal that'll begin with a bout July
22.
</P>
<P>
   HBO also has locked up contracts with Lennox Lewis, the
undisputed heavyweight champ in most people's eyes. It has the
flamboyant Prince Nasheem Hammed. It has Mosley. It has Fernando
Vargas. And although Roy Jones Jr. has only one more fight left on
his HBO contract, it'll probably retain him.
</P>
<P>
   That makes quite a murderer's row of fighters committed to a
network that makes it clear that it's not a promoter or manager in
the seedy boxing game.
</P>
<P>
   But fights have been part of HBO's makeup since the network
launched in late 1972. Three months into it, HBO was putting on its
first fight - George Foreman vs. Joe Frazier from Jamaica. In '75,
it showed the Muhammad Ali-Frazier ``Thrilla in Manila'' - the
first HBO presentation transmitted by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, more than 100 world championship fights had taken place
on the network, involving everyone from Mike Tyson (who signed with
HBO long before he was a champion), Evander Holyfield, Sugar Ray
Leonard and Marvin Hagler (another HBO original signee).
</P>
<P>
   The reason HBO has become such a boxing fixture in the past
decade is because of Abraham and the aggressive work of Lou
DiBella, who recently left as the company's head of programming.
DiBella developed another tier of matchups - one where the fighters
and managers could be guaranteed of repeat appearances and work
their way into the major spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a revolutionary force,'' HBO boxing broadcaster Jim
Lampley said. ``He proved not every fight had to be a showcase. It
dramatically broadened the pond and opened more options for
matchmaking. Outside of ESPN and USA Network, there wasn't any
talent development organism in the boxing TV world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou forever changed the way TV executives did their
business,'' Abraham admits. ``He became proactive as a matchmaker.
But let's make it clear - we're not managers. We're TV networks.
Many people in the boxing community have labeled HBO as a promoter.
We're not a promoter. We don't house fighters. People who know that
business like Don King and Bob Arum know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our influence is our checkbook.''
</P>
<P>
   With DiBella only a consultant to HBO, the thought might be that
the network will lose some of its clout with Kerry Davis replacing
him in that negotiation role. But Abraham doesn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about how boxing has been marginalized, or it
appeals to only a niche audience,'' Abraham said. ``It might be
true in other places, but not at Time-Warner. For us, it's anything
but an outpost.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Showtime as their chief rival, HBO continues to have
serious game when it comes to locking in matchups. For example,
talk of a Tyson- Lewis fight on Showtime have been ongoing, but as
Showtime's Jay Larkin said recently, ``hell will freeze over before
HBO allows Lennox Lewis to fight Mike Tyson on Showtime ... there
will be pork chops growing on the palm trees of Tel Aviv first.''
</P>
<P>
   And De La Hoya's future with the network will also depend on
what happens Saturday. A rematch with Trinidad is something HBO
badly wants, but if that doesn't happen, they'll focus attention on
making a Trinidad-Vargas matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday's fight impacts everything,'' Abraham said. ``It's
right on the San Andreas fault and the tectonic plates will shift
after Saturday, no matter who wins.''
</P>
<P>
   And HBO's Richter scale will be there not just to measure it,
but to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-mile drivers: It's practically unheard of that a network
will commit to four-day coverage of a major golf tournament, but
that's what NBC began Thursday with this weekend's U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, thank you, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Can't really go wrong, though, with it being the 100th such
event from as majestic a venue as foggy Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   While CBS gets the annual honors of the PGA Tour event from
Pebble Beach each January, NBC got its first crack at doing an
event from the Monterey Peninsula when it carried last summer's
U.S. Amateur championship.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Sports executive producer Tom Roy said: ``We used the
Amateur to test out different angles, and the one thing I'll say
about Pebble is the way other broadcasters have shown events from
here has really accentuated the beauty, but the first time I played
here I didn't realize just how good each and every one of these
holes are. So we've really gone the extra effort to show angles
that do show just how tough these holes are instead of just one
camera behind the green.''
</P>
<P>
   The other thing viewers might not readily notice: Roy has done
everything possible not to get NBC camera towers in the way.
Thursday's incredible coverage proved he was on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate seeing our own equipment in the shots,'' he said. ``I
just want to see the pristine beauty of the golf course and the
players. We specifically designed our coverage and our layout to
avoid seeing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``On holes where you have vistas where a green may be at the top
of the horizon, I purposely don't put a camera tower there. So at
17, if you stand on the tee, you can look straight over the ocean
instead of seeing a camera tower out there.''
</P>
<P>
   One more cool tool in NBC's arsenal (which will be introduced
this weekend) is a boat camera, shooting live from the Pacific
Ocean toward the course. Roy said technology used from coverage of
the America's Cup - putting the camera on a gyromount so it won't
flop around as the surf hits the boat - goes into this device that
will give new looks to the ocean holes 4 through 10 and then to the
magical 17 and 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually happens to be prettier looking from the ocean back
toward the land,'' Roy said.
</P>
<P>
   If that's possible.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   Bob Miller, who just finished his 27th year as the Kings'
play-by-play man, completes the trifecta of Los Angeles' Hall of
Fame broadcasters with his inclusion Thursday in the Hockey Hall of
Fame in Toronto. After Vin Scully and Chick Hearn into the baseball
and basketball shrines, Miller becomes the 22nd hockey broadcaster
to be inducted, honored with the Foster Hewett Memorial Award,
named for the longtime Toronto Maple Leafs announcer. ``I'm very
honored and very surprised,'' Miller said from his West Hills home.
``It's such a thrill. You know, there were times under (former
Kings owner) Jack Kent Cooke when I thought there'd be no way I'd
last a week on the job. This honor was the farthest thing from my
mind then.'' Miller, who now has a lifetime contract with the
Kings, will be inducted in ceremonies Nov. 13. ``I just hope we
don't have a game that night,'' Miller added.
</P>
</TEXT>
