<HEADLINE>
IN RACING MONEY DOESN'T GUARANTEE SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dale Earnhardt Jr. signed with Budweiser for a reported $10
million a year in 1998, it was the most money ever given to a
rookie driver and one of the largest primary sponsorships in
NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years later, it's a pittance.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon recently signed a five-year deal with DuPont that
reportedly will pay him $20 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Valvoline, which has become synonymous with Mark
Martin, is leaving his car after 12 years and will be replaced by
Pfizer's Viagra brand. Reportedly, Pfizer will pay Martin $12
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   As Winston Cup racing becomes more complex and more top teams
run closer together, money becomes a key factor in achieving and
sustaining success.
</P>
<P>
   More money means more research and development, which might
allow you to find an aerodynamic edge in the body or a few extra
horsepower in the engine, and that might mean the difference
between winning and losing.
</P>
<P>
   But money, by itself, does not win races. The key is still
having the right people on your team to build the cars and the
right people to drive them.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is a perfect example of that. Even without the new DuPont
deal, his team was generally considered the best funded on the
circuit, having perhaps $30 million or more to spend annually.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, crew chief Ray Evernham left and took three
or four key people, including Ed Guzzo, Evernham's right-hand man
when he ran Gordon's team. After those losses, Gordon is no longer
in the elite classification.
</P>
<P>
   When good people leave, they are difficult to replace because
there are not that many around. Perhaps Gordon can rebuild; maybe
with the new influx of cash he can simply buy the talent he needs.
But keeping key personnel together is still critical in developing
a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, despite rule changes, new cars and
whatever else has affected the sport, a time-tested group of teams
have stayed consistently on top. Bobby Labonte, Rusty Wallace, Dale
Earnhardt, Mark Martin and Dale Jarrett are always right there.
Since he's been with Martin and Jack Roush, Jeff Burton is another.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has also been in this group, but he has slipped a bit
this year, and money alone won't bring him back.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
