u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-15 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART WORLD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: London, Texas)   By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finalists Picked For Tate Prize
</P>
<P>
   The Tate Gallery in London has announced the finalists for its
2000 Turner Prize, the prestigious $32,000 award given annually to
a British artist under 50.
</P>
<P>
   Every June when the list is released, it is met with a certain
amount of criticism. One year it was attacked for excluding women
and another year for including only women. One year people said it
was lacking in painters in favor of video artists. This year's list
_ three men and one woman _ includes two painters. Three of the
four artists are not British-born.
</P>
<P>
   None are among the trendy YBAs, or ``Young British Artists.''
The native Briton, Glenn Brown, was included in ``Sensation: Young
British Artists from the Saatchi Collection,'' shown at both the
Royal Academy in London and the Brooklyn Museum, but he has never
been considered one of the high-profile YBA's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've moved on,'' said Nicholas Serota, director of the Tate.
``This year's list shows a depth and range of cultural focus.'' He
added that the three artists who are not British-born have lived in
the London area for more than 10 years, in part because London has
good art schools and is a stimulating place for young artists.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Brown, a photo realist painter, the list includes
Michael Raedecker, a painter whose work incorporates thread and
embroidery; Tomoko Takahashi, whose sprawling installations
incorporate detritus and snapshots; and Wolfgang Tillmans, a
photographer known for his still lifes of clothes and portraits.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists' work will be on view at the Tate Britain at
Millbank from Oct. 25 to Jan. 14 . The winner is to be announced on
Nov. 28th. Antiquities Acquired
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth went shopping at this
week's antiquities sales in New York and ended up buying two
exceptionally rare pieces: a Greek vase from the fifth century B.C.
and a bronze Roman head dating from about the first century B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The vase, which the museum bought at Christie's for $1.7
million, was from the collection of Elie Borowski, a collector and
curator of antiquities at the Royal Ontario Museum in Toronto.
Dating from around 480 B.C., the vase measures 11{ inches in
diameter and has painted scenes on both the interior and exterior.
</P>
<P>
   The head, which the Kimbell bought at Sotheby's for $4.5
million, a record for a classical antiquity and an ancient bronze,
measures 11} inches in height. A Roman copy of a lost Greek
original, the head is believed to have been discovered in the 16th
century and was acquired by the 18th-century Venetian collector
Bernardo Nani. More recently it was owned by Hans Calmann, an Old
Master drawings dealer in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two objects will transform our classical collection, which
hasn't been one of our strongest departments,'' said Timothy Potts,
director of the Kimbell. ``There hasn't been anything like these
pieces on the market for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Italian Photographs
</P>
<P>
   Building an impressive photography collection has been a high
priority for the Museum of Fine Arts in Houston. When it opened its
$50 million building in March, the museum had its first permanent
photography gallery. In January it acquired 22 photographs by
artists including Diane Arbus, Gerhard Richter and William
Eggelston. Recently, its photography curator, Anne Wilkes Tucker,
has turned toward collecting Italian photographs from the 1940s and
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   She approached Giorgio Borlenghi, a Houston real estate
developer, and his sister Ermy, both contributors to the museum and
both acquainted with this period in Italian photography. With money
from Giorgio Borlenghi and his wife, Cathy, and Ermy Borlenghi and
her husband, Gordon Bonfield, along with help from some trustees,
the museum formed the Carla and Lorenzo Borlenghi Collection, named
after Giorgio and Ermy's parents.
</P>
<P>
   The collection consists of 18 photographs by photographers who
worked in Florence, Milan, Venice and Rome. ``There were different
aesthetics and schools,'' Tucker said. ``Rome was the center of
paparazzi photographs, while Florence and Venice produced work that
was more formalist and abstract.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the photographs acquired five by Tazio Secchiaroli.
Secchiaroli, who died two years ago, was the celebrity-hounding
photographer who was the inspiration for Paparazzo, the central
character in Federico Fellini's 1960 film ``La Dolce Vita.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said the Italian photographs would be part of an
exhibition going on view in February 2002.
</P>
<P>
   New Costume Curator
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After the much-publicized cancellation of the Coco
Chanel retrospective, which was to be the Costume Institute's big
exhibition in December, officials at the Metropolitan Museum issued
a statement saying that the death of Richard Martin, its chief
curator of the Costume Institute, last November made the Chanel
show impossible to organize. He had initiated the show, and the Met
had no one to fill his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   While people in the art and fashion worlds expressed strong
views _ both for and against canceling the show, which was to be
financed by Chanel _ and with no one inside the museum able to plan
such a complex project, the museum may have felt more pressure than
ever to name a successor to Martin.
</P>
<P>
   This week it announced that Harold Koda, an associate curator of
the Costume Institute in the mid-1990s, was returning as its
curator-in-charge. Koda is to start at the Met on Nov. 6 after
serving as a co-curator with Germano Celant of the Giorgio Armani
exhibition that opens at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum in
October.
</P>
<P>
   The Met also announced that James C.Y. Watt, a senior curator
and expert of Chinese art, had been named chairman of the museum's
department of Asian art. He succeeds Wen Fong, who is retiring on
June 30 and will become a curator emeritus. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
