<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH KIDS TO TAKE TO WHICH MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gone in 60 Seconds
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Cage, Giovanni Ribisi, Angelina Jolie, Robert Duvall,
Delroy Lindo, Timothy Olyphant, T.J. Cross, Christopher Eccleston
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Dominic Sena
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 _ 119 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For a one-step action plot, assign a huge task and allow no
time. In this case the object is to steal 50 automobiles and have
them on a container ship in four days. ``These are not Honda
Civics,'' says Memphis Raines ( Cage), a former master car thief.
You could pay $150,000 for some of these vehicles _ snarly new
Lamborghinis and Ferraris, a 1967 Shelby Mustang GT 500, a 1962
Aston Martin DBI.
</P>
<P>
   So switch off the brain ignition and get ready for a summer
clang-banger of an auto show and demolition derby courtesy of the
producer Jerry Bruckheimer, who wrecked a lot of stuff in ``Con
Air,'' also with Cage, a few summers ago.
</P>
<P>
   Situations like these call for another action staple: the
legendary pro who has sworn off whatever bad thing he was so good
at doing but is forced to resume with extreme reluctance. Memphis,
lately a legitimate go-cart dealer, returns because of his little
brother, Kip ( Ribisi), who is still stealing cars.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of swift, computer-assisted thievery, Kip still throws
a brick through one plate-glass window and drives the Porsche
through another plate-glass window. Little wonder he is behind in
his deliveries to Raymond Calitri ( Eccleston), an auto-theft
impresario eager to meet his quotas and uphold his reputation in
South American stolen-car circles.
</P>
<P>
   Handcuffing Kip to a car about to be crushed in a scrap-yard
compactor, Calitri summons Memphis and tells him to steal 50 cars
in the time allotted or his brother is a bouillon cube. All right,
all right, says Memphis, who then proceeds to fritter away three of
the four days rounding up his old car-stealing crew. With but hours
left, Memphis and associates start picking off the treasured 50.
Everybody drives very fast, and there are a lot of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ People get roughed up and so do the paint jobs.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ Memphis and a colleague ( Jolie) get into the carnal
spirit while waiting for a couple to start lovemaking and become
distracted enough not to notice that their purple Ferrari is being
stolen. But this being a PG-13 movie, things are too hot not to
cool down.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ Some strong cussing can be heard over the engines'
scream.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 11 _ The film is not suitable for young children, but
for age 10 or so some parents may relent.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP _ Those cars. Those chases.
</P>
<P>
   Big Momma's House
</P>
<P>
   Martin Lawrence, Nia Long, Terrence Howard, Ella Mitchell, Paul
Giamatti, Jascha Washington
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Raja Gosnell
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 _ 97 minutes
</P>
<P>
   To trap an escaped killer named Lester ( Howard), an F.B.I.
agent named Malcolm ( Martin) and his partner, John ( Giamatti),
trail Lester's ex-girlfriend, Sherry ( Long), who they hope will
flee and lead Lester to her grandmother's house in suburban
Georgia: Big Momma's house.
</P>
<P>
   A stakeout is set up across the street, but the opportunity to
get into the place to plant surveillance devices presents itself
when Momma ( Mitchell) departs for an extended time away. Malcolm
then decides to become the woman, which plays into Lawrence's
considerable talent for transformation and introduces elements of
``Tootsie.''
</P>
<P>
   To impersonate Big Momma, an extremely large woman, Malcolm
applies great slabs of latex to all parts of his body. The face
especially threatens to slide south, and at one point Malcolm,
making an emergency exit from an upper floor, falls through the
bottom of the rig.
</P>
<P>
   But he certainly fools Sherry, who appears on Momma's doorstep
with her young son, Trent (Jascha Washington). Along with the rest
of the town, Sherry takes to the imitation Big Momma as if she were
the genuine article. Malcolm appreciates Sherry, too, particularly
in abbreviated outfits, but ogling from within Big Momma's
mountainous folds gets awkward.
</P>
<P>
   As Momma, Malcolm finds out that he's a prolific cook of greasy
baked goods and a midwife. (``It's a baby!'' he shrieks during a
birth.) He's also a jivey preacher, a gospel belter and, stirring
in Malcolm's talents, a pretty fair playground basketball player.
Granny's got game, but then Lester appears and Malcolm is forced
into some police activity. Finally the real Big Momma returns, and
there are romantic matters to straighten out.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ Quite a bit, but always comic and plainly so.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ There is the childbirth scene, and Malcolm's Big Momma has
a hard time containing her lust for Sherry.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ The bathroom variety, loud and crude.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10 _ The movie is both relatively harmless and
basically inappropriate for small children.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 _ Lawrence is gamey, but he is a funny man. Children
would have a good time. Parents must decide.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP _ Why, sure.
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai Noon
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Chan, Owen Wilson, Lucy Liu, Xander Berkeley, Walton
Goggins, Roger Yuan, Brandon Merrill
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tom Dey
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 _ 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Unwillingly betrothed to a chubby fellow who stuffs himself with
cupcakes, Princess Pei Pei ( Liu) is luckily kidnapped and ends up
in Nevada, where, the year being 1881, Indians are warring and
Chinese slave laborers are building a railroad. Sent in pursuit, a
detail of imperial bodyguards brings an emperor's ransom to be
offered for her return.
</P>
<P>
   The most determined of the emperor's men, Chon Wang ( Chan),
falls in with a blond, very relaxed train robber named Roy O'Bannon
( Wilson) and rescues a little girl after a wild brawl with a
half-dozen Crow warriors. That makes him a hero in an Indian
village, where he puffs too much peace pipe and wakes up with the
chief's daughter ( Merrill), to whom he is married forthwith.
</P>
<P>
   Many martial arts altercations lie ahead for Chon Wang
(pronounced John Wayne by this time in his adventures), who in best
Jackie Chan fashion erupts as if a string of firecrackers had gone
off in his trousers. O'Bannon, a New Age forerunner, has calming
advice and a habit of disappearing in a crunch. The princess
meanwhile decides she will stay in Nevada to help her laboring
countrymen. Could it be that she has fallen for Chon Wang? And what
is to be done with all that ransom?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ The hand-to-hand combat is furious, funny and partly
realistic. People also get shot and killed, but the cumulative
effect is humorous. &QL; 
SEXA tepee tryst is revealed the morning after.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ Some rowdy cowboy talk.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 8 _ Chan is a delight at any age, but all this would
be confusing, overwhelming and just not right for the little ones.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 8-10 _ The film is a bit of a gray area at this level.
Parents know best.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP _ Fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
