<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT REPORT BLASTS FEDERAL OFFICE OF PIPELINE SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal agency responsible for pipeline safety
is a weak, overly compliant regulator that seldom imposes fines
when violations are found, fails to fully involve state officials,
and often ignores reforms demanded by Congress, according to an
independent study of the agency released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office's conclusions about the Office of
Pipeline Safety largely confirm complaints raised by Washington
state lawmakers and citizens in the wake of last year's deadly
gasoline pipeline leak and explosion in Bellingham, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Since the June 10, 1999, accident, which killed three people,
the pipeline safety office has been criticized by lawmakers and
residents alike for not moving faster and more aggressively to
ensure that the web of pipelines nationwide are safely maintained
and operated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the GAO's report ... paints a picture of an
agency that places disturbing amounts of faith in the industry it
is supposed to regulate, and is either unable or unwilling to carry
out any of its responsibilities under the law,'' said Rep. John
Dingel, D-Mich., who asked for the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GAO report shows that in regard to accident data and in
other areas, OPS monitoring and oversight of the industry is
abysmal,'' Dingel wrote to Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater.
</P>
<P>
   The report was made public the same day that a Senate committee
approved legislation designed to significantly reform the way
pipelines are regulated. That step, along with the report, could
improve chances that Congress approves legislation this year to
make pipelines safer, said Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a scathing report that will give us additional ammunition
to push legislation forward,'' said Inslee, who is sponsoring a
bill along with Rep. Jack Metcalf, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Inslee said he will introduce a second bill next week to address
some of the specific problems highlighted by the General Accounting
Office, which is the investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Among its findings:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The proportion of enforcement actions brought by the
Office of Pipeline Safety that resulted in fines fell from 49
percent to 4 percent between 1990 and 1998. Agency officials
defended that approach by saying working cooperatively with
companies allows problems to be fixed faster.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The agency has failed to put into place 22 statutory
requirements ordered by Congress. Twelve of them date from 1992 or
earlier. The agency has also ignored recommendations from the
National Transportation Safety Board, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that Office of Pipeline Safety did not act
``because it believes (the changes) would be too costly for the
pipeline industry compared to expected benefits.'' However, some
analyses of costs and benefits are flawed because the agency did
not consider all the benefits, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The number of major pipeline accidents increased by 4
percent a year between 1989 and 1998. Over that period, 226 people
were killed, more than 1,030 injured and $700 million in property
damaged. Pipelines carrying hazardous liquids, such as the one in
Bellingham, ``account for the smallest portion of total pipeline
mileage (but) have almost eight times as many major accidents per
mile as natural gas transmission lines.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Kelley Coyner, the administrator of the Office
of Pipeline Safety, said: `We agree with GAO's recommendations. ...
The Office of Pipeline Safety is using its legislative authority
for regulating pipeline safety, testing and enforcement to the
maximum extent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, the Commerce Committee yesterday unanimously
approved a bill that would require more frequent and thorough
inspections, better training for operators and more timely and
detailed public information about the location and condition of
pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   It also would also increase fines that could be imposed, protect
``whistle blowers'' who report pipeline problems, and allow state
and local governments to offer comment on pipeline management
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would require pipeline operators to carry out a
detaalysis to determine potential risks along a pipeline and
adopt a plan for addressing problems where they exist. The plan
would also outline steps the operator would take to safely operate
the pipeline. States would be allowed to review the plans and
suggest changes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it would give the secretary of Transportation authority
to shut down a pipeline indefinitely in the event of an ``imminent
hazard'' and it lowers the threshold for reporting a pipeline spill
from 2,100 gallons to five gallons.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Patty Murray, D-Wash., and Slade Gorton, R-Wash., praised
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bodes really well,'' Murray said. The GAO report also
``shows significant reason for taking action this year,'' Murray
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the outcome here,'' Gorton said. But for the bill to
move to the Senate floor, Gorton must convince Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., that it can earn quick approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``His problem is not going to be any substantive concern with
the bill,'' Gorton said of Lott. ``It's going to be whether there
will be time to do it. If we can convince him that it would move in
a couple of days I think he'll bring it up.''
</P>
<P>
   That is by no means assured. There is opposition from oil-state
senators who believe the bill will lead to onerous, expensive and
not effective regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Challenges will come from the other side as well. Environmental
groups and pipeline reform advocates such as SAFE Bellingham
believe the bill should be even tougher.
</P>
<P>
   The original bill, introduced by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was
named after two 10-year-old boys who were killed in the Bellingham
accident. The version approved yesterday did not include the name
because aides said they could not contact the parents in time to
find out if they agreed with some changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5198 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DROUGHT-ART-2TAKES-NY     06-15 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERE DROUGHT AFFECTING LARGE SECTIONS OF SOUTH AND MIDWEST
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JO THOMAS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALPARAISO, Neb. _ The pond on Dave Barry's farm, once six feet
deep, has dried to a mud puddle, and the purple flowers on the
surrounding alfalfa are an ominous sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should reach two feet before it blooms, but it's only four
inches,'' Barry said the other day as a hot, dry wind ruffled the
stumpy plants. ``It's fit for a lawn mower. It's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in eastern Nebraska, in a swath of the Gulf Coast from
Florida to New Orleans, in the hills of West Texas and in Georgia
and Alabama, pockets of extraordinary drought, by some measures the
worst in a century, are baking farms and homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, alligators are roaming out of lakes and ponds that
have all but disappeared. In southeast Louisiana, rice crops and
drinking wells are being ruined by salt water that has seeped into
the parched aquifer. In West Texas, ranchers are selling off goats
and sheep as the grasslands dry up. In Georgia, the red soil is
baked hard as concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Here and there this week, the first rain in months has fallen.
But far more will be needed and the damage is already done for many
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   John Saichuk, a rice specialist in Louisiana State University's
Cooperative Extension, said salt water that has been drawn into the
depleted aquifer is killing crops and can also ruin the soil and
next year's crop.
</P>
<P>
   In Concho County, Texas, Lance Rasch, the county extension
agent, said most ranchers have liquidated their herds, with only 25
percent of the livestock left compared with four years ago. Some
large ranches have no livestock at all, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not just farmers are feeling the effects.
</P>
<P>
   In the lush suburban neighborhoods of Tampa and Atlanta, ``water
police'' roam, enforcing regulations to restrict watering lawns.
</P>
<P>
   Parched communities in northern Florida have become tinderboxes,
with almost daily brush fires in several counties. The smoke from
one brush fire that raged just outside Orlando earlier this month
set off fire alarms in a downtown hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the severity in some areas, the effects are not as
widespread as in some past droughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a drought of national geography,'' Agriculture
Secretary Dan Glickman said. Glickman said it has not affected
prices and production of major crops like wheat, corn and soybeans
or pushed up food prices, as a nationwide drought did in 1988. ``I
don't believe we're going to have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, where the drought has hit, it has hit uncommonly
hard. Glickman said there is little precedent for the weather's
extreme volatility in recent years, with severe dry spells and then
torrential rain and floods. ``That's what's unusual _ those intense
weather patterns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Collins, chief economist at the U.S. Department of
Agriculture in Washington, saw serious effects on production of two
crops _ peanuts and cotton. In Alabama, which produces 10 percent
of the nation's peanuts, growing conditions for 83 percent of the
crop are poor, indicating sharply reduced harvests.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, source of half the nation's peanuts, 28 percent of
the crop has been caught in such conditions. In Texas, source of a
third of the nation's cotton production, the department says 21
percent of the current crop has been struck.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers in parched areas who rely on irrigation have been hit
doubly hard, by the drought and the rising cost of the oil to drive
the irrigation systems. Sen. Bob Kerry, D-Neb., said that in the
state's southwestern corner, the cost of irrigating wheat has
jumped from $100 an acre to $200.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Gov. Mike Johanns of Nebraska declared a state of
emergency and sought aid for the most stricken counties.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Dutcher, the state climatologist, says the drought began
in the southeastern corner of the state in the middle of July last
year. ``It wasn't really until the month of September that we saw
everyone in the state go dry,'' Dutcher said. ``It was eight weeks
before anyone got precipitation at all. Then it was dry again until
February.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska wheat farmers depend on fall and spring rains to build
up moisture in the soil. With no rain, farmers found themselves
needing 25 inches of rain in a growing season that typically
provides 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now need 200 percent of normal rainfall,'' Dutcher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pastures didn't respond this spring,'' he said. ''We
didn't have the moisture for growth when it was cool, and the
temperature skyrocketed in May. We had 100 degree readings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing that went down was the wheat crop. Harvesting
will begin this week, but our yields in a lot of places will be 50
percent or less. In the southeast, a lot of people are cutting the
wheat for grazing, as supplemental cattle feed.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the governor said he would allow farmers in 46
counties to harvest grass along state and federal roads to feed
their animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the lack of moisture and the hot, dry winds, there's a
lot of fear,'' said Merlyn Carlson, Nebraska's director of
agriculture. ``As streams decline, we may have to restrict
irrigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska has 13 million acres in corn, sorghum, and soy beans.
And 55 to 60 percent of this is irrigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Center-pivot irrigation has to run 24 hours a day,'' said
Dutcher. ``There's no moisture in the soil to rely on. Irrigators
will not be able to keep up with crop water demands. ``
</P>
<P>
   Barry, who farms 1,500 acres of corn, soybeans, and alfalfa, was
manning water pumps on his farm the other day, but only for 60
acres. ``The price of fuel makes watering corn that sells for $1.60
a bushel a waste of time,'' he said. ``Without rain, we'll have to
water for 60 days, and we'll lose $1 a bushel.''
</P>
<P>
   He has already moved his 160 cows, with their calves, to
pastures where it rains, 280 miles away, at a cost of $2 a mile. As
he drove away from his rock-hard alfalfa fields, which yielded only
a fourth of their usual harvest this spring, he passed Conservation
Reserve Program pastures, held in reserve for soil conservation and
wildlife. Today the Federal government released them for use by
farmers who want to rent them for grazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too late for us,'' Barry said. ``I've moved my cattle.
People south of Lincoln sold theirs two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Roadside haying, which will begin next Monday, ``could help
some,'' he said, ``but there's bottles and cans and broke- off tree
stumps. You ruin as much equipment as you make in hay.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unless rain falls soon, South Alabama could be facing the driest
first half of a year in this century. Already, Alabama has been
scorched by the worst drought since the 1950s with rainfall a foot
below normal in some areas this year and two feet below over two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Don Siegelman has declared a state of emergency in 19 of
the state's 67 counties. Faye and Joe Williams and her husband,
Joe, raise corn, cotton, peanuts, grain sorghum for their cattle on
1,000 acres in Newton, in the heart of the drought in far southeast
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal year, the 5-foot, 3-inch tall Williams could hide in
her corn stalks. This year, she noted, ``It's up to my waist.'' She
said, ``We didn't plant as much cotton as anticipated. We got all
of our peanuts planted but about a third came up.'' Williams one of
the farm's said the farm has two streams that have gone dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farming has got way out of balance too,'' Williams said.
``Everything we have to buy is up, up, up but the prices are at a
standstill level.''
</P>
<P>
   On his farm near Montezuma, Ga., Lynmore James cannot graze his
cattle on barren pastures and the earth is baked hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't dig a hole'' James said. ``You can't get anything to
scratch the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We could get the blues,'' he added, ``but we try to keep in
good spirits. We go to church and we meet and talk about our
problems. ''
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Much needed rain fell on Wednesday in South Alabama and the
Florida Panhandle but unless the thunderstorms stick around for
days or even weeks the rainfall will not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, the first real rain in months fell on Tampa, and
people rushed outside to watch and to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think once the rainy season has begun, we might catch
up slowly,'' said a cautious Eric Oglesby, a hydrologist for the
National Weather Service at Ruskin, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In east Nebraska rain is spotty. It may rain an inch in Lincoln,
as it did this week, and only a few drops will fall on Barry's
farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a miracle to make a corn crop,'' he said.
``Ten inches have to go into the ground in the next ten days. An
inch isn't going to do us any good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
