<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-RESTORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDMARK STATUS FOR HARLEM BUILDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By NINA SIEGAL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though their days were embittered by segregation and
prejudice, African-Americans in Jazz Age New York always suspected
that life was sweeter on Sugar Hill.
</P>
<P>
   As they gazed up the hill from ``the valley,'' as central Harlem
was sometimes called, Harlemites saw a shimmering bluff that would,
from 1929 until midcentury, become a hub of elite black society.
The names of those who lived there read like a Who's Who of black
history: Ralph Ellison, Thurgood Marshall, Joe Louis, W.E.B. Du
Bois, James Baldwin, Adam Clayton Powell Sr., Zora Neale Hurston,
Duke Ellington and Paul Robeson, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some seven decades after the grand 19th-century row houses,
brownstones and apartment buildings on Sugar Hill were first opened
up to black renters and home buyers, the neighborhood is expected
to become an official historic landmark on June 27, when the New
York City Landmarks Preservation Commission designates a section as
the Hamilton Heights/Sugar Hill Historic District.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first phase of a process that will ultimately create
a historic district encompassing almost 400 buildings from 145th
Street to 155th Street, with jagged borders from Edgecombe Avenue
to Amsterdam Avenue. The next phase is expected to begin in July,
and the commission hopes the whole district will be designated as a
landmark by June 2001.
</P>
<P>
   One might expect that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has said that
he is looking to improve his relations with the city's minority
residents, would be shouting from the rooftops about the landmark
designation. Not so. In fact, the commission chairwoman he
appointed in 1994, Jennifer Raab, who is widely credited with
pushing through the designation after almost 15 years of inactivity
on the issue, is reluctant to call the district a ``black
district.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a phenomenal volume of perfectly preserved row
houses,'' Raab said. ``They have their stoops, their ornaments, and
it is remarkable in New York to find such a volume of intact
architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked whether she considers Hamilton Heights and Sugar
Hill a black historic district, Raab said, ``I will have to think
about that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Landmark designation is always a subject of debates, and talking
about race in any context is touchy. Landmarks officials seem to be
particularly wary of combining the two. They may be sensitive, in
part, because of previous accusations by some preservationists that
the commission has neglected Harlem since it designated the
Hamilton Heights Historic District, just south of the new district,
in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Once the commission finally began carving out the new district
in an area almost consecrated in black lore, the debates became
more complicated: Should a historic district be created based on
its architectural merits or on its cultural history?
</P>
<P>
   This question is not unique to New York. In other cities where
``heritage tourism'' is encouraged in historic areas like
Bronzeville in Chicago's South Side and Beale Street in Memphis,
preservationists have also encountered difficulty in convincing
officials to define these areas as ``black historic districts.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hamilton Heights/Sugar Hill will be one of the largest
such districts in the nation when it is completed, it has not been
a simple matter to trumpet it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the historic row houses on the hill were designed for
rich white families at the turn of the century. It was not until
the end of the 1920s _ late in the Harlem Renaissance _ that blacks
were allowed to buy and rent the palatial homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the commission calls it, there's no question that
we're into a celebration of revolutionary terrain, because this is
the central launching pad for black leadership in postwar
America,'' said Carolyn Kent, a chairwoman of the landmarks
committee for Community Board 9 in West Harlem, which encompasses
the historic district.
</P>
<P>
   Yet today, African-Americans are not the only ones living on the
hill, as more homes are owned or rented by Hispanic, Asian, West
African and white people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at it as a black district historically, but how can we
say that now?'' said George Goodwill, chairman of the community
board. ``It's tricky and it could become quite confrontational. I
try to stay away from controversy and let the name Sugar Hill speak
for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Mayangar says she was the only white person living on West
147th Street between Convent and St. Nicholas Avenues in 1988, when
she bought a four-story brownstone for $300,000. She knew something
about the area's cultural history at the time, but moved in because
of its well-preserved homes and the prevailing sense of
neighborhood pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the architectural reasons we want to keep it that way, not
just the cultural reasons,'' she said, adding that two mixed-race
couples recently moved onto her block.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Landmarks Preservation Commission was created in 1965,
it has designated about 1,000 individual landmarks and about 70
historic districts. According to the commission's spokeswoman,
Terri Rosen Deutsch, cultural factors ``drove the designations''
for a few sites in the city, like the recently designated Charlie
Parker house on Avenue B. But, she added, ``I don't think there's
any building that you can look at that we designated solely for
cultural reasons. They all have some architectural merit.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is an increasingly vocal group of preservationists
throughout the city who would like to change that. One is Laura
Hansen, a director of Place Matters, a joint project of the
Municipal Art Society and City Lore, a cultural organization.
</P>
<P>
   She said it is sometimes hard to make the argument for cultural
designations. ``It's a lot easier to interpret how to regulate
something with architectural details, simply because there's a lot
of consensus in the architectural canon,'' she said. ``But with
cultural history, there's a lot less agreement about what should be
included.''
</P>
<P>
   Yuien Chin, coordinator of the Hamilton Heights/Sugar Hill
Historic District Committee, said Sugar Hill was a test case. ``It
has presented a unique opportunity for the commission to really
grapple with the idea of cultural landmarking,'' she said. ``It is
an issue that is not unique to Harlem, but it's really important
here because it is one of the largest African-American communities
that has made such an impact on the history of its people, and it
should be acknowledged as such.''
</P>
<P>
   Some preservationists who argue this point say historic
districts like Greenwich Village and South Street Seaport are de
facto white historic districts.
</P>
<P>
   A loose-knit group of Sugar Hill residents first introduced the
idea of creating a landmark district there about 15 years ago, but
the commission lost their documentation, Goodwill of the community
board said. In 1994, when Raab became chairwoman, she announced
that one of her top priorities was Harlem; three years later, a new
group of residents formed a committee to push again for a historic
district.
</P>
<P>
   In the early planning stages, the commission focused on the
exquisite row houses on the side streets, but was skeptical about
including several large, more modern apartment buildings on
Edgecombe Avenue. To some neighborhood historians, the idea of
forsaking Edgecombe was unfathomable. The street sits on the cliff
above central Harlem, and the long stretch of towering apartment
buildings, many residents argued at commission hearings, were like
the gates of the Emerald City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgecombe Avenue is synonymous with Sugar Hill,'' Chin said.
``It was the first place that people think of when you mention
Sugar Hill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
