<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT WITNESS SHOCKED 
BY RACISM ALLEGATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
 TESTIMONY-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For more than two decades, Walter Quijano has
nudged his career as a clinical psychologist into becoming one of
the most respected expert witnesses in hundreds of criminal trials
across Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Chief psychologist for the Texas Department of Criminal Justice
for more than five years and a former consultant for the Federal
Bureau of Prisons, Quijano has expertise in substance abuse
counseling, mentally ill prison populations, sex offenders and
other forensic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past 10 days, however, the 51-year-old Quijano has
seen his reputation plummet from respected social scientist to
pariah _ all because of racially tinged testimony he gave at a 1996
capital murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Quijano said Thursday of the fallout from the
Victor Saldano case, which the U.S. Supreme Court last week sent
back for a new sentencing trial.
</P>
<P>
   He initially viewed the court's action as one indicating some
procedural error involving the inadmissibility of evidence at
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then it turned ugly, and (people are saying) I am a
racist,'' said the Filipino-American. &UR;  &LR; ``That part shocked me.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked the attorney general's office to send him a copy of the
transcript of his testimony in the Saldano case ``because, my God,
if I am appearing racist in my testimony, I should apologize and I
should quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saldano case, however, is just the first of several capital
murder convictions that could be jeopardized by Quijano's
testimony. Since the Saldano ruling, Texas Attorney General John
Cornyn has identified six other capital cases in which the
psychologist gave somewhat similar testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Then earlier this week, the fallout spread to civil proceedings
against predatory sex offenders examined by psychologist Roger
Saunders, whose expertise has been called into question solely
because he is Quijano's associate.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys with the state prison system's Special Prosecution
Unit on Wednesday dropped trial proceedings against Terry D.
Ingram, the first Texas sex offender the state had hoped to force
into continued treatment and surveillance under a new Texas law.
Four other sex offender cases could be similarly affected because
Quijano or Saunders was scheduled to testify as an expert witness.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Saunders' credibility was impugned by Quijano's
testimony in the capital murder cases.
</P>
<P>
   Quijano said he and his partner, who practice in Conroe, Texas,
are among several psychologists with whom TDCJ has contracts to
examine sex offenders to determine if they should be subjected to
civil commitment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But Quijano insisted Thursday that statistical data about
over-representation of racial and ethnic minorities in Texas
prisons _ the kind of testimony that has jeopardized the capital
murder cases _ is not part of his evaluation of sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Although both types of cases involve the prediction of future
dangerousness, Quijano said Texas' sex offender commitment law is
so tightly written that experts can analyze only three issues:
whether the person's crime was predatory, whether it was violent
and whether he has a behavioral abnormality that likely will make
him a predator in the future.
</P>
<P>
   When one critic told Quijano that his discussion of race and
ethnicity equated to testifying that a person is genetically
predisposed to commit future violence, Quijano was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my gosh, if that is how I am coming across, that is no
good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one weakness in my presentation is that I assume when
I say statistical significance, people know what statistical means
_ that it is simply a manipulation of numbers and that it is simply
a correlation, not a causation,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Quijano's testimony in various capital cases ranges from the
mere use of the word ``race'' in one case to more lengthy
discussions about Hispanics, African-Americans and percentages of
different races and ethnicities in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The issue raised by Quijano about the Hispanic ethnicity of
Saldano, a native of Argentina, was one of 24 factors listed in a
chart to convince a Collin County jury that he posed a future
threat of violence and deserved to die for the 1995 murder of Paul
King.
</P>
<P>
   But Quijano said he has been working ``from the same outline''
for the past 25 years, regardless of whether he was testifying for
the defense or the prosecution. And never once _ until Saldano's
defense lawyers raised the issue on appeal _ has anyone criticized
or tried to bar his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   He said sometimes defense lawyers have asked him at trial to
elaborate on race or ethnicity. It offers a chance to explain that
minorities historically have faced disadvantaged upbringing that
mitigates against tough sentences, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people never had a chance,'' Quijano said.
``They grew up in a violent neighborhood, they grew up with an
education that's poor, nobody inspired them to go to school, there
are no jobs. In other words, I am describing a very horrible
upbringing that happens to minorities not because they are white or
black or green but because of lack of opportunities, historical
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Quijano is hoping his tarnished reputation is only a temporary
setback, but whether he has become such a lightning rod that
neither side will risk hiring him in the future remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter has a reputation for speaking the truth as he sees
it,'' said psychologist Windell Dickerson, who gave Quijano his
first job after he finished graduate school. ``You may or may not
agree with what he sees, and he may not always be politic about how
he words things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
