<SLUG> BC-AUTO-DODGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO TECHNOLOGY: A HYBRID WITH BRAINS AND BRAWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hybrid-power vehicles, the engineers point out, can
come in all shapes and sizes. The first two on the market are the
two-passenger Honda Insight and the five-passenger Toyota Prius.
</P>
<P>
   They are notable for using electric motors to achieve remarkable
gasoline fuel economy. And they look like hybrids: eggy, sleek and
futuristic.
</P>
<P>
   But DaimlerChrysler is demonstrating another tack entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the red-meat hybrid, an SUV as brawny as a pure gasoline
version, in exactly the same body, with the same tough-looking
wheels and grille, and four-wheel drive. But this Dodge Durango is
modified to get 30 percent of its horsepower through an electric
motor instead of from the gasoline engine. As with the Japanese
entries, the result is better fuel economy. The improvement is just
three miles per gallon, but on a big sport utility like the
Durango, that is a full 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler showed the truck here recently at the conclusion
of the American Tour de Sol, an annual electric-car race.
</P>
<P>
   An early fan was Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, who is chairman
of the Energy Committee. ``Feels like a normal car,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Insight, a two-seater that gets about 70
miles per gallon but owes part of that to its sleek form and
aluminum frame, or the Prius, which has a slightly boxy appearance,
the hybrid Durango prototype is indistinguishable from the gasoline
version _ unless you spot the ``state of charge'' meter on the
dashboard, or crawl under the front to see the 70-horsepower
electric motor, mounted sideways, that drives the front wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the soccer mom car,'' Senator Murkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   It is also, by far, the simplest of the three. The Insight has
an electric motor sandwiched into the drivetrain between the
gasoline engine and the manual transmission. The Prius has a
planetary gear, a specially developed device that means that at any
given moment, the electric motor can be working alone, or assisting
the gasoline engine, or draining energy from the gasoline engine to
recharge the battery.
</P>
<P>
   The Durango is far simpler; an ordinary V-6 gasoline engine in
the front drives ordinary wheels in the back, and the electric
motor under the front of the car turns the front wheels; the only
connection between the two drivetrains is the pavement. When the
driver pushes the brake pedal, the electric motor switches into a
generator, robbing the car of momentum and converting that into
current to recharge the batteries.
</P>
<P>
   If the batteries are depleted as the car cruises, the motor in
front will start letting the wheels drag a little and recharge the
batteries, using the pavement to transfer energy from the gasoline
system to the electric one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a leap in technology that can get you an instant
improvement,'' said William Craven, a project-management specialist
who works on the Durango and the Epic, the company's all-electric
minivan.
</P>
<P>
   His competitor, David Hermance, an executive engineer at Toyota,
whose car and its unusual gearing system is perhaps more of a leap,
put it differently.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, he said: ``There are three attributes
you're trading off _ emissions, fuel economy and acceleration, or
performance. You decide what it is you want your vehicle to do in
those three attributes, and then you size your internal-combustion
engine and your motor so as to get the combination you're
interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   To get acceleration, Hermance said, use a larger gasoline
engine; to get better fuel economy and pollution control, favor the
electric side.
</P>
<P>
   The Toyota relies on the electric motor alone when it is moving
slowly, and the Honda makes heavy use of the electric motor every
time the driver shifts to a higher gear; both shut off the gasoline
engine entirely when the car is waiting at a stop sign or red
light.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them were designed as hybrids, from the ground up. And
both, but especially the Honda, gain performance by shedding
weight. Their performance is good but nothing special.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Durango weighs the same in the hybrid version,
and performs about the same _ that is to say, like a hard-charging
bull. It has a slightly lower towing rating than the all-gasoline
version of the Durango. The Prius and Insight, on the other hand,
are unlikely candidates to tow anything.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler said that teaming the 3.9 liter V-6 with a Siemens
3-phase AC induction motor gave ``V-8 performance with better than
V-6 fuel economy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the parlance of this emerging technology, the Durango is a
``mild hybrid,'' and the Insight and Prius are ``heavy hybrids.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other differences. The Prius and Insight have no
direct cost comparisons, since they are not new versions of an
all-gasoline car, but both appear to sell at a modest premium above
what a conventional gasoline car that size would cost.
</P>
<P>
   American manufacturers suggest that Toyota and Honda are
actually taking considerable losses on each of the cars sold,
something that DaimlerChrysler does not seem willing to do.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler says each hybrid Durango would cost $3,000 extra
to make; it is lobbying for special tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese entries are on the road now. The population of
hybrid Durangos is one lonely preproduction prototype. If the
Chrysler division decided now to produce it, the hybrid would go on
sale in about three years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ASPEN-FRAUD-SUIT-2TAK     06-15 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASPEN-FRAUD-SUIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAMBOYANT OIL INVESTOR IS SUED BY ASPEN GROUP FOR FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: skedded earlier as KAZAKSTAN-INVESTOR) 
 By STEVE LeVINE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMATY, Kazakhstan _ One of Viktor Kozeny's strengths has always
been audacity.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Kozeny, an investment promoter, graduated
from Harvard, returned to his Czech homeland, and persuaded 800,000
local citizens that they would earn 10 times their money by
investing with him. Labeled the ``pirate of Prague'' after he left
town with $200 million and most other participants in the
investment plan almost broke, Kozeny said it was ``hurtful'' to be
unappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting two years ago to Aspen, Colo., Kozeny awed the rich ski
town with his extravagance, which included buckets of beluga caviar
and $1,000 bottles of Chateau Petrus. Soon, Aspen people had
entrusted Kozeny with their money _ an estimated $450 million in
what would become another investment-gone-bad.
</P>
<P>
   When some complained, Kozeny accused them of ``rabid greed'' and
sour grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Kozeny, 36, appears in trouble because of what his
former Aspen friends call his own greed. His fortune is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   In the sternest and most detailed of a chain of legal setbacks,
U.S. District Judge Lewis Babcock said on Tuesday in Denver that
the Aspen group had a ``substantial likelihood'' of proving fraud
and racketeering against him.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also raised questions about the accuracy of a report
by the Zurich arm of the Chicago-based accounting firm Grant
Thornton LLP, which the plaintiffs say they relied upon in making
their investment.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves a venture, managed by Kozeny, to acquire
control of the lucrative state-run petroleum company in Azerbaijan,
a former Soviet republic adjoining the western Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, including the Wall Street hedge-fund manager
Leon G. Cooperman and an insurance giant, the American
International Group, are seeking $160 million, representing their
$141 million investment plus interest and legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperman and AIG have obtained orders freezing Kozeny's assets
in from courts in Aspen, London, the Bahamas and the British Virgin
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The assets include some odd items, such as a couch hand-sewn
with 33 alligator skins, according to court documents. But there
are also art and furniture collections from the 17th, 18th and 19th
centuries; a wine cellar with 500 bottles of rare merlots and 23
cases of vintage Port, a sprawling Bahamas home, a London mansion
and a 23,000-square-foot Aspen chalet.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone at Kozeny's Bahamas home was busy in numerous
attempts to obtain comment. Kozeny also did not respond to an
invitation to present his side, conveyed through Jacqueline S.
Miller, his lawyer in Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The judges in all four courts have so far accepted the essence
of each other's findings. But Babcock's 41-page opinion is by far
the most comprehensive written analysis of the case, quoting the
judges in London and the British Virgin Islands, who said there was
a strong case of fraud, and largely accepting the plaintiffs' key
assertions of fact.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock wrote that the Aspen plaintiffs had demonstrated
evidence that Kozeny had ``engaged in racketeering activity by
perpetuating frauds and laundering monetary instruments or funds.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, which is not expected to be resolved until next year,
is emblematic of the boom-time fever that prevailed in the Caspian
region until about two years ago _ with its share of adventurers,
mysterious middlemen and outright con artists.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, Kozeny bought his $19.7 million home on Red
Mountain in Aspen, a haunt of entrepreneurs seeking venture capital
from some of America's most receptive investors, and began holding
lavish parties. An affair on Dec. 20 included a private concert by
Natalie Cole and was said to have cost $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   At all of them he spoke of a killing to be made in Azerbaijan
oil. Many in the affluent crowd felt part of a fashionable Viktor
Kozeny club.
</P>
<P>
   A networking bacchanalia erupted. Neighbors, including Frederick
Bourke of Dooney &AMP; Bourke, a handbag company; and a Florida
investment adviser, Aaron Fleck, staked an estimated $50 million on
Kozeny's venture in Azerbaijan. Then, Fleck introduced Kozeny to
New York friends, including Cooperman, who assembled other
investors including AIG and a Columbia University trust fund. The
former Senate majority leader, George Mitchell, was persuaded not
only to invest, but to help lead a Washington lobbying effort that
Kozeny suggested would help the investment.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, however, the warm feelings about Kozeny soured.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan made clear that it was not selling its oil company.
And Kozeny's investment vehicle _ privatization vouchers and their
accompanying option certificates _ became worthless, mostly because
the oil company was thought to be the only Azerbaijani state
enterprise worth buying.
</P>
<P>
   Kozeny was unmoved when his American partners protested. He
countered that they had lost money in ``an extraordinarily reckless
and imprudent speculation.'' In court papers filed in Denver, he
said, ``The exhibits tell a story of the extraordinary risks men
possessed with rabid greed will take when they see a
once-in-a-lifetime chance to reap billions.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozeny also blamed Azerbaijan's government, saying it had
deceived him. Azerbaijani officials have denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperman declined to comment. But in the suit, he and AIG say
they sued Kozeny not over Azerbaijan's refusal to sell the oil
company but because, they contend, Kozeny defrauded them from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Their contract, they say, specified that they would not pay more
than Kozeny did for the vouchers and option certificates needed to
buy control of the Azerbaijani oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Kozeny bought his options for an average of 40 cents each,
according to documents and affidavits filed in Denver, then in
November 1997 persuaded officials in Azerbaijan to raise the price
to the equivalent of $25.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on the official price, Cooperman and AIG wired $75.1
million to Kozeny's Swiss bank to cover the purchase of 3 million
options. That gave Kozeny an instant profit of $73.8 million, which
the suit asserts Kozeny diverted into his personal accounts.
</P>
<P>
   According to bank documents filed in Denver, Kozeny spent $9.7
million of Cooperman's and AIG's money on his Aspen chalet. The
expenses included the construction of a gymnasium for his wife,
Ludka, and a suite of rooms for a woman described as his ``female
companion.''
</P>
<P>
   At Kozeny's instruction, the documents assert, workers built a
hiding place beneath his house, painting over a wall to camouflage
it, and created another hidden space in his closet.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperman and AIG contend that another important reason they
were misled was a Grant Thornton report that, they say, vastly
understated Kozeny's inventory of vouchers and options. On May 23,
they filed six claims seeking a total payment of $160 million from
Grant Thornton, asserting that the report produced an erroneous
inventory on which they relied.
</P>
<P>
   The report, researched by Grant Thornton before their investment
was made, showed that Kozeny possessed just 300,000 ``extra''
options _ those not needed for his own investment.
</P>
<P>
   Dated March 24, 1998, the report was signed by Rolf Hess,
managing partner of the firm's Zurich office. The Grant Thornton
accountant who prepared the report, Ian Bryson, included a chart
dated March 13 that showed there were 10,156,000 extra options,
according to documents filed in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a memo written on June 29, 1998 by another Grant
Thornton accountant, Marlies Nievergelt, noted that in the previous
report ``we only showed 300,000'' extra options ``instead of
approximately 8 million.'' The memo said Kozeny had made $93
million on the option sales.
</P>
<P>
   Kozeny, the memo added, had instructed Nievergelt to ``make sure
that these figures are not being disclosed to anyone outside but
remain for internal use only for the time being.''`
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Hess said the March 24 report he
signed was not an official audit. ``Normally, firms are in trouble
if they sign an audit report that is not correct,'' Hess said.
``But we never acted as auditors, but as accountants and as
bookkeepers.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Bryson's inventory, Hess said: ``I can't comment on
that because I am not aware of any discrepancy. What is really
important is what Grant Thornton officially issued. If people have
internal documents, they might be preliminary and not a final
report.''
</P>
</TEXT>
