<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M UNIVERSITY AWAITS 
WORD ON FUTURE OF BONFIRE 
 

</HEADLINE>
 PROBE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After six weeks huddling with students, alumni,
parents and others, Texas A&AMP;M University President Ray Bowen is
scheduled Friday to announce the future of his school's most
venerable tradition _ bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   While Bowen has done a seemingly good job of keeping secret his
decision amid intense lobbying, a consensus of bonfire proponents
and opponents are prepared for this year's event to be canceled at
the College Station campus.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, most believe Bowen will appoint a panel to
determine if a safer, cost-effective design and construction
process can be established for future bonfires.
</P>
<P>
   Any subsequent one likely will be significantly smaller than
recent ones, which often exceeded the school-mandated 55-foot
height limit, they said.
</P>
<P>
   A special commission studying the cause of the Nov. 18 bonfire
collapse, which killed 12 and injured 27, determined it fell
because of poor construction techniques, inadequate supervision and
an unstable wedding cake design.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bowen) hasn't told me what he's going to do, but my gut
feeling is that this will be his approach,'' said Texas A&AMP;M Regent
Dionel Aviles of Houston. ``That seems to be what most people
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M chemistry professor Danny Yeager, a longtime bonfire
critic, said he also believed that will be Bowen's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's to the detriment of the university and to the
detriment of the students because it makes Texas A&AMP;M look
foolish,'' Yeager said.
</P>
<P>
   Representing the burning Aggie spirit, the bonfire has grown
from a small trash fire in 1909 into a mammoth timber tower
organized and built each year by students.
</P>
<P>
   If the bonfire is canceled this November, it would be only the
third time since 1909 it did not burn for the school's football
game against cross-state rival, the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, school officials canceled the bonfire in honor of the
slain President Kennedy. Last year, the bonfire was canceled after
the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be disappointed if it didn't occur this year, but we're
not going to erase safety in order to have a tradition,'' said
student government President Forrest Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen took on the one-man task of determining the future of the
bonfire after the special commission presented a report in May
outlining the cause of the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which cost the school $1.8 million, blamed the
entire Texas A&AMP;M culture for tunnel vision that blinded officials
to problems with the bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   In making a decision, Bowen must look carefully at the
commission's judgment that the school likely could not adequately
train students to build a safe bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that were possible, it would be too costly to train new
students each year, the report determined.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there will likely have to be a major overhaul of
the entire bonfire process, starting with creating the first
blueprints for the structure if it is to continue. The commission
was critical of the way students passed down the design by word of
mouth each year, allowing for dangerous deviations.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition, Bowen must walk a tight political rope,
balancing safety concerns against intense pressure to continue the
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can get things done for a bonfire this
year,'' Aviles said. ``But you probably can in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the decision, most voiced support of Bowen, who
has said he will use his brain and not his heart to make a final
call.
</P>
<P>
   Students and former students have mounted lobbying efforts to
keep the bonfire burning. More than 8,000 signatures were presented
to university officials by students. The Association of Former
Students sent Bowen a letter urging him to continue some form of
the bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
