<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANTASIZING A FANTASTIC FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS - It's no longer a question of whether they'll win
the NBA championship or even when they'll win it. It's a question
of how.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it ends tonight, Monday or Wednesday, the story of the
1999-2000 Lakers deserves a great tagline.
</P>
<P>
   How should it end?
</P>
<P>
   It should end with one more Kobe Bryant lob pass and Shaquille
O'Neal dunk, symbolizing the two stars' synthesis, reliving the
signature moment of the classic comeback against Portland, bridging
the 12 years between this Lakers team and the Showtime champions
who gave us the Coop-a-Loop.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Robert Horry flying past three bigger
opponents to grab one more rebound and lay it in the basket.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Ron Harper driving for a textbook layup past
a guard who's 10 years younger and a step quicker.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Rick Fox luring one more opponent into a
charging foul, goading one more opponent into a shoving match,
giving one more referee a ``who, me?'' look.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Derek Fisher diving for one more loose ball,
leaving one more layer of skin on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Brian Shaw flinging in one more 3-pointer -
off the backboard for comic effect.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with John Salley dispensing one more one-liner,
matching his points-per-game average.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with the Lakers falling behind early, then
catching up and going ahead, then flinching at prosperity and
falling behind again.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Phil Jackson sitting calmly on the bench,
refusing to call time out, as his team gives up 20 points in a row
to make every other Lakers partisan break out in a cold sweat.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Glen Rice sitting next to Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with the Lakers on the court figuring out for
themselves what's going wrong and correcting the problem in the
nick of time.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Bryant breaking a leg in the first quarter
and scoring 20 points in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with an opponent causing injury by committing a
``flagrant'' foul against O'Neal - the injury to the opponent, not
Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with O'Neal sinking a free throw with seconds on
the clock to give the Lakers the winning point - after missing nine
in a row to make that necessary.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Jerry West in hiding, too nervous to watch
the NBA Finals in person or on television, emerging only after
receiving the good news from a carrier pigeon.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Roy Firestone phoning to ask West, ``Who
won?''
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Jackson saying he's close to figuring this
team out.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Christina Fernandez Rice calling a press
conference to announce her husband Glen is trying free agency and
to charge that Jackson is to blame for the Kennedy assassination.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Dennis Rodman watching in a bar, Nick Van
Exel watching in Cancun, Kurt Rambis watching from the press table,
Del Harris reading the result off the stat sheet.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Jerry Buss celebrating with a girl and a
bottle of wine - the wine old enough to be the girl's mother.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with David Stern conducting the trophy
presentation on a satellite hookup from a WNBA game.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with Chick Hearn signing a contract extension to
keep him behind the Lakers microphone through the 2010 season or
through his 100th birthday, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   It should end with A.C. Green issuing one last warning against
proclaiming Shaq the new Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Kobe the new Michael
Jordan or the 2000 Lakers the equals of the 1980s Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should end in a blowout. But we've always liked to prolong
things, to go down to the seventh game, and win in the fourth
quarter,'' Green said Thursday, as the Lakers, up 3-1 in the
best-of-seven-game series, pondered the possibility of an
uncharacteristically quick wrapup. ``As long as we win in the end,
I don't care if we kick the ball in (the basket).''
</P>
<P>
   ``It should just (begin ital)happen(end ital),'' Fisher said.
``I think for this basketball team, that's how it's been all year,
it's just happened. It hasn't been predetermined, it hasn't been
planned out, it hasn't been one guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can write a script for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   If I could write a script, the final act would be the lob.
Bryant driving, O'Neal spinning around an overaggressive defender,
Kobe catching O'Neal's eye, Kobe throwing it up, Shaq throwing it
down. The sudden blend of the fundamental and the spectacular.
Summing up the season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, summing up the playoffs, we might have to wait till
Game 7 for them to get it right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
