<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5211 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-DEATH-PENALTY-N     06-15 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEATH ROW DISPUTE, A WITNESS STANDS FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: a Washington-datelined folo is attached) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Nineteen years ago, Bernadine Skillern caught a quick
glimpse of a man who had just committed a nighttime murder in a
grocery store parking lot. She identified him in court as Gary
Graham in testimony so strong that, despite almost no other
evidence, a jury found him guilty and later sentenced him to death.
</P>
<P>
   With Graham scheduled to die next Thursday and death penalty
opponents mounting an all-out effort to stop his execution,
Skillern testified again Thursday, this time in the court of public
opinion. Again and again at an hourlong news conference, Skillern
repeated her unwavering belief that Graham was the man she had seen
shoot Bobby Lambert outside a Safeway supermarket in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Graham shoot and kill Lambert on that parking lot in
1981,'' said Skillern, 53. ``That has not changed. That is not
going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Skillern's emotional but unflinching appearance was a pointed
rebuttal in a public relations battle that, until now, has been
dominated by advocates for Graham.
</P>
<P>
   With protests planned in Texas for next week, the Graham case is
attracting national attention and creating a political headache for
Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee who has staunchly defended capital punishment in his state
despite growing outside criticism focusing on, among other issues,
the quality of legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's advocates say his original trial was a travesty: His
court-appointed lawyer, Ronald G. Mock, conducted virtually no
investigation of the case and put on new witnesses during the guilt
phase of the trial. Ballistics tests showed that a .22-caliber
revolver taken from Graham after his arrest did not match the
murder weapon. Two other witnesses who could have contradicted
Skillern's story were never called to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other case that has more doubts of innocence today
than this man right here,'' said Lawrence C. Marshall, legal
director of the Center on Wrongful Convictions at Northwestern
University, which has helped exonerate nine death row inmates in
Illinois and has taken on the Graham case.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting before a bank of television cameras at a conference
table Thursday morning, Skillern said she decided to speak out
because of ``misinformation'' about the case in the news media. On
the night of May 13, 1981, when she witnessed the murder, Skillern
said, she waited in her car with her two youngest daughters, then
nine and five, as her 14-year-old daughter shopped inside the
Safeway. It was about 9:30.
</P>
<P>
   According to the trial transcript, Skillern testified that she
saw Graham ``off and on about 60 seconds, maybe a little longer.''
She told the jury she saw the side of his face, then she blew her
horn, at which point she looked directly at his face for ``a split
second, maybe a second.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, she repeated roughly the same story, saying that she
saw his face from different angles three or four times over a
period of 90 seconds. Looking through her windshield, she said, she
looked directly into his face when he walked in front of her
headlights, about a car distance away. She honked her horn, she
said, because she wanted to stop him from shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Don't! Don't shoot,''' recalled Skillern, who held
her news conference in the office of her spokesman, Rusty Hardin, a
former state prosecutor who is now a defense lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference earlier in the week, Graham's advocates
praised Skillern's sincerity but raised questions about the
reliability of eyewitness testimony in general, particularly in the
absence of other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Thompson, a rape victim from North Carolina, told of
identifying her attacker, who was convicted and sentenced to
prison, only to later discover from DNA evidence that she had
identified the wrong man.
</P>
<P>
   So certain was she of her initial identification that when she
was later shown a photograph of the real assailant, she said it was
not him. (He was ultimately convicted, based on DNA evidence.)
</P>
<P>
   Graham's advocates have suggested that detectives steered
Skillern toward identifying Graham by manipulating mug shots and
the subsequent lineup.
</P>
<P>
   But Skillern disputed any suggestion that she had been unduly
influenced. She said that she had picked out Graham's mug shot, but
that she had wanted to see him in person to confirm her belief that
he was the killer. When she saw him in the lineup the next day, she
said, she shuddered with fear, not realizing that he could not see
her behind a glass wall.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles will vote on
whether to commute Graham's sentence or go forward with the
execution. In 1993, the Board voted against commutation but
then-Gov. Ann Richards granted Gray a 30-day stay of execution that
led to his case being re-examined.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who did plead guilty to a string of armed robberies, was
17 at the time of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Graham has already received one stay sets up a
tricky legal situation. Under Texas law, a governor is only allowed
to grant an inmate one stay of execution.
</P>
<P>
   As is his custom, Bush has remained silent about the Graham
case, but a campaign aide said the governor's legal advisers
believe that under the law Bush cannot grant a stay. Advocates for
Graham say the law could be interpreted to mean one stay per
governor, but they say commutation or a conditional pardon, which
can occur only with the parole board's blessing, to allow a new
trial is their real goal.
</P>
<P>
   Skillern has not spoken publicly about the case since Graham was
nearly executed in 1993. She said her testimony has altered her
life. She quit her job as an elementary school secretary because of
controversy from the trial, though she now works as a secretary in
a local school district. She said she has received death threats
and harassing telephone calls. But, she said, she has never changed
her mind about what she saw that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very sure,'' she said. ``There's never been a doubt in my
mind. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEFENSE PURSUES HITMAN THEORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Graham's lawyers are pursuing a theory that the man
he was convicted of killing, Bobby Lambert, was actually murdered
by a hit man.
</P>
<P>
   Federal court records indicate that Lambert had been arrested in
Oklahoma City in August 1980 on charges of drug smuggling. Federal
officials had subpoenaed him in hopes that he would testify against
higher-ups in the alleged drug operation.
</P>
<P>
   Just prior to his murder, Lambert had been seen inside a grocery
store with a thick wad of bills. ``We thought he was killed for his
money, said Steve Beck, the head Drug Enforcement Administration
agent in Oklahoma City at the time of the murder, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But police found $6,000 in cash in Lambert's back pocket after
his killer fled. ``That makes it seem rather strange to me, that it
was a robbery,'' Beck, now a private investigator, said in a
telephone interview. ``That does cast a rather funny connection on
the shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston district attorney has dismissed the possibility of a
hitman as ``pure speculation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
