<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soros to Turn to Outsiders to Help Run Hedge Fund
</P>
<P>
   George Soros said that a $6.5 billion revamped Quantum Fund
would seek lower returns and be run in part by outside money
managers as he continues to withdraw from hands-on management of
his huge hedge funds. Soros, 69, said he would put more of his
money into more stable real estate and private equity investments.
He also said that the new fund, which will be created by merging
the Quantum Emerging Growth Fund with the Quantum Fund, would rely
less on borrowed money than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Legal Maneuvering in Napster Case
</P>
<P>
   Napster, the Internet service that allows music files to be
transmitted online, said that it was hiring David Boies, the lawyer
who led the government's case against Microsoft, to help defend it
in a battle with the recording industry in a case that many see as
landmark for technology-era copyright issues. The industry has
asked a court to stop Napster from operating pending the outcome of
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Plans to Sell St. Louis Unit
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said that it was in talks to sell a parts operation with
1,700 employees at a plant in St. Louis to improve its efficiency.
Potential buyers were not disclosed. The unit makes parts from
sheet metal and composite materials, the type of work Boeing has
sought to shed to concentrate on design, final assembly and
services like maintenance. Shares of Boeing, based in Seattle, rose
$1.3125, to $40.125.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Replies to Appeals Brief
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the battle of the briefs, Microsoft told the Court of
Appeals that the judges should ignore a government brief asking
them not to begin work on the company's antitrust appeal until the
Supreme Court decides whether to consider it.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Steel Makers Attack Limits
</P>
<P>
   American limits on steel imports have cost United States
consumers up to $150 billion in the last three decades, according
to a study sponsored by foreign steel producers. The Clinton
administration dismissed the report, which was written by lawyers
for foreign steel makers and supported by the American Institute
for International Steel, as biased.
</P>
<P>
   `Survivor' Could Help CBS Thrive
</P>
<P>
   CBS's enormous summer hit, ``Survivor,'' soared to new ratings
heights on Wednesday night, pulling in more viewers than CBS has
had on any Wednesday night since the Nielsen Media Research company
transformed its ratings system in 1987. Given the effect that ABC's
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' had on the last television
season, when it expanded from a summer show to a regular-season
show, ``Survivor'' has the potential to turn around CBS's ratings
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Oil Investor Is Accused of Fraud
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has said that investors in Aspen, Colo., have a
``substantial likelihood'' of proving a fraud and racketeering case
against Viktor Kozeny, an investment promoter who persuaded them to
put up $450 million in an investment-gone-bad. The case involves a
venture, managed by Kozeny, to acquire control of the lucrative
state-run petroleum company in Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Heinz Earnings Increase 9.8 Percent
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Heinz, the maker of condiments, tuna fish and frozen goods,
said that its fourth-quarter profit rose 9.8 percent on lower
manufacturing costs and increased sales, meeting forecasts. Sales
rose 4.9 percent, to $2.59 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial Production Rises 0.4 Percent
</P>
<P>
   A burst in output at utilities helped send industrial production
up 0.4 percent in May, the government reported, surprising
economists who had predicted a decline of 0.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
