<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-REPUBS-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      06-15 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP FOLLOWS `SCRIPT' ON PRESCRIPTION DRUGS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas., Va., Md., Okla., Pa.)   (Political Analysis) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans, warned by one of their pollsters
that the prescription drug issue could cost them their majority in
November, are following his script for defusing the issue almost
word for word.
</P>
<P>
   A memorandum from the pollster, distributed to the Republicans
at their caucus last week, suggested ``phrases that work'' on the
issue, including: ``Too many senior citizens are forced to choose
between putting food on the table and being able to afford the
prescription drugs they need to stay alive. In our great nation,
this is morally wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, announcing the Republican drug plan for
government-approved and subsidized private insurance plans, Speaker
Dennis Hastert said: ``In fact, too many senior citizens and
disabled Americans are forced to choose between putting food on the
table and being able to afford the prescription drugs they need to
stay alive. In our great nation, this is morally wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   At a House hearing that day, Rep. Bill Archer of Texas, chairman
of the House Ways and Means Committee, said, ``I really hope we can
proceed on this very, very important issue without turning it into
a political issue.'' The Republican leadership wants the bill voted
on before the July 4 recess.
</P>
<P>
   But five days earlier, Glen Bolger, a pollster with Public
Opinion Strategies, a Virginia firm, warned the House Republican
Conference that the prescription drug issue was a political problem
for Republicans. While the GOP has strong messages on other
important issues aside from drugs, ``Democrats enjoy a huge generic
advantage as the party best perceived as being able to handle this
issue,'' Bolger's memo said.
</P>
<P>
   However the issue may affect congressional candidates,
prescription drugs were the subject last week of Vice President Al
Gore's first national television commercial, which portrayed the
prospective presidential nominee as ``fighting for a prescription
drug benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolger advised the Republican House members in the memorandum
that the issue was ``very important'' to swing voters, including
``rural residents, rural women, white women, South residents, New
England residents, women, working women, homemakers, age 55-64, age
65 plus, women 18-34, 60-plus retired women.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited polls by others showing that only 20 percent of
Americans felt Republicans would do a better job ``helping elderly
Americans get access to affordable prescription drugs,'' while 53
percent said Democrats would do better. Based on focus groups he
conducted for the National Republican Congressional Committee,
Bolger said that people felt ``Republicans aren't doing anything
for seniors'' and that ``upset seniors don't believe politicians
(especially Republicans) understand how important and concerning
this issue is to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He offered the advice, ``It is more important to communicate
that you have a plan as it is to communicate what is in the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The pollster warned Republicans to beware of and answer
potential Democratic attacks like: ``Republicans are in the back
pocket of HMOs, insurance companies and pharmaceutical companies.
Republicans are out to protect the special interests, not the real
interests of senior citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority
leader who had a copy of Bolger's material, said at the White
House, ``The House Republicans have cynically cloaked in
pollster-provided rhetoric a prescription drug plan that benefits
insurance and drug companies far more than it benefits seniors
without drug coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of Bolger's advice dealt with how to sell the issue,
and his clients were plainly listening or reading.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested Republicans say of their plan, ``By making it
available to everyone, we're making sure that no senior citizen or
disabled American falls through the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Rep. Roscoe Bartlett of Maryland told the House:
``By providing prescription drug coverage for everyone, Republicans
want to make sure that no senior citizen or disabled American falls
through the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolger's memorandum said ``seniors like the idea of a voluntary
plan'' and repeatedly urged Republicans to stress that their scheme
was ``affordable.'' Rep. J.C. Watts Jr. of Oklahoma, chairman of
the Republican caucus, told the House: ``Our plan is voluntary. It
is also affordable and available to all.'' Rep. Sam Johnson of
Texas said the Republican plan provided ``coverage for all, and it
is coverage that will be affordable and available for all
seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bartlett, Watts, Johnson and Curt Weldon of
Pennsylvania all cited the food versus prescription drugs dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   But no one followed the Bolger script more earnestly than
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Bolger suggested, ``Our plan protects low-income seniors by
giving them prescription drug coverage, and offers ALL other
seniors a number of affordable options to best meet their needs and
protect them from financial ruin.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said: ``Our plan not only protects low-income seniors
who lack prescription drug coverage, it also offers ALL others a
number of affordable options to best meet their needs and protect
them from financial ruin.''
</P>
<P>
   The pollster wrote: ``A stronger Medicare with prescription drug
coverage is a promise of health security and financial security for
older Americans, and we're working to ensure that promise is kept.
America's senior deserve no less.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker said: ``Strengthening Medicare and providing
prescription drug coverage is a promise of health security and
financial security for older Americans, and we're working to ensure
that promise is kept. Our senior citizens and disabled Americans
deserve no less.''`
</P>
<P>
   Bolger said Thursday afternoon that he was happy to see that his
advice was being taken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
