<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5219 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     06-15 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS TRY TO STAY FOCUSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS - Last fall, Phil Jackson demurred, and a few
months later, he took the hem-and-haw approach. Then he delayed and
pondered and occasionally nodded with a smile, but each time he
skillfully avoided the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Lakers championship material? Their first-year coach
never was ready to make that proclamation - not after sweeping road
trips, nor after beating the league's best teams on their home
courts, nor after a trio of double-digit winning streaks.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)They're growing. They're making me believe.(end
ital) But never a plain, old, (begin ital)Yes, they could win it
all.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Now the Lakers need just one more victory over the Indiana
Pacers to claim their first NBA championship in 12 years. They can
get it as soon as tonight, in Game 5 of the Finals at Conseco
Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The coach can't undersell them anymore, just appreciate how far
they have come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I've been waiting for the, you know, 'aha!' light to go
on in this team for some time, and it comes and goes,'' Jackson
said Thursday, a day after the Lakers' overtime win in Game 4.
``That's one of the reasons I felt that this was premature to kind
of expect anything of that nature yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain sense or a certain nature about a team when
they identify their opponent, they identify their defense, that
they're giving them the understanding offensively what they have to
do. That they get that instinct of how to do it. And it becomes a
matter of putting a puzzle together in a different way, a different
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Reshuffle the pieces and the Lakers have found new ways to
succeed. They won Game 2 of the Finals with Kobe Bryant injured,
took Game 4 with Bryant hobbled and Shaquille O'Neal having fouled
out.
</P>
<P>
   The championship is not yet theirs but certainly close. And the
Lakers are starting to feel the excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really thinking about it, but I'm trying not to think
about it that much,'' said O'Neal, trying to follow his first MVP
award with his first ring, at age 28. ``We still have to win one
game. I don't want to get too amped up. We're going to be very
prepared (for Game 5), we're going to be loose. My guys are going
to be loose.... I'm sure if we get the win, I'm sure all the
emotions will probably come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, they already are seeping out. That giddy hug
O'Neal gave Bryant after Wednesday night's win. The relaxed poses
on the practice court Thursday. The satisfied smiles all around.
</P>
<P>
   Like kids ready to pounce on a new toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to feel like that a little bit,'' said Brian
Shaw, eyeing his first ring after 11 pro seasons with seven teams.
``We are all excited about the fact that we only have to win one
more game to close the series out and be crowned champions. You see
everyone a little more relaxed and having fun today.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the veterans of past championships - A.C. Green, Ron
Harper, Robert Horry and John Salley - are trying hard to remind
their teammates that there is still work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tough, because you start losing your focus and your
concentration,'' said Green, who won titles with the Lakers in 1987
and '88. ``But it's up to the guys on the team and the coaches to
put everybody on the same page. I mean, you can't start sizing your
finger up and wondering, what am I going to do next week? All that
kind of stuff is celebration. This is still a business trip for us
and that's the message I've been trying to give to the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   To lose the championship, the Lakers would have to lose three
straight games. They haven't all season and don't appear ready to
start any new bad habits. But the Pacers have been competitive in
this series and as a veteran team doesn't seem likely to roll over.
</P>
<P>
   So Harper, who won three championships with Jackson's Chicago
Bulls, had a simple message for his teammates: ``The only thing I
told them is get some sleep, because it ain't going to be easy....
You have to earn the ring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
