<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 15, 2000 -- NY-BOWERY-HISTORY -- The
Bowery is nobody's idea of paradise. But when the aging buildings
and their fire escapes shimmer in the morning light, it's a place
of urban beauty, alluring like an Edward Hopper painting. Edward
Mooney House. In around 1789, the merchant Edward Mooney built this
three-story Georgian-influenced house, at what is now the corner of
Pell Street. The structure is Manhattan's oldest surviving town
house and the Bowery's oldest building. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- June 15, 2000 -- CLINTON-ARAFAT --
President Clinton meets with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
left, in the Oval office, Thursday. Looking on are Sandy Berger,
right, Clihnton's national security advisor, and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
