<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BIGDIG-FBI-BOS &LR;      06-15 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-FBI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI, US ATTORNEY BEGIN CRIMINAL PROBE OF `BIG DIG' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY AND THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The FBI and the US Attorney's office have opened a
criminal investigation into the ``Big Dig,'' sources familiar with
the probe said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After nine years of construction and three months of management
turmoil, law enforcement investigators are asking questions about
the massive cost increases that the now-$13.6 billion highway
renovation project has required since it began in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to know who knew what, when,'' said one Central
Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel project official, who asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents have interviewed at least two employees in the
Cambridge office of the Federal Highway Administration, according
to sources familiar with that office.
</P>
<P>
   The specific nature of the investigation could not be learned,
and it is apparently in the early stages. Officials for the FBI and
the US Attorneys office said they could neither confirm nor deny
the existence of any probe.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Landolfi, a spokesman for Turnpike chairman Andrew S.
Natsios, said he was unaware of a criminal investigation into the
Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is apparently not directly related to a civil
probe of the Big Dig's controversial insurance program, which is
being conducted in the office of US Attorney Donald Stern.
</P>
<P>
   It is also separate from a Securities &AMP; Exchange Commission
investigation concerning what Big Dig and state officials told Wall
Street about the financial condition of the project before
Massachusetts borrowed millions of dollars in the bond market late
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Said Landolfi, ``We are continuing to cooperate completely with
the US Justice Department investigation into the insurance
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides that and the SEC investigation, he said, ``We have not
been contacted by anyone else regarding criminal matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Dig officials made a sudden announcement on Feb. 1 that the
project would cost $1.4 billion more than expected. For six years,
Massachusetts Turnpike Authority Chairman James J. Kerasiotes, who
had overseen the project, had insisted that $10.8 billion would be
the final price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Federal transportation officials were furious about the
announcement of the cost increase, which took them by surprise only
hours after they had approved the state's Big Dig finance plan _
which did not reflect the whopping $1.4 billion jump in cost.
</P>
<P>
   The cost increase has since been adjusted to about $2 billion.
In its conceptual stages in the mid-1980s, the project carried a
cost estimate of only about $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The recent large cost increase surprised even officials in the
Federal Highway Adminstration office in Cambridge, which is both a
monitor and a partner in the highway, bridge, and tunnel project.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Markle, Massachusetts division administrator, was
reassigned by his superiors in Washington as a result of the
unexpected cost overrun. And, following a scathing Federal Highway
audit that charged Massachusetts officials with deceiving
Washington about the true cost of the project, Governor Paul
Cellucci fired Kerasiotes in April.
</P>
<P>
   The task force that audited the Big Dig concluded that ``senior
management of the Central Artery project had sufficient evidence of
the potential $1.4 billion cost overrun. The Central Artery project
officials deliberately, however, chose to withhold that
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after federal officials questioned Big Dig officials'
continuing insistence that the project would not cost more than
$10.8 billion, project director Patrick M. Moynihan wrote a letter
rejecting suggestions that costs were being underestimated, and
suggesting that the federal officials did not understand the
project's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to an estimate by the US Department of Transportation
inspector general's office last fall that construction costs could
soar an additional $942 million, Moynihan accused the federal
watchdogs of committing ``factual errors, misstatements, and
misleading calculations.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet only about three months later he and his boss, pressed by
the Secretary of Administration &AMP; Finance, acknowledged the $1.5
billion increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
