 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES (moved on Wedneday, June 7) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June 7,
about a survey of 500 students on ways in which they used the
Internet when selecting colleges included an erroneous reference to
its sponsorship and to the role of Richard A. Hesel, who commented
on the extent of the students' Web access. The poll was sponsored
by an online educational services company, Embark.com, and
conducted by the Art &AMP; Science Group. Mr. Hesel, who works for the
Art &AMP; Science Group, published the results. He is not the publisher
of the group, and the group is not sponsored by Embark.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-GPS-UPDATED (moved on Wedneday, June 13) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June 14
about the improved accuracy of the Global Positioning System
misidentified the car rental company that offers NeverLost, a
navigation system using G.P.S. It is Hertz, not Avis.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
