<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- June 15, 2000 -- VOYEUR-TV-COX -- We've
become a nation of peeping Toms. We like to watch, and we
especially like to watch real people in dangerous, pathetic,
embarrassing or scandalous situations. Of course, television by its
definition is voyeuristic, as are other forms of dramatic
entertainment. The audience sits and watches. Theatergoers watch
actors on a stage, who pretend nobody's watching. Movies take it a
step further, with the action tossed up on a huge screen in front
of an audience sitting in the dark. But television has that added
element of privacy that takes voyeurism to another level. If you're
watching something awful, nobody has to know. (Cox News Service
Illustration)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MARENGO, Ill. -- June 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JUNE 18
-- WAVE -- Infatuated with a tiny Nasdaq stock called Wave Systems,
two brothers caught the ride of their lives. Douglas McCoy, front,
with son, Kyle, and his brother, David, with daughter Haley. The
McCoys who lost a paper fortune in Wave Systems stock, were just
two of many ``wavoids'' who road the stock from $1 to $50. One day
it was a $500,000 gain and shopping for Porsches; the next selling
the Honda to meet margin calls. (Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- June 15, 2000 -- BOX-JUDAH-FAMILY -- Yoel
Judah once kept his distance as a father but now has full custody
of all seven sons. The boys idolize him and none has been lost to
the prison system nor the streets of Brooklyn. And none expects
anything less than to succeed. Judah, seated right, with his sons
Zabdiel, standing, the junior welterweight champion of the
International Boxing Federation and one of his younger sons, also
named Yoel, 8, at Gleason's gym in Brooklyn. (Fred R. Conrad/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- June 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JUNE 18 --
MEXICO-FAIR-COX -- It hasn't taken place yet, but Mexico's July 2
presidential election is already being called the cleanest and most
competitive in this country's tarnished electoral history. The
election is indeed expected to be tight. This is the first race
since 1929 that Mexico's long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, faces the real possibility of losing the presidency.
Vicente Fox, an opposition presidential candidate, at a recent
campaign parade, who has mounted a strong challenge against
Mexico's ruling party, says he trusts the Mexico's elections
institute ``but it is not in control of the whole process.''
(Fernando Vazquez Ortiz/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- June 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JUNE 18 --
FATHERS-VIETNAM-COX -- Among the 58,209 Americans lost during the
Vietnam War, about a third were fathers. The sons and daughters of
the men whose names are chiseled on the polished black granite of
the Vietnam War Memorial in Washington are themselves grown now.
Army Capt. William A. Branch's daughter, Jen, now 32, reaching for
her father's name, was a toddler when he was killed at Dau Tieng in
1970. Ever since, folks have told her, ``Oh, you were only 2. You
didn't know him.'' ``These men did not die for nothing,'' says Jen.
``Their spirit is living on in their children and their
grandchildren.'' (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BEIJING -- June 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JUNE 18 --
NKOREA-INVESTING-COX -- Roger Barrett, the United States' chief
representative of Foreign Business Development, in his Beijing
office. The Foreign Business Development Association now boasts
more than 30 members, including three American companies. With the
blessing of the authorities in Pyongyang, N. Korea, the
association, run like a chamber of commerce, promotes some
government projects while helping member companies navigate the
nuances of North Korea. (Julie Chao/Cox News Service Photo)
