<HEADER>
A5240 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORESHAKE-UP-HNS &LR;      06-15 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALEY REPLACES COELHO AS HEAD 
OF GORE'S PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN 

</HEADLINE>
 SHAKE-UP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
LOCKLAND, Ohio _ As his campaign struggles to regain its footing,
Al Gore announced Thursday that Commerce Secretary William Daley, a
member of the prominent Chicago political dynasty, will chair his
presidential campaign.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daley, 51, will replace Tony Coelho, the hard-driving and
sometimes controversial political operative who informed Gore late
Wednesday that he was resigning for health reasons. Coelho entered
the hospital earlier this week with an inflamed colon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Daley has done an outstanding job as secretary of
commerce. He has done an outstanding job in everything he has put
his hand to,'' said Gore, as he introduced his new chairman during
a hastily called news conference after a campaign event in suburban
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, who flew to Ohio to meet the vice president after
accepting the job early Thursday, takes the helm of a bumpy
campaign that has made several transformations in an effort to win
over voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign is about leadership. It is about setting the
tone for the new century,'' said Daley, who will move next month to
Nashville, Tenn., where the campaign is headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   Daley faces a number of challenges, including calming nervous
Democrats who have watched Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican candidate, successfully move to the ideological center
over the last two months while Gore appeared largely reactive and
unfocused.
</P>
<P>
   The new chairman will also be responsible for ensuring that the
Democratic Convention in Los Angeles in August runs smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Daley and Gore said they did not consult President Clinton
before they made their decision, but called him later. It is not
clear whether the president will name a new commerce secretary with
just over six months left before he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he does not expect Daley to take the campaign in a
different direction, even though the vice president has lost some
ground against Bush since the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to miss a beat,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said the shake-up had nothing to do with
ethical problems that have dogged Coelho, who is being investigated
by the State Department for alleged abuses while he headed the U.S.
mission to the 1998 World Expo in Lisbon, Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that the stress of the campaign had aggravated
Coelho's health problems, which also included three epileptic
seizures this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a wonderful chair and he's a wonderful friend and I
wish him well,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign responded with both sympathy and skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish Coelho well and hope his health improves,'' said Bush
spokeswoman Karen Hughes. ``I wonder whether naming a new chairman
involves yet another reinvention of the Gore campaign. Which vice
president will campaign next week?''
</P>
<P>
   The leadership changes came as the vice president spent the
third day of his ``progress and prosperity'' tour in Ohio
announcing an expansion of his tax cut proposals, made possible by
the growing surplus. Gore said he will propose $500 billion in tax
cuts over 10 years, up from $350 billion in reductions that he
unveiled last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer said Gore was merely
following the Texas governor's lead in advocating tax cuts. Bush
has advocated tax cuts of about $1.3 trillion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The staff changes clearly overshadowed the tour theme, which is
intended to highlight the economic progress during the current
administration and the vice president's plans for using the bulging
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, the son of the late Chicago Mayor Richard J. Daley and
the brother of that city's current mayor, Richard M. Daley, is
considered a shrewd political operator. He led the Clinton
administration's efforts to pass a number of trade agreements,
including the North American Free Trade Agreement and recent China
trade pact.
</P>
<P>
   That could prove a sticking point in Gore's efforts to woo
organized labor, which largely opposed the agreements. Gore made a
point Thursday of calling John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO,
to inform him of the change.
</P>
<P>
   Named by Clinton to head the Commerce Department in 1996, Daley
has forged close relationships with business and was considered
part of the president's inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
