<HEADLINE>
FOX: LAKERS SHOULD LEARN FROM PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS - They have passed nearly every test, and for their
Finals exam, the Lakers get a simple yes-or-no question: Have they
learned to throw the knockout punch?
</P>
<P>
   They hold a 3-1 lead over the Indiana Pacers, and have their
first chance to win the championship tonight in Game 5 at Conseco
Fieldhouse. But the Lakers have yet to close out a series on their
first try.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't proved we've learned anything yet,'' Rick Fox said.
``We've been known to let teams back into a series, so we'd like to
put that to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento came back from a 2-0 deficit and pushed their
best-of-five series to a fifth game. Phoenix went down 3-0, but the
Lakers could not sweep. They took a 3-1 lead on Portland and needed
three more games to win the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the Lakers 3-5 in elimination games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team is never out of a series until you put them away,'' Fox
said. ``We saw a Portland team down 3-1, just like this team is,
and we had a Game 7. That's not something we'd like to deal with
again.''
</P>
<P>
   No joy: General manager Mitch Kupchak, like executive Jerry West
earlier this week, said he won't enjoy this moment until the
championship is won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can really enjoy the Portland series or a
Sacramento series or the game (Wednesday) night, really, until it's
all over, and you're looking back on it,'' he said. ``I think from
an entertainment point of view, people who are basketball people
and fans in general can enjoy this team and what they've done to
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've been away from this level of play for over 10 years
now and we feel we've been in position to compete the last couple
of years. And we also know that getting in this position with
players being healthy, things falling the way they've fallen in the
playoffs, it doesn't come along very often. So we are in a
position, we're up 3-1, and we want to win the fourth game. And
that will be the time that we can sit back and say, 'Hey, this has
been a great year for this team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the famously wrought West won't be here to witness
the potential finale. ``There's no way,'' Kupchak said. ``There's
an excellent chance he won't even watch it. ... I can see how he
feels the way he feels. Because it is torture to sit and watch, but
you kind of have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The other rings: Kupchak said the Lakers would like to see Kobe
Bryant on the Olympic team this summer, provided Bryant's sprained
left ankle has healed. Bryant has been mentioned as a possible
replacement for the injured Grant Hill but has not said if he would
accept an invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played in the '76 Olympics, and I know Jerry (West) played
in the '60 Olympics. Personally, I don't know why anybody would
turn down that opportunity to do it,'' Kupchak said. ``Our No. 1
concern is that he take some time off and get that ankle healed.
And actually I spoke to our team doctor this morning, and he does
need a degree of rest. ... But I don't know why if he's healthy,
why he wouldn't love to play in something like that. And as an
organization, if any of our players played in the Olympics, we'd be
happy for them and we'd be proud to have them on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Bryant, who played 47 minutes in Wednesday's
overtime win, said his ankle was no worse off. He received the
usual dose of therapy Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ankle feels pretty good right now, actually,'' he said.
``I kept the swelling down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
