<SLUG> BC-STATES-ONY-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; Some Like Travel And Others Like Stocks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lawmakers' personal financial statements are made public. &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Laura J. Winter &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 States News Service &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (June 15) - Rep. Bob Borski, D-Philadelphia, did not
earn a dime outside of his government paycheck last year, while
Senate challenger Rep. Ron Klink, D-Murrysville, padded his pot
with stock dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the day when the press and anyone who cared,
stopped by the House Clerk's office to check out House member's
wealth, travel and earnings outside of their salary for 1999. They
earned last year an average salary of $136,000 each for their
service on the Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Filings from the challengers for the lawmakers' seats were also
available in the clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   Senate personal financial forms were released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding the exact amount of wealth each lawmaker held was
impossible to determine because values were given in broad ranges.
Primary homes and spouse's incomes were exempt from the filing.
</P>
<P>
   While Pennsylvania's Senate candidates would like to think of
themselves as sharing few interests, they both like stock market
investments.
</P>
<P>
   While Sen. Rick Santorum, R- Pittsburgh, earned $3,300 to $9,000
from mutual funds. Rep. Ron Klink, the democratic challenger,
earned from $1,204 up to $3,200 from dividends. He also sold joint
stock in Intel, K-Mart and others companies for a total ranging
from $50,000 up to $165,000.
</P>
<P>
   Klink also owned an IRA account with Paine Webber that was worth
$50,000 to $100,000. His wife's IRAs have a possible worth of
$102,000 up to $261,000.
</P>
<P>
   While Santorum is paying off two mortgages on his Pennsylvania
real estate, he did find room for giving. He donated to charity a
$500-fee he was paid for a speaking engagement with the Brent
Society in Falls Church, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Reps. Chaka Fattah and Bob Borski, both Democrats,
enjoyed travel at the expense of private organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Fattah took trips to Palm Springs, Panama City and St. Croix -
paid by the Education Finance Council, Sallie Mae and the Caribbean
News respectively. Fattah was the only Philadelphia candidate with
debt - owing between $10,000 and $15,000 for a personal loan and
between $15,000 and $50,000 to the Law Office of Howard Goldsmith
in legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Fattah is running for his congressional seat unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern Santa Fe picked up Borski's travelling tab
when he in May 1999 went from Washington to Chicago and then home
to Philadelphia. The lawmaker seemed content with his congressional
salary.
</P>
<P>
   A file for Borski's opponent Steven Kush, R-Philadelphia, was
not found at the House Clerk's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Bob Brady's opponent Charles Dougherty, a
Republican, earned a total of $75,266 as a consultant in 1999.
Among his consulting jobs was a stint with the Washington public
relations firm Cassidy and Assoc., which represents political
interests, and the Miss Philadelphia pageant.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Brady was content with his salary and earnings from
dividends - ranging from $2,003 up to $10,400. He held assets worth
$182,000. And while he is an unpaid administrative assistant for
the Metropolitan Regional Council, the organization paid $6,624.80
for his pension.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
