<HEADER>
A5282 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHR     06-15 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NET WORTH: PROFESSOR'S IRRATIONAL ROUTE TO `GENIUS' GRANT  &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Matthew Rabin just won a MacArthur ``genius''
grant _ $100,000 a year for five years _ for his research on how
procrastination and other self-control issues affect economic
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin knows his subject matter. You might say he's a poster
child for procrastination.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old economics professor at the University of
California at Berkeley only recently opened a retirement account at
work, and only after he was prodded by family and assisted by
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   And Rabin admits he keeps too much money _ $20,000 to $50,000 _
in a checking account instead of in a long-term investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict that in five years, I'll have $500,000 in my
checking account,'' he quips. Make that $250,000 or so after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Rabin thinks traditional economic models _ which
assume that people act rationally, in their best long-term
self-interests _ are flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin is among a handful of leading figures in the emerging
field of behavioral economics, which applies psychology to the
dismal science.
</P>
<P>
   Take retirement. Most economists believe this is such an
important issue that everyone will automatically plan and save for
retirement. Therefore, government and employers don't need to
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   But Rabin argues that most people will postpone anything that
involves immediate costs and/or delayed gratification. And the
higher the cost in terms of time and effort, and the greater price
of failure, the more they will procrastinate. That's why so many
people put off retirement planning for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks shockingly irrational to economists,'' Rabin says.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but procrastination also tends to be ``time
inconsistent,'' meaning that in the long-run we do want what's best
for us, but in the short term, we want it and we want it now.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you bring research subjects into a room and say,
``You can have $10 now or $15 in one week,'' some will choose each
option.
</P>
<P>
   But if the choice is $10 in 50 weeks or $15 in 51 weeks,
everyone will choose the latter. However, when the 50th week rolls
around, some will take the $10 rather than waiting another week for
$15.
</P>
<P>
   The ``real killer,'' Rabin says, ``is our overoptimism about our
discipline in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   His research shows that in most but not all cases, people who
admit they're slugs are better off than those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin is loath to suggest any practical applications of his
research, but when pressed, he had some advice.
</P>
<P>
   Ask yourself: How many times have I told myself I'd do something
in the future? If you know you're a procrastinator, establish
deadlines, either external or internal. Get your friends to help.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin has enlisted Richard Thaler, another leading behavioral
economist at the University of Chicago. ``He offers external
deadline services. I owe him $1,000 if I don't switch my money out
of a checking account or submit a paper by a certain day.''
</P>
<P>
   Employers can also help, by offering in-house retirement
seminars that people can attend during their work hours.
</P>
<P>
   Government can help by imposing more investment deadlines,
similar to the April 15 cutoff for contributing to IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin concedes that not everyone is a procrastinator. ``Some
people can't enjoy themselves if they have a project hanging over
their head, so for them, immediate gratification is doing the
project now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabin says his collaborator, Ted O'Donoghue, is one of the few
people he knows who has no problems with self-control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our (research) papers are him observing me and writing
it down and me getting all the credit,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donoghue has heard that line before. ``Matthew thinks I behave
a little too rationally,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donoghue was a graduate student at Cal when he started working
with Rabin. Now he's an assistant economics professor at Cornell
University, although he's now on leave, working with Rabin in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   He describes his mentor as a ``character'' who wears nothing but
tie-dyed T-shirts, except for the time when he had to give a
presentation and showed up in a dress shirt with a tie-dyed tie.
</P>
<P>
   The MacArthur people ``made a good choice, given their stated
goals of helping people who are creative, but outside the
boundaries of traditional research,'' O'Donoghue says. ``We've met
resistance from some of the traditional sources'' of research
funding. The MacArthur money, and the attendant publicity, should
help.
</P>
<P>
   At one of his favorite cafes in the Castro district yesterday,
Rabin was conducting back-to-back media interviews and felt obliged
to pay for my coffee. When the guy behind the counter had to go to
the men's room, he asked Rabin to keep an eye on the till.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he figures I don't need the money,'' Rabin says.
</P>
<P>
   VALUE REVIVAL?: After more than five years of underperformance,
value stocks are making a strong comeback, according to a new study
by Paul Rabbit of Rabbit Analytics, a quantitative investment firm
in Hermosa Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 90 days, there was a tremendous shift toward
value,'' says Rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   The market is roughly divided into two camps: value stocks have
relatively low price-earnings, price-to-cash-flow, price-to-sales
and price-to-book ratios. Growth stocks have high ratios.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, Rabbit says, growth has beat value. But its winning
streak may be over.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit compared the 20 percent of companies in the Russell 3000
index with the lowest PE ratios to the 20 percent with the highest
PE ratios.
</P>
<P>
   What he found: In the 90 days ending May 31, low-PE stocks beat
the Russell 3000 index by 7 percent, and high PE stocks lagged the
index by 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   June, he says ``has been kind of drifty.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at other yardsticks, Rabbit found that stocks with the
strongest earnings surprises (growth stocks) lagged the market by
1.5 percent per month in the three months ending in May, after
beating the market by more than 1 percent per month over the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   He also considered relative strength, a momentum indicator. In
the last 90 days, companies with high relative strength (growth
stocks) lagged the market by 4 percent per month, whereas in the
last 12 months, they beat the market by more than 3 percent per
month.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he found that companies with high dividend yields
(value stocks) beat the market by 2 percent per month in the past
three months, after lagging the index by 1 percent per month over
the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit says he's been a growth investor for the past six years
and is ``hesitant to say one should abandon growth. This economy
has grown in an unprecedented fashion, without inflation,'' because
of productivity gains from technology. ``I'm not convinced
productivity enhancement is over.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks investors should stay in technology, but ``I wouldn't
continue to buy growth stocks with impunity. One should pay
attention to value.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
