<HEADER>
A5287 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CAR-ENTERTAINMENT     06-15 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CAR-ENTERTAINMENT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: portable televisions. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtually all of the entertainment units designed specifically
for cars use LCD screens. There are also floor-mounted
entertainment units designed for the amateur installer; they are a
step up from those that strap temporarily in place. A much bigger
step up is the ceiling-mounted, flip-down television monitor, which
is not recommended for amateur installers. The wiring has to run
inside one of the car's roof support posts and in the ceiling
cover.
</P>
<P>
   The ceiling-mounted televisions have some advantages. Although
they may partly block the rear-view mirror, they will not keep a
parent from reaching into the back seat, as some floor-mounted
units can. And they may also be better for passengers who suffer
from motion sickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are finding out is, kids are more likely to get sick
looking down or level because when they look up they see the
horizon in the peripheral vision,'' Langenhorst said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Oman, a scientist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology who has studied motion sickness for 25 years, agreed
that seeing the horizon might help. When someone watches television
or tries to read a newspaper in a car, he said, ``the motion you
are experiencing does not match the brain's expectations _ you
aren't creating the motion, and you don't have confirming visual
cues.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter where the screen is mounted, some people are
simply prone to motion sickness. Susceptibility decreases as
children mature so preteen-agers are most likely to become ill.
``The one thing users of TV can do is sort of pace themselves, and
if they feel queasy, look away,'' Oman said.
</P>
<P>
   Most mobile televisions use a VCR as the entertainment source,
and many offer jacks for video game consoles. Manufacturers say
more mobile DVD players are on the horizon, and they talk about a
convergence of Internet, navigation and entertainment material, all
accessible on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   As for watching television stations, some systems offer a tuner,
although the signal is not very good in a moving vehicle. ``It's
not going to be the quality TV you enjoy at home with cable,''
Mathews said.
</P>
<P>
   That's just as well, say some child-rearing experts, like Dr.
Dorothy Singer of the Yale University Family Television Research
Center. Although some bemoan the idea that television has invaded
another treasured family ritual, Singer is not concerned that
watching television or videos on trips will dangerously increase
the time spent in front of the tube. But she does recommend that
parents take along videotapes that are instructive and stimulating
and that can be discussed as part of the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think if you are going on a four-hour or five-hour
trip that you should have the TV on the whole time,'' she said. ``I
think that is feeding into the `TV is the baby sitter' attitude
that we fall into.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer recommends that parents use television as a reward if the
children play well together first. And that periods of watching
television be broken up with periods of talking or listening to
books on tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a book in and it really teases your imagination,'' she
said. ``It's like old-time radio. Anything that stimulates the
imagination is good, but when you watch TV, the images are provided
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents who want to heed her advice are in luck. Many
entertainment systems, some using wireless headphones, can
broadcast different programming to each person in the car. That
works out well for Davis and Nancy Weaver and their teen-age boys,
Matthew and Mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys have trouble agreeing on the same entertainment,''
Davis Weaver said. The adult Weavers have a similar problem: He
likes the occasional Faith Hill CD, while she likes to listen to
sports on the radio. With a 30-hour drive from their home in
Landenberg, Pa., to the Florida Keys ahead of them this summer,
they found a solution in a top-of-the-line van with a multizone
entertainment system that lets Davis Weaver listen to the radio
while his wife listens to music on a headset and the boys, also
using headsets, watch a movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quiet in the car now,'' Weaver said. ``It's great. It's
nice to take a long trip.'' And now that his oldest son can drive,
Weaver will be able to spend some time watching the scenery and
listening to his favorite music on a headset without torturing the
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a John Denver-type person,'' he said. ``My kids can't
stand John Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
