<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-NAPSTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPSTER MANEUVERS FOR A COPYRIGHT BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Wash.)   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Napster, an Internet music startup, and the
recording industry sharpened their legal strategies this week in a
battle with potentially broad implications for copyright law in the
Internet era. The moves were punctuated by Napster's disclosure
Thursday that it is hiring the lawyer who led the government's case
against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The legal maneuvering is a precursor to a July 26 hearing in
federal court in San Francisco in a case that many see as a
landmark for unresolved Internet and technology-era copyright
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief filed late Monday, the Recording Industry Association
of America, which represents major record labels, argued that the
court should stop Napster from operating pending the outcome of the
trial. The brief said Napster is contributing to growing and
irreparable harm to the commercial music industry.
</P>
<P>
   Napster, based in San Mateo, Calif., responded Thursday, saying
it had hired David Boies, the Justice Department's special counsel
in the antirust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an obviously important case,'' Boies said in an
interview Thursday, explaining his decision to work with Napster.
``People are focusing on the music, but it's a case that raises
broader policy issues and legal issue'' about copyright law on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Napster makes software that can be used to share music files
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Napster asked Chief U.S. District Judge Marilyn Patel of the
Northern District of California to throw out the industry
association's suit, but on May 8 the judge denied the request,
setting the stage for the case to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   The association brief filed Monday asserts ``over 10 million
Napster users are sharing tens of millions of copyrighted files.''
The brief states Napster is guilty of contributing to copyright
infringement because it knows of the practice, profits from the
practice and has the technological wherewithal to detect the
nefarious activity.
</P>
<P>
   Boies acknowledged Thursday that the recording industry may have
a point, though he argued that studies on the issue are
inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief this week, the association cited a survey it
commissioned by the Field Research Corp., a San Francisco based
research firm, that stated 22 percent of Napster users said that
because of Napster, they don't buy CDs any more or buy fewer CDs.
</P>
<P>
   However, a study by the Digital Media Association released this
week stated that 59 percent of people who download or stream music
over the Internet said the activity has led them to later purchase
music.
</P>
<P>
   Boies said that the case will turn in part on a legal question:
whether the individual Napster users are violating copyright law.
He said Napster will argue they are not.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he said that Napster users are participating on a grand
scale in a behavior that is widely accepted on a smaller scale
today. For instance, he said that individuals would not be sued for
copyright infringement for making a copy of a song or a television
movie for a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Boies said he will argue that if the users of Napster are not
guilty of copyright infringement, than Napster itself cannot be
held accountable for abetting copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   However, the recording association argues that the behavior of
Napster users clearly is not legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not it is lawful for users to share music one on
one, on a small scale, there can be no question it is unlawful when
done on a large scale as with Napster,'' said Cary Sherman, general
counsel for the association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
