<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REFORM PARTY: WAR CLOUDS OVER LONG BEACH
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's convention is taking on some of the trappings
of a World Wrestling Federation spectacle, with partisans
``woofing'' at each other on the Internet and demanding extra
security guards for the thriller of a nominating show in Long
Beach, Calif., in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``COME ON BABY, lets ROCK 'cause we've already LOCKED and
LOADED!!!!!!'' a Texas party functionary said in an e-mail exchange
between party members quarreling over Pat Buchanan's slow progress
toward the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Buchanan have no real candidate to oppose him and
have begun warning of credentials challenges and possible violence
at the convention. ``I anticipate some emotional, physically
aggressive people confronting other people,'' said Cedric Scofield,
a party committee member. ``We need more security.'' He proposed
that floor bouncers be hired.
</P>
<P>
   But Gerry Moan, the party chairman, said opponents of Buchanan's
views may present a bigger problem outside the convention center.
Accordingly, he has moved more funds to perimeter security.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH SNUBS KENNEDY FOE
</P>
<P>
   It would seem like an easy decision for the Republican
presidential contender to endorse the Republican challenger to Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. George W. Bush of Texas knows how to walk around a
political minefield when he sees one. Asked yesterday about Jack E.
Robinson, the only Republican candidate to collect enough
signatures to take on Kennedy, Bush said at Logan International
Airport in Boston, ``It's hard to endorse somebody I've never heard
of.'' Earlier in the day he told radio station WBZ: ``I'm very
close to Governor Cellucci. I'm going to take my advice from
Paul.''
</P>
<P>
   After some uncomplimentary news articles, Robinson, a
39-year-old businessman, released an 11-page list of embarrassing
incidents in his life. Cellucci, who had originally backed
Robinson, dropped his support.
</P>
<P>
   GOP AVOIDS FLORIDA FIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to avoid a divisive primary and protect their hold on a
U.S. Senate seat, Florida Republican leaders and Gov. Jeb Bush
orchestrated a political shuffle that left Rep. Bill McCollum as
the party's presumptive Senate nominee and shifted his chief
opponent to a race for state office. That opponent, state Education
Commissioner Tom Gallagher, announced Thursday that he would seek
his old job as insurance commissioner, deferring to McCollum in the
race to succeed Sen. Connie Mack, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   McCollum was far ahead in the money race but the primary was
likely to have been tough, and could have left the winner weakened
in the general election against the Democratic candidate, Bill
Nelson, the current insurance commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   While Florida Democrats are disappointed that the Republicans
will skirt an intramural fight, many believe that McCollum, who was
a House impeachment prosecutor, will make the better foil.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Canton, Ohio; Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ No public events
</P>
