   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NORTH AMERICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: GUN LAW UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has unanimously upheld the nation's gun
control law, the strictest in North America. Rejecting a challenge
by Canada's 2 territories and 6 of its 10 provinces, the court
upheld the 1995 Firearms Act, which requires the licensing of all
of Canada's gun owners by the end of this year and the registration
of all guns by the end of 2002. Firearms owners had largely
boycotted the licensing process, awaiting the outcome of the court
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: POVERTY CLASHES
</P>
<P>
   Anti-poverty protesters fought with the police outside the
Ontario legislature in Toronto. Several people were injured and at
least three were arrested. Protesting the austerity policies of
Ontario's Conservative government, the demonstrators, some with
their faces obscured with bandannas, gas masks or helmets, attacked
the police with rocks, bricks and paint bombs. The police responded
with pepper spray and horseback charges.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CANDIDATE EXITS RACE
</P>
<P>
   Porfirio Munoz Ledo, one of Mexico's six presidential
candidates, formally withdrew from the race to throw his support
behind the leading opposition contender, Vicente Fox. Munoz Ledo, a
onetime leader of the governing party, helped found Mexico's
largest leftist party in 1989, but was running this year as the
nominee of the tiny Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: BARDOT CONVICTED
</P>
<P>
   Brigitte Bardot was found guilty of inciting ``discrimination,
hatred or racial violence'' for criticizing a Muslim festival in
which sheep are slaughtered, and she was ordered to pay fines and
damages of $7,150. The actress and animal rights activist lamented
in her 1999 book, ``Pluto's Square,'' that ``my country, France, my
homeland, my land is again invaded by an overpopulation of
foreigners, especially Muslims.'' Bardot was convicted for similar
remarks in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: TAX AMNESTY EXTENDED
</P>
<P>
   The government has extended by two weeks a tax amnesty plan
that, according to Finance Minister Shaukat Aziz, has already led
errant taxpayers to declare $96 million in assets. Less than 1
percent of the country's people pay any income tax, and the
military government has declared that such evasion must cease if
Pakistan is ever to climb out of debt.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: DROUGHT RELIEF
</P>
<P>
   Trying to reach drought victims in the remote northern province
of Jowzjan, the United Nations World Food Program is using 700
donkeys to deliver 130 tons of wheat through rugged mountain
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: U.S. TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers, who is traveling through
Africa, met with his counterparts from several southern African
nations in Pretoria, South Africa, to talk about poverty, debt
relief and the effects of health problems like AIDS on the region's
economies. Summers, who stopped in Nigeria and Tanzania before
arriving in South Africa, will also visit Mozambique and Egypt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
