<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-DALEY-NYT &LR;      06-15 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DALEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SON OF CHICAGO: WILLIAM MICHAEL DALEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif.)  (With GORE-COELHO) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To some, Commerce Secretary William Daley is as
affable, self-effacing and disarmingly smooth as any top-drawer
lobbyist in this town. To others, he is the perfect child of
Chicago's gritty machine politics: brass-knuckles tough, vindictive
and, at times, searingly blunt.
</P>
<P>
   But there is broad agreement among those who know him that Daley
is perhaps the best political mind in President Clinton's Cabinet.
And for that reason, many Democrats cheered the announcement
Thursday that Daley will be leaving the administration next month
to become chairman of Vice President Al Gore's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is genetically prepared for this,'' said Sen. Richard
Durbin, D-Ill. ``Politics is in his bloodstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley, the youngest son of Chicago's most famous mayor and the
brother of its current one, inherits a campaign that has been
described by some Democrats as adrift, dispirited and plagued by
divisions. And while no one expects Daley to fix all those problems
by himself, many Democrats say he brings the right mixture of tools
to the task.
</P>
<P>
   He is a centrist with strong ties to business leaders at a time
when Gore is trying to position himself as a prudent manager of the
economy. He is a consummate behind-the-curtains manager adept at
avoiding the kind of controversy that has at times bedeviled the
Gore campaign. And he is tough enough an infighter to enforce
discipline on a campaign that has sometimes lacked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know there is a price to pay if you cross him,'' said Rep.
Robert Matsui, D-Calif. ``And that's extremely important in running
a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Daley, 51, has been a central figure in the
administration's push to get Congress to give China permanent
normal trade relations. Congressional and White House officials
credit Daley not only with being one of the administration's best
lobbyists on the China bill, but also its chief strategist. It was
Daley who drew up the initial list of undecided Democrats to focus
on. And it was Daley who had the best instincts about how to handle
each one, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His instincts are such that he knows when to be exceedingly
blunt, and when to be softer and gentler in tone,'' said Charlene
Barshefsky, the U. S. trade representative. ``He is very affable
and on a dime can become very steely.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Daley's effective handling of the China bill did not sit
well with leaders of organized labor, and Daley will have to move
swiftly to smooth things over with Gore's union allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some wounds out there in the labor community that
need to be heeled,'' said Rep. Rod Blagojevich, a Chicago Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has never run for office, Daley has had ample
experience helping on the presidential campaigns of Walter Mondale,
Michael Dukakis and Clinton. But it was at his father's feet, and
in the mayoral campaigns of his brother, Richard, that Daley
clearly learned his politics.
</P>
<P>
   David Axelrod, a Democratic consultant from Chicago who has
worked for the Daleys, tells a story about how Daley responded to a
newspaper column by Mike Royko describing Daley and his brother,
Richard, as ``too dumb to tie their shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hollering back, Daley called the columnist and said,
``I just want you to know we're all wearing loafers now.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Daley's brother, John, fondly describes how his
younger sibling consistently escaped punishment at their Roman
Catholic school, even though he was engaging in the same kinds of
pranks as the other kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never got caught,'' said John, a Cook County commissioner.
``You couldn't talk the Jesuits out of anything. He just knew how
far to go. He was very smart.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say Daley's suave exterior can hide a vindictive
personality. Rep. Luis Gutierrez, a Chicago Democrat, said that
Daley called his office and berated one of his aides after
Gutierrez endorsed former Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's the kind of Machiavellian person behind the
prince,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   William Michael Daley was born on Aug. 9, 1948 in Chicago, where
he stayed for all of his schooling: De La Salle High School, Loyola
University and John Marshall Law School.
</P>
<P>
   He was president and chief operating officer of the Amalgamated
Bank of Chicago from 1990 to 1993, and has been a partner in one of
Chicago's biggest law firms, Mayer, Brown &AMP; Platt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, after Daley helped run the Clinton campaign in
Illinois, the president tapped him to shepherd the North American
Free Trade Agreement through Congress. And in 1996, Clinton chose
him to replace Commerce Secretary Ronald Brown, who had died in a
plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Loretta, have three children. The family still
resides in Chicago, where Daley returns on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Today, both Democrats and Republicans who support the China bill
lamented that Daley would not be around to help push the measure
through the Senate. But Democrats said they are counting on Daley
to bring the same efficiency to managing the Gore campaign that his
father brought to running Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has the best political gut of anyone I've ever known,''
said Axelrod, the Chicago consultant. ``I think that is an
inherited trait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
