<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-ARAFAT-420&AMP;AD     06-15 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ARAFAT-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAID TO SIDESTEP A STICKING POINT IN TALK WITH ARAFAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton met with the Palestinian leader,
Yasser Arafat, for an unusually long session at the White House on
Thursday to try to set the stage for a summit meeting here, but
they did not resolve one of the immediate obstacles to convening
the meeting, a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, efforts by the administration to get the summit meeting
off the ground are expected to accelerate in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   The official said negotiations between Palestinian and Israeli
officials now under way in Washington would continue for the next
few days. The administration's senior envoy, Dennis Ross, will fly
to the region next week and Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright will go in 10 days to assess whether a summit meeting is
feasible, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, is reported to want the
three-way summit meeting _ Barak, Arafat and Clinton as mediator _
soon after July 4, a timetable that also dovetails with Clinton's
need to hold a meeting before the presidential election season gets
under way in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   During their more than three hours together Thursday, Clinton
and Arafat dwelled on all the major issues of a final peace accord,
paying particular attention to the proposed borders for a
Palestinian state, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   There was little discussion, he said, of Arafat's insistence
that the Israeli government proceed with the final withdrawal from
land on the West Bank called for in the Oslo accords of seven years
ago. Arafat has threatened that if the Israelis fail to make the
final pullout, which would give the Palestinians more than 80
percent of the territory on the West Bank, he would refuse to go
ahead with a summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared from the account by the senior administration
official that Clinton decided to defuse that immediate issue by
putting it to one side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't try to move him off it,'' the official said, adding
that the withdrawal remained ``very important'' to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader publicly kept up the pressure, saying as
he emerged from the White House that Barak was unwilling to do what
he had promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Barak up to this moment lacks a desire to work with us in
order to achieve a comprehensive lasting peace in the region,''
Arafat said. He singled out the slow rate of release of Palestinian
prisoners from Israeli jails. The Palestinian leader said that
Barak was offering to free only three prisoners. ``That's an
insult,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have sounded notes of guarded
optimism and then slight pessimism in the last two weeks as they
have concentrated on pushing the Israelis and the Palestinians
close enough on the issues to merit a summit meeting for a peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In Lisbon two weeks ago, Clinton said that a summit meeting was
``in view'' but made clear that substantial progress was needed to
narrow the gaps on the vital issues of the shape of a Palestinian
state, the future of refugees and the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the White House does not want is a summit meeting that
collapses. ``For a date for a summit we have to be in a position to
have at least a reasonable chance to reach bridging solutions,''
the senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the official said, the two leaders are not yet
prepared to make the necessary decisions on the big issues, and the
talks between the negotiating teams have not yet played out.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's choreography for bringing the summit
meeting together includes a three-pronged approach: the
Palestinian-Israeli talks now in progress in Washington, involving
senior officials from both sides; visits by Albright to the region;
and one-on-one sessions of Clinton with Barak and with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Thursday's session at the White House appeared to
focus on Clinton's sounding out Arafat on what ground he was
willing to give and what Arafat needed from Barak to make a summit
meeting work.
</P>
<P>
   But a fundamental tension has infused the efforts since Clinton,
while in Lisbon, announced his desire for a summit meeting, Israeli
and Palestinian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Israeli side, ``there is a feeling that Arafat wants more
without giving,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Palestinian side, there is an intense frustration, a
Palestinian official said. Israel has threatened that if the
Palestinians reject its request to postpone the final pullout, it
will stick to a decision of the government of Benjamin Netanyahu
and give up only one percent of the West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
