<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB OPPOSITION LEADER IS SHOT IN MONTENEGRO 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ A well-known Serbian opposition leader,
Vuk Draskovic, was shot and wounded on Thursday night at his home
by gunmen, an adviser said. Draskovic was hit twice in the head
when attackers fired through a window from his garden, but he was
wounded only slightly, said Ognjen Pribicevic, Draskovic's chief
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hit in the ear and on the left side of the head,''
Pribicevic said, adding that Draskovic had been taken to a hospital
and was released in three hours.
</P>
<P>
   As leader of the largest opposition party, the Serbian Renewal
Movement, Draskovic is the most important opponent to President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia. Draskovic has been leading a
campaign for early elections to remove Milosevic from power.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his charisma, he has failed to mobilize much support on
the streets in recent months or to unite convincingly with other
opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the government moved to close his party's television
station, Studio B, a sign of its irritation with its presence.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic apparently feared for his safety, and immediately
traveled to Montenegro, Serbia's sister republic in the Yugoslav
Federation, and asked for protection from President Milo
Djukanovic, who leans toward the West.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic has repeatedly accused the government of trying to
kill him and has warned that Belgrade is waging a campaign of
``state terrorism'' to maintain its power.
</P>
<P>
   His party faults Belgrade for an automobile accident in the fall
in which Draskovic's brother-in-law and bodyguards were killed.
Draskovic adds that the truck that slammed into the car was
intending to kill him and his wife, who were in the same convoy.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials have also suggested that the government was
behind recent high-profile murders in Belgrade, including that of
Defense Minister Pavle Bulatovic.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic was watching television alone in his home in a seaside
resort, Budva, when the attackers fired at 11:30.
</P>
<P>
   He thought that there were two attackers who approached through
the garden and broke the window glass as they fired, Pribicevic
said. Draskovic managed to escape to a neighbor's apartment, from
where he was taken to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   From the hospital, he spoke by telephone with his wife, who had
remained in Belgrade. He left the hospital for an unknown
destination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
