<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-WEALTH-NYT &LR;      06-15 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-WEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK IN LAWMAKERS' WALLETS, FAT AND SLIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ill., Mo., N.J., Neb., W Va., Del., Ore., La.,
Utah)   (No byline)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Personal wealth and power do not necessarily
correspond on Capitol Hill, with some of the leading members of
Congress holding few assets and avoiding the booming stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, took the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the majority leader and a former
college professor, has no assets beyond a checking account. He
supplements his income of $151,800 with an annual teacher's pension
of less than $2,500, according to House personal financial
disclosures released Thursday. (Other lower ranking members make an
annual salary of $136,700.)
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of the House, Dennis Hastert, earned a salary of
$175,400 for 1999. He reported assets from investments and real
estate, but also had considerable liabilities. Hastert listed
property, including a 270-acre farm in Shipman, Ill., a town house
in Washington and an opera house in Plainfield, Ill. The building,
which he now rents out, once housed a theater and his father's
restaurant. Hastert valued the farm and opera house at $100,001 to
$250,000; rental income from the farm and opera house, he said, was
$15,001 to $50,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   He is paying mortgages on the property. And he signed loans for
home repair, and co-signed several loans with family members.
</P>
<P>
   The House minority leader, Dick Gephardt of Missouri, reported a
mutual fund worth $15,001 to $50,000, with several other
investments of less than $15,000. But the cost of education
countered his assets. Gephardt, who earned $151,800 in salary, owed
$50,001 to $100,000 on one student loan, and $15,001 to $50,000 on
another. He also borrowed $15,001 to $50,000 on his life insurance
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip, and the House's
third-ranking Republican, valued his Exxon stock at $50,001 to
$100,000 and reported a bank account of $1,001 to $15,000. He has
no significant debt.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1970s, members of Congress have been required
each year to file broad financial disclosure reports that reveal
that they do not have holdings that might pose a conflict of
interest. The rules permit the members to provide a rough snapshot
of their assets and debts.
</P>
<P>
   From the other side of the Capitol, Sen. Robert Torricelli,
D-N.J., was very active in the stock market last year, buying and
selling technology stocks. He made more than 100 stock transactions
last year, sometimes buying and selling stocks on the same day.
Torricelli's stock holdings were valued from $260,000 to $775,000,
for technology companies like Amazon.com and CompUSA Inc., the
computer retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Torricelli bought $1,001 to $15,000 worth of the
DrKoop.com stock on Aug. 5 and sold it the same day. He listed a
purchase of the same amount of Novell stock on Aug. 10 and sold it
the next day. And on Aug. 11, Torricelli bought $15,001 to $50,000
worth of AmeriTrade stock and sold it on Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who is a former investment banker,
reported assets of $1 million to $5 million and $500,000 to $1
million in two Merrill Lynch accounts. He also listed $100,001 to
$250,000 in a Longview Capital fund.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, John Rockefeller IV, D-W Va., reported three
blind trusts worth more than $80 million. Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill.,
listed stock he owns in the Bank of Montreal that he inherited from
his father.
</P>
<P>
   Not all members of the Senate were drawn to the stock market.
Sen. Joseph Biden Jr., D-Del., reported two credit union accounts
of less than $1,000, and at least $15,000 of debt owed to
Mastercard. Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., held a Senate credit union
savings account of $1,001 to $15,000 and property in his home state
worth $200,001 to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's disclosure statements, which were made public on
Wednesday, were not without some quirky details. Sen. John Breaux,
D-La.,, won $5,625 in prize money at a charity tennis tournament on
Long Island. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, received $241.68 for a
brief appearance on the CBS television series ``Walker, Texas
Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the chairman of the Judiciary
Committee, earned composing income of $6,125 from Prime Recordings
Inc. of Provo, Utah, and royalties of $12,048. Hatch, who has
written lyrics for hundreds of songs, and has produced or
co-produced seven CDs, says on his Web site that his music focuses
on ``family, faith and love of country.'' He reported $500 of
royalties from MTV, the music television network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-STEEL-IMPORTS-NYT &LR;  &QC;  &UR; U SAYS   06-15 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEEL-IMPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAYS REPORT FROM FOREIGN PRODUCERS 
</HEADLINE>
   U.S. CURBS ON STEEL IMPORTS ARE COSTLY, By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. trade restrictions on imported steel have cost
customers in this country as much as $150 billion in the last three
decades, according to a new study sponsored by foreign steel
producers.
</P>
<P>
   The report, written by lawyers for foreign steel makers and
supported by the American Institute for International Steel, was
dismissed by the Clinton administration as biased.
</P>
<P>
   The 300-page study takes aim at U.S. anti-dumping laws that it
says protect domestic companies, including Bethlehem Steel and
USX-U.S. Steel Group, against more efficient competitors in Japan,
South Korea, Brazil and other nations. Those protections and some
government subsidies effectively raise the cost of everything with
steel components, from aircraft to kitchen utensils, it said.
</P>
<P>
   ``American consumers and taxpayers have paid a high price to
protect an antiquated industry that refuses to modernize and
compete fairly,'' said Horst Buelte, chairman of the steel group.
``The vital interests of many key U.S. business sectors have been
sacrificed to the narrow demands of the U.S. steel industry.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. steel-making companies have waged an intense campaign to
persuade the Clinton administration to protect them against some
foreign competitors in recent years. The companies pointed to a 30
percent surge in imports in 1998 that undercut the profitability of
domestic steel makers, forcing layoffs and plant closings.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the U.S. steel makers and unions, President
Clinton has imposed punitive duties on a wide range of steel
imports, saying they were sold in this country at artificially low
prices. In response this week, South Korea filed a case against the
United States at the World Trade Organization, protesting measures
Washington took to limit imports of line pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. LaRussa, acting under secretary of commerce for
international trade, called the study ``totally ridiculous and
absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to argue that the U.S. market is not the most
open market in the world, especially in steel,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
