u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLD     06-15 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN CALLS ARREST OF MEDIA COMPANY OWNER `EXCESSIVE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS graf at end with quote from newspaper)  
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian President Vladimir Putin said Thursday that
prosecutors had gone ``too far'' in jailing the owner of Russia's
largest independent media company two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe that this is excessive,'' Putin said
during his state visit to Berlin. ``I think it should have been
possible to handle this without an arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's remarks were the first time that he has criticized the
detention of Vladimir Gusinsky, the owner of Russia's largest media
company, Media-MOST, an influential amalgam of newspaper, radio and
television interests that had been critical of the government.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has repeatedly insisted that he cannot influence the
actions of Russia's prosecutor general, Vladimir Ustinov. And
Thursday Putin stopped short of saying the case against Gusinsky
was without merit.
</P>
<P>
   But his comments raised questions not only about the arrest, but
about Putin's control over his Kremlin aides, many of whom he
inherited from President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   If Putin was not aware of Gusinsky's arrest, as he has said
before, and did not approve of it, as he said Thursday, the
question was who ordered it, and why. Some in the Russian capital,
including Gusinsky's aides, traced the actions against Media-MOST
to Alexander Voloshin, the Kremlin chief of staff, who is close to
the inner circle of the former Kremlin regime, known in Moscow as
the ``family.''
</P>
<P>
   And if senior Kremlin officials had acted behind his back, the
question was whether Putin would try to take action against them,
and thus test his political independence. The Russian president is
expected to return to Moscow on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility was that Putin was simply trying to distance
himself from a decision that had sparked intense criticism at home
and abroad. U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott appeared
in an unusual taped interview on Gusinsky's NTV television network
Thursday and warned that government interference with the press
will hurt Russia's standing in the world.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday Robert Strauss, a former U.S. ambassador to Russia,
canceled plans to lead several top U.S. business executives to
Moscow for a meeting with Putin. The trip was to have been
conducted under the auspices of the U.S.-Russia Business Council, a
Washington trade association. Strauss, who said he knew Gusinsky
when serving in Moscow, said it would be inappropriate to promote
commercial investment there now because the jailing of the top
media executive well known for criticizing Putin ``raised political
and legal questions'' about Russia under its new president.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky was arrested on Tuesday on suspicion of embezzling
millions of dollars in state property. He has denied the charges,
and his detention is widely seen in Russia as a
politically-motivated campaign against a powerful media tycoon who
had criticized the government and made enemies in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year old Gusinsky owns the nation's only independent
television network, one that avoided the Kremlin's embrace during
the recent parliamentary and president elections, and has provided
reasonably objective coverage of the brutal war in Chechnya. He
also controls several important publications.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was put in jail, Russia's most powerful business
tycoons have assailed the move, fearing it could be the start of a
crackdown that could lead to their detention as well.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky remains in the Butyrskaya prison. The chief prosecutor
in the case, Valery Nikolayev, said that charges would be brought
against Gusinsky on Friday, and suggested that Gusinsky might be
released afterwards pending trial.
</P>
<P>
   As the furor over the arrest continued, Geni Reznik, Gusinsky's
lawyer stood outside the prison and read a two-page handwritten
statement that he said came from his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a political intrigue organized by high-ranking
representatives of the government who consider freedom of speech a
danger,'' the statement said. ``During the first interrogation, I
witnessed a laughable scene as two investigators quarreled and
interrupted one another for half an hour as they tried to say what
they suspect me of.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks Thursday, Putin said Gusinsky should not have
been jailed, but merely questioned. Rather than put him in jail,
``It would have been possible to insist that he not leave the
country,'' Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   Ustinov, the prosecutor general, is believed to have been
appointed by Putin at the insistence of Kremlin aides who are close
to members of the Yeltsin family and the financier Boris
Berezovsky, including Voloshin, the Kremlin chief of staff.
Virtually nobody in Russia believes that the prosecutor is truly
independent of powerful political and financial interests.
</P>
<P>
   One view of Putin's role is that he is not yet fully in control
of the Kremlin, but is dependent on aides like Voloshin, who helped
bring him to power. That runs counter to the image that Putin has
sought to foster of a decisive leader who is determined to bring
order to Russia. The other view is that Putin was disingenuous when
he insisted he was not behind the campaign against Gusinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The first scenario, the newspaper Moskovsky Komsomolets observed
acerbically Thursday, ``means the presi- dent is weak and not in
charge.'' The second scenario ``means he is the main persecutor of
dissent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
