<SLUG> BC-COMMERCE-SECRETARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALEY'S DEPUTY LIKELY TO BE NAMED ACTING COMMERCE SECRETARY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is likely to name Robert L.
Mallett, the deputy commerce secretary, as acting commerce
secretary to replace William M. Daley as a result of the
announcement that Daley would lead the Gore campaign, an
administration official said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the White House chief of staff, John Podesta,
convened a meeting Thursday afternoon to begin discussing
candidates to replace Daley for the six months remaining in
Clinton's term.
</P>
<P>
   The official said that the White House had not made a final
decision whether Mallett would be formally nominated to succeed
Daley but that he was on a short list of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Though Mallett ranks as the No. 2 official at Commerce, he keeps
a relatively low profile. He is perhaps best known for his work on
developing trade ties with Africa and working on disease prevention
and poverty relief there. He also helps oversee the department's
many agencies, including the Census Bureau and the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration.
</P>
<P>
   A 1979 graduate of Morehouse College, Mallett attended Harvard
Law School and later worked as legal counsel to former Sen. Lloyd .
Bentsen, D-Texas, and as deputy mayor of the Washington city
government.
</P>
</TEXT>
