<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MILITARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO SELL ST. LOUIS PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. has put a St. Louis, Mo., manufacturing
unit on the auction block, taking an ambitious step in its campaign
to become a leaner player in the aerospace and defense markets.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced Thursday it is talking to a several
potential buyers about its St. Louis fabrications business,
expected to fetch hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The move is the latest, and one of the strongest signs in recent
years, that Boeing is serious about shedding under-utlized plants
and assets as it strives to become a leaner competitor. The
potential sale, however, also left 1,665 Missouri-based employees
in limbo over their professional future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are really trying to rethink what they (should)
be doing and what they should not be ... doing,'' said Sam
Pearlstein, an analyst for First Union Securities. ``We have been
hearing (about) it for awhile, but we have never seen any major
steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives tried to assure the targeted employees
Thursday, saying they expect the new boss to hire most of the
workers.
</P>
<P>
   They backed up that assurance with provisions that call for the
final buyer to take on the existing pension plans and wage scales,
according to a congressional staffer briefed on the transition
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Boeing warned workers to brace for some initial
reductions once the deal is signed, which could take 3 to 6 months,
according to one union leader. Eventually the sale could create new
business and jobs at the facility, according to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   While the union can't block the sale, it ``can and will insist
that all current wages, benefits and other terms and conditions of
work remain in full force'' for the 1,127 union workers, said Tom
Buffenbarger, president of the International Association of
Machinists, in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Boeing had little choice but to sell an asset that
is only operating at 40 percent of capacity to an owner who could
perhaps expand the business and workforce, said Jerry Daniels,
president of Boeing's Military Aircraft and Missile Systems group
in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a prime contractor, we must focus on the strategic aspects
of our business _ aerospace technology development, program
development and the core competencies at which Boeing is or intends
to be the best in the world,'' Daniels said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is also prepared to cut the plant loose because it will
make it easier for the company to land the lucrative Joint Strike
Fighter contract _ a federal prize worth as much as $300 billion _
and other customers, according to Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street embraced the move, perhaps viewing it as a sign that
Boeing is intensifying its campaign to strip away assets outside
its key businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Investors pushed Boeing's stock up $1.56, or 4 percent, to
$40.38 in trading Thursday. By comparison, the broad Dow Jones
Industrial Average rose 26.87 points, or .3 percent, to 10714.82.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fits in line with the company strategy to outsource more,''
said Christopher Mecray, an analyst at Deutsche Bank. ``It's a neat
strategy and we would like to see more of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The asking price for the unit, which builds parts and composites
for Boeing's missiles and military jets, such as the F/A-18 E/F and
the F-15, wasn't available. But, the price could reach roughly $225
million, according to Paul Nisbet, who tracks Boeing for JSA
Research. Nisbet based his analysis on the price the Carlyle Group
paid Northrop Grumman Corp. for an aerospace unit earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Local union officials and Boeing officials are already
discussing the proposed sale and plan to sit down next week to
discuss the transition, according to Rick Smith, president of the
Machinists District 837 in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also put the fabrication unit up for sale only a day
after its chief financial officer, Micheal Sears, told financial
analysts the aerospace giant is likely to accelerate its effort to
consolidate operations in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear where that effort will hit next, but financial
observers expect Boeing to put other assets on the market. While
Boeing officials declined to speculate on any potential moves, at
least one analyst suggested some facilities in Wichita, Kansas,
could be sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have been surprised if it (Thursday's announcement)
had been part of Wichita,'' said JSA Research's Nisbet. ``I think
they will continue to look for units that they can not too
painfully pull out and sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Another obvious candidate for consolidation is California, where
Boeing is likely to get rid of some satellite building facilities
after it acquires Hughes Space and Communication.
</P>
<P>
   There was no evidence Thursday the plan would extend to the
Pacific Northwest, but it's conceivable it could reach Portland and
the Seattle-area, according to one financial observer.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tim Flynn, a spokesman for IAM District 751, said he
had heard nothing about Boeing selling units in the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   But, even Daniels said the company would have to perform with
less in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business philosophy at work here is pretty simple. If
we're going to be healthier, we're going to have to control costs
and do more with fewer assets,'' Daniels told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Information from Bloomberg News was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
