<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD NEIGHBORHOODS APPRAISE DE LA HOYA, MOSLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An imposing two-story banner emblazoned with the
image of Shane Mosley adorns the front of a Denny's restaurant off
the 10 Freeway in Pomona, overlooking the town like a protective
father as his fight with Oscar De La Hoya approaches.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't miss it if you tried.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty miles away, the Oscar De La Hoya Youth Center has become a
pulsating hub - and godsend, according to some parents - in East
L.A. On this day, it's bustling with young boxers trying to emulate
the world champion while others play on computers and do their
homework.
</P>
<P>
   Those in Pomona, unaccustomed to a celebrity in their midst, are
kinder to their favorite son than those across town are to De La
Hoya. The Golden Boy, rich beyond his dreams, cannot win the hearts
of the predominantly Mexican-born population in his old
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many Pomona residents are only now learning of
Mosley, an undefeated fighter whose championship fight with De La
Hoya on Saturday at Staples Center is his first foray into big-time
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   They seem fascinated with his growing celebrity and pleased that
one of their own is making good.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, (begin ital)everyone(end ital) in East L.A. knows
about De La Hoya. Those who watched him grow up have a positive
image of the once-painfully shy boy while others - mostly the
Mexicans - appreciate his undeniable talent but find it difficult
to embrace him.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems clear: No one in either community is bigger than
Shane Mosley and Oscar De La Hoya at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   POMONA
</P>
<P>
   Pomona residents love talking about Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   The East-county town once produced a heavyweight champion, Mike
Weaver, but his star burned out quickly and he fought a generation
ago. Mosley, a young-looking 28, is fresh, exciting, charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   And he's one of theirs. Mosley could afford to live anywhere but
chose to buy a home a few blocks from the house in which he grew up
in Pomona, where his parents still live.
</P>
<P>
   He put it very simply: ``I like it here, I'm comfortable here.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees at Denny's, which is owned by Miles Holland, a friend
of the Mosley family, all know him. He and his family have eaten
there regularly for years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after all the publicity surrounding Saturday's fight, more
and more people approach him with a big smile and an outstretched
hand. Their impressions? The first thing out of everyone's mouth is
the same: (begin ital)really(end ital) nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks to everybody, signs autographs. He's not conceited at
all,'' said waitress Belen Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   The affection goes beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   Locals admit that if Pomona has an image, it's not necessarily
good. That's why they so readily embrace Mosley, who is nothing but
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He promotes a positive image,'' Holland said. ``And he cuts
through all the racial lines. He's just a good person, a successful
person who's still down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Pomona has taken a lot of hits over the years, a lot
of negative stuff. When he stands up for Pomona, that's special.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Tharpe was Mosley's principal when the fighter attended
Roosevelt Elementary School, and now oversees Yorba Elementary,
where Mosley's 9- year-old son, Shane Jr., goes to school.
</P>
<P>
   Tharpe remembers the elder Mosley as a good kid from a good
family who had a ``big, beautiful smile.'' He never found trouble.
Today, the fighter speaks to grade-school children around town,
hoping to point them in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Manzanares, a friend of Shane Jr. at Yorba, is as big a
Shane Mosley fan as anyone on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great person for Pomona,'' the articulate fifth-grader
said. ``Sometimes on TV, he tells people he's from Pomona. Some
parts are bad and he still tells them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Araugo, the cook at Denny's and a resident of Pomona, is
proud to fix Mosley's meals. Araugo, a Mexican national, also is a
big boxing fan. His favorite fighter? No question: Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a home boy, a local guy,'' Araugo said proudly. ``And
he's going to take De La Hoya's (WBC welterweight) title on
Saturday. You just watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like De La Hoya. I've never liked him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EAST L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Velazquez, a part-time taxi driver and journalist in
Los Angeles, said he asked 100 passengers born in Mexico who they
hoped would win on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The result of his poll was predictable: 83 percent said Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Delgado, a 13-year-old born in Mexico and living in East
L.A., spends half his life at the youth center, which De La Hoya
established four years ago. Still, the boy, perhaps regurgitating
what he hears at home, didn't hesitate to express his dislike for
the center's benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really like Oscar,'' he said. ``He tries to be
Mexican, but he really isn't. His parents are, not him. He just can
never be.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one apparent reason Mexican nationals have a problem with
him. There are many others: the fact he twice beat Mexican idol
Julio Cesar Chavez, his pretty-boy image in a macho culture, his
sometimes-reluctant fighting style, perhaps the fact he tries
(begin ital)too(end ital) hard to earn their love and respect.
</P>
<P>
   Even among Mexican-Americans, probably De La Hoya's strongest
fan base, he has his detractors. Their reasons? Jealousy, many
people suspect, or the fact he moved out of his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, who has yearned to be universally loved, today seems
more willing than ever to accept the fact you can't please
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the facts of life,'' he said with a slight grin.
</P>
<P>
   However, all of the above is only half the story.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been touched by De La Hoya - even Mexican
nationals - often have a completely different opinion of him.
</P>
<P>
   Ask 12-year-old Jesus Salas, an aspiring boxer from the
neighborhood who trains at the youth center: ``He did all this for
us so we can come out and train, so we can succeed. He's proud to
be Mexican and it makes me proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Romy Diaz of East L.A., who has three kids who train and
study at the center: ``Hey, I'm a single mother. Where else would
my kids be? I notice a difference in them since they started coming
here, especially in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're learning more. Oscar's the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Rafaela Cortez, who still lives in the house next to the
four-unit apartment building in which De La Hoya grew up. She
remembers an active but quiet boy from a nice family who has
greeted her warmly when he has returned to the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good boy,'' she said through an interpreter. ``He's
doing a good job. The family was so poor. Now, he tries to help
people who are poor. I feel really proud of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he fights, I think, 'He has to win, he has to
win.'''
</P>
<P>
   Susana Ruiz, a Mexican national, runs a taco stand a block from
the youth center. She knows what some people say about De La Hoya
and is baffled by it. She sees clearly the value of the youth
center and other charitable commitments, the living proof that
those from East L.A. (begin ital)can(end ital) achieve tremendous
success in spite of obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   She even pointed out that he recently paid for the funeral when
relatives of a boy who spent time at the youth center were killed
in a car accident a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   This, she believes strongly, is what youngsters should strive to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand, I just don't understand,'' she said
through an interpreter, shaking her head. ``Since he was small, he
forced himself to work hard, to be someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who don't like him, they're jealous because they
can't do what he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Few can, which is the reason people are talking about both
fighters - whether they like them or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-INVESTMENTS-     06-15 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-INVESTMENTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S OPTION TRADING BEFORE '97 TAKEOVER IS CALLED UNUSUAL  
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY and FLOYD NORRIS    
 2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Rick A. Lazio entered Congress in 1993, he had an
unremarkable portfolio of personal investments. With mutual funds,
municipal bonds and a blue-chip stock or two, Lazio had salted away
his money in the kind of assets that countless other middle-class
suburbanites have embraced.
</P>
<P>
   But in August 1997, Lazio suddenly took what appeared to be an
uncharacteristic gamble: he spent $2,300 on speculative securities
trades in a company controlled by some of his campaign
contributors. The securities, called options, gave him the right to
buy shares at a fixed price for a limited time.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks later, Lazio's first foray into high-risk
options trading had paid off handsomely: stock in the company
soared on word of a possible takeover, and Lazio's $2,300 soon
became nearly $16,000, a roughly 600 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lazio, who is now the Republican nominee for the
U.S. Senate from New York, said there was nothing unusual about the
windfall. The spokesman, Dan McLagan, noted that a few months
earlier, Lazio had purchased stock in the company, Quick &AMP; Reilly,
a brokerage house, and that it had been the subject of takeover
rumors. Lazio had simply made a shrewd bet, McLagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Lazio decided to buy options for the first time,
instead of more stock in the company, McLagan said, ``We are not
talking about a tremendous amount of money. He was feeling bullish
on the company. It had good press and it was viewed as a takeover
target. So he invested a modest amount and was hoping for a good
return.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts in securities law, though, said Lazio's entry into
speculative options trading, coupled with his sizable short-term
profit on the deal and his relationship with company executives,
might have led to an insider-trading investigation by the
Securities and Exchange Commission had it been aware of the trades
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first-ever options purchase is always a red flag,'' said
Paul Gerlach, a partner in the law firm of Sidley &AMP; Austin and a
former associate director of enforcement for the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his options profit, Lazio also made a 53 percent profit,
or $6,900, in Quick &AMP; Reilly stock in 1997 and 1998. Over all,
Lazio's trading in Quick &AMP; Reilly securities was far more
successful than any other trades he has made since going to
Washington, according to his financial disclosure forms.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Quick and Christopher C. Quick, former senior executives
of Quick &AMP; Reilly who along with other company executives have
donated at least $35,000 to Lazio's campaigns since 1995, said they
never discussed the company's stock with Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a director and an officer of Quick &AMP; Reilly, I had a legal
and ethical responsibility to the company and to the
shareholders,'' said Peter Quick, who was recently named president
of the American Stock Exchange. ``I absolutely did not talk to Rick
Lazio or any other investor about proprietary information.''
</P>
<P>
   While distinct in important respects _ Lazio engaged in a
different kind of speculation over a much shorter period, and did
not reap nearly as much money _ his options windfall contains some
echoes of the trading success of his Senate opponent, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton turned a $1,000 investment into nearly $100,000 over 10
months by trading in volatile commodities futures when her husband
was attorney general and then governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, by speculating and investing in Quick &AMP; Reilly,
Lazio was making a bet on a company over which he wielded influence
because he is on the House Banking and Commerce Committees. In
fact, members of the Quick family have been officers of the
Securities Industry Association, Wall Street's lobbying arm in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are no rules barring members of Congress from investing in
companies with interests before their committees, but some members
put their investments in blind trusts to avoid even the appearance
of a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Quick, a Long Island resident like Lazio, said in a
telephone interview that he knew Lazio from lobbying on Capitol
Hill. Lazio also serves on the Commerce subcommittee that oversees
many Wall Street issues.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $35,000 in campaign contributions made to Lazio by Quick
&AMP; Reilly executives, at least $8,000 came a month after Lazio sold
the options in September 1997. A Quick &AMP; Reilly subsidiary donated
$2,000 around the same time to a New York political action
committee set up by Lazio, Friends of Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio declined to be interviewed about Quick &AMP; Reilly or to
release copies of his stock-trading records and personal income tax
returns. Information about Lazio's trades was first gleaned from
annual financial disclosure statements that he is required to file
with the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The forms do not detail how much was paid for each share, or how
many shares were traded. That information was provided by Lazio's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal securities law, people are barred from trading in
a stock if they have obtained ``material nonpublic information''
from a company insider. It is legal to trade on the basis of
rumors, so long as the trader has not learned from an insider that
the rumors are true.
</P>
<P>
   There is no indication that Lazio's investments attracted the
attention of the SEC at the time. He described the investments in
financial disclosure forms in 1998 and they drew no publicity until
they were mentioned in an article in Newsday last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission usually begins such investigations when trading
volume and price movement before a deal is announced make it clear
that word of the deal has leaked. But such a circumstance was not
present in this instance, trading records show.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, an extensive search of news articles before Lazio's
option purchase indicates that there was little public discussion
of Quick &AMP; Reilly as a takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   Options are speculative investments because they have only a
limited life. The option Lazio bought would have expired,
worthless, if the stock did not rise before Oct. 17, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's first purchase of Quick &AMP; Reilly came on Feb. 11, 1997,
a few weeks after he joined the House Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio paid about $25.50 a share, adjusted for a subsequent
split. The price rose above $26 when the split was announced a few
days later, but it soon slipped and by late June, Lazio's
investment was showing a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than take the loss, he bought more stock, paying $23.75 a
share on June 24, 1997. It was the first time he had ever added to
an existing holding since joining the House in 1993, records show.
</P>
<P>
   The date of the additional purchase, June 24, was also the day
that Quick &AMP; Reilly hired Gleacher NatWest, an investment banking
firm, to look for a company to buy Quick &AMP; Reilly. Quick &AMP; Reilly
hired Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Company to join the effort on July 10, 1997,
although neither action was disclosed to the public until several
months later.
</P>
<P>
   Volume in Quick &AMP; Reilly stock began to climb when Goldman Sachs
was hired, and the price began to edge up a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 1, 1997, Lazio bought the options on Quick &AMP; Reilly
stock. With the stock trading around $27 a share, Lazio bought
options entitling him to buy shares of Quick &AMP; Reilly for a price
of $30 anytime until Oct. 17, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The $1,396 he spent on the options would vanish if the stock did
not rise above $30 before the expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   After the close of trading on Aug. 1, the Dow Jones News Service
ran an article quoting a Lehman Brothers analyst as saying that
there had been speculation that Quick &AMP; Reilly would be an
acquisition candidate.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 4, Lazio spent an additional $905.48 on Quick &AMP; Reilly
options.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 11, word leaked out that Quick &AMP; Reilly was seeking a
buyer. On Sept. 17, the company announced that it was being
acquired by Fleet Financial Group. On that same day, Lazio sold the
options for $15,944.46, his campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   He sold his stock in Quick &AMP; Reilly the following January,
shortly before the acquisition by Fleet was completed, for $40 a
share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
