<HEADER>
A5314 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-15 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON SET TO JOIN HANNUM IN RECORD BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In 1967 Alex Hannum set foot on a piece of
pristine NBA history. Ever since then he has been an island unto
himself, a survivor starved for more company. If it were up to him,
Hannum would have voted Bill Fitch onto his hallowed grounds in
1986, he would have voted Pat Riley on in 1994, he would have voted
Del Harris on and Chuck Daly on and Lenny Wilkens on, too.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there's a higher power at work. Not any network executive,
not the Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Fate is all.
</P>
<P>
   This being real life as the NBA knows it and not MTV or CBS or
NBC, there was no tidy script that assured a satisfying ending.
There was no guarantee that a coach who guided one team to pro
basketball's championship would win it all again with another
organization to render worthwhile all his sleepless nights and
physical suffering; all the backbiting and the backlashes; the
steady diet of two-legged rats.
</P>
<P>
   Destiny delivered NBA championships to Hannum when he was
coaching St. Louis in 1958 and Philadelphia nine years later. He
was the first coach to win NBA titles with two different teams.
Thirty-three years later, he remains the only one.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a lovely, rather lonely legacy. But Hannum, at long
last, is preparing for company. He's mulling over the wording of
the telegram he plans to send Phil Jackson in the event the Lakers
are able to close out Indiana in their best-of-seven championship
series.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson coached the Chicago Bulls to six NBA titles in eight
years before repairing to his ranch in Montana. He remained retired
for one year, until the Lakers' Jerry Buss and Jerry West offered
him the head seat at a Lakers' table that, while beautifully set,
had had Utah and San Antonio sweep the tablecloth right out from
under the players' noses in successive postseasons, creating a
terrible mess.
</P>
<P>
   In eight months Jackson has managed to sanitize things so that
Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal are breaking bread together and
passing the basketball and the team as a whole is defending so well
it cuts opponents off from second and third helpings of offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rooting for Jackson,'' Hannum said Thursday from his home
in San Diego. ``I can't think of a more deserving guy I'd wish
would get the honor (of joining his exclusive company.) I think the
guy is the greatest. I'm going over in my mind what I'm going to
say to him in the telegram. It'll be short and sweet but it'll
impart how much admiration I have for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers hold a 3-1 lead over the Pacers, and it wouldn't
surprise Hannum in the least if they send Indiana into a sticky
Midwestern offseason tonight, in Game 5 at Conseco Fieldhouse. It
would be just like Destiny, wouldn't you agree, to have Jackson
join Hannum's company exactly one year to the day after the Lakers
hired the ex-Chicago coach to help the Lakers out of their 12-year
championship slump?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great,'' Jackson said, smiling at the thought of
it.
</P>
<P>
   When Hannum heard last June 16 that the Lakers had hired Jackson
to replace Kurt Rambis (who had supplanted Del Harris earlier in
the lockout-shortened season), he knew his days as the only coach
to lead two different teams to an NBA title were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Hannum and Jackson already had so much in common, why shouldn't
they share this honor, too? Hannum played professionally with and
under Red Holzman in Rochester, N.Y. Jackson played professionally
for Holzman in New York, with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's longtime assistant, Tex Winter, played basketball with
Hannum at USC. Winter was the one who set up a lunch between Hannum
and Jackson (a few privileged others joined in) when the Bulls
played the Clippers at the Pond a couple years back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked basketball and found we agreed on many things,''
Hannum said. ``We both live by the credo that the game is the most
important thing, that it's about the fundamentals and having fun. I
remember walking away thinking I have complete respect for this
young coach. He's the glue in my opinion that holds that Laker team
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson doesn't come undone very easily. Opponents have put
together double-digit runs throughout the postseason, causing
Winter's hair to turn a paler shade of white. Time and again Winter
nervously has turned to Jackson to implore him to call a timeout,
only to see Jackson serenely studying his fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 54, is a communicator in the manner of a teacher, not a
tyrant. In his classroom, the triangle offense is a complex
equation and the hardwood floor the blackboard where his players
work out the answer, possession by painstaking possession.
</P>
<P>
   He is content to sit back and let his players problem-solve on
their feet because it's important to Jackson that they learn the
game of basketball and not simply regurgitate what he knows.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has been able to connect with everybody from the
wallflower (A.C. Green) to the class clown (O'Neal) to the whiz kid
(Bryant). If he has failed to reach anybody, it's Glen Rice, the
class rabble-rouser. And yet on Wednesday we couldn't help but
notice that Jackson ran the first play of Game 4 for Rice,
communicating his confidence in his frustrated forward without
saying a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil has always had the knack of getting his main players to
support the game he wants to play and then those guys lead
everybody else,'' said Jack Ramsay, who coached Portland to the NBA
crown in 1977. ``He just has that personal quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson burns his imprint into his teams. Sometimes, yes, with
incense - that ``aromatherapy stuff,'' as Bryant refers to it - but
always with the insight gleaned from a life lived uniquely as his
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``He marches to his own beat,'' Ramsay said. ``He has his own
way of doing things, some of which fly in the face of traditional
coaching. He doesn't care. He's very confident, very calm. The
players see that. They like the fact he doesn't panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Backing yoga, bowing to Eastern religions, giving a nod to
Nietzsche; it's all consistent with Jackson's lifetime search for
peace and contentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about all the Zen stuff, all the trickery,'' said
reserve point guard Derek Fisher. ``It's really not that deep. His
composure and his poise; that's what sets Phil apart. All my
coaches have always been the kind to get after you. They rant a
little bit, they rave a little bit. That was part of the
adjustment, being around a coach who not many things seem to bother
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
