<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5448 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MISSING-BOY-NYT &LR;      06-15 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-BOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETECTIVES HOPE BASEMENT HOLDS CLUES TO BOY WHO DISAPPEARED IN
1979 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mont., Calif.)   By ROBERT D. McFADDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a spring day 21 years ago, 6-year-old Etan Patz
left his family's SoHo loft to walk to his school bus alone for the
first time, and vanished without a trace. Over the years, his
unsolved disappearance haunted investigators and came to symbolize
the agonies of families with children missing in America.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, the prime suspect in what investigators believe
was Etan's abduction and murder has been Jose A. Ramos, 55, a
former mental patient now imprisoned for molesting a boy in
Pennsylvania. While Ramos is said to have made admissions about
Etan, no proof _ or a body _ has ever been found. And Ramos is up
for parole in September.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, working with some urgency but quietly so as to
raise no false hopes of a breakthrough in the case, a dozen police
officers and detectives spent eight hours in the dark, filthy
basement of a tenement at 234 E. Fourth St. on the Lower East Side,
where Ramos was living on May 25, 1979, the day Etan vanished a
mile away.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected to find a body or even fragments of one after so
many years. In the boiler room, however, the police broke up a
rusted, unused 1939 coal-fired furnace and hauled it out in chunks,
and they carried away a dozen blue plastic barrels of ash and dirt
shoveled up from the basement floor. None of the officers at the
scene would comment on what they were up to.
</P>
<P>
   But Inspector Joseph Reznick, the commander of special
investigations, the Police Department's umbrella unit for major
cases and missing-persons investigations, said Thursday night that
all the materials are to be examined for DNA evidence that might
prove that Etan's body had been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge mass of material and my guess is it will take two
weeks to go through it,'' the inspector said. ``There will be no
overnight announcement. But this is a long-term investigation, and
I won't be satisfied until we've done everything possible to solve
this case.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Ramos' parole hearing in September had given
urgency to the search for a crucial missing link. ``It's got our
clock ticking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Etan's parents, Stanley and Julie Patz, who still live in the
same loft at 113 Prince St. and who have campaigned successfully
over the years to raise the national consciousness about missing
children, were told about the search for new evidence, but were not
expecting any major breakthrough immediately. ``Don't hold your
breath about what they're going to find,'' Stanley Patz said.
``Don't forget, this is something we live with every day. It's
difficult to get excited.'' Nonetheless, he remained hopeful that a
case that has seen thousands of leads and theories come to nothing
might finally be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   While no one was ever charged in the disappearance and apparent
death of blond, blue-eyed Etan Patz, Ramos' name surfaced in the
inquiry in the late 1980s when Stuart R. GraBois, a former federal
prosecutor who had spent years working on the case, discovered
strong circumstantial evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, a drifter who had a history of trying to lure young boys
into sexual encounters in Montana, California and elsewhere, turned
out to be an acquaintance of a woman who had worked for the Patzes
as a baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, while Ramos was serving a seven-year sentence in
Pennsylvania for child molestation and was facing a new charge of
sexually molesting an 8-year-old boy, GraBois took the unusual step
of having himself named a deputy state attorney general to help
prosecute the suspect by pressuring him _ in exchange for leniency
_ to disclose his possible role in the Patz case.
</P>
<P>
   Under intense questioning by investigators, Ramos was said to
have admitted that he was with the boy the day he vanished, but he
denied abducting and killing him and did not disclose any details
that might have implicated him. He pleaded guilty in the
Pennsylvania case and was sentenced to up to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   There was no further development until April, when investigators
in New York reported that Ramos had told a cellmate that he had
taken Etan to his apartment on May 25, 1979, and had sexually
assaulted him. The cellmate quoted him as saying, ``Etan is dead,
there is no body, and there will never be a body.''
</P>
<P>
   The cellmate, who was not identified, also gave investigators
what he said was a map drawn by Ramos showing the Patz loft in SoHo
and, a mile to the east, his own building at 234 E. Fourth St. on
the Lower East Side. The building had been searched for evidence
years ago, but nothing had been found.
</P>
<P>
   Among other developments in the intervening years, forensic
scientists have developed techniques for extracting genetic
evidence from strands of DNA in fragments of material that might be
years old. That hope inspired investigators to look again at the
basement, where, they said, Etan's body may have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Four police vehicles _ a truck, a van, a patrol car and an
unmarked supervisor's car _ drew up about 8 a.m. outside the
six-story red-brick building between Avenues A and B, and a dozen
officers, many wearing heavy work gloves and carrying shovels,
picks, hammers and other equipment, went into the basement, a
warren of small rooms.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, the officers began rolling out barrels of ash
and dirt, and chunks of rusted iron that were pieces of the old
coal-fired boiler, unused since a new boiler was installed in 1998,
Reznick said.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the building could recall Ramos. But Victor Serrano,
36, who lives across the street at No. 241 and was a teenager in
1979, said he remembered the man. He said Ramos lived on the second
or third floor of No. 234, but seemed more like a homeless person.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to come with a supermarket cart,'' Serrano said. ``He
was always friendly with all the kids,'' to whom he sometimes gave
toys. ``But I never got friendly with him. He always spooked me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
