<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RETURNS TO FUND RAISING AFTER FAMILY VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Mass.)   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After five days at his family's compound in
Kennebunkport, Maine, George W. Bush returned Thursday to the
campaign trail and embarked on a 72-hour, five-state fund-raising
drive that is expected to bring in nearly $5 million for
Republicans to wage the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In his one public campaign event before a round of closed
receptions for donors in Maine and Boston, Bush, the Texas
governor, proposed an additional $880 million in federal spending
and tax incentives over five years to help disabled Americans with
work, public access and new technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal now is clear _ to speed up the day when our country
has removed the last barrier to full, independent, productive lives
for every person with or without disability,'' Bush said in a
15-minute speech to a small group of people, many in wheelchairs,
at Alpha One, a nonprofit organization that provides services to
the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``All citizens with disabilities ask is a chance to use their
own gifts and talent to make their own contribution,'' Bush said
after making a quick tour of the Alpha One building in South
Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, recalled
that his father, the former president, signed the Americans With
Disabilities Act 10 years ago this month. The law is intended to
provide the disabled with greater opportunities and equal access to
services, public buildings and employment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush then proposed an array of new programs, spending increases
and tax incentives to help the disabled with new technology and
public access. They included $20 million a year in matching funds
to states to guarantee loans so the disabled could buy computers
and modems to work at home, a tripling to $33 million of the
federal research budget for universities to develop technology, and
$10 million in matching funds to help make places of worship more
accessible to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who brought in a record $80 million for his presidential
primary campaign, spent much of the day raising $1.1 million for
the Republicans' autumn offensive, including the kinds of
unregulated, unlimited donations that the House has voted to ban.
Senate Republicans have consistently blocked the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   At the Eastland Park Hotel in Portland, Maine, Bush raised an
estimated $100,000 for the Maine Republican Party. Then he flew to
Boston, where he spoke briefly to reporters at Logan International
Airport before heading to two events that were to bring in $1
million for the national Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Bush plans to raise another $1.1 million for
Republicans in appearances in Ohio and Kentucky, and on Saturday in
Florida he is to raise $2.75 million for the state and national
parties.
</P>
<P>
   The fund raising followed Bush's five-day retreat at his
family's Maine compound, where he celebrated his parents' birthdays
and made plans, with aides and strategists, for the Republican
National Convention, at the end of July in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, Bush's main rival in the Republican
primaries _ who had put the abolition of big-money fund raising at
the center of his campaign _ has agreed to speak on the second
night of the convention, said Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The night will focus on America's role in the world and is also
likely to feature former Republican presidents. ``We think it's
appropriate that a hero and former prisoner of war speak to our
convention about the need to rebuild America's military,'' Hughes
said of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Although the second night's most prominent convention slot is
usually reserved for a keynote speaker, McCain was not offered that
role. Bush's advisers said that historical spot might be done away
with. They plan to have retired Gen. Colin Powell speak on the
opening night of the convention, July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in his Boston news conference, repeated his call to
preserve the current Republican platform's plank on abortion, which
calls for a ban on the practice without exception and the
appointment of judges who respect ``the sanctity of innocent human
life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a pro-life party,'' Bush said. ``I recognize good
people can disagree. We are going to be a pro-life party at the
convention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
