<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5456 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-VIVENDI-SEAGRAM-LADN     06-15 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIVENDI-SEAGRAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCHMAN MAY RUN UNIVERSAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Universal City, Calif. _ The merger of Seagram Co. with the
Vivendi SA, world's largest water company, should be completed by
month's end, thus making Universal Studios Inc. a bicontinental
company, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, Vivendi Universal, is expected to be
headquartered in Paris with the Seagram chief executive officer,
Edgar M. Bronfman Jr., becoming vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   It will be one of the world's biggest media and entertainment
companies, with projected revenues of $65 billion and a market
capitalization of $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi Chairman Jean Marie Messier told reporters in Paris on
Thursday that negotiations between its television subsidiary Canal
Plus and Seagram were at an advanced stage. He will lead the new
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The companies confirmed Wednesday that they were talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some technical issues that need to be negotiated and
finalized. But if they are not nailed down, there is no deal,'' a
source familiar with the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   While Bronfman's title has been decided, his scope of influence
hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they have decided on the portfolio yet,'' the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   With the new company being headquartered in Paris, there is
speculation that the new Universal studio chief will be based
there.
</P>
<P>
   The front-runner now is the Canal Plus chairman and chief
executive officer, Pierre Lescure, who would become the first
Frenchman to run a major Hollywood studio, industry trades Daily
Variety and the Hollywood Reporter said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman, in an interview with Business Week, said that Vivendi
will acquire Seagram in a stock swap valued at $75 to $79 a share.
Seagram will also control five of 18 board seats, and Bronfman
family members will be the largest shareholders, with an 8 percent
stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think of it as a partnership, but Messier will be the
ultimate leader,'' Bronfman told the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram acquired Universal in 1997 through the purchase of its
parent, MCA Inc., for $5.7 billion. The film operations struggled
for several years before reversing 13 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, Universal has had a number of $100
million-grossing films, including ``The Mummy,'' ``Notting Hill,''
``American Pie'' and ``Erin Brockovich.'' The latter was this
year's first film to crest that mark and helped the studio dominate
the spring box office. Universal also co-produced the current
DreamWorks hit ``Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-production deals, with profits and costs shared, are common
in Hollywood. For example, Universal co-produced the Academy
Award-winning hit ``Shakespeare In Love'' with Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, analyst Jeff Logsdon at W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co. said
Vivendi is offering pretty good terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Bronfmans are able to sell Seagram in the price range
of $75 to $80 a share, that would be a very nice ending to what has
been a tumultuous story for the last few years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there is any expectation among the Bronfmans
of running the studio. I would sense they are happy to go off into
the sunset with a big smile on their faces and their wallets fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Logsdon notes that Canal Plus has been held in high regard and
Lescure has done a good job of running the company.
</P>
<P>
   But taking over an American film company would be a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``These boys are only going to be run so hard,'' he said of
American movie executives. ``Many have tried and few have
succeeded. I don't recall in my 18 years (of covering the industry)
of a foreigner who has successfully run a studio. But this is more
than a studio. This is a global (enterprise).
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Glynn Williams at Newcrest Capital Inc. agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When non-U.S. folks move in to run a Hollywood studio, they
get toasted. It's a lot harder business than most people think.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vivendi and Canal Plus boards will meet Monday to discuss
the Seagram deal.
</P>
<P>
   Messier, speaking at the Fortune Global Forum in Paris, said his
company is not interested in Seagram's beverage lines, so what
happens to those is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the deal puzzles some Seagram watchers like
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I find so bizarre is it's part of the family heritage,''
he said of the company known for its line of spirits. ``Seagram's
management is very smart, and they have great advisers, so I would
have to think this is part of a bigger chess game. I can see the
board right now, but I don't see what the game is.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
