<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5461 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-BRYANT-LADN     06-15 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BRYANT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SCENES LEFT IN BRYANT'S HIGHLIGHT REEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS - Rewind the Kobe Bryant documentary past the
overhead putback that clinched Game 4 of the NBA Finals two days
ago.... Past The Lob to Shaquille O'Neal in Game 7 against
Portland.... Past the last-second jump shot that won Game 2 of the
Lakers' series against Phoenix.... Past all the plays that made him
an All-Star and an All-NBA selection and an All-Defensive team
member....
</P>
<P>
   Rewind the tape back to a quiet moment at the Great Western
Forum in Inglewood, in the spring of 1999, and you will see a hint
of what brought him here, to the brink of his first NBA
championship at age 21.
</P>
<P>
   Practice has just ended and Bryant is casually watching a PGA
tournament on the locker-room television when a writer asks if he
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf? No. I could never play anything that I couldn't
master,'' Bryant says flatly.
</P>
<P>
   His visitor scoffs. ``And you can (begin ital)master(end ital)
basketball?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Bryant says. ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant says ``absolutely'' a lot, which is fitting. The Lakers'
flashy playmaker is all about absolutes. He is as supremely
confident as he is supremely talented. So there are no ``maybes''
in his repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   It's what makes Bryant, as young as he is, a superstar and
clutch performer in the mold of Magic Johnson and Michael Jordan
and Larry Bird. And if the Lakers win the championship tonight, on
the momentum of Bryant's amazing 28-point effort Wednesday, his
legend will begin a path right behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has as much talent or more than any player who has ever
lived,'' enthused Alex Hannum, who once coached Wilt Chamberlain
and won a pair of NBA championships with St. Louis and
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one ever questioned Bryant's talent. It's his
on-court maturity that has been an issue for his first four pro
seasons. Teammates were frustrated by his individual play, his
perceived selfishness, his impulse to try to win games by himself _
all products of the same immense confidence that makes him great.
</P>
<P>
   So rewind the documentary back another few months, to early
1999, and a practice session at L.A. Southwest College. Bryant's
coach from Lower Merion High in Pennsylvania is visiting and Bryant
introduces him to a few visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Bryant says with a smile, ``is the guy who taught me
not to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant laughs at his own joke. Yes, the kid can be as
self-deprecating as he is self-confident. And even self-aware.
</P>
<P>
   Even as teammate Shaquille O'Neal grew irritated by Bryant's
solo flights of fancy, the kid he dubbed ``Showboat'' was pushing
his way through one lesson after another. And slowly figuring out
that his spectacular one-on-one skills alone would not lead the
Lakers to a championship.
</P>
<P>
   But it took the arrival of coach Phil Jackson last summer _
armed with six Chicago Bulls championships, a legacy as Jordan's
mentor and a short leash for Bryant _ to begin the greatest stage
of Bryant's development.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really is way ahead of schedule for a kid who's 21 years
old,'' said Lakers general manager Mitch Kupchak. ``I think having
Phil here expedited the process a little bit. But he's such a
good-natured, talented kid, that he would have gotten there anyway.
It may have been at 26 or 27, but he would have gotten there, no
doubt about it. Having Phil here expedited the process, and winning
became a factor, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Kobe wanted to succeed, but I'm not sure if he knew
what winning at this level was all about. And I think he's learning
that now, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not about footwork, or reading defenses, or finding
opponents' weaknesses, although Jackson has brought much of that
education to Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was a certain poise or composure or confidence that
Phil brings,'' which he has imparted to his players, Kupchak said.
</P>
<P>
   In Bryant's case, that also meant having confidence in
teammates. Jackson made him the facilitator in the triangle
offense, not the Jordan position of scorer he coveted. And with
several trials and numerous errors and the occasional glare and a
benching, Bryant grew into the role. And his teammates grew to
appreciate him more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always on Kobe,'' O'Neal said. ``We knew eventually he
was going to come around. We didn't really want to put a cap on
what he could do. We just try to teach him to use his (skills) to
better everybody else. He can break anybody down (off the dribble).
When he gets to the lane, he has four, five guys waiting for him.
So every now and then, we want him to kick it out to Glen Rice, one
of the best shooters; every now and then, rip it out to me so I can
get it to the backboard apparatus, pass it to one of the players.
He's done an excellent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Where once Bryant tried to do it all, he has become almost a
consummate team player. But it was when Jackson took the leash off
that allowed Bryant to write his own chapter of NBA history. After
O'Neal fouled out Wednesday in overtime, Jackson gave Bryant
license to create _ and he scored six of the Lakers' last eight
points in the victory.
</P>
<P>
   In those closing minutes, his supreme confidence _ now tempered
by wisdom _ led the Lakers to victory.
</P>
<P>
   So fast-forward the tape again, to Conseco Fieldhouse on
Wednesday, Game 4 of the NBA Finals, and a timeout with 2:33 left
in overtime. The Lakers lead the Indiana Pacers by three points,
O'Neal has just fouled out, and Bryant is addressing his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'In a situation like this, Jordan wouldn't let his
team lose. I'm not going to let us lose.' He had that look in his
eye,'' Brian Shaw recalled. ``I knew, after that timeout, he was
going to take most of the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   He misses only one, blocked by Rik Smits. But Bryant, now as
great a defensive force as an offensive weapon, pays Indiana back,
blocking Austin Croshere from behind at the other end. Minutes
later, led by Bryant's 28 points, the Lakers secure a 3-1 lead in
the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is still the young phenom with the devastating one-on-one
skills. He's just a wiser one, with the good judgment to know when
to pounce and when to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just realizing the time to attack,'' Bryant said.
``(Jackson) brought it to me in a different light. It was more kind
of relaxing, going with the flow of the game, just investigating
the floor, really. You penetrate. You know that you can get to that
spot, so you say, 'OK, I know I can get there, I'll come back there
later, I might come back there in the fourth quarter.' Little mind
games that you play. That's how he approached it with me. It was
just so interesting. He taught me very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson was hired one year ago, he called his youngest
charge ``uneducated in basketball and in life.'' Now that Bryant is
also engaged to be married in a few weeks, neither description
seems to fit anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's mature beyond his years,'' Jackson said,
referring to both basketball and life. ``I think he's handling this
very well. I think that he's grown a lot in one year, and yet I see
a young man who's still got 13, 14 years of excellent basketball
ahead of him and a terrific future, hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   So reserve a few reels of film for a few hundred sequels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
