<SLUG> BC-RAPPER-CONVICTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAP SINGER CONVICTED OF ASSAULT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Star rapper Stanley Howse of the Grammy
Award-winning ``Bone Thugs-N-Harmony'' was convicted Thursday of
assault with a firearm largely because of his girlfriend's
testimony, jurors said.
</P>
<P>
   After deliberating just four hours, Van Nuys Superior Court
jurors said statements by Jennifer Spencer, Howse's only witness at
trial, led them to convict the 27-year-old rapper,
``Flesh-N-Bone.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer insisted Howse did not have a gun Dec. 26, when police
said he threatened two men with an AK-47 rifle at her Woodland
Hills apartment. But she also said the two men later attacked Howse
in a stairwell, taunting him with ``So where's your gun now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just confirmed there were guns around,'' said a juror, a
50-year-old Van Nuys insurance examiner who did not want to be
identified. ``If she hadn't said that, it might have made a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Howse was found guilty of assault with a firearm and for being
an ex-con with a gun. He could get up to 20 years in prison when
sentenced July 14 by Judge Darlene Schempp.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's verdict was the most recent conviction for Howse,
whose group's latest record is in the Billboard Top 100. He was
barred from possessing guns after pleading no contest to felony
assault and explosives possession in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant's girlfriend sealed his fate,'' said Los Angeles
County Deputy District Attorney Shellie Samuels. ``It was a
credibility case. The rest was just diversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Howse's attorney, Phillis Brown-Scarlett, said she had hoped the
jury would take more time to question the gun evidence and
conflicting accusations against Howse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised and disappointed in the verdict,'' said
Brown-Scarlett, who plans an appeal. ``I thought there was
overwhelming reasonable doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Howse is set to go on trial in Los Angeles for
unrelated firearms charges, terrorist threats and resisting an
officer. He is accused of storming a relative's South Los Angeles
home in January with a sawed-off shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man just keeps getting more violent,'' Samuels said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had to overcome several challenges to win the Van
Nuys trial. The victim, Tarrance Vickers, a friend of Howse's, told
police about the attack immediately afterward but recanted the
accusations at trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult to believe him; his story changed from
when he told police to what he told the detective the next day.
When he got on the stand, it changed again,'' said a 62-year-old
female juror.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors said they did not believe Vickers' testimony and instead
put their faith in the police reports and the testimony of Vickers'
brother, Fred Nelson of San Jose, who stuck by his original account
of the incident during his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
