<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD'S LAST GAME IS IMMINENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS - It was unusual from the beginning, but then this
was Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   And so it's come to this - win or lose, tonight's Game 5 will be
the last for Bird at the Conseco Fieldhouse as the Pacers' head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Lose, and it's his last as the Pacers coach.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Pacers are in need of any extra motivation facing
an elimination game, but there it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely want him to go out with a bang,'' said forward
Dale Davis. ``That's what we set out to do this year. We want to
win for him, and ourselves. We've had some good times and it was a
great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird said when he took the Pacers job it would be strictly a
three-year run. Three quick years later, Bird is facing the end.
</P>
<P>
   Bird, ever the warrior, and most of the Pacers, claim to be too
focused on keeping their Finals bid alive to get sentimental over
his possible last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be our last game,'' Bird said.
``These guys are down. We have to snap back. This is the Finals.
You don't worry about what's going to happen next. You don't give
up. You just try to go out and win a ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacers forward Austin Croshere said with practices and at least
one game left, Bird is coaching and his exit seems distant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do take time to think about it, it's obviously
disappointing,'' Croshere said. ``He's been a great coach for me
this year. But he feels like he needs to move on. That's been a
disappointing thought in the back of my mind all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up the ol' gang: Bird isn't the only part of the Pacers
who won't be back next year. Six players will become free agents,
including four starters - Reggie Miller, Jalen Rose, Mark Jackson,
Rik Smits, plus Sam Perkins and Croshere.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins plans to retire and Smits has discussed joining him.
With Travis Best able to run the point, Jackson could also be let
go.
</P>
<P>
   After making it to their first Finals ever, the Pacers might be
on the verge of a complete dismantling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything can happen,'' Jackson said. ``I do know this team has
proven it's capable of winning this thing. Whatever happens, we
have a lot to be proud of - and I'm not talking like it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Mismatch of the century: Hmmm, let's see, 5-foot-11 and
184-pound Best vs. 7-foot-1, 335-pound Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   And Goliath felled David.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the strangest sights in NBA Finals history, Best
climbed the mountain to deliver a flagrant foul on O'Neal Wednesday
night, before ricocheting hard to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   That left him with a sprained left shoulder. X-rays are
scheduled today and the Pacers are calling him probable, but Best
said if the game was Thursday he would have been out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't move it,'' Best said. ``I can't move it very fast and
my range of motion is just gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The big finish: The Pacers draw hope from knowing the Lakers
have struggled to close out each of their three previous playoff
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Croshere said. ``I think there was a little bit
of a letup on their part in Game 3. Certainly they're susceptible
to doing that again in Game 5. We can win here on Friday night in a
place we play much better and shoot much better, can get some
confidence going into L.A., then you never know what can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   My name is Reggie: Did anyone expect Miller to second-guess
himself for his 3-pointer that came up short in the closing seconds
of Wednesday's 120-118 overtime loss in Game 4?
</P>
<P>
   Miller said if he had pump-faked Robert Horry and stepped up, he
would have been fouled but was uncertain if it would have been
called.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to lose, I want to lose with me shooting,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: When Magic Johnson hit his ``junior-junior
skyhook'' in the final two seconds of Game 4 at Boston Garden to
put the Lakers up 3-1 in the 1987 NBA Finals, Celtics forward Larry
Bird was asked how he felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you think I feel?'' Bird said. ``I know when I'm up
3-1, I say it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won in six games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
