<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5467 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX     06-15 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE ANTI-GAMBLING STAND BY COACHES DOES MAKE SENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Upfront, let me say this:
</P>
<P>
   I don't bet on college sports. Basically, I don't bet on
anything involving two-legged creatures. But horses, now that's
different. Much different. This isn't about horses, however. This
really isn't even about calling up your friendly neighborhood
bookmaker and getting down on the Ol' Alma Mammy when it's playing
the hated Other Guys U.
</P>
<P>
   And one more clarification. I own no stock in any Las Vegas
casinos, and have visited that interesting city like once in the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   That was me, however, laughing like crazy this week at _ my
opinion here _ the absurdity of Tubby Smith and Lou Holtz, two
distinguished college coaching names, being house boys for
do-gooder, crusading politicians in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There were congressional hearings being held, and there are
bills pending in both houses of Congress that would stop Vegas
casino sports books from taking bets on any college games. Such
wagering is legal in one state _ Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Smith, the University of Kentucky basketball coach, and Mr.
Holtz, the well-traveled football coach, were, of course, speaking
in support of those bills. And also, I'm sure, speaking the truth
as they see it.
</P>
<P>
   But how can street-smart, been-around-the-block-more-than-once
guys like this come across, my opinion again, as so turnip-truck
naive? Neither exactly rode into town on a load of jock straps.
Grab a clue, fellows.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, however, gambling on college sports in this
country has pushed coaches and administrators into a panic, mainly
because the credibility of NCAA games is at stake. That's what
brought Holtz and Smith to Washington this week. And the college
coaching brotherhood is with them on this.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officialdom often stands accused of foolish over reaction
on a variety of issues, but not necessarily this time. At least not
in the big picture. They've got a massive problem with gambling.
They've had recent scandals with points-shaving and such. Big-time
gamblers got to players. The fear is what might come next. What if
one of those scandals suddenly surfaces in the NCAA's mother-lode
event, the Final Four? Billions in revenue would be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the NCAA has a large worry here.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I've got no solution for them.
</P>
<P>
   But if they are small-minded enough to think the answer is a
government ban on Las Vegas college sports wagering, then the wrong
people are seeking answers to troubling questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think that,'' said Bill Saum, from NCAA headquarters
in Indianapolis. ``This legislation is not a solution, but we do
feel it's a key component in encouraging the young people of
America not to wager. What would happen is that this bill would
eliminate a very high-profile place to bet on college sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Saum is the NCAA director responsible for finding those gambling
solutions. He has several helpful contacts in Vegas who keep him
advised on how money is flowing on college games. Saum also knows
that in both the recent Arizona State and Northwestern scandals,
the money was ``laid-off'' in Nevada because it's easier to spread
around large bets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the ringleaders in the Northwestern case testified if
there hadn't been Nevada, he couldn't have done it,'' Saum said.
</P>
<P>
   Betting is going to happen. Action on college football and
basketball, legal and illegally, ranks up there dollar-wise with
the operational budget of General Motors. But Las Vegas is the one
place where it's closely monitored, and where large wagers on one
team immediately raises suspicion. The very last thing the Vegas
boys want is a fixed game. They lose big. They also accept big
bets.
</P>
<P>
   As Saum pointed out, your friendly neighborhood bookmaker is not
going to take big-money wagers from a stranger. Nevada is really
the one and only place for that kind of action. And while the
landscape of sports wagering has changed dramatically with the
influx of ``off-shore'' betting parlors, those are done by account
wagering, which is another way of keeping tabs on who is betting,
and how much. The ``off-shore'' shops are illegal in this country,
but are growing like crazy on the Caribbean islands, and they
service American bettors by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   For the NCAA, however, the larger issue is curbing the campus
bookmaker _ moonlighting students have been directly involved in
the latest college sports scandals. In conjunction with that, the
NCAA is beefing up its police force where gambling and the athlete
is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not naive enough to think we can stop the gambling, but
part of our problem goes back to Las Vegas accepting bets \Ron
college sports\S,'' Saum said. ``Again, it's not a solution to our
problem, but if you take it away, it helps us. And we do need much
help in this.''
</P>
<P>
   So, I guess, never mind on Tubby and Lou. Maybe, just maybe,
they were making more sense up there in Washington than originally
thought.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
