<HEADER>
A5468 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-CAMPAIGN-NYT     06-15 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE FOR SENATE IS OFTEN STUCK IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Right about the time Rep. Rick A. Lazio's voting
record was being condemned by Hillary Rodham Clinton on Wednesday
in her fiercest campaign attack to date, Lazio was on the floor of
the House casting a most prosaic vote, to approve the record of the
previous day's proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   More significant votes would follow over the next 48 hours, and
Lazio, the Republican nominee for the U. S. Senate from New York,
was there, off the campaign trail, to keep up a sterling attendance
record out of a sense of duty and because he knew his opponent was
watching closely.
</P>
<P>
   In a week in which Clinton has intensified her criticism, Lazio
has spent much of his time attending to congressional duties in
Washington, juggling news media interviews and raising funds. He
attended two fund-raising events here.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio says he remains committed to balancing an aggressive
campaign schedule with his House obligations. He has not promised
to attend all votes _ and he has missed some since entering the
race May 20 _ but he has said he would make an effort to be present
for significant ones.
</P>
<P>
   Independent analysts say Lazio's predicament is a common one for
incumbents, who find their voting records under attack and
therefore must dash back to Washington from the campaign trail to
show their commitment and concern.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Rothenberg, who publishes a nonpartisan political
newsletter here tracking congressional races, said Lazio's
situation was a bit exacerbated by the timing of Clinton's barrage,
coming just when he needs to be in New York to make himself better
known. Several polls have shown the race at a virtual tie, with
many people supporting Lazio more out of opposition to Clinton than
because of familiarity with what he stands for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows her to determine and dictate the state agenda and
discussion,'' Rothenberg said. ``If he is in Washington, it's hard
to respond, to counterpunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the last week, in an attempt to portray Lazio as
indecisive and beholden to the House Republican leadership,
Clinton's staff has issued statements accusing Lazio of changing
his vote on some measures to go along with Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The latest criticism came Thursday, when Clinton's staff said
Lazio changed a vote Tuesday evening on a measure to require drug
companies that receive federal financing to offer the resulting
products at a reasonable cost to consumers. A spokesman for Lazio
responded by saying that Lazio's final vote in favor of the measure
reflected his previously stated position on the issue and that, in
the 15 minutes generally allotted for voting, members often adjust
their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was not available for an interview, his campaign aides
said, but they brushed off Clinton's attacks and said Lazio would
keep up his congressional duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes this job very seriously and he likes to be informed
about the issues and a broad range of subjects,'' said Bryan Flood,
a campaign spokesman. He said Lazio planned to resume campaigning
on Friday and over the weekend, with events upstate and in the New
York City region. Next week, he said, Lazio will probably return to
Washington for a few days for more voting as the session winds down
to the Fourth of July recess.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance was an issue in the 1998 Senate campaign, with the
Republican incumbent, Alfonse M. D'Amato, accusing his Democratic
challenger, Charles E. Schumer, of missing House votes until it was
learned that D'Amato had missed votes as a member of the Nassau
County Board of Supervisors in 1980 while he ran for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was present for 99 percent of the votes in the House in
1999, according to Congressional Quarterly; the average was 96.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   House records show that since May 20, Lazio has missed a handful
of votes on incremental pieces of legislation, like amendments to
amendments on bills. He did miss a final vote on a bill dear to
Republican leaders _ to phase out the federal estate and gift tax _
on June 9, which passed 279 to 136. Flood said Lazio missed it to
attend a funeral for an uncle on Long Island. It was also the day
he named his campaign manager and, in the evening, visited a Sons
of Italy club in the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Lazio voted for a bill giving electronic signatures
on legal documents weight equal to handwritten ones, a measure that
passed 426 to 4. He did buck the House leadership in voting against
a $339.5 billion measure for education, health and labor programs,
which passed 217 to 214 in a vote largely along party lines. Lazio
joined seven other Republican moderates, primarily from the
Northeast, and 206 Democrats in opposing the measure, which
President Clinton has promised to veto on grounds that it is
insufficient and lacks provisions to hire more teachers and repair
schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
