<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARRING SESSIONS OF PAST MEAN LITTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They've been talking about sparring sessions in
1992 since the promotional campaign for Saturday's bout was kicked
off.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Mosley helped his Saturday opponent, Oscar De La Hoya,
prepare for the Barcelona Games that year by working with him in
the gym. Mosley said he got the better of the sessions, and De La
Hoya said most recently that he really doesn't remember them
clearly.
</P>
<P>
   That's because there's virtually nothing to remember if a video
of one session is an indication.
</P>
<P>
   The two toyed with one another and seemed to pull their punches
from beginning to end. It didn't look as if a serious punch was
thrown by either fighter. The session certainly offers no
indication how Saturday's bout might go.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has changed. It's eight years later and pro fighters wear
gloves with less padding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't compare amateur to professional,'' De La Hoya said.
``When you wear eight-ounce gloves, believe me, the punches hurt
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Small talk: De La Hoya doesn't buy into the argument that he has
a significant size and strength advantage because Mosley moved from
135 pounds to 147 only two fights ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Trainer) Robert (Alcazar) and my brother (Joel) say he's not
a true welterweight,'' De La Hoya said. ``He's at my weight. That's
all that matters to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``... He's had a few fights at 147. He says he feels strong,
people rave about him. What else is there to say?''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, De La Hoya said his walk-around weight is
about 157 pounds and Mosley said he's typically around 162.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Mosley has fought in the same weight class as or higher
than De La Hoya for six of their eight years as professionals. De
La Hoya started at 130 pounds and Mosley has fought almost his
entire career at 135.
</P>
<P>
   Comparison: De La Hoya was asked to compare Mosley with Felix
Trinidad, the only fighter to beat him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power isn't the same,'' he said. ``I think Trinidad is
stronger behind his punches. Shane is a boxer who can move on his
toes and use speed. And he's very intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trinidad is a one-dimensional fighter. He comes straight
forward and tries to utilize his punching power. Shane thinks more
about his punches and his combinations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If something doesn't work,'' he went on, ``he goes to
something else. I think that's the difference between Shane and
Trinidad.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how the weeks leading up to the fight have been: mutual
respect.
</P>
<P>
   The other card: WBC lightweight champ Stevie Johnston (30-1, 15
KOs) will defend his title against Jose Luis Castillo at 2 p.m.
Saturday at the Bicycle Casino in Bell Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Johnston's fourth title defense since he regained the
championship from Cesar Bazan in February of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo (40-4, 37 KOs) is a former Mexican champion.
</P>
<P>
   The fight be televised on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   On the same card, successful amateurs Marshall Martinez and
Steven Luevano will make their pro debuts in separate bouts.
Martinez, a lightweight from Fontana, was 143-19 as an amateur.
Luevano, a featherweight from La Puente, was 189-16.
</P>
<P>
   In Indio: Antonio Diaz of Coachella, one of the most promising
junior welterweights in the world, faces Omar Gabriel Weis tonight
on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz (33-2, 24 KOs) is coming off an impressive victory over
Ivan Robinson. Weis (33-1, 16 KOs) is the Argentine 140-pound
champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
