<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN, IN NEW YORK, LINKS GANG SEX ATTACKS TO CRITICISM OF
POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pat Buchanan suggested Thursday that ``liberal
cop-bashing'' by Hillary Rodham Clinton and others had encouraged
the sexual assault spree by a gang of men in Central Park on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who is running for president, launched, unbidden, into
an attack on the first lady and Senate candidate in the midst of a
news conference he held near the United Nations to denounce the
proposed creation of an international war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a Republican who is seeking to run as the Reform Party
candidate, suggested the Central Park sexual assaults were, at
least in part, the product of declining police morale caused by
criticism of police tactics over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The liberal cop-bashing by folks like Hillary Rodham Clinton
is in part responsible for the new diminishment of the morale of
the police,'' Buchanan said at a news conference that was sparsely
attended, reflecting a significantly lower profile in his latest
bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it would not surprise me in the least,'' he said, ``if a
lot of these cops were far less aggressive in defending citizens,
and far less likely to get involved in what they ought to be doing
_ which is, quite frankly, busting a few heads and taking those
folks to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for an example of ``liberal cop-bashing'' by Clinton,
Buchanan noted the time she referred to the ``murder of Amadou
Diallo,'' just before the trial of the four police officers who
shot him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an outrageous, outrageous, slanderous, vicious,
stupid statement,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   The police officers were subsequently acquitted. Clinton has
said that she misspoke in describing the shooting as a murder, and
apologized for her remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, campaigning Thursday on Long Island, near the home base
of her Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, responded by attacking
Buchanan again. ``This is another in a long line of Mr. Buchanan's
attacks on people _ anti-Semitic comments, his racist and bigoted
comments,'' she said. ``So I'm not surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Thursday that she was ``outraged'' by the incident
in the park. And Buchanan described it as ``an act of barbarism and
animalism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
