<HEADER>
A5479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-AGCA-PARDON-NYT &LR;      06-15 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AGCA-PARDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PARDON FOR THE POPE'S ATTACKER 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 16:
</P>
<P>
   The pardon of Mehmet Ali Agca, would-be assassin of Pope John
Paul II, is a reminder that cold-war mysteries may still lie buried
in the archives of the former Soviet Union and the East bloc. Agca
shot the pope at his weekly general audience in St. Peter's Square
on May 13, 1981. John Paul was wounded in his hand and stomach, and
required two operations and four and a half months of
convalescence. Whether Agca acted alone or at the bidding of the
KGB and the Bulgarian secret service, or was backed by the Gray
Wolves, a right-wing Turkish terror group to which he belonged, is
still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The pardon granted by Italy's president was long sought by the
pope, who announced from his bed after the shooting that he forgave
Agca. The pope visited Agca in prison in 1983, and later received
Agca's mother at the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Agca has been returned to prison in Turkey. He was convicted in
absentia for the murder of a moderate Turkish newspaper editor and
sentenced to death, but the sentence was later reduced to 10 years.
While it is possible that Agca will now speak about his crime, it
is unlikely he will clear up the mysteries. He has said that the
Bulgarians and Soviets backed him. But he has also said he acted
alone, and claimed in court to be Jesus. In 1986 three Bulgarians
and three Turks were acquitted of conspiracy to kill the pope for
lack of evidence, an ambiguous verdict in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   East bloc archives are inconclusive. The Russian government has
produced cables that purport to show that the KGB was surprised by
the attempt. But KGB defectors have said they saw other cables
asking how to ``get close'' to the pope _ code, they assert, for
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that after the pope saw his assailant in
prison, he said, ``I spoke to him as I would speak to a brother
whom I have forgiven and who enjoys my confidence.'' Those standing
outside the cell watched him fold his hands around Agca's several
times. The existence of such profound humanity is a mystery of
another sort, one that will remain always elusive.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-00 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000615.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-60MINUTES-INTERVIEW-N     06-15 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-60MINUTES-INTERVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`60 MINUTES' FACES DOUBTS OVER REPORTED TERRORIST `CZAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Sunday, June 4, the CBS News program ``60
Minutes'' showed a striking report as its lead segment: a man
claiming to be Ahmad Behbahani, a ``czar of Iranian state-sponsored
terrorism,'' was being held under armed guard in Turkey, where he
was seeking to get his story out.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed off camera, he told a compelling story. Among other
things, he said he had planned the bombing of a Pan Am jet over
Scotland in 1988, as well as two other terrorist acts that have
been linked to Iran: the bombing of the Khobar Towers building in
Saudi Arabia in 1996, which killed 19 American soldiers, and the
attack on a Jewish community center in Buenos Aires, Argentina, in
1994, which killed 86 people.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two weeks later, ``60 Minutes'' is still not sure who the
man is, and the CIA and the FBI are saying he is an impostor. In
addition, ``60 Minutes'' has backed off somewhat on his importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our source, who is at a high level in our government and whom
we trust totally, has told us that the CIA and the FBI have
concluded he was in Iranian intelligence, but not as high up as he
claimed he was,'' said Lesley Stahl, the correspondent who reported
the story.
</P>
<P>
   But the network is defending its treatment of the interview,
saying it had taken great care to make clear that it was reporting
only the man's claims.
</P>
<P>
   The story behind the story has the murky intricacies of a John
LeCarre novel. It involves a cast of characters that includes the
exiled former Iranian president Abolhassan Bani-Sadr, armed Turkish
police officers, a former CIA terrorism specialist and unnamed
sources in the Clinton administration, as well as references to
several of the most infamous terrorism episodes of the past 12
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes'' said it found the man from a tip provided by
Bani-Sadr. It rushed to a refugee camp in central Turkey to secure
the information that Bani-Sadr said the man was eager to disclose.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who was being held under armed guard by the Turkish
police, never appeared on camera. Instead, an Iranian-born
associate producer from ``60 Minutes'' sneaked into the camp and
questioned the man, who identified himself as Ahmad Behbahani. The
producer then reported what she had heard to Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   The program used a former CIA terrorism specialist, Robert Baer,
as a consultant, and he managed to ask the man a question about an
assassination in Iran that, Baer said, only someone directly
involved could have known.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Baer, who is a very good guy, saying frankly, `This guy
knows some things,''' said Don Hewitt, the executive producer of
``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hewitt acknowledged that ``when you're in this world, you
often have no idea what the truth is,'' and that was one reason he
had hesitated to go with the segment.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt said he decided to show the interview after Stahl
reported receiving word from the CIA that the agency's chief in
Ankara, Turkey, had interrogated the man for two days, a sign of
his importance, and finally secured a comment from an official in
Washington that the man was at least ``in Iranian intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt said, ``I said that was enough to go with the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl said, ``We tried very hard to make sure this was right.''
She noted that the actions of the Turks, who followed the ``60
Minutes'' crew everywhere it went and guarded the crew's subject
much more tightly than anyone else in the camp, indicated to her
that he was somebody important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never told, by any of our sources, `Don't go on the
air with this, you're making a mistake,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Stahl said, on the Friday before the broadcast, a
CBS correspondent in Washington called to say he had been hearing
that such a story existed. ``We thought the story was leaking
out,'' Stahl said. ``That was a factor in the decision to go with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, at midday that Saturday, Hewitt made the decision to put the
report in the air. He explained: ``I said, `Let's put it on but
let's be very careful.' If you noticed, we were still very careful
in how we said this is a man who says he is Behbahani, who says he
was involved in these things.''
</P>
<P>
   But a week later, The Washington Post reported that officials in
the CIA and the FBI had concluded that the man was ``an impostor
who lacks basic knowledge of Iran's intelligence apparatus.'' The
newspaper also reported Iran's denial that the man was Ahmad
Behbahani and that the Iranian Intelligence Ministry had identified
him as Shahram Beladi Behbahani.
</P>
<P>
   One main area of dispute was the man's age. The experts cited in
the Post said the man would have been no more than 20 when the Pan
Am jet exploded, too young, they said, for such an assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl said, ``To be fair, we did hear some discrepancy about his
age.'' But she added that they had information that the man is 38,
not 32. She said Bani-Sadr had seen a photograph of the man they
spoke to and had said he ``looked like'' Ahmad Behbahani.
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes'' had hoped to have additional evidence on the
story, perhaps this week. The program had been told that a section
of videotape from a Iranian newscast might show the man they
questioned in a security detail for the former Iranian leader
Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
   But when ``60 Minutes'' asked for the tape to be sent from
Ankara by Federal Express, it mysteriously disappeared somewhere in
Istanbul _ twice. This led Stahl to believe that someone did not
want ``60 Minutes'' to see the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say the loss of that tape does add to my
suspicions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl also said she wondered why anyone would believe an
identification offered by the Iranian Intelligence Ministry, and
why her interview subject, if he really is no one important, had
not been released from custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why go to these lengths to keep him hidden?'' Hewitt asked.
``If he's a fake, trot him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, the man is still apparently being held by the
Turks, outside the reach of the press.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl said: ``I don't know what to think. Of course, it goes
without saying that if we were wrong, perhaps we should have
waited. But I'm suspicious of everybody in this story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
