<HEADLINE>
SIX MORE ARRESTED IN SEX ATTACKS IN CENTRAL PARK
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Armed with a flood of tips that followed the release
of suspects' photographs, the police Thursday arrested six young
men, from all around the region and all walks of life, and charged
them in the rampage of sexual assaults Sunday in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   One of the suspects, a barber from Queens, described getting
into ``an innocent water fight that got out of hand.'' Another, a
minister's son, planned to go to college and hoped to become a
lawyer. A third, a high school student, told his mother that he was
actually trying to help a women being attacked. And a fourth, a
father of two boys from Jersey City, was described by friends as a
good parent.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department, buoyed by it sudden success in making
arrests, released photographs of 13 more suspects taken from
videotapes of the melee, saying that as many as 20 people were
still being sought in attacks on as many as 37 women. In addition
to Thursday's six arrests, two people were arrested immediately
after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's arrests began at 5:30 a.m. and continued throughout
the day. For the police, it was a frenetic day: the victims of the
attacks filed through the Manhattan South Homicide Squad's offices
on East 21st Street to watch videotapes of the attack, and at one
point, with more than a dozen women waiting to watch the videos,
the police ordered four more VCRs and monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The men arrested Thursday, who ranged in age from 16 to 31, were
all charged with first-degree sexual abuse, a felony, and may face
additional charges, said Deputy Chief William Taylor, who is
overseeing the investigation. Most had no arrest records or arrests
for minor crimes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested first Thursday was John Taylor, 24, who was picked up
at his mother's home in Queens about 5:30 a.m. Steven Burt, 31, of
Jersey City, N.J., surrendered to the authorities there. Isaias
Lozano, 20, of Queens, and Manuel Nunez, 18, were arrested in the
morning, and 16-year-old Roberto Camacho of Inwood, Long Island,
surrendered later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Vargas, 18, of the Bronx, the man the police described as
the ``main player'' or ``instigator,'' surrendered Thursday night.
``He is identified by at least five or six of the women,'' a senior
investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Nunez wept Thursday as she described how the police came
for her son, Manuel Nunez, an 18-year-old with a year left at Taft
High School. He had not mentioned the parade until a friend spotted
his photo in the paper Thursday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another parent shared her shock. ``I was surprised and it hit me
hard because I know he's innocent,'' said Isaias Lozano, Lozano's
father, a minister. ``He was at the parade in the wrong place at
the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in Jersey City recalled Steven Burt, 31, as a conscientious
father of two boys and companion to their mother, Genise Shuler,
until the couple broke up six years ago. ``He was a nice guy who
worked and took care of his family,'' Shuler said. ``He was always
by himself and not with a crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Camacho of Inwood, who climbed out a window in the back
of his house while his mother spoke to the police Wednesday,
surrendered Thursday after people in his Long Island community
identified him.
</P>
<P>
   As more than 75 detectives concentrated on identifying suspects
and making arrests in the attacks, Internal Affairs detectives
looked into complaints that police officers had failed to respond
to reports of the assaults. The detectives questioned nearly 100
police supervisors and prepared to begin questioning officers
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on the arrests, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
defended the conduct of the majority of the police who patrolled
the parade, but acknowledged that some may have failed to respond
properly to reports of the attacks. He said complaints against them
would be vigorously investigated.
</P>
<P>
   He also stressed that the situation was created by the unruly
men who had committed the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Gov. George Pataki said he would propose
legislation to designate gang sexual assault as a separate crime,
said Caroline Quartararo, a spokeswoman for Pataki. The crime would
be a class D felony with a maximum prison sentence of seven years,
a far more serious crime than simple sexual assault, a misdemeanor
punishable by up to a year in jail, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
