<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON UNHAPPY WITH BATTING AVERAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. - Garret Anderson admits he is not feeling
good about himself when he looks at the stat sheet and sees that
he's hitting .245. After all, Anderson went into the season hitting
.300 for his career.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's power numbers - 16 homers and 42 RBI - have him on
course for career highs in those categories. But that is of little
consolation to a man who was a protege of former Angels hitting
coach Rod Carew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say it doesn't bother me, I have pride,'' Anderson
said. ``Seeing my average that low is embarrassing. There's nothing
I can do about it but take it one at-bat at a time. I'm not going
to make it up in one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of irritating to me sometimes. I'm making outs and
I'm not facing the best pitchers in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is typically a slow starter, but the slow start has
carried over to June this season. And he said it has nothing to do
with sacrificing average for power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so, I'm not trying to hit home runs,'' he said.
``I'm trying to hit my line drives. I feel comfortable and I'm
seeing the ball fine. But when I get a pitch to hit, I foul it off.
And when I do center the ball and hit it hard, it's going right at
people.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the solution?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a checklist of things that I go through to make sure I
have the right approach,'' he said. ``I keep it simple. There are
not a lot of adjustments to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take bits and pieces of what people say, but I know what
I've done in the past and what I did to get here. I know what works
for me.... Mentally, it's not wearing on me because I know I'm a
good hitter. As long as I know I'm prepared, it's something I have
to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulking up: Catcher Matt Walbeck has added considerable muscle
to his 5-foot-11, 188-pound frame since the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idle time,'' Walbeck explained.
</P>
<P>
   Walbeck has the extra time to spend in the weight room these
days because Bengie Molina is getting most of the starts. And with
good reason. Molina is hitting .335 and has thrown out 38 percent
(17 of 45) of would-be base stealers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Walbeck has started 16 games this season, Molina
49.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing pretty well,'' Walbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Short hops: Pitcher Ken Hill made a rehab start for Triple-A
Edmonton on Thursday night but showed he isn't near ready to rejoin
the Angels' rotation. Hill threw 78 pitches in four innings,
allowing five runs and seven hits.... Jason Dickson is scheduled to
make his second rehab start for Edmonton tonight.... Shortstop
Kevin Stocker's strained left hip flexor was feeling better
Thursday, keeping him off the disabled list. Manager Mike Scioscia
said Stocker might start tonight's game in Baltimore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
