<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ALBANY'S TASK ON GUNS AND BALLOT ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 16:
</P>
<P>
   With the current New York legislative session limping toward a
close, negotiators in Albany are focusing on key issues where
action should be possible before adjournment next week. Ballot
reform and gun control are of critical importance.
</P>
<P>
   In April, with the memory still fresh of the ballot-rigging that
nearly prevented Sen. John McCain from competing in the state's
presidential primary, the State Senate approved remedial
legislation offered by one of the chief architects of that debacle,
Gov. George Pataki. The measure would automatically place all
recognized GOP candidates on the primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The bill contains a disappointing provision that would turn the
Republican presidential primary into a winner-take-all contest, and
it fails to address Democratic Party procedures. But that is no
excuse for the lack of interest shown so far by the Assembly
speaker, Sheldon Silver. He needs to seize this rare opportunity to
ensure that New York's voters have a wider choice of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Last-minute maneuvering will also decide the fate of the
constructive gun control package that Pataki introduced in March.
The Senate, which is usually allergic to gun controls, would
probably be forced to go along if the governor and the Assembly can
agree on a bill. The governor's package includes a ban on assault
weapons, background checks for guns purchased at gun shows, raising
the age for purchasing guns from 18 to 21, ballistics
fingerprinting of all new guns to make them easier to trace, and a
requirement that gun dealers provide a trigger lock with every gun
sale. The bill should be strengthened by requiring built-in trigger
locks and including penalties for those who fail to store their
weapons safely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
